window.COURSE = {"title": "NCATT/ASTM AET Certification", "passMark": 0.73, "modules": [{"n": 0, "title": "Orientation & Exam Strategy", "standards": "Intro", "lesson": "<h3>1. What is the AET, and why should you care?</h3>\n<p><strong>AET</strong> stands for <strong>Aircraft Electronics Technician</strong>. It is a certification that proves you understand the electrical and electronic systems on an aircraft &mdash; the wires, radios, instruments, and \"black boxes\" that make a modern plane fly safely.</p>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Note</span>Think of it like a driver's license for aircraft electronics. Anyone can poke at wires. But an employer wants proof you know what you are doing. The AET is that proof.</div>\n<p>The AET grew out of <strong>NCATT</strong> (the National Center for Aerospace &amp; Transportation Technologies). In 2014 the standard was taken over by <strong>ASTM International</strong>, a big standards organization. So today people say \"NCATT AET\" or \"ASTM AET\" &mdash; same thing. The governing standard is <strong>ASTM F3245</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>The real prize:</strong> if you earn the AET <strong>plus one avionics \"endorsement\"</strong> (a specialty add-on, like radio communication systems), that combination satisfies the formal-training requirement in <strong>14 CFR 65.101(a)(5)(ii)</strong>. That regulation is one of the doors to an <strong>FAA Repairman Certificate</strong> &mdash; an actual FAA credential that lets you sign off on certain avionics work.</p>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Why this matters to you</span>You are already in A&amp;P school. The AET stacks neatly on top of that. The electronics you learn here (and in FAA-H-8083-30B Chapter 12) is the <em>same</em> material, just aimed at a credential that opens an avionics door the A&amp;P alone does not.</div>\n\n<h3>2. The exam, in plain numbers</h3>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Key facts</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>90 questions</strong>, all multiple choice.</li>\n<li><strong>73% to pass.</strong> That is about <strong>66 of 90</strong> correct. Miss more than 24 and you fail.</li>\n<li><strong>About 2 hours</strong> of testing time.</li>\n<li><strong>Proctored</strong> (someone watches you test). Administered through <strong>SpaceTEC Partners (SPI)</strong> via their <strong>Credential Testing Services (CTS)</strong> network.</li>\n<li><strong>No prerequisites.</strong> You do not need a degree, an A&amp;P, or any prior cert to sit for it.</li>\n<li><strong>Lifetime certification.</strong> Once you pass, it does <strong>not</strong> expire and there is no renewal.</li>\n<li>The exam is owned by <strong>ASTM / NCATT</strong> &mdash; <strong>not ETA International</strong>. If a study site tells you it is an ETA exam, that site is wrong.</li>\n</ul></div>\n<p>The questions are drawn from <strong>34 \"Standards\"</strong> grouped into <strong>4 domains</strong>. The test will ask one or more questions from each of the standards areas.</p>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">What 73% really means</span>The cut score is high, but the questions are mostly definition and recognition level, not trick math. If you truly learn the vocabulary and the \"why,\" 73% is very reachable. Our course checkpoint is also 73% &mdash; on purpose &mdash; so every module quiz mirrors the real bar.</div>\n\n<h3>3. Big decision: AET vs. CAET</h3>\n<p>This is the one thing I want you to actually <strong>decide on</strong> early, so read carefully.</p>\n<p>In <strong>March 2025</strong>, the <strong>Aircraft Electronics Association (AEA)</strong> launched a newer credential called the <strong>CAET</strong> (Certified Aircraft Electronics Technician). It is meant to be the modernized successor to the AET.</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th></th><th>AET (legacy)</th><th>CAET (new, 2025)</th></tr>\n<tr><th>Owner</th><td>ASTM / NCATT</td><td>AEA</td></tr>\n<tr><th>Questions</th><td>90</td><td>100</td></tr>\n<tr><th>Time</th><td>~2 hours</td><td>~90 minutes</td></tr>\n<tr><th>Pass score</th><td>73%</td><td>70%</td></tr>\n<tr><th>Content</th><td>Essentially the same body of avionics knowledge</td><td>Essentially the same body of avionics knowledge</td></tr>\n<tr><th>Status</th><td>Becoming a legacy credential</td><td>The forward-looking one</td></tr>\n</table>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Note</span>CAET figures (100 q, ~90 min, 70%, ~$119 fee) are the AEA's published launch numbers and may change &mdash; verify current details with the AEA before you pay.</div>\n<p><strong>The good news:</strong> because the content overlaps so heavily, this course prepares you for either exam. You are not choosing which to <em>study</em> &mdash; you are only choosing which to <em>sit</em>. There is also a cheap bridge: if you pass the AET first, a small <strong>upgrade exam</strong> (reported as ~50 questions, 80% to pass, about <strong>$49</strong>) converts your AET into a CAET.</p>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">My honest recommendation</span>Decide based on one phone call: ask your target avionics employer (or AIM's avionics program) which credential they actually recognize. That single answer outranks everything else. If they say <strong>CAET</strong>, sit the CAET. If they say <strong>AET</strong>, \"either is fine,\" or you cannot get a clear answer, sit the AET now, then do the ~$49 upgrade to CAET later &mdash; you get a credential today and keep the modern one in reach for almost nothing.</div>\n\n<h3>4. How this course works</h3>\n<p>This is a <strong>course</strong>, not a quiz dump. I teach you, I check that you got it, and I only move on when you are solid. Here is the loop I run for every module:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Read the lesson</strong> &mdash; plain English first (with an analogy if it is new), then tightened up to the exact exam wording. Every formula gets a worked example.</li>\n<li><strong>Take the quiz</strong> &mdash; a clickable quiz on your live quiz link (same place as your A&amp;P quizzes).</li>\n<li><strong>Pass at 73%</strong> &mdash; the same bar as the real exam. If you fall short, I re-teach the gaps before we advance.</li>\n<li><strong>Next module unlocks</strong> &mdash; passing one module opens the next one.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Why the loop works</span>Reading once and forgetting is normal. The fix is <em>retrieval practice</em> &mdash; pulling the answer out of your head on a quiz. That is why every module ends with a quiz, not just a summary. (Module 0 is the only exception: it is the intro, so it has no graded quiz. Mark it complete to unlock Module 1.)</div>\n<p>There are <strong>14 modules</strong> in all (this orientation plus 13 teaching modules):</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>#</th><th>Module</th><th>Standards</th></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td>Orientation &amp; Exam Strategy (you are here)</td><td>Domain I (references)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>DC Fundamentals</td><td>1, 5, 6</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>Circuits &amp; Troubleshooting</td><td>4</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>Resistors</td><td>7, 8</td></tr>\n<tr><td>4</td><td>Reactive Components</td><td>9, 10, 11, 12, 13</td></tr>\n<tr><td>5</td><td>Semiconductors &amp; Analog</td><td>14</td></tr>\n<tr><td>6</td><td>Power Supplies &amp; Filters</td><td>15, 16, 17</td></tr>\n<tr><td>7</td><td>Signal Circuits</td><td>18, 19</td></tr>\n<tr><td>8</td><td>Digital</td><td>20, 21</td></tr>\n<tr><td>9</td><td>Safety &amp; Shop Practices</td><td>22, 23, 24, 27, 29</td></tr>\n<tr><td>10</td><td>Tools, Pubs &amp; Corrosion</td><td>25, 26, 28</td></tr>\n<tr><td>11</td><td>Wiring &amp; Test Equipment</td><td>30, 31, 32</td></tr>\n<tr><td>12</td><td>Aircraft Fundamentals</td><td>33, 34</td></tr>\n<tr><td>13</td><td>Exam Prep &amp; Endorsements (full 90-q mock)</td><td>all</td></tr>\n</table>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Key facts</span>You are already studying <strong>FAA-H-8083-30B Chapter 12 (Electricity &amp; Electronics)</strong> for A&amp;P school. That chapter covers most of <strong>Standards 1&ndash;21</strong> &mdash; the same DC, AC, components, semiconductors, and digital material. Where you crush it, we move fast. Where you wobble, we slow down. No wasted time.</div>\n\n<h3>5. The blueprint: 34 Standards across 4 domains</h3>\n<p>The whole exam is built from 34 Standards. NCATT does <strong>not</strong> publish how many questions come from each domain, so the smart move is to <strong>study all four domains evenly</strong>. Do not gamble that one area is \"small.\"</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Domain</th><th>What it covers</th><th>Standards</th></tr>\n<tr><th>I. Introductory &amp; General</th><td>Reference materials &amp; orientation (this module)</td><td>References</td></tr>\n<tr><th>II / III. Electronics Fundamentals</th><td>DC &amp; AC basics, Ohm's &amp; Kirchhoff's laws, resistors/color codes, inductors, capacitors, transformers, semiconductors, power supplies, filters, wave/limiter circuits, digital numbering &amp; logic</td><td>1&ndash;21</td></tr>\n<tr><th>II. Common Maintenance Practices</th><td>Hazards/safety, hazmat, FOD, technical pubs, common tools, ESD, corrosion, safety devices, aircraft wiring, wire maintenance, test equipment</td><td>22&ndash;32</td></tr>\n<tr><th>IV. Aircraft Fundamentals</th><td>Aircraft structures &amp; theory of flight; aircraft handling &amp; safety</td><td>33&ndash;34</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>One more thing worth knowing: each Standard carries an <strong>NCATT level</strong> (like \"Level A &mdash; knows facts,\" up to \"Level D &mdash; knows evaluation,\" plus task levels). It just tells you <em>how deep</em> the exam expects you to know that topic &mdash; a \"Level A\" topic is recognition; a higher level wants you to troubleshoot.</p>\n\n<h3>6. Free study resources (your budget-friendly stack)</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The official NCATT AET Study Guide</strong> &mdash; the ~60-page PDF this course teaches from. It defines all 34 Standards with the exact terms the test uses. (primary source)</li>\n<li><strong>FAA-H-8083-30B, Chapter 12</strong> &mdash; \"Fundamentals of Electricity &amp; Electronics.\" Free from the FAA. Your deep-dive text for Standards 1&ndash;21, and you are already reading it for A&amp;P.</li>\n<li><strong>AC 43.13-1B/2B</strong> &mdash; free FAA advisory circular for wiring, bonding, and acceptable practices (Standards 30&ndash;32).</li>\n<li><strong>FAR Handbook for Aviation Maintenance Technicians</strong> (14 CFR Parts 43, 65, 91) &mdash; for the regulatory and pubs questions.</li>\n<li><strong>This course's quizzes</strong> &mdash; one per module on your live quiz link, every answer cited.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Note</span>Everything above is free. No paid subscription is needed to pass this exam.</div>\n\n<h3>7. What's next</h3>\n<p>Two steps from here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Mark this module complete</strong> to unlock <strong>Module 1 &mdash; DC Fundamentals</strong> (Standards 1, 5, 6): voltage, current, resistance, electron theory, Ohm's Law, Watt's Law, and meters. With your Chapter 12 background, this should feel like review with sharper exam wording.</li>\n<li><strong>Plan the work.</strong> 13 teaching modules. A few focused hours per module is roughly 40&ndash;55 hours total spread over your schedule &mdash; and likely less for the early electronics modules you can partly test out of.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Key facts</span>The only rule of this course: we do not advance on a shaky foundation. We go at <em>your</em> pace. Sources: NCATT AET Study Guide pp. 1&ndash;53; 14 CFR 65.101; ASTM F3245. CAET figures per AEA (2025), marked [verify].</div>\n", "quiz": [], "drill": [{"label": "Exam length", "text": "The AET exam is 90 multiple-choice questions, ~2 hours, proctored."}, {"label": "Pass score", "text": "You need 73% to pass &mdash; about 66 of 90 correct. The course checkpoint mirrors this at 73%."}, {"label": "Prerequisites", "text": "No prerequisites. No degree, A&P, or prior cert required to sit the AET."}, {"label": "Validity", "text": "Lifetime certification &mdash; it does not expire and there is no renewal."}, {"label": "Who owns/administers it", "text": "Owned by ASTM / NCATT (standard ASTM F3245); administered by SpaceTEC Partners (SPI) via Credential Testing Services. It is NOT an ETA International cert."}, {"label": "Career payoff", "text": "AET + one avionics endorsement satisfies 14 CFR 65.101(a)(5)(ii), a pathway toward an FAA Repairman Certificate."}, {"label": "AET vs. CAET", "text": "The CAET (AEA, launched March 2025) is the modernized successor; same study content. If you pass AET, a ~$49 upgrade exam converts AET&rarr;CAET. Confirm with your employer which they recognize."}, {"label": "Blueprint", "text": "Exam draws from 34 Standards across 4 domains; per-domain weighting is not published, so study all domains evenly."}]}, {"n": 1, "title": "DC Fundamentals", "standards": "1, 5, 6", "lesson": "<h3>Why this matters on a real aircraft</h3>\n<p>Every landing light, fuel pump, radio, and warning horn on the airplane runs because electrons are pushed through a wire. When something stops working, your meter and these three numbers &mdash; <strong>voltage, current, resistance</strong> &mdash; are how you find the fault. Master this one module and the rest of avionics is just stacking ideas on top of it. <em>(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-1)</em></p>\n<p>You told me you're starting from zero, so we build this brick by brick. Every term gets defined, every calculation shows every step. Read it slow &mdash; nothing here is hard once you see it.</p>\n\n<h3>1. What electricity actually is (electron theory from scratch)</h3>\n<p><strong>Everything is made of atoms.</strong> All physical stuff &mdash; the aluminum skin of the plane, a copper wire, the air &mdash; is <strong>matter</strong>. Matter is anything that has mass and takes up space. Matter is built from tiny building blocks called <strong>atoms</strong>. The atom is the most basic building block of all matter. <em>(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-1)</em></p>\n<p>An atom has three kinds of particles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Proton</strong> &mdash; a <strong>positively (+) charged</strong> particle that sits in the center of the atom (the <em>nucleus</em>). Protons are <strong>not</strong> involved in conducting electricity. <em>(SG p. 6; FAA p. 12-1)</em></li>\n<li><strong>Neutron</strong> &mdash; a <strong>neutral (no charge)</strong> particle, also in the nucleus. Neutrons are <strong>not</strong> involved in conducting electricity. <em>(SG p. 5; FAA p. 12-1)</em></li>\n<li><strong>Electron</strong> &mdash; a <strong>negatively (&minus;) charged</strong> particle that orbits (circles) the nucleus, far out at the edge. Electrons are the particles <strong>involved in the conduction of electricity</strong>. <em>(SG p. 5; FAA p. 12-1)</em></li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Note</span>Picture an atom like a tiny solar system. The <strong>nucleus</strong> is the sun in the middle (protons + neutrons packed together). The <strong>electrons</strong> are planets whizzing around it. The \"sun\" stays put; it's the outer \"planets\" (electrons) that can break loose and travel &mdash; and that traveling is electricity. When the number of (+) protons exactly equals the number of (&minus;) electrons, the atom is balanced &mdash; we say it has a <strong>neutral charge</strong>. <em>(FAA p. 12-2)</em></div>\n<p><strong>Free electrons &mdash; the key idea.</strong> Electrons sit in layers called <strong>shells</strong> around the nucleus. The electrons in the <strong>outermost shell</strong> are held only loosely. Those loosely-held outer electrons are called <strong>free electrons</strong>, because they can be knocked loose and travel from atom to atom. A <strong>free electron</strong> is a loosely-bound outer-shell electron that can be easily dislodged and move from atom to atom. <strong>That flow of free electrons, when it happens in a circuit, is electric current.</strong> <em>(FAA p. 12-2, 12-16)</em></p>\n<p><strong>Conductors vs. insulators vs. semiconductors.</strong> Whether a material carries electricity comes down to one thing: <strong>how many free electrons it has.</strong> More free electrons = more current can flow. <em>(FAA p. 12-2)</em></p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Type</th><th>Free electrons?</th><th>Carries current?</th><th>Examples</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Conductor</td><td>Many</td><td>Yes, easily</td><td>Silver, copper, gold, aluminum</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Insulator</td><td>Almost none</td><td>No (or barely)</td><td>Glass, ceramic, rubber, plastic</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Semiconductor</td><td>In between</td><td>Sometimes (controllable)</td><td>Silicon, germanium</td></tr>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Conductor</strong> &mdash; the building block that easily lets electrons move from the source to the load and back with minimum resistance. Copper and silver have one electron in their outer orbit, so a piece of silver wire has <em>billions</em> of free electrons at room temperature. <em>(SG p. 4; FAA p. 12-3)</em></li>\n<li><strong>Insulator</strong> &mdash; a material used to prevent the passage of electricity (also heat or sound). Under normal conditions insulators make no free electrons, so current can't flow. Only an extremely strong field forces electrons loose &mdash; that's called <em>breakdown</em> and it usually wrecks the insulator. <em>(SG p. 5; FAA p. 12-3, 12-4)</em></li>\n<li><strong>Semiconductor</strong> &mdash; falls between the two. In their pure state silicon and germanium are not good conductors <em>or</em> insulators; they can be made to act like either. They're what transistors and chips are built from. <em>(FAA p. 12-4)</em></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Static electricity:</strong> an electrical charge built up on a non-conductive surface by friction (rubbing). It just sits there (no flow) and serves no useful purpose &mdash; but a sudden discharge can destroy sensitive avionics parts. <em>(SG p. 6; FAA p. 12-4)</em></p>\n\n<h3>2. The Big Three: Voltage, Current, Resistance (the water-pipe analogy)</h3>\n<p>The one analogy that explains all of it: picture water in a pipe.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>VOLTAGE</strong> = the <strong>water pressure</strong> pushing the water. No pressure, no flow.</li>\n<li><strong>CURRENT</strong> = the <strong>amount of water flowing</strong> past a point.</li>\n<li><strong>RESISTANCE</strong> = the <strong>friction / narrowness of the pipe</strong> that fights the flow.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Squeeze harder (more pressure) and more water flows (more current). Use a narrower, rougher pipe (more resistance) and less water flows. That's literally Ohm's Law, coming up next.</p>\n<p><strong>Voltage &mdash; the electrical \"push\" (unit: the VOLT, symbol E).</strong> Electrons won't move on their own; something has to push them. That push is called <strong>electromotive force (EMF)</strong> &mdash; \"the force that causes electrons to flow through a conductor.\" Its unit of measurement is the <strong>volt</strong>. In math problems voltage is the letter <strong>E</strong>. <em>(SG p. 5)</em></p>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Key terms &amp; numbers</span>\n<p><strong>Volt (V), symbol E:</strong> the basic unit of electrical pressure. <strong>A volt is the amount of force required to cause one amp of current to flow through one ohm of resistance.</strong> Voltage also goes by: voltage drop, potential difference, EMF, or IR drop. <em>(SG p. 6)</em></p>\n</div>\n<p>An aircraft battery shows this directly: between its two terminal posts there is an EMF of <strong>12 or 24 volts</strong> available to push current through the circuit. <em>(FAA p. 12-16; SG p. 4)</em> Important detail: voltage is always measured <em>between two points</em> &mdash; it's the <strong>difference</strong> in electrical pressure. In the two-water-tank picture, water flows because of the <em>difference</em> in pressure between the tanks, not the pressure of one tank alone. <em>(FAA p. 12-16)</em></p>\n<p><strong>Current &mdash; the flow (unit: the AMPERE, symbol I).</strong> Electrons in motion make up an electric current. \"The flow of electrons through a conductor is known as current flow,\" and the rate of that flow is measured in amperes. <em>(SG p. 4; FAA p. 12-16)</em></p>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Key terms &amp; numbers</span>\n<p><strong>Ampere (A, \"amp\"), symbol I:</strong> the unit used to express the flow of electrons (current). <strong>One ampere is a rate of flow of one coulomb passing a given point per second.</strong> <em>(SG p. 4; FAA p. 12-17)</em></p>\n<p><strong>Coulomb (C):</strong> the basic unit of electrical quantity. <strong>One coulomb = 6.28 billion-billion electrons (6.28 &times; 10<sup>18</sup>).</strong> <em>(SG p. 4; FAA p. 12-17)</em></p>\n<p>Put them together: <strong>1 amp = 1 coulomb of charge (6.28 &times; 10<sup>18</sup> electrons) flowing past a point every second.</strong> As a formula: <strong>I = Q / t</strong> &mdash; current (I) equals charge in coulombs (Q) divided by time in seconds (t). <em>(FAA p. 12-16, 12-17)</em></p>\n</div>\n<p><strong>Resistance &mdash; the opposition (unit: the OHM, symbol R, sign &Omega;).</strong> Resistance is the opposition a circuit or material presents to the flow of electricity. It \"opposes or slows down another force, drops voltage, and consumes power.\" Measured in <strong>ohms</strong>, symbol <strong>R</strong>. <em>(SG p. 6)</em></p>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Key terms &amp; numbers</span>\n<p><strong>Ohm (&Omega;), symbol R:</strong> the unit of electrical opposition to current. <strong>A circuit has one ohm of resistance when it limits the flow of current to one amp under a voltage pressure of one volt.</strong> <em>(SG p. 6; FAA p. 12-18)</em></p>\n</div>\n<p>Four things change a conductor's resistance &mdash; worth memorizing <em>(FAA p. 12-18, 12-19)</em>:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Material</strong> &mdash; copper conducts better than aluminum of the same size.</li>\n<li><strong>Length</strong> &mdash; <em>longer wire = more resistance</em> (double the length, double the resistance).</li>\n<li><strong>Cross-sectional area (thickness)</strong> &mdash; <em>thicker wire = less resistance</em> (double the area, half the resistance).</li>\n<li><strong>Temperature</strong> &mdash; for most metals, hotter = more resistance.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Two directions of \"flow\" you'll see (don't let it confuse you):</strong></p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Theory</th><th>Says current flows...</th><th>Note</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Conventional flow</td><td>from + to &minus; (positive to negative)</td><td>Older idea (Ben Franklin); still in many books.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Electron flow</td><td>from &minus; to + (negative to positive)</td><td>What actually happens. <strong>The FAA officially uses electron flow (&minus; to +).</strong></td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>For troubleshooting it barely matters which you use &mdash; just stay consistent. But for the AET exam, remember the FAA defines current as <strong>electron flow, negative to positive</strong>. <em>(FAA p. 12-14)</em></p>\n\n<h3>3. Ohm's Law &mdash; the most important formula you'll ever learn (Standard 5)</h3>\n<p>The three quantities are tied together by one rule. <strong>Ohm's Law:</strong> \"the amount of current flowing in a circuit is directly proportional to the circuit voltage and inversely proportional to the circuit resistance.\" Plain-language version: <strong>One (1) volt causes One (1) ampere to flow through a resistance of One (1) ohm.</strong> <em>(SG p. 6)</em></p>\n<p>\"Directly proportional to voltage\" = push harder, more current. \"Inversely proportional to resistance\" = more resistance, less current. The formula:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;font-size:18px\"><strong>E = I &times; R</strong><br><em>Voltage (E) = Current (I) &times; Resistance (R)</em></p>\n<p><strong>The Ohm's Law triangle &mdash; how to never forget it.</strong> Put <strong>E</strong> on top, <strong>I</strong> and <strong>R</strong> on the bottom. Cover the letter you want; what's left tells you the math. <em>(FAA p. 12-18)</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cover <strong>E</strong> &rarr; you see <strong>I R</strong> side by side &rarr; <strong>E = I &times; R</strong></li>\n<li>Cover <strong>I</strong> &rarr; you see <strong>E over R</strong> &rarr; <strong>I = E &divide; R</strong></li>\n<li>Cover <strong>R</strong> &rarr; you see <strong>E over I</strong> &rarr; <strong>R = E &divide; I</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>That's all three rearrangements from one picture. Now let's actually use them.</p>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example</span>\n<p><strong>1 &mdash; find CURRENT (I = E &divide; R).</strong> A 28-volt aircraft circuit has a landing-light resistance of 14 ohms. How much current flows?</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Step 1 &mdash; Write what you know: E = 28 V, R = 14 &Omega;, find I.</li>\n<li>Step 2 &mdash; Cover I in the triangle &rarr; formula is I = E / R.</li>\n<li>Step 3 &mdash; Plug in: I = 28 V &divide; 14 &Omega;.</li>\n<li>Step 4 &mdash; Divide: 28 &divide; 14 = <strong>2</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Answer: I = 2 amperes.</strong></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example</span>\n<p><strong>2 &mdash; find VOLTAGE (E = I &times; R).</strong> A relay coil of 50 ohms draws 0.5 amp. What voltage is across it?</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Step 1 &mdash; Known: I = 0.5 A, R = 50 &Omega;, find E.</li>\n<li>Step 2 &mdash; Cover E &rarr; E = I &times; R.</li>\n<li>Step 3 &mdash; Plug in: E = 0.5 A &times; 50 &Omega;.</li>\n<li>Step 4 &mdash; Multiply: 0.5 &times; 50 = <strong>25</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Answer: E = 25 volts.</strong></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example</span>\n<p><strong>3 &mdash; find RESISTANCE (R = E &divide; I).</strong> 24 volts pushes 3 amps through a heater element. What is its resistance?</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Step 1 &mdash; Known: E = 24 V, I = 3 A, find R.</li>\n<li>Step 2 &mdash; Cover R &rarr; R = E / I.</li>\n<li>Step 3 &mdash; Plug in: R = 24 V &divide; 3 A.</li>\n<li>Step 4 &mdash; Divide: 24 &divide; 3 = <strong>8</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Answer: R = 8 ohms.</strong></p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example</span>\n<p><strong>4 &mdash; a real \"what changed?\" question.</strong> In a 12-volt circuit, current is 4 amps. If you keep the voltage the same but the resistance <em>doubles</em>, what is the new current?</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Step 1 &mdash; Find the original R: R = E / I = 12 V &divide; 4 A = 3 &Omega;.</li>\n<li>Step 2 &mdash; Double it: new R = 3 &times; 2 = 6 &Omega;.</li>\n<li>Step 3 &mdash; New current: I = E / R = 12 V &divide; 6 &Omega; = 2 A.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Answer: 2 amps.</strong> Doubling resistance cut the current in half &mdash; that's the \"inversely proportional\" part of Ohm's Law in action. <em>(FAA p. 12-17)</em></p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>4. Power &mdash; Watt's Law (Standard 5 continued)</h3>\n<p>Voltage, current, and resistance describe the flow. <strong>Power</strong> describes how much <em>work</em> the electricity does &mdash; how much energy it uses every second (heat, light, motion).</p>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Key terms &amp; numbers</span>\n<p><strong>Watt (W):</strong> the basic unit of power &mdash; the <strong>product of voltage multiplied by current</strong>. One watt is the power produced in a circuit that has one amp of current flowing under a pressure of one volt. <em>(SG p. 6)</em></p>\n<p><strong>1 horsepower = 746 watts.</strong> So a 1-hp electric motor needs 746 watts of electrical energy. <em>(FAA p. 12-21)</em></p>\n</div>\n<p>The main formula (sometimes called Watt's Law) is:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;font-size:18px\"><strong>P = I &times; E</strong><br><em>Power (watts) = Current (amps) &times; Voltage (volts)</em></p>\n<p>Because Ohm's Law lets us swap E for I&times;R, there are <strong>two more forms</strong> of the power formula &mdash; use whichever fits the numbers you have <em>(FAA p. 12-22)</em>:</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Form</th><th>Use it when you know...</th></tr>\n<tr><td>P = I &times; E</td><td>current and voltage</td></tr>\n<tr><td>P = I<sup>2</sup> &times; R</td><td>current and resistance</td></tr>\n<tr><td>P = E<sup>2</sup> &divide; R</td><td>voltage and resistance</td></tr>\n</table>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example</span>\n<p><strong>5 &mdash; power from current &amp; voltage (P = I &times; E).</strong> A device draws 2 amps from a 24-volt bus. How much power does it use?</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Step 1 &mdash; Known: I = 2 A, E = 24 V.</li>\n<li>Step 2 &mdash; Formula: P = I &times; E.</li>\n<li>Step 3 &mdash; Plug in: P = 2 A &times; 24 V.</li>\n<li>Step 4 &mdash; Multiply: 2 &times; 24 = <strong>48</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Answer: P = 48 watts.</strong> (matches FAA p. 12-22 example)</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example</span>\n<p><strong>6 &mdash; power from voltage &amp; resistance (P = E<sup>2</sup> &divide; R).</strong> 24 volts is applied across a 20-ohm resistor. How much power is dissipated?</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Step 1 &mdash; Known: E = 24 V, R = 20 &Omega;.</li>\n<li>Step 2 &mdash; Formula: P = E&sup2; / R.</li>\n<li>Step 3 &mdash; Square the voltage first: 24 &times; 24 = 576.</li>\n<li>Step 4 &mdash; Divide by R: P = 576 &divide; 20 = 28.8.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Answer: P = 28.8 watts.</strong> (matches FAA p. 12-22 example)</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>5. Measuring it all &mdash; the meters (Standard 6)</h3>\n<p>Knowing the numbers is useless if you can't read them off a real circuit. Three meters do the job, and <strong>each one connects to the circuit differently.</strong> Getting the connection wrong can damage the meter or give a false reading &mdash; so this is high-yield.</p>\n<p><strong>The VOLTMETER &mdash; measures volts &mdash; connect in PARALLEL.</strong> The voltmeter is the testing instrument used to measure electrical voltage <em>across</em> components; values are given in volts. <em>(SG p. 15)</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Connect it in PARALLEL</strong> &mdash; touch the two probes <em>across</em> the two points you want the voltage between. <em>(FAA p. 12-71)</em></li>\n<li>A voltmeter has <strong>HIGH resistance</strong> on purpose. If it had low resistance it would \"steal\" current from the circuit and give a wrong reading. <strong>Use a high-resistance voltmeter to avoid loading the circuit.</strong> <em>(FAA p. 12-71)</em></li>\n<li><strong>Power is ON</strong> &mdash; a voltmeter finds a circuit problem <em>with power on the circuit</em>. <em>(SG p. 11)</em></li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Note</span><strong>V</strong>oltmeter = <strong>V</strong>ery high resistance, sits <strong>across</strong> (parallel) like a bridge spanning the gap. Think \"voltage is measured <em>across</em> two points,\" so the meter goes <em>across</em>.</div>\n<p><strong>The AMMETER &mdash; measures amps &mdash; connect in SERIES.</strong> The ammeter is the testing instrument used to measure the amount of current flowing <em>through</em> a load; values are given in amps (some read milliamps/microamps for tiny currents). <em>(SG pp. 11, 14)</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Connect it in SERIES</strong> &mdash; you must break the circuit open and put the ammeter <em>in line</em> so all the current flows <em>through</em> it. <em>(FAA p. 12-69)</em></li>\n<li>An ammeter has <strong>VERY LOW resistance</strong> so it doesn't slow the current it's measuring.</li>\n<li><strong>Power is ON.</strong> <em>(SG p. 11)</em></li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Note</span><strong>Critical safety rule:</strong> NEVER connect an ammeter across a voltage source (like straight across a battery). Its resistance is so low that even a volt or two will drive a huge current through it and destroy the meter. Always wire it in series. <em>(FAA p. 12-69, 12-70)</em> Memory hook: current flows <em>through</em> things, so the <strong>A</strong>mmeter goes <em>in line (series)</em> &mdash; low resistance, like a wide-open gate.</div>\n<p><strong>The OHMMETER &mdash; measures ohms &mdash; POWER OFF.</strong> The ohmmeter is the testing instrument used to measure resistance in a circuit or component; values are given in ohms. <em>(SG p. 14)</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Power must be REMOVED from the circuit</strong> &mdash; an ohmmeter is used to find a circuit problem <em>when power is removed</em>. <em>(SG p. 11)</em></li>\n<li>It has its own <strong>internal battery</strong> that sends a small known current through the part; it reads the resistance from how much comes back. Outside power would ruin the reading and can damage the meter. <em>(FAA p. 12-71)</em></li>\n<li>Reading the scale: leads <strong>open</strong> (not touching) = infinite (&infin;) resistance / open circuit; leads <strong>shorted together</strong> = zero resistance. \"Zero-adjust\" the meter by touching the leads and setting it to 0. <em>(FAA p. 12-71)</em></li>\n<li>It's also a quick way to test the condition of a switch. <em>(SG p. 14)</em></li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Note</span><strong>Ohmmeter = power OFF.</strong> It brings its <em>own</em> battery to the party, so the circuit's power must be dead first.</div>\n<p><strong>The MULTIMETER (VOM / DMM) &mdash; all three in one box.</strong> A multimeter is a multi-function meter that tests current, voltage, <em>or</em> resistance &mdash; a <strong>selector switch</strong> sets it to act as an ammeter, voltmeter, or ohmmeter. It's \"the most versatile electrical measuring instrument used by aircraft technicians.\" Use a multimeter whenever possible. <em>(SG pp. 10, 14)</em> The old analog version is called a <strong>VOM</strong> (Volt-Ohm-Milliammeter). The modern digital version is a <strong>DMM</strong> (Digital MultiMeter). DMMs are easier to read, more accurate, and have higher input resistance (so they load the circuit even less). <em>(FAA p. 12-78)</em></p>\n<p>One more instrument to recognize: the <strong>oscilloscope</strong> displays voltage as a <em>waveform</em> over time &mdash; it measures AC peak-to-peak values, frequency, and phase. You don't read a plain DC number off it; you see the signal's shape. <em>(SG pp. 11, 14)</em></p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Meter</th><th>Measures</th><th>Connect</th><th>Its resistance</th><th>Power state</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Voltmeter</td><td>Volts</td><td>PARALLEL (across)</td><td>HIGH</td><td>ON</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Ammeter</td><td>Amps</td><td>SERIES (in line)</td><td>LOW</td><td>ON</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Ohmmeter</td><td>Ohms</td><td>across the part</td><td>(own battery)</td><td>OFF</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Key terms &amp; numbers</span>\n<table>\n<tr><td><strong>Volt (E)</strong></td><td>Unit of electrical pressure / EMF. Force to push 1 amp through 1 ohm.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Ampere (I)</strong></td><td>Unit of current. 1 amp = 1 coulomb per second.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Ohm (R, &Omega;)</strong></td><td>Unit of resistance. 1 ohm limits current to 1 amp under 1 volt.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Coulomb (C)</strong></td><td>Unit of quantity = 6.28 &times; 10<sup>18</sup> electrons (6.28 billion-billion).</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Watt (W)</strong></td><td>Unit of power = volts &times; amps. 1 watt = 1 amp under 1 volt.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Ohm's Law</strong></td><td>E = I &times; R (also I = E/R, R = E/I). 1 V drives 1 A through 1 &Omega;.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Power forms</strong></td><td>P = I&times;E = I&sup2;&times;R = E&sup2;/R.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>1 horsepower</strong></td><td>= 746 watts.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Electron</strong></td><td>Negative particle, orbits nucleus, carries electricity.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Proton / Neutron</strong></td><td>In nucleus (+ / neutral). NOT involved in conduction.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Conductor</strong></td><td>Many free electrons (Cu, Ag, Au, Al). Carries current easily.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Insulator</strong></td><td>Almost no free electrons (glass, rubber, plastic). Blocks current.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>FAA current dir.</strong></td><td>Electron flow: negative (&minus;) to positive (+).</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Voltmeter</strong></td><td>PARALLEL, high resistance, power ON.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Ammeter</strong></td><td>SERIES, low resistance, power ON. Never across a source.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Ohmmeter</strong></td><td>Measures resistance, power OFF (own battery).</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Multimeter (VOM/DMM)</strong></td><td>Volt + ohm + amp in one, set by a selector switch.</td></tr>\n</table>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Check yourself</h3>\n<div class=\"selfq\">Q1. Which particle actually carries electricity through a wire?<span class=\"a\">Answer: the electron (negatively charged, orbits the nucleus). Protons and neutrons stay in the nucleus and do not conduct. (SG pp. 5&ndash;6)</span></div>\n<div class=\"selfq\">Q2. A 24-volt circuit has 6 ohms of resistance. How much current flows?<span class=\"a\">Answer: 4 amps. I = E / R = 24 &divide; 6 = 4 A. (SG p. 6; FAA p. 12-17)</span></div>\n<div class=\"selfq\">Q3. You need to read how many amps are flowing through a fuel-pump motor. How do you connect the meter?<span class=\"a\">Answer: an ammeter, in SERIES (break the circuit and put it in line so current flows through it). Never connect it across a voltage source. (SG p. 11; FAA p. 12-69)</span></div>\n<div class=\"selfq\">Q4. A 12-volt lamp draws 3 amps. How many watts does it use?<span class=\"a\">Answer: 36 watts. P = I &times; E = 3 &times; 12 = 36 W. (SG p. 6; FAA p. 12-22)</span></div>\n<div class=\"selfq\">Q5. Before measuring a resistor with an ohmmeter, what must you do to the circuit?<span class=\"a\">Answer: turn the power OFF / remove power. The ohmmeter supplies its own current from an internal battery; outside power gives a false reading and can damage it. (SG p. 11; FAA p. 12-71)</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">What's next</span><strong>Module 2: Circuits &amp; Troubleshooting (Standard 4).</strong> Now that you know the big three and Ohm's Law, we wire components together: <strong>series</strong> circuits (one path, current the same everywhere) and <strong>parallel</strong> circuits (multiple paths, current splits), plus Kirchhoff's Laws, voltage drops, and how to chase down <strong>opens</strong> and <strong>shorts</strong> &mdash; the two faults you'll meet most on the flight line. After this lesson, take the Module 1 retention quiz on your quiz link and aim for &ge;73% before we move on.</div>\n<p><em>Sources: NCATT/ASTM AET Study Guide, Standards 1, 5, 6 (pp. 4&ndash;15). FAA-H-8083-30B (General), Chapter 12, Fundamentals of Electricity &amp; Electronics (pp. 12-1 through 12-78). Citations shown inline throughout.</em></p>", "quiz": [{"q": "Which subatomic particle actually carries electricity through a conductor?", "options": ["The proton", "The neutron", "The electron", "The nucleus"], "correct": 2, "short": "The electron", "expl": "Electrons are the negatively-charged particles that orbit the nucleus and are involved in the conduction of electricity. Protons (+) and neutrons (neutral) stay in the nucleus and do NOT conduct.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 5-6; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-1", "topic": "Std 1 · Electron theory"}, {"q": "A proton carries what charge?", "options": ["Negative (−)", "Positive (+)", "Neutral / no charge", "It alternates"], "correct": 1, "short": "Positive (+)", "expl": "Protons are positively-charged particles in the nucleus. They are NOT involved in conducting electricity.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 6; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-1", "topic": "Std 1 · Electron theory"}, {"q": "A neutron carries what charge?", "options": ["Positive (+)", "Negative (−)", "Neutral / no charge", "Double negative"], "correct": 2, "short": "Neutral (no charge)", "expl": "Neutrons are neutral subatomic particles inside the nucleus and are not involved in conduction.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 5; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-1", "topic": "Std 1 · Electron theory"}, {"q": "What is a 'free electron'?", "options": ["An electron with no charge", "A loosely-bound outer-shell electron that can move from atom to atom", "An electron locked tightly in the nucleus", "A proton that has lost its charge"], "correct": 1, "short": "A loosely-bound outer electron that can travel atom-to-atom", "expl": "Outermost electrons are loosely held and easily dislodged. Once freed, they travel atom to atom — and that flow IS electric current.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-2, 12-16", "topic": "Std 1 · Electron theory"}, {"q": "Whether a material conducts electricity depends mainly on its number of:", "options": ["Protons", "Neutrons", "Free electrons", "Nuclei"], "correct": 2, "short": "Free electrons", "expl": "More free electrons available = more current the material can conduct. This is what separates conductors, insulators, and semiconductors.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-2", "topic": "Std 1 · Conductors/Insulators"}, {"q": "Which group lists good electrical CONDUCTORS?", "options": ["Glass, rubber, plastic", "Silver, copper, gold, aluminum", "Ceramic, quartz, wood", "Silicon, germanium, air"], "correct": 1, "short": "Silver, copper, gold, aluminum", "expl": "Conductors have many free electrons. Copper and silver each have one electron in their outer orbit, giving billions of free electrons.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 4; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-3", "topic": "Std 1 · Conductors/Insulators"}, {"q": "Which material is an INSULATOR?", "options": ["Copper", "Silver", "Glass", "Aluminum"], "correct": 2, "short": "Glass", "expl": "An insulator is used to prevent the passage of electricity. Insulators (glass, ceramic, plastic, rubber) make almost no free electrons.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 5; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-3", "topic": "Std 1 · Conductors/Insulators"}, {"q": "Silicon and germanium, in their pure state, are best described as:", "options": ["Excellent conductors", "Perfect insulators", "Semiconductors", "Superconductors"], "correct": 2, "short": "Semiconductors", "expl": "Semiconductors fall between conductors and insulators and can be made to act like either. Silicon and germanium are the most common, used in transistors and chips.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-4", "topic": "Std 1 · Conductors/Insulators"}, {"q": "Static electricity is best described as:", "options": ["Electrons flowing steadily in one direction", "An electrical charge built up on a non-conductive surface by friction", "Alternating current at 400 Hz", "The current inside a battery"], "correct": 1, "short": "A charge built up on a non-conductive surface by friction", "expl": "Static electricity is a buildup of charge (electrons at rest) from rubbing non-conductive materials. There is no current flow, and it serves no useful purpose.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 6; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-4", "topic": "Std 1 · DC Basic Terms"}, {"q": "In the water-pipe analogy, VOLTAGE is like the:", "options": ["Amount of water flowing", "Pressure pushing the water", "Friction of the pipe", "Size of the tank"], "correct": 1, "short": "Pressure pushing the water", "expl": "Voltage = electrical pressure (EMF) that pushes electrons. Current = amount flowing; resistance = friction opposing flow.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 6; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-16", "topic": "Std 1 · DC Basic Terms"}, {"q": "The VOLT is the basic unit of what?", "options": ["Current", "Resistance", "Electrical pressure (EMF)", "Power"], "correct": 2, "short": "Electrical pressure (EMF)", "expl": "A volt is the basic unit of electrical pressure — the amount of force required to cause one amp to flow through one ohm of resistance.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 6", "topic": "Std 1 · DC Basic Terms"}, {"q": "In math problems, voltage is represented by which letter?", "options": ["I", "R", "E", "V only"], "correct": 2, "short": "E", "expl": "Voltage (EMF) is expressed by the letter E in formulas like E = I × R.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 5", "topic": "Std 5 · Symbols"}, {"q": "The AMPERE is the unit used to express:", "options": ["Resistance", "The flow of electrons (current)", "Electrical pressure", "Power"], "correct": 1, "short": "The flow of electrons (current)", "expl": "The ampere measures current. One ampere = a flow of one coulomb passing a point per second. In math, current is the letter I.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 4; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-17", "topic": "Std 1 · DC Basic Terms"}, {"q": "One ampere equals a flow of one coulomb past a point in:", "options": ["One minute", "One hour", "One second", "One millisecond"], "correct": 2, "short": "One second", "expl": "1 amp = 1 coulomb per second. Current I = Q (charge in coulombs) ÷ t (time in seconds).", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 4; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-17", "topic": "Std 1 · DC Basic Terms"}, {"q": "One coulomb is equal to how many electrons?", "options": ["6.28 million", "6.28 billion", "6.28 billion-billion (6.28 × 10¹⁸)", "186,000"], "correct": 2, "short": "6.28 × 10¹⁸ (6.28 billion-billion)", "expl": "The coulomb is the basic unit of electrical quantity: 6.28 × 10¹⁸ electrons.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 4; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-17", "topic": "Std 1 · DC Basic Terms"}, {"q": "The OHM (Ω) is the unit of:", "options": ["Current", "Opposition to current flow (resistance)", "Pressure", "Power"], "correct": 1, "short": "Resistance (opposition to current)", "expl": "The ohm is the unit of electrical opposition to current. A circuit has one ohm when it limits current to one amp under a pressure of one volt.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 6; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-18", "topic": "Std 1 · DC Basic Terms"}, {"q": "'A circuit has one ohm of resistance when it limits the flow of current to ___ under a pressure of ___.'", "options": ["one volt … one amp", "one amp … one volt", "one watt … one amp", "one coulomb … one second"], "correct": 1, "short": "one amp … one volt", "expl": "Verbatim definition: one ohm limits current to one amp under a voltage pressure of one volt.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 6; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-18", "topic": "Std 1 · DC Basic Terms"}, {"q": "Which four factors affect a conductor's resistance?", "options": ["Color, weight, shape, age", "Material, length, cross-sectional area, temperature", "Voltage, current, power, frequency", "Brand, coating, insulation, gauge color"], "correct": 1, "short": "Material, length, area, temperature", "expl": "A conductor's resistance depends on its material, length, cross-sectional area, and temperature.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 4; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-18", "topic": "Std 1 · DC Basic Terms"}, {"q": "If you DOUBLE the length of a wire (same everything else), its resistance:", "options": ["Stays the same", "Doubles", "Is cut in half", "Becomes zero"], "correct": 1, "short": "Doubles", "expl": "Resistance is directly proportional to length. Twice the length = twice the resistance, which halves the current.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-18, 12-19", "topic": "Std 1 · Resistance"}, {"q": "The FAA officially defines current flow using which theory/direction?", "options": ["Conventional flow: positive to negative", "Electron flow: negative to positive", "Conventional flow: negative to positive", "Alternating flow"], "correct": 1, "short": "Electron flow: negative (−) to positive (+)", "expl": "Electron flow is what actually happens; the FAA officially defines current using electron theory, negative to positive.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-14", "topic": "Std 1 · Current direction"}, {"q": "Ohm's Law states current is ___ to voltage and ___ to resistance.", "options": ["inversely proportional … directly proportional", "directly proportional … inversely proportional", "directly proportional … directly proportional", "equal … opposite"], "correct": 1, "short": "directly proportional to V, inversely proportional to R", "expl": "Ohm's Law: current is directly proportional to circuit voltage and inversely proportional to circuit resistance.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 6", "topic": "Std 5 · Ohm's Law"}, {"q": "Which is the correct Ohm's Law formula to solve for CURRENT?", "options": ["I = E × R", "I = E ÷ R", "I = R ÷ E", "I = E + R"], "correct": 1, "short": "I = E ÷ R", "expl": "From the triangle (E on top, I and R below): cover I and you get E over R, so I = E / R.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-17, 12-18", "topic": "Std 5 · Ohm's Law"}, {"q": "A 28-volt circuit has 14 ohms of resistance. How much current flows?", "options": ["0.5 A", "2 A", "14 A", "42 A"], "correct": 1, "short": "2 amps", "expl": "I = E ÷ R = 28 V ÷ 14 Ω = 2 A.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 6; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-17", "topic": "Std 5 · Ohm's Law calc"}, {"q": "A 50-ohm relay coil carries 0.5 amp. What voltage is across it?", "options": ["10 V", "25 V", "100 V", "0.01 V"], "correct": 1, "short": "25 volts", "expl": "E = I × R = 0.5 A × 50 Ω = 25 V.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-18", "topic": "Std 5 · Ohm's Law calc"}, {"q": "24 volts pushes 3 amps through a heater. What is its resistance?", "options": ["3 Ω", "8 Ω", "27 Ω", "72 Ω"], "correct": 1, "short": "8 ohms", "expl": "R = E ÷ I = 24 V ÷ 3 A = 8 Ω.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-18", "topic": "Std 5 · Ohm's Law calc"}, {"q": "In a circuit, if voltage stays the same but resistance DOUBLES, the current:", "options": ["Doubles", "Stays the same", "Is cut in half", "Goes to zero"], "correct": 2, "short": "Is cut in half", "expl": "Current is inversely proportional to resistance. Double R → half the current (e.g., 12V/3Ω=4A becomes 12V/6Ω=2A).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-17", "topic": "Std 5 · Ohm's Law"}, {"q": "The WATT is the basic unit of:", "options": ["Current", "Power", "Resistance", "Charge"], "correct": 1, "short": "Power", "expl": "The watt is the basic unit of power — the product of voltage times current. One watt = one amp under one volt.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 6", "topic": "Std 5 · Power"}, {"q": "Which is a correct power (Watt's Law) formula?", "options": ["P = I ÷ E", "P = I × E", "P = R ÷ E", "P = E − I"], "correct": 1, "short": "P = I × E", "expl": "Power = current × voltage. The other valid forms are P = I²R and P = E²/R.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 6; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-22", "topic": "Std 5 · Power"}, {"q": "A device draws 2 amps from a 24-volt bus. How much power does it use?", "options": ["12 W", "26 W", "48 W", "96 W"], "correct": 2, "short": "48 watts", "expl": "P = I × E = 2 A × 24 V = 48 W.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-22", "topic": "Std 5 · Power calc"}, {"q": "24 volts is applied across a 20-ohm resistor. Power dissipated? (P = E² / R)", "options": ["1.2 W", "28.8 W", "480 W", "576 W"], "correct": 1, "short": "28.8 watts", "expl": "P = E² / R = (24 × 24) / 20 = 576 / 20 = 28.8 W.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-22", "topic": "Std 5 · Power calc"}, {"q": "One horsepower equals how many watts?", "options": ["100 W", "550 W", "746 W", "1,000 W"], "correct": 2, "short": "746 watts", "expl": "1 horsepower = 746 watts. A 1-hp electric motor needs 746 W of electrical energy.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-21", "topic": "Std 5 · Power"}, {"q": "To measure VOLTAGE across a component, the voltmeter is connected:", "options": ["In series (in line)", "In parallel (across the component)", "After removing power", "Only at the battery"], "correct": 1, "short": "In parallel (across the component)", "expl": "Voltmeters are connected in parallel — across the two points whose voltage you want. They have HIGH resistance so they don't load the circuit. Power is ON.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 15; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-71", "topic": "Std 6 · Voltmeter"}, {"q": "A voltmeter should have a HIGH internal resistance because:", "options": ["It makes the needle move faster", "Low resistance would draw off current and give a wrong reading (load the circuit)", "It protects the battery", "It is required to read AC"], "correct": 1, "short": "So it doesn't load the circuit / steal current", "expl": "A low-resistance voltmeter shunts current and lowers the circuit's effective resistance, changing the reading. Use a high-resistance voltmeter.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-71", "topic": "Std 6 · Voltmeter"}, {"q": "To measure CURRENT through a load, an ammeter is connected:", "options": ["In parallel (across)", "In series (in line)", "Across the battery", "With power off"], "correct": 1, "short": "In series (in line)", "expl": "The ammeter must be in series so all the current flows THROUGH it. It has very low resistance. Power is ON.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 14; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-69", "topic": "Std 6 · Ammeter"}, {"q": "Why must you NEVER connect an ammeter directly across a battery or voltage source?", "options": ["It only reads AC there", "Its resistance is so low that huge current flows and destroys the meter", "It will reverse the battery", "It will read zero"], "correct": 1, "short": "Its low resistance lets huge current flow and ruins the meter", "expl": "An ammeter's resistance is extremely low. Across a source, even a volt or two drives very high current through it, damaging the meter. Always wire it in series.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-69, 12-70", "topic": "Std 6 · Ammeter safety"}, {"q": "An OHMMETER must be used with the circuit's power:", "options": ["ON, at full voltage", "ON, but reduced", "OFF / removed", "Reversed"], "correct": 2, "short": "OFF / power removed", "expl": "An ohmmeter has its own internal battery and is used when power is removed from the circuit. Outside power gives false readings and can damage it.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 11; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-71", "topic": "Std 6 · Ohmmeter"}, {"q": "On an analog ohmmeter, leads held OPEN (not touching) read:", "options": ["Zero ohms", "Infinite (∞) resistance / open circuit", "1 ohm", "The battery voltage"], "correct": 1, "short": "Infinite (∞) / open circuit", "expl": "Open leads = full-scale = infinite resistance (open). Shorting the leads together reads zero ohms (and is used to zero-adjust the meter).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-71", "topic": "Std 6 · Ohmmeter"}, {"q": "A MULTIMETER measures voltage, current, and resistance by using a:", "options": ["Bigger battery", "Selector switch that sets it as voltmeter, ammeter, or ohmmeter", "Second technician", "Separate oscilloscope"], "correct": 1, "short": "Selector switch (volt / amp / ohm)", "expl": "A multimeter is a multi-function meter; a selector switch sets it to act as an ammeter, voltmeter, or ohmmeter. It's the most versatile tool the AET uses.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 10, 14", "topic": "Std 6 · Multimeter"}, {"q": "The abbreviation 'VOM' (an analog multimeter) stands for:", "options": ["Voltage Over Meter", "Volt-Ohm-Milliammeter", "Variable Output Module", "Voltmeter-Only Mode"], "correct": 1, "short": "Volt-Ohm-Milliammeter", "expl": "Analog multimeters are called VOMs (Volt-Ohm-Milliammeter). Digital ones are DMMs, which read easier and load the circuit less.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-78", "topic": "Std 6 · Multimeter"}, {"q": "Which instrument displays a voltage WAVEFORM (shape over time), not just a DC number?", "options": ["Voltmeter", "Ammeter", "Ohmmeter", "Oscilloscope"], "correct": 3, "short": "Oscilloscope", "expl": "An oscilloscope displays the waveform of electrical signals — AC peak-to-peak values, frequency, and phase relationships.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 11, 14", "topic": "Std 6 · Oscilloscope"}, {"q": "An aircraft storage battery is generally rated at what voltage?", "options": ["1.5 or 3 volts", "12 or 24 volts", "120 or 240 volts", "400 volts"], "correct": 1, "short": "12 or 24 volts", "expl": "Aircraft storage batteries are generally rated at 12 or 24 volts, providing the EMF that pushes current through the circuit.", "cite": "AET Study Guide p. 4; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-16", "topic": "Std 1 · Battery"}], "drill": [{"label": "Volt (E)", "text": "Unit of electrical pressure. The force to push 1 amp through 1 ohm."}, {"label": "Ampere (I)", "text": "Unit of current. 1 amp = 1 coulomb passing a point per second."}, {"label": "Ohm (R, Ω)", "text": "Unit of resistance. 1 ohm limits current to 1 amp under 1 volt."}, {"label": "Coulomb (C)", "text": "Unit of quantity = 6.28 × 10¹⁸ electrons (6.28 billion-billion)."}, {"label": "Watt (W)", "text": "Unit of power = volts × amps. 1 watt = 1 amp under 1 volt."}, {"label": "Ohm's Law", "text": "E = I × R  (so I = E/R and R = E/I). 1 V drives 1 A through 1 Ω."}, {"label": "Power forms", "text": "P = I × E  =  I² × R  =  E² / R."}, {"label": "1 horsepower", "text": "= 746 watts."}, {"label": "Electron carries current", "text": "Negative particle, orbits nucleus. Protons/neutrons do NOT conduct."}, {"label": "Conductors vs insulators", "text": "Conductors = many free electrons (Cu, Ag, Au, Al). Insulators = almost none (glass, rubber, plastic)."}, {"label": "FAA current direction", "text": "Electron flow: negative (−) to positive (+)."}, {"label": "Meter rules", "text": "Voltmeter = PARALLEL, high R, power ON. Ammeter = SERIES, low R, power ON. Ohmmeter = power OFF."}]}, {"n": 2, "title": "Circuits & Troubleshooting", "standards": "4", "lesson": "<h3>Why this matters on a real aircraft</h3><p>In Module 1 you learned the Big Three &mdash; <strong>voltage, current, resistance</strong> &mdash; for one resistor on a wire. But a real airplane never has just one load on a wire. The bus that feeds a panel might run the radio, the landing light, and a fuel pump all at once. To find a fault, you have to know <strong>how the parts are wired together</strong> (in a line, or side-by-side) and <strong>what a healthy circuit's numbers should be</strong>, so when your meter reads something wrong you know which way to chase it. That is Standard 4 &mdash; Basic Circuit Troubleshooting. <span class=\"cite\">(NCATT AET Study Guide p. 10)</span></p><p>We build this brick by brick, just like before. Two wiring shapes (series and parallel), two laws that govern them (Kirchhoff), two failures (open and short), and one method to hunt the fault. Then a quick intro to AC so the word isn't a stranger later.</p><div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">The two shapes, in one sentence</span><strong>Series</strong> = one single path, parts in a line (current has no choice). <strong>Parallel</strong> = two or more paths, parts side-by-side (current splits up). Almost every aircraft circuit is a mix of both, called <strong>series-parallel</strong>. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-40, 12-42)</span></div><h3>1. Series circuits &mdash; one path for the current</h3><p>A <strong>series circuit</strong> is wired so there is exactly <strong>one path</strong> for current to follow. The electrons leave the source, go through the first part, then the second, then the third, and back &mdash; like cars on a one-lane road with no exits. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-35)</span></p><p>Three rules fall out of having one path. Memorize these &mdash; they are the heart of series:</p><ul><li><strong>Current is the same everywhere.</strong> One lane, so the same number of cars pass every point. I&nbsp;=&nbsp;I&#8321;&nbsp;=&nbsp;I&#8322;&nbsp;=&nbsp;I&#8323;.</li><li><strong>Voltage drops add up to the source.</strong> Each resistor &ldquo;uses up&rdquo; a share of the push. Add the shares and you get the source voltage back. E&#8347;&nbsp;=&nbsp;E&#8321;&nbsp;+&nbsp;E&#8322;&nbsp;+&nbsp;E&#8323;. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-36)</span></li><li><strong>Total resistance is the sum.</strong> R&#8348;&nbsp;=&nbsp;R&#8321;&nbsp;+&nbsp;R&#8322;&nbsp;+&nbsp;R&#8323;. Adding resistors in series always makes the total <strong>bigger</strong>.</li></ul><div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example &mdash; series</span>Three resistors in series: R&#8321;&nbsp;=&nbsp;1&nbsp;k&#937;, R&#8322;&nbsp;=&nbsp;3&nbsp;k&#937;, R&#8323;&nbsp;=&nbsp;5&nbsp;k&#937;, with a total current of 1&nbsp;mA flowing.<br><strong>Step 1 &mdash; total resistance (add):</strong> R&#8348;&nbsp;=&nbsp;1&nbsp;k&#937;&nbsp;+&nbsp;3&nbsp;k&#937;&nbsp;+&nbsp;5&nbsp;k&#937;&nbsp;=&nbsp;<strong>9&nbsp;k&#937;</strong>.<br><strong>Step 2 &mdash; source voltage</strong> (Ohm's law, E&nbsp;=&nbsp;I&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;R&#8348;): E&#8347;&nbsp;=&nbsp;1&nbsp;mA&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;9&nbsp;k&#937;&nbsp;=&nbsp;<strong>9&nbsp;V</strong>.<br><strong>Step 3 &mdash; check by drops:</strong> the 1&nbsp;k&#937; drops 1&nbsp;V, the 3&nbsp;k&#937; drops 3&nbsp;V, the 5&nbsp;k&#937; drops 5&nbsp;V. 1&nbsp;+&nbsp;3&nbsp;+&nbsp;5&nbsp;=&nbsp;<strong>9&nbsp;V</strong>. It matches the source &mdash; the math is right. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-36)</span></div><h3>The voltage divider</h3><p>Because series resistors split the source voltage into shares, a string of series resistors is also a <strong>voltage divider</strong> &mdash; a device that lets you pull <strong>more than one voltage</strong> out of a single power source by tapping between the resistors. The bigger a resistor's share of the total resistance, the bigger its share of the voltage. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-37)</span></p><div class=\"selfq\">A 12&nbsp;V source feeds two series resistors, R&#8321;&nbsp;=&nbsp;100&nbsp;&#937; and R&#8322;&nbsp;=&nbsp;300&nbsp;&#937;. What is the voltage drop across R&#8322;?<span class=\"a\">Answer: R&#8348;&nbsp;=&nbsp;400&nbsp;&#937;, so I&nbsp;=&nbsp;12&nbsp;V&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;400&nbsp;&#937;&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.03&nbsp;A. E&#8322;&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.03&nbsp;A&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;300&nbsp;&#937;&nbsp;=&nbsp;9&nbsp;V. (R&#8322; is 3/4 of the resistance, so it gets 3/4 of the 12&nbsp;V.)</span></div><h3>2. Parallel circuits &mdash; more than one path</h3><p>A <strong>parallel circuit</strong> is wired so two or more loads are connected <strong>across the same voltage source</strong>, giving the current <strong>more than one path</strong>. Each separate path is called a <strong>branch</strong> &mdash; like a wide river splitting around an island and rejoining. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-40)</span></p><p>Parallel rules are almost the mirror image of series &mdash; this is exactly where test questions try to trick you:</p><ul><li><strong>Voltage is the same across every branch.</strong> Every branch sits across the same two source terminals, so each gets the full source voltage. E&nbsp;=&nbsp;E&#8321;&nbsp;=&nbsp;E&#8322;&nbsp;=&nbsp;E&#8323;.</li><li><strong>Branch currents add up to the total.</strong> The river splits, then rejoins. I&#8348;&nbsp;=&nbsp;I&#8321;&nbsp;+&nbsp;I&#8322;&nbsp;+&nbsp;I&#8323;. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-41)</span></li><li><strong>Total resistance is LESS than the smallest branch.</strong> Adding a path is adding another road &mdash; it only makes it <em>easier</em> for current to flow, so total resistance goes <strong>down</strong>. This is the opposite of series, and the most-tested fact in this module.</li></ul><div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Parallel resistance formulas</span><strong>Two resistors &mdash; product-over-sum:</strong> R&#8348;&nbsp;=&nbsp;(R&#8321;&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;R&#8322;)&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;(R&#8321;&nbsp;+&nbsp;R&#8322;).<br><strong>Any number &mdash; reciprocal formula:</strong> 1/R&#8348;&nbsp;=&nbsp;1/R&#8321;&nbsp;+&nbsp;1/R&#8322;&nbsp;+&nbsp;1/R&#8323;&nbsp;&hellip; (then flip the answer).<br><strong>Equal resistors shortcut:</strong> R&#8348;&nbsp;=&nbsp;value&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;number of branches (two 100&nbsp;&#937; in parallel = 50&nbsp;&#937;). <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-41)</span></div><div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example &mdash; parallel (product-over-sum)</span>R&#8321;&nbsp;=&nbsp;500&nbsp;&#937; in parallel with R&#8322;&nbsp;=&nbsp;400&nbsp;&#937;.<br><strong>Product:</strong> 500&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;400&nbsp;=&nbsp;200,000.<br><strong>Sum:</strong> 500&nbsp;+&nbsp;400&nbsp;=&nbsp;900.<br><strong>Divide:</strong> 200,000&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;900&nbsp;=&nbsp;<strong>222.2&nbsp;&#937;</strong>.<br>Notice the answer (222&nbsp;&#937;) is smaller than the smaller resistor (400&nbsp;&#937;) &mdash; exactly as the rule promised. If it came out bigger, you'd know you made a mistake. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-41)</span></div><div class=\"selfq\">Two 60&nbsp;&#937; resistors are wired in parallel. Without a calculator, what is the total resistance?<span class=\"a\">Answer: 30&nbsp;&#937;. Equal resistors in parallel = value &divide; number of branches = 60&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;2 = 30&nbsp;&#937;, which is less than the smallest branch (60&nbsp;&#937;).</span></div><h3>3. Series-parallel circuits</h3><p>Most circuits a technician sees are <strong>neither pure series nor pure parallel</strong> &mdash; they are groups of resistors, some in series and some in parallel, mixed together. The trick is simple: <strong>solve the parallel groups first, replace each group with its single equivalent resistor, then the whole thing collapses into a plain series circuit you already know how to do.</strong> <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-42)</span></p><div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example &mdash; series-parallel</span>R&#8321;&nbsp;=&nbsp;1&nbsp;k&#937; in series with a parallel pair (R&#8322;&nbsp;=&nbsp;2&nbsp;k&#937; &#8741; R&#8323;&nbsp;=&nbsp;3&nbsp;k&#937;), source E&#8347;&nbsp;=&nbsp;24&nbsp;V.<br><strong>Step 1 &mdash; collapse the parallel pair</strong> (product-over-sum): R&#8322;&#8323;&nbsp;=&nbsp;(2k&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;3k)&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;(2k&nbsp;+&nbsp;3k)&nbsp;=&nbsp;6,000k&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;5k&nbsp;=&nbsp;<strong>1.2&nbsp;k&#937;</strong>.<br><strong>Step 2 &mdash; now it's series:</strong> R&#8348;&nbsp;=&nbsp;1&nbsp;k&#937;&nbsp;+&nbsp;1.2&nbsp;k&#937;&nbsp;=&nbsp;<strong>2.2&nbsp;k&#937;</strong>.<br><strong>Step 3 &mdash; total current:</strong> I&#8348;&nbsp;=&nbsp;24&nbsp;V&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;2.2&nbsp;k&#937;&nbsp;=&nbsp;<strong>10.9&nbsp;mA</strong>. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-43)</span></div><h3>4. Kirchhoff's two laws</h3><p>Gustav Kirchhoff gave us two bookkeeping rules that are really just &ldquo;nothing gets lost.&rdquo; They let you find a missing voltage or current when Ohm's law alone isn't enough.</p><p><strong>Kirchhoff's Voltage Law (KVL):</strong> going all the way around any closed loop, the source voltage minus all the voltage drops equals <strong>zero</strong> &mdash; the drops always add up to the source. Plain-English: every bit of push the battery gives is used up by the loads by the time you get back to the battery. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-37)</span></p><div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example &mdash; Kirchhoff's Voltage Law</span>A 100&nbsp;V source feeds four series resistors. Three drops are known: E&#8321;&nbsp;=&nbsp;2&nbsp;V, E&#8322;&nbsp;=&nbsp;10&nbsp;V, E&#8323;&nbsp;=&nbsp;20&nbsp;V. Find E&#8324;.<br>KVL: E&#8347;&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;E&#8321;&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;E&#8322;&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;E&#8323;&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;E&#8324;&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.<br>100&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;2&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;10&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;20&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;E&#8324;&nbsp;=&nbsp;0&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp;68&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;E&#8324;&nbsp;=&nbsp;0&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp;<strong>E&#8324;&nbsp;=&nbsp;68&nbsp;V</strong>. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-37)</span></div><p><strong>Kirchhoff's Current Law (KCL):</strong> the current flowing <strong>into</strong> a junction (node) equals the current flowing <strong>out</strong> of it. A junction is any point where two or more paths meet &mdash; nothing piles up there. For the branches of a parallel circuit: I&#8348;&nbsp;=&nbsp;I&#8321;&nbsp;+&nbsp;I&#8322;&nbsp;+&nbsp;I&#8323;. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-41)</span></p><div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example &mdash; Kirchhoff's Current Law</span>A node has 75&nbsp;mA flowing in (I&#8348;). Two branches leaving carry I&#8321;&nbsp;=&nbsp;30&nbsp;mA and I&#8323;&nbsp;=&nbsp;20&nbsp;mA. Find the third branch I&#8322;.<br>In&nbsp;=&nbsp;Out: 75&nbsp;mA&nbsp;=&nbsp;30&nbsp;mA&nbsp;+&nbsp;I&#8322;&nbsp;+&nbsp;20&nbsp;mA&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp;I&#8322;&nbsp;=&nbsp;75&nbsp;&minus;&nbsp;50&nbsp;=&nbsp;<strong>25&nbsp;mA</strong>. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-42)</span></div><div class=\"selfq\">In a series circuit a 24&nbsp;V source has two resistors. The first drops 9&nbsp;V. By Kirchhoff's Voltage Law, what does the second drop?<span class=\"a\">Answer: 15&nbsp;V. The drops must add to the 24&nbsp;V source, so 24 &minus; 9 = 15&nbsp;V.</span></div><h3>5. Open vs. short &mdash; the two basic faults</h3><p>Almost every electrical failure is one of two things. Learn the symptoms of each cold &mdash; this is the core of troubleshooting.</p><p><strong>OPEN circuit:</strong> a <strong>break</strong> in the path &mdash; an incomplete path for current to flow. A broken wire, a blown fuse, a burned-open resistor, a corroded connector. <strong>No current flows</strong> (or none in that branch). An open resistor or fuse can fail <em>without any visible sign of damage</em>. <span class=\"cite\">(NCATT AET Study Guide p. 16; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-28)</span></p><p><strong>SHORT circuit:</strong> an <strong>unwanted low-resistance path</strong> that lets current flow across a part that should have acted as an insulator &mdash; current takes a shortcut and skips the load. A short causes <strong>excessive current</strong>, which makes heat fast and is what blows fuses and pops breakers. Shorts often come from foreign material (a dropped washer, swarf, frayed insulation touching the airframe) or from traces too close together on a board. <span class=\"cite\">(NCATT AET Study Guide p. 16; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-27)</span></p><table><tr><th>Fault</th><th>What it is</th><th>Current</th><th>Meter clue</th></tr><tr><td><strong>OPEN</strong></td><td>Break in the path</td><td>Zero (no flow)</td><td>Ohmmeter reads infinite &#937;; voltmeter reads full source voltage <em>across the break</em></td></tr><tr><td><strong>SHORT</strong></td><td>Unwanted low-resistance shortcut</td><td>Too high (excess)</td><td>Ohmmeter reads near 0&nbsp;&#937;; voltage drop across the shorted part is near 0&nbsp;V; blows the fuse/breaker</td></tr></table><div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">The meter-clue you must not mix up</span>Across an <strong>OPEN</strong>, a voltmeter reads the <strong>full source voltage</strong> (all the push piles up at the one break because no current flows to drop it elsewhere). Across a <strong>SHORT</strong>, the voltmeter reads about <strong>0&nbsp;V</strong> (no resistance, so no voltage drop). An ohmmeter (power OFF) reads <strong>infinite</strong> for an open and <strong>near zero</strong> for a short. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-28, 12-45)</span></div><h3>6. The troubleshooting method</h3><p>Standard 4 wants a <strong>step-by-step, logical hunt</strong>, not random part-swapping. The NCATT process: <span class=\"cite\">(NCATT AET Study Guide p. 11)</span></p><ul><li><strong>Isolate the problem first.</strong> Ask questions: Is the equipment being operated properly? Is the fault constant or intermittent? Worse during taxi, takeoff, cruise, or landing? Does weather affect it? Is the software loaded right?</li><li><strong>Check for the obvious.</strong> Loose connections, broken/bent/frayed wiring, bad bonds, cracked or punctured parts, dead indicator lights &mdash; eyeball it before you reach for a meter.</li><li><strong>Split-half search.</strong> Measure at the middle of the suspect run, decide which half holds the fault, then split that half again. Each measurement throws away half the circuit &mdash; you corner the fault in a few moves instead of testing every point.</li><li><strong>Use the right meter.</strong> See below.</li></ul><div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Which meter, and when</span><strong>Voltmeter</strong> &mdash; power <strong>ON</strong>; finds a problem with the circuit live. Good first move: check the input voltage is even present. <strong>Ammeter</strong> &mdash; power <strong>ON</strong>; reads how much current is actually flowing (micro-/milliammeters for tiny currents). <strong>Ohmmeter</strong> &mdash; power <strong>OFF</strong>; reads resistance and runs <strong>continuity checks</strong> (is there a complete path between two points?). A <strong>multimeter</strong> is all three in one box &mdash; the most versatile instrument the technician owns. <span class=\"cite\">(NCATT AET Study Guide p. 10&ndash;11)</span></div><div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Continuity check</span>A <strong>continuity check</strong> tests whether a complete electrical path exists between two points (usually with the ohmmeter, power off). Good continuity = near 0&nbsp;&#937; (a beep on most meters). No continuity = infinite &#937; = an <strong>OPEN</strong>. Test at <strong>each terminal</strong> along the run to walk in on exactly where the break is. <span class=\"cite\">(NCATT AET Study Guide p. 11)</span></div><div class=\"selfq\">A landing light is dead. You put a voltmeter across the suspected broken wire (power on) and read the full 28&nbsp;V of the bus. Open or short?<span class=\"a\">Answer: OPEN. Full source voltage across a gap, with no current flowing, is the signature of an open. A short would read near 0&nbsp;V and would have blown the breaker.</span></div><h3>7. AC basics &mdash; a first look</h3><p>So far everything has been <strong>DC &mdash; direct current</strong>, which flows constantly in one direction with constant polarity. <strong>AC &mdash; alternating current</strong> changes direction at regular intervals, swinging positive then negative over and over. Plotted against time it traces a smooth <strong>sine wave</strong>. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-44, 12-48)</span></p><p>Picture pushing a child on a swing &mdash; forward, back, forward, back. DC is a steady shove in one direction; AC is the back-and-forth. One complete back-and-forth (0&deg; &rarr; +peak &rarr; 0 &rarr; &minus;peak &rarr; 0) is one <strong>cycle</strong>. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-49)</span></p><ul><li><strong>Cycle</strong> &mdash; one full repetition of the waveform (one 360&deg; trip).</li><li><strong>Frequency</strong> &mdash; how many cycles happen each second, measured in <strong>hertz (Hz)</strong>. 60&nbsp;Hz = 60 cycles per second.</li><li><strong>Period</strong> &mdash; the time for one cycle. Period and frequency are reciprocals: period&nbsp;=&nbsp;1&nbsp;&divide;&nbsp;frequency. Faster wave (higher Hz) = shorter period.</li><li><strong>Peak value</strong> &mdash; the largest instantaneous value, reached at 90&deg; (and the negative peak at 270&deg;).</li></ul><p><strong>Why aircraft use AC:</strong> AC transmits over distance more easily, its voltage can be stepped up or down with <strong>transformers</strong>, and AC motors are smaller, lighter, and brushless (no commutator trouble at altitude). Many 24&nbsp;V&nbsp;DC airplanes still carry equipment that needs <strong>400&nbsp;Hz</strong> AC &mdash; that's the aviation power standard, much higher than the 60&nbsp;Hz in your house. <span class=\"cite\">(FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-43, 12-44)</span></p><div class=\"selfq\">An aircraft AC system runs at 400&nbsp;Hz. What is the period of one cycle?<span class=\"a\">Answer: period = 1 &divide; frequency = 1 &divide; 400 = 0.0025&nbsp;s = 2.5&nbsp;milliseconds.</span></div><div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Module 2 must-knows</span>Series: same current, voltages add, R adds. Parallel: same voltage, currents add, R is less than the smallest branch. Product-over-sum: (R&#8321;R&#8322;)/(R&#8321;+R&#8322;). KVL: drops add to the source. KCL: current in = current out. OPEN = break, no current, full voltage across the gap, ohmmeter infinite. SHORT = unwanted low-R path, excess current, ~0&nbsp;V across it, ohmmeter ~0&nbsp;&#937;, blows fuse. Voltmeter/ammeter = power ON; ohmmeter/continuity = power OFF. AC: sine wave; frequency in Hz; period = 1/frequency; aircraft = 400&nbsp;Hz.</div>", "quiz": [{"q": "In a series circuit, which quantity is the SAME at every point in the circuit?", "options": ["Resistance", "Current", "Power", "Voltage"], "correct": 1, "short": "Series: same current", "expl": "A series circuit has only one path, so the same current flows through every part. Voltage drops differ; current does not.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-35", "topic": "Series behavior"}, {"q": "Three resistors of 1 kΩ, 3 kΩ, and 5 kΩ are connected in series. What is the total resistance?", "options": ["1 kΩ", "9 kΩ", "0.65 kΩ", "3 kΩ"], "correct": 1, "short": "Series R adds: 9 kΩ", "expl": "In series, total resistance is the simple sum: 1 + 3 + 5 = 9 kΩ. Adding series resistors always increases the total.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-36", "topic": "Series R calc"}, {"q": "In a parallel circuit, which quantity is the SAME across every branch?", "options": ["Voltage", "Power", "Resistance", "Current"], "correct": 0, "short": "Parallel: same voltage", "expl": "Every branch connects across the same two source terminals, so each branch sees the same voltage. The branch currents differ.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-40", "topic": "Parallel behavior"}, {"q": "Compared to the smallest branch resistor, the total resistance of a parallel circuit is always:", "options": ["Equal to the smallest branch", "Less than the smallest branch", "Larger than the smallest branch", "Equal to the sum of all branches"], "correct": 1, "short": "Parallel R < smallest branch", "expl": "Adding a parallel path gives current another road, lowering total resistance. The result is always less than the smallest individual branch — the opposite of series.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-41", "topic": "Parallel R rule"}, {"q": "Two resistors of 500 Ω and 400 Ω are connected in parallel. Using product-over-sum, what is the total resistance?", "options": ["222.2 Ω", "450 Ω", "200,000 Ω", "900 Ω"], "correct": 0, "short": "(500×400)/(500+400)=222 Ω", "expl": "Product/sum = (500×400)/(500+400) = 200,000/900 = 222.2 Ω. Note it is less than the smaller resistor (400 Ω), confirming the parallel rule.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-41", "topic": "Parallel R calc"}, {"q": "Two 60 Ω resistors are connected in parallel. What is the total resistance?", "options": ["60 Ω", "15 Ω", "30 Ω", "120 Ω"], "correct": 2, "short": "Equal pair: 60/2 = 30 Ω", "expl": "For equal resistors in parallel, divide the value by the number of branches: 60 ÷ 2 = 30 Ω, which is less than the smallest branch.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-41", "topic": "Parallel R calc"}, {"q": "The correct product-over-sum formula for two resistors in parallel is:", "options": ["R1 + R2", "(R1 × R2) / (R1 + R2)", "(R1 + R2) / (R1 × R2)", "1 / (R1 + R2)"], "correct": 1, "short": "Rt = (R1·R2)/(R1+R2)", "expl": "Total resistance for two parallel resistors equals the product of the two divided by their sum: (R1×R2)/(R1+R2).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-41", "topic": "Parallel formula"}, {"q": "In a series circuit, the individual voltage drops across the resistors must add up to:", "options": ["The source voltage", "The total resistance", "Zero", "The total current"], "correct": 0, "short": "Drops sum to source", "expl": "Each resistor uses a share of the push; the shares add back to the applied source voltage (this is Kirchhoff's Voltage Law).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-36", "topic": "Series voltage"}, {"q": "A 12 V source feeds two series resistors: R1 = 100 Ω and R2 = 300 Ω. What is the voltage drop across R2?", "options": ["3 V", "12 V", "9 V", "6 V"], "correct": 2, "short": "Divider: 9 V on R2", "expl": "Rt = 400 Ω, I = 12/400 = 0.03 A, E2 = 0.03 × 300 = 9 V. R2 holds 3/4 of the resistance so it drops 3/4 of the 12 V.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-37", "topic": "Voltage divider"}, {"q": "A device that uses series resistors to obtain more than one voltage from a single power source is called a:", "options": ["Rectifier", "Transformer", "Current divider", "Voltage divider"], "correct": 3, "short": "Voltage divider", "expl": "A voltage divider is a series resistor string with taps; different voltages appear between the taps because the source voltage divides among the resistors.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-37", "topic": "Voltage divider"}, {"q": "Kirchhoff's Voltage Law states that around any closed loop, the source voltage minus all the voltage drops equals:", "options": ["The source voltage", "Zero", "The largest drop", "The total current"], "correct": 1, "short": "KVL: loop sums to zero", "expl": "KVL: applied voltage minus the sum of all drops equals zero — every bit of the source's push is used up by the loads around the loop.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-37", "topic": "Kirchhoff KVL"}, {"q": "A 100 V source feeds four series resistors. Three drops are 2 V, 10 V, and 20 V. By Kirchhoff's Voltage Law, the fourth drop is:", "options": ["50 V", "100 V", "68 V", "32 V"], "correct": 2, "short": "100−32 = 68 V", "expl": "KVL: 100 − 2 − 10 − 20 − E4 = 0, so 68 − E4 = 0, giving E4 = 68 V.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-37", "topic": "Kirchhoff KVL"}, {"q": "Kirchhoff's Current Law states that the current flowing into a junction (node):", "options": ["Equals the source voltage", "Equals the current flowing out of it", "Is always zero", "Is greater than the current out"], "correct": 1, "short": "KCL: in = out", "expl": "At any junction, current in equals current out — nothing accumulates. For parallel branches this gives It = I1 + I2 + I3.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-41", "topic": "Kirchhoff KCL"}, {"q": "75 mA flows into a node. Two branches leaving carry 30 mA and 20 mA. By Kirchhoff's Current Law, the third branch carries:", "options": ["50 mA", "5 mA", "25 mA", "125 mA"], "correct": 2, "short": "75−50 = 25 mA", "expl": "Current in = current out: 75 = 30 + 20 + I2, so I2 = 75 − 50 = 25 mA.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-42", "topic": "Kirchhoff KCL"}, {"q": "In a parallel circuit, the total current drawn from the source equals:", "options": ["The smallest branch current", "The sum of all branch currents", "The same current in every branch", "The largest branch current"], "correct": 1, "short": "It = sum of branches", "expl": "The source current splits among the branches and rejoins, so It = I1 + I2 + I3 (Kirchhoff's Current Law applied to a parallel circuit).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-41", "topic": "Parallel current"}, {"q": "To solve a series-parallel circuit, the FIRST step is usually to:", "options": ["Find the smallest resistor", "Add all resistors together", "Measure the source voltage", "Reduce each parallel group to its single equivalent resistor"], "correct": 3, "short": "Collapse parallel groups first", "expl": "Solve the parallel groups first and replace each with one equivalent resistor; the circuit then collapses into a simple series circuit you can sum.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-42", "topic": "Series-parallel"}, {"q": "R1 = 1 kΩ is in series with a parallel pair (2 kΩ and 3 kΩ). What is the total resistance of the circuit?", "options": ["2.2 kΩ", "3.6 kΩ", "1.2 kΩ", "6 kΩ"], "correct": 0, "short": "1k + 1.2k = 2.2 kΩ", "expl": "Parallel pair: (2k×3k)/(2k+3k) = 1.2 kΩ. Then series add: 1 kΩ + 1.2 kΩ = 2.2 kΩ.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-43", "topic": "Series-parallel calc"}, {"q": "An OPEN circuit is best described as:", "options": ["A break or incomplete path so no current flows", "A circuit drawing excessive current", "An unwanted low-resistance shortcut", "A path with exactly the rated resistance"], "correct": 0, "short": "Open = break, no current", "expl": "An open is an incomplete path for current — a break, blown fuse, or burned-open part — so no current flows in that path.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide p. 16", "topic": "Open circuit"}, {"q": "A SHORT circuit is best described as:", "options": ["An open fuse", "A correctly sized resistor", "An unwanted low-resistance path that lets current bypass the load", "A break in the path"], "correct": 2, "short": "Short = unwanted low-R path", "expl": "A short allows current to flow across a part that should insulate, bypassing the load. It causes excessive current and rapid heating.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide p. 16", "topic": "Short circuit"}, {"q": "What is the typical symptom of a SHORT circuit in terms of current?", "options": ["No current flows", "Excessive current that can blow a fuse or breaker", "Normal rated current", "Current reverses direction"], "correct": 1, "short": "Short = excess current", "expl": "A short is a near-zero-resistance shortcut, so current spikes and generates heat quickly — this is what trips circuit protection.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-28", "topic": "Short symptoms"}, {"q": "A voltmeter placed across a suspected break in an energized circuit reads the FULL source voltage. This indicates:", "options": ["A short circuit", "A correctly working load", "A blown branch resistor in parallel", "An open circuit"], "correct": 3, "short": "Full V across gap = open", "expl": "With an open, no current flows, so no voltage is dropped elsewhere — the entire source voltage appears across the break.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-45", "topic": "Open symptoms"}, {"q": "With power removed, an ohmmeter across a component reads infinite (∞) ohms. The component is:", "options": ["Shorted", "A current divider", "Within tolerance", "Open"], "correct": 3, "short": "Infinite Ω = open", "expl": "Infinite resistance means no complete path — an open. A short would read near 0 Ω.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-28", "topic": "Ohmmeter open"}, {"q": "Which fault can occur in a resistor or fuse WITHOUT any visible sign of damage?", "options": ["An open", "A solder bridge", "Incorrect color band", "A short"], "correct": 0, "short": "Open can be invisible", "expl": "The NCATT guide notes a resistor or fuse can open with no visible damage, so a meter/continuity check is needed to confirm it.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide p. 16", "topic": "Open circuit"}, {"q": "Which meter is used to find a circuit problem with the power REMOVED from the circuit?", "options": ["Ohmmeter", "Oscilloscope", "Voltmeter", "Ammeter"], "correct": 0, "short": "Ohmmeter = power off", "expl": "The ohmmeter measures resistance and runs continuity checks with power off. The voltmeter and ammeter are used with power on.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide p. 11", "topic": "Meter selection"}, {"q": "Which meter is used to find a circuit problem with the power ON, and is a good first check for input voltage?", "options": ["Megohmmeter", "Ohmmeter", "Voltmeter", "Continuity tester"], "correct": 2, "short": "Voltmeter = power on", "expl": "The voltmeter works on a live circuit; checking that input voltage is even present is a recommended starting point.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide p. 11", "topic": "Meter selection"}, {"q": "A continuity check is performed to verify:", "options": ["That a complete electrical path exists between two points", "That a capacitor is charged", "The exact resistor color code", "The peak value of an AC waveform"], "correct": 0, "short": "Continuity = complete path?", "expl": "A continuity check confirms a complete path exists between two points; it is usually done with an ohmmeter or voltmeter, testing at each terminal.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide p. 11", "topic": "Continuity"}, {"q": "Which single instrument combines a voltmeter, ammeter, and ohmmeter and is the most versatile tool the technician uses?", "options": ["Signal generator", "Megohmmeter", "Multimeter", "Oscilloscope"], "correct": 2, "short": "Multimeter = all three", "expl": "A multimeter contains a voltmeter, ammeter, and ohmmeter, measuring voltage, current, and resistance — the most versatile electrical instrument.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide p. 10", "topic": "Test tools"}, {"q": "In the troubleshooting process, the recommended FIRST action is to:", "options": ["Isolate the problem by asking how and when it occurs", "Cut the suspect wire", "Start replacing components one by one", "Apply maximum voltage to the circuit"], "correct": 0, "short": "Isolate first", "expl": "The NCATT process begins by isolating the problem — is it intermittent, worse during taxi/takeoff/cruise/landing, weather-related — before touching parts.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide p. 11", "topic": "Troubleshooting method"}, {"q": "When narrowing down where a fault is along a wire run, the efficient measurement strategy is to:", "options": ["Only check the load end", "Measure at the middle, decide which half holds the fault, then split again", "Test every single terminal in order from the source", "Replace the whole harness"], "correct": 1, "short": "Split-half search", "expl": "Measuring at the midpoint and discarding the good half each time corners the fault in a few moves instead of testing every point.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide p. 11", "topic": "Troubleshooting method"}, {"q": "Direct current (DC) differs from alternating current (AC) in that DC:", "options": ["Reverses direction at regular intervals", "Flows constantly in one direction with constant polarity", "Always traces a sine wave", "Cannot power a motor"], "correct": 1, "short": "DC = one direction", "expl": "DC flows constantly in one direction with constant polarity; AC reverses direction at regular intervals, tracing a sine wave.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-44", "topic": "AC basics"}, {"q": "The number of complete AC cycles that occur each second is called the:", "options": ["Peak value", "Period", "Amplitude", "Frequency"], "correct": 3, "short": "Frequency, in hertz", "expl": "Frequency is cycles per second, measured in hertz (Hz). The time for one cycle is the period.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-47", "topic": "AC frequency"}, {"q": "If an aircraft AC system operates at 400 Hz, the period of one cycle is:", "options": ["400 seconds", "40 milliseconds", "0.4 seconds", "2.5 milliseconds"], "correct": 3, "short": "1/400 = 2.5 ms", "expl": "Period = 1 ÷ frequency = 1 ÷ 400 = 0.0025 s = 2.5 ms. Period and frequency are reciprocals.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-49", "topic": "AC period"}, {"q": "One reason aircraft use AC rather than DC for many systems is that AC voltage:", "options": ["Cannot be changed once generated", "Can be easily stepped up or down with transformers", "Never produces heat", "Requires brushes in every motor"], "correct": 1, "short": "AC + transformers", "expl": "AC can be raised or lowered by transformers, transmits over distance more easily, and AC motors are smaller, lighter, and brushless.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-44", "topic": "AC advantages"}], "drill": [{"label": "Series current", "text": "In a series circuit the current is the same at every point (one path)."}, {"label": "Series voltage", "text": "In a series circuit the voltage drops add up to the source voltage."}, {"label": "Series resistance", "text": "Series total resistance is the sum: Rt = R1 + R2 + R3 (always larger)."}, {"label": "Parallel voltage", "text": "In a parallel circuit the voltage is the same across every branch."}, {"label": "Parallel current", "text": "In a parallel circuit the branch currents add to the total: It = I1 + I2 + I3."}, {"label": "Parallel resistance", "text": "Parallel total resistance is always LESS than the smallest branch resistor."}, {"label": "Product-over-sum", "text": "Two resistors in parallel: Rt = (R1 × R2) / (R1 + R2)."}, {"label": "Kirchhoff Voltage Law", "text": "KVL: around any closed loop, source voltage minus all drops equals zero."}, {"label": "Kirchhoff Current Law", "text": "KCL: current into a junction equals current out of it."}, {"label": "Open circuit", "text": "OPEN = a break, no current flows; full source voltage appears across the gap; ohmmeter reads infinite."}, {"label": "Short circuit", "text": "SHORT = unwanted low-resistance path, excessive current, ~0 V across it; ohmmeter reads near 0 Ω; blows the fuse."}, {"label": "Meter rule & AC", "text": "Voltmeter/ammeter = power ON; ohmmeter/continuity = power OFF. AC is a sine wave; period = 1 ÷ frequency; aircraft AC = 400 Hz."}]}, {"n": 3, "title": "Resistors", "standards": "7, 8", "lesson": "<h3>Why resistors matter on an aircraft</h3>\n<p>Almost every avionics box on the airplane is full of resistors. A <strong>resistor</strong> is a part whose only job is to <strong>oppose (limit) current</strong> so the right amount of current reaches the right place. Think of a resistor like a <strong>kink in a garden hose</strong> &mdash; squeeze the hose and less water flows; open it up and more flows. The resistor is a permanent, calibrated \"kink\" for electricity.</p>\n<p>The NCATT Study Guide (Standard 7) says your job is to <strong>find the value of a fixed resistor</strong> three ways: read it off the <strong>schematic</strong>, <strong>measure it with an ohmmeter</strong>, or <strong>read the color-code bands</strong> on the resistor itself. Standard 8 then says you must be able to <strong>isolate a faulty resistor</strong> &mdash; spot one that is open, shorted, or out of tolerance.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">What a resistor does</span>It limits current. By Ohm's Law (<strong>I = E &divide; R</strong>), the bigger the resistance R, the smaller the current I for the same voltage. Resistors set bias, drop voltage, divide voltage, and protect parts from too much current. (FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-24)</div>\n\n<h3>Types of resistors</h3>\n<p>All fixed resistors do the same job; they just differ in how they are built and how much heat (power) they can handle.</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Type</th><th>How it's built</th><th>Good for</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Carbon composition</strong></td><td>Finely ground carbon/graphite mixed with insulating filler and binder, pressed into a rod with \"pigtail\" leads, sealed in coating. More graphite = lower resistance.</td><td>Cheap, general use; low power</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Film</strong> (carbon film, metal film, metal-oxide, metal glaze)</td><td>A thin resistive layer deposited evenly on a ceramic rod.</td><td>More precise (tighter tolerance) than carbon comp</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Wirewound</strong></td><td>Resistance wire wound around a porcelain (ceramic) rod, then coated. Both ends go to terminals.</td><td><strong>Large current, high power</strong>; precision (Manganin wire) versions exist</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>You'll also meet <strong>variable resistors</strong> you can adjust by hand: a <strong>rheostat</strong> (two terminals, varies <strong>current</strong>) and a <strong>potentiometer</strong> (three terminals, varies <strong>voltage</strong> &mdash; like a volume knob). And temperature/light-sensitive ones: a <strong>thermistor</strong> (resistance drops as it gets hotter &mdash; negative temperature coefficient) and a <strong>photoconductive cell</strong> (resistance changes with light). (FAA-H-8083-30B pp. 12-24&ndash;12-27)</p>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Rheostat vs. potentiometer</span><strong>Rheostat = 2 terminals = varies CURRENT.</strong> <strong>Potentiometer = 3 terminals = varies VOLTAGE</strong> (the third terminal is the moving wiper). (p. 12-26)</div>\n\n<h3>The Resistor Color Code &mdash; the whole thing</h3>\n<p>Small resistors are too tiny to print numbers on, so the value is shown with <strong>colored bands</strong>. Read the bands <strong>from the end toward the center</strong>. The body color means nothing &mdash; only the bands count, and the body is never the same color as a band. (p. 12-25)</p>\n<p>On a standard 4-band resistor:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Band 1</strong> = first digit (never gold/silver)</li>\n<li><strong>Band 2</strong> = second digit (never gold/silver)</li>\n<li><strong>Band 3</strong> = the <strong>multiplier</strong> = how many zeros to add</li>\n<li><strong>Band 4</strong> = the <strong>tolerance</strong> (gold &plusmn;5%, silver &plusmn;10%, no band &plusmn;20%)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Memorize the 10 colors in order, 0 through 9. A classic memory line is <strong>\"Bad Boys Race Our Young Girls But Violet Generally Wins.\"</strong> The NCATT guide gives the longer \"Big Bears Romp On Yellow Grass But Violets Grow Without...\" &mdash; either works.</p>\n\n<table>\n<tr><th>Color</th><th>Digit (bands 1&amp;2)</th><th>Multiplier (band 3)</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Black</strong></td><td>0</td><td>&times;1</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Brown</strong></td><td>1</td><td>&times;10</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Red</strong></td><td>2</td><td>&times;100</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Orange</strong></td><td>3</td><td>&times;1,000 (1k)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Yellow</strong></td><td>4</td><td>&times;10,000 (10k)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Green</strong></td><td>5</td><td>&times;100,000 (100k)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Blue</strong></td><td>6</td><td>&times;1,000,000 (1M)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Violet</strong></td><td>7</td><td>&times;10,000,000</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Gray</strong></td><td>8</td><td>&times;100,000,000</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>White</strong></td><td>9</td><td>&times;1,000,000,000</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Gold</strong></td><td>&mdash;</td><td>&times;0.1 (tolerance &plusmn;5%)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Silver</strong></td><td>&mdash;</td><td>&times;0.01 (tolerance &plusmn;10%)</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Tolerance band &mdash; lock this in</span><strong>Gold = &plusmn;5%. Silver = &plusmn;10%. No 4th band = &plusmn;20%.</strong> Tolerance is the manufacturing \"wiggle room\": how far the real value may legally be from the marked value, plus or minus. (NCATT Std 7; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25)</div>\n\n<p><strong>Heads-up (honest note):</strong> The FAA color-code chart on p. 12-25 also lists a <em>tolerance value for each color digit</em> (brown 1%, red 2%, green 5%, etc.) and treats a gold or silver <em>third</em> band as a fractional multiplier (gold &times;0.1, silver &times;0.01). Both NCATT and the FAA agree on the part that matters most for the exam: <strong>gold = &plusmn;5%, silver = &plusmn;10% in the tolerance position.</strong> Learn the standard scheme above first; just don't be surprised if a question puts gold/silver in the third (multiplier) slot.</p>\n\n<h3>Worked decodes (do these until they're automatic)</h3>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Example 1 &mdash; Brown, Black, Red, Gold</span>Brown=1, Black=0 &rarr; digits \"<strong>10</strong>\". Red multiplier = &times;100 (add 2 zeros) &rarr; <strong>1,000 &Omega; = 1 k&Omega;</strong>. Gold = &plusmn;5%. <br><strong>Answer: 1,000 &Omega; &plusmn;5%</strong> (range 950&ndash;1,050 &Omega;).</div>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Example 2 &mdash; Yellow, Violet, Orange, Silver</span>Yellow=4, Violet=7 &rarr; \"<strong>47</strong>\". Orange = &times;1,000 (add 3 zeros) &rarr; <strong>47,000 &Omega; = 47 k&Omega;</strong>. Silver = &plusmn;10%. <br><strong>Answer: 47,000 &Omega; &plusmn;10%</strong> (range 42,300&ndash;51,700 &Omega;).</div>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Example 3 &mdash; Green, Blue, Brown, Gold</span>Green=5, Blue=6 &rarr; \"<strong>56</strong>\". Brown = &times;10 (add 1 zero) &rarr; <strong>560 &Omega;</strong>. Gold = &plusmn;5%. <br><strong>Answer: 560 &Omega; &plusmn;5%</strong> (range 532&ndash;588 &Omega;).</div>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Example 4 &mdash; Brown, Green, Green, Silver</span>Brown=1, Green=5 &rarr; \"<strong>15</strong>\". Green multiplier = &times;100,000 (add 5 zeros) &rarr; <strong>1,500,000 &Omega; = 1.5 M&Omega;</strong>. Silver = &plusmn;10%. <br><strong>Answer: 1.5 M&Omega; &plusmn;10%.</strong></div>\n\n<p><strong>Going backward (value &rarr; colors):</strong> Need a <strong>2,200 &Omega; (2.2 k&Omega;) &plusmn;5%</strong>? Digits 2,2 = Red, Red. To get 2200 from \"22\" add two zeros = &times;100 = Red. Tolerance &plusmn;5% = Gold. So it's <strong>Red-Red-Red-Gold</strong>.</p>\n\n<h3>Power rating &mdash; don't melt the resistor</h3>\n<p>A resistor turns the energy it blocks into <strong>heat</strong>. Its <strong>power rating</strong> (watts) is the most heat it can shed without burning up &mdash; common sizes are 1/8 W, 1/4 W, 1/2 W, 1 W, 2 W, and big wirewounds for many watts. Power used: <strong>P = I&sup2; &times; R = E&sup2; &divide; R = E &times; I</strong>. Always pick a resistor rated <strong>above</strong> the watts it will actually dissipate, or it overheats, drifts out of tolerance, and eventually <strong>opens</strong>. (FAA-H-8083-30B pp. 12-20, 12-24)</p>\n\n<h3>Resistors in series and parallel (quick recap)</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Series:</strong> resistances add up. <strong>R&#8348; = R&#8321; + R&#8322; + R&#8323; ...</strong> Total is always <em>larger</em> than the biggest one.</li>\n<li><strong>Parallel:</strong> total is always <em>smaller</em> than the smallest one. Two in parallel: <strong>R&#8348; = (R&#8321; &times; R&#8322;) &divide; (R&#8321; + R&#8322;)</strong>. (FAA-H-8083-30B pp. 12-31, 12-40)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Fault Isolation &mdash; finding the bad resistor (Standard 8)</h3>\n<p>The Study Guide lists four resistor faults you must recognize:</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Fault</th><th>What it is</th><th>Ohmmeter reads</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Open</strong></td><td>The current path is broken inside &mdash; <strong>no path</strong> from one end to the other. Can happen with <em>no visible damage</em>.</td><td><strong>Infinite &Omega;</strong> (&infin; / \"OL\" / over-limit)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Shorted</strong></td><td>Current sneaks across what should block it (often solder bridge, debris, or a fried part).</td><td><strong>0 &Omega;</strong> (or near zero)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Out of tolerance</strong> (wrong value)</td><td>Reads, but the value is outside its &plusmn; band &mdash; usually from overheating/aging.</td><td>A real number, but <strong>outside</strong> the color-code range</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Improperly installed</strong></td><td>Wrong value fitted, or not installed to standard.</td><td>Reads, but not the value the schematic calls for</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">How to test a resistor with an ohmmeter &mdash; the steps</span>\n<strong>1. POWER OFF.</strong> Never ohm a live circuit &mdash; voltage damages the meter and gives false reads. (The ohmmeter uses its <em>own</em> battery.)<br>\n<strong>2. ISOLATE one end.</strong> Lift/disconnect at least one lead so other parts in parallel don't sneak through and fool the reading.<br>\n<strong>3. Read the color code</strong> to know the <strong>expected</strong> value and tolerance.<br>\n<strong>4. Measure</strong> and compare:<br>\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&bull; <strong>&infin; (OL)</strong> = <strong>OPEN</strong> (bad).<br>\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&bull; <strong>0 &Omega;</strong> = <strong>SHORTED</strong> (bad).<br>\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&bull; A number <strong>inside</strong> the tolerance band = good.<br>\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&bull; A number <strong>outside</strong> the tolerance band = <strong>out of tolerance</strong> (bad).\n</div>\n\n<p><strong>Why isolate?</strong> If a resistor is still soldered into the circuit, other components in parallel give the meter a second path. The meter then shows the <em>combination</em>, which is always lower than the resistor alone &mdash; a good resistor can look bad. Lifting one lead removes those sneak paths. (NCATT Std 8; FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25, 12-40)</p>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Example &mdash; is it good?</span>A resistor is marked <strong>Brown-Black-Red-Gold</strong> = 1,000 &Omega; &plusmn;5% (range 950&ndash;1,050 &Omega;). You power down, lift one lead, and the ohmmeter reads <strong>1,180 &Omega;</strong>. That's above 1,050, so it's <strong>out of tolerance &mdash; replace it.</strong> If it had read <strong>OL</strong> it would be <strong>open</strong>; if <strong>0 &Omega;</strong>, <strong>shorted</strong>.</div>\n\n<h3>&#9733; Key Terms &amp; Numbers (the test asks these almost word-for-word)</h3>\n<table>\n<tr><td><strong>Resistor</strong></td><td>Component that opposes/limits current; the value is fixed by construction.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Color sequence (0&ndash;9)</strong></td><td>Black, Brown, Red, Orange, Yellow, Green, Blue, Violet, Gray, White.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Band 1 / Band 2 / Band 3 / Band 4</strong></td><td>1st digit / 2nd digit / multiplier (zeros) / tolerance.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Tolerance</strong></td><td>Gold &plusmn;5%, Silver &plusmn;10%, none &plusmn;20%.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Open</strong></td><td>Broken path &rarr; ohmmeter reads <strong>infinite</strong>.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Shorted</strong></td><td>Unwanted current path &rarr; ohmmeter reads <strong>0 &Omega;</strong>.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Out of tolerance</strong></td><td>Real value falls outside its &plusmn; band.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Ohmmeter rule</strong></td><td>POWER OFF; isolate one end before reading.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Power rating</strong></td><td>Max heat (watts) the resistor can dissipate; P = I&sup2;R.</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>&#10003; Check Yourself</h3>\n<div class=\"selfq\">A resistor is banded Orange-Orange-Brown-Gold. What is its value and tolerance?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: Orange=3, Orange=3 &rarr; \"33\"; Brown = &times;10 (one zero) &rarr; 330 &Omega;; Gold = &plusmn;5%. So 330 &Omega; &plusmn;5%.</span></div>\n<div class=\"selfq\">You put an ohmmeter across a resistor and it reads infinite (OL). What's wrong with the resistor?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: It's OPEN &mdash; the internal current path is broken. Replace it.</span></div>\n<div class=\"selfq\">Before measuring resistance, what two things must you always do?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: (1) Turn the power OFF, and (2) isolate the resistor by disconnecting at least one lead so parallel paths don't fool the reading.</span></div>\n<div class=\"selfq\">Which band color means &plusmn;10% tolerance, and which means &plusmn;5%?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: Silver = &plusmn;10%; Gold = &plusmn;5%. (No fourth band = &plusmn;20%.)</span></div>\n<div class=\"selfq\">A 1,000 &Omega; &plusmn;5% resistor measures 1,140 &Omega; after you isolate it. Good or bad, and why?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: Bad &mdash; out of tolerance. &plusmn;5% of 1,000 is &plusmn;50, so the legal range is 950&ndash;1,050 &Omega;. 1,140 is above 1,050, so replace it.</span></div>", "quiz": [{"q": "What is the primary job of a resistor in a circuit?", "options": ["To oppose (limit) the amount of current flow", "To store electrical charge", "To increase voltage", "To convert AC to DC"], "correct": 0, "short": "It limits current.", "expl": "A resistor's general use is to limit the amount of current flow.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-24", "topic": "Resistor basics"}, {"q": "In the standard resistor color code, what digit does BLACK represent?", "options": ["1", "0", "8", "9"], "correct": 1, "short": "Black = 0.", "expl": "The color sequence starts Black=0, Brown=1, Red=2...", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 7", "topic": "Color code"}, {"q": "What digit does the color WHITE represent?", "options": ["7", "8", "9", "0"], "correct": 2, "short": "White = 9.", "expl": "White is the highest digit, 9, at the end of the 0-9 color sequence.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Color code"}, {"q": "Reading from the end toward the center of a 4-band resistor, what does the THIRD band represent?", "options": ["The first significant digit", "The tolerance", "The power rating", "The multiplier (number of zeros to add)"], "correct": 3, "short": "Third band = multiplier.", "expl": "Band 3 tells how many zeros to add to the first two digits.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Color code"}, {"q": "On a standard 4-band resistor, what does the FOURTH band indicate?", "options": ["The first digit", "The second digit", "The tolerance", "The multiplier"], "correct": 2, "short": "Fourth band = tolerance.", "expl": "The fourth band gives the percentage tolerance; no fourth band means +/-20%.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Color code"}, {"q": "A GOLD tolerance band means the resistor is accurate to within:", "options": ["+/-5%", "+/-1%", "+/-10%", "+/-20%"], "correct": 0, "short": "Gold = +/-5%.", "expl": "Gold tolerance band = +/-5%.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 7", "topic": "Tolerance"}, {"q": "A SILVER tolerance band means the resistor tolerance is:", "options": ["+/-2%", "+/-5%", "+/-20%", "+/-10%"], "correct": 3, "short": "Silver = +/-10%.", "expl": "Silver tolerance band = +/-10%.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 7", "topic": "Tolerance"}, {"q": "A resistor has NO fourth (tolerance) band. What tolerance is understood?", "options": ["+/-5%", "+/-20%", "+/-15%", "+/-10%"], "correct": 1, "short": "No band = +/-20%.", "expl": "If there is no fourth band, the tolerance is understood to be 20 percent.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Tolerance"}, {"q": "Decode Brown-Black-Red-Gold. What is the value and tolerance?", "options": ["1,000 ohms +/-5%", "100 ohms +/-5%", "10,000 ohms +/-10%", "1,000 ohms +/-10%"], "correct": 0, "short": "1,000 ohms +/-5%.", "expl": "Brown=1, Black=0 -> 10; Red x100 -> 1,000 ohms; Gold = +/-5%.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Decode"}, {"q": "Decode Yellow-Violet-Orange-Silver.", "options": ["4,700 ohms +/-10%", "47,000 ohms +/-10%", "47,000 ohms +/-5%", "470,000 ohms +/-10%"], "correct": 1, "short": "47,000 ohms +/-10%.", "expl": "Yellow=4, Violet=7 -> 47; Orange x1,000 -> 47,000 ohms; Silver = +/-10%.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Decode"}, {"q": "Decode Green-Blue-Brown-Gold.", "options": ["56 ohms +/-5%", "5,600 ohms +/-5%", "560 ohms +/-5%", "560 ohms +/-10%"], "correct": 2, "short": "560 ohms +/-5%.", "expl": "Green=5, Blue=6 -> 56; Brown x10 -> 560 ohms; Gold = +/-5%.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Decode"}, {"q": "Decode Red-Red-Red-Gold.", "options": ["222 ohms +/-5%", "2,200 ohms +/-10%", "22,000 ohms +/-5%", "2,200 ohms +/-5%"], "correct": 3, "short": "2,200 ohms +/-5%.", "expl": "Red=2, Red=2 -> 22; Red x100 -> 2,200 ohms; Gold = +/-5%.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Decode"}, {"q": "Decode Brown-Green-Green-Silver.", "options": ["155,000 ohms +/-10%", "15,000 ohms +/-10%", "1,500,000 ohms +/-10%", "1,500 ohms +/-10%"], "correct": 2, "short": "1.5 Mohm +/-10%.", "expl": "Brown=1, Green=5 -> 15; Green x100,000 -> 1,500,000 ohms; Silver = +/-10%.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Decode"}, {"q": "What is the correct order of the first five color-code colors (digits 0 through 4)?", "options": ["Black, Brown, Red, Orange, Yellow", "Brown, Black, Red, Orange, Yellow", "Black, Red, Brown, Yellow, Orange", "Black, Brown, Orange, Red, Yellow"], "correct": 0, "short": "Black, Brown, Red, Orange, Yellow.", "expl": "0=Black, 1=Brown, 2=Red, 3=Orange, 4=Yellow.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 7", "topic": "Color code"}, {"q": "Which color represents the digit 5?", "options": ["Blue", "Violet", "Yellow", "Green"], "correct": 3, "short": "Green = 5.", "expl": "Green=5. (Blue=6, Yellow=4, Violet=7.)", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Color code"}, {"q": "Which color represents the digit 7?", "options": ["Gray", "Violet", "Blue", "White"], "correct": 1, "short": "Violet = 7.", "expl": "Violet=7. A common confusion is Blue=6 vs Violet=7.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Color code"}, {"q": "A resistor's first two bands are Blue then Gray. What two digits is that?", "options": ["6 and 8", "8 and 6", "6 and 7", "5 and 8"], "correct": 0, "short": "Blue=6, Gray=8.", "expl": "Blue=6, Gray=8 -> '68'.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Color code"}, {"q": "Which resistor type is built from finely ground carbon/graphite mixed with an insulating filler and binder, pressed into a rod?", "options": ["Wirewound", "Carbon composition", "Film", "Thermistor"], "correct": 1, "short": "Carbon composition.", "expl": "Carbon composition uses graphite + filler + binder; graphite amount sets the resistance.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-24", "topic": "Resistor types"}, {"q": "Which resistor type typically handles LARGE current and has HIGH power ratings, built by winding resistance wire on a porcelain rod?", "options": ["Carbon composition", "Carbon film", "Wirewound", "Metal-oxide film"], "correct": 2, "short": "Wirewound.", "expl": "Wire-wound resistors control large currents and have high power ratings.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-26", "topic": "Resistor types"}, {"q": "A film resistor is made by:", "options": ["Winding wire on a ceramic rod", "Stacking carbon disks", "Pressing graphite and filler into a rod", "Depositing a thin resistive material evenly on a ceramic rod"], "correct": 3, "short": "Thin film deposited on a ceramic rod.", "expl": "Film resistors deposit resistive material (graphite, nickel-chromium, etc.) on a ceramic rod.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-24", "topic": "Resistor types"}, {"q": "What is the difference between a rheostat and a potentiometer?", "options": ["A rheostat has 3 terminals; a potentiometer has 2", "Both are fixed resistors", "A rheostat varies current (2 terminals); a potentiometer varies voltage (3 terminals)", "A rheostat is temperature-sensitive; a potentiometer is light-sensitive"], "correct": 2, "short": "Rheostat varies current; potentiometer varies voltage.", "expl": "Rheostat = 2-terminal, varies current. Potentiometer = 3-terminal (wiper), varies voltage.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-26", "topic": "Variable resistors"}, {"q": "A thermistor is a variable resistor that responds to:", "options": ["Temperature", "Light intensity", "Pressure", "Voltage"], "correct": 0, "short": "Temperature.", "expl": "A thermistor is temperature-sensitive with a negative temperature coefficient.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-27", "topic": "Resistor types"}, {"q": "Before measuring a resistor's value with an ohmmeter, you must:", "options": ["Apply full system voltage", "Heat the resistor", "Increase the current", "Turn the circuit power OFF"], "correct": 3, "short": "Power OFF.", "expl": "An ohmmeter uses its own internal battery; circuit power must be off or it damages the meter and gives false reads.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 8", "topic": "Ohmmeter testing"}, {"q": "When testing a resistor in-circuit, why should you disconnect (isolate) at least one lead?", "options": ["So the resistor cools faster", "So parallel components don't provide a sneak path that falsifies the reading", "To increase the voltage across it", "Because the ohmmeter needs two batteries"], "correct": 1, "short": "To remove parallel sneak paths.", "expl": "Other components in parallel give the meter a second path, reading lower than the resistor alone; lifting a lead isolates it.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 8", "topic": "Ohmmeter testing"}, {"q": "An ohmmeter across an isolated resistor reads INFINITE (OL). The resistor is:", "options": ["Open", "Shorted", "Out of tolerance but usable", "Good"], "correct": 0, "short": "Open.", "expl": "Infinite resistance means a broken path with no continuity = an open resistor.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 8", "topic": "Fault isolation"}, {"q": "An ohmmeter across an isolated resistor reads 0 ohms. The resistor is:", "options": ["Open", "Shorted", "Good", "Out of tolerance"], "correct": 1, "short": "Shorted.", "expl": "Zero ohms means current passes where it should be opposed = a shorted resistor.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 8", "topic": "Fault isolation"}, {"q": "The NCATT guide says an OPEN resistor is a fault caused by:", "options": ["Too much current flow", "A foreign metal bridging two traces", "An incomplete path for current from one terminal to another", "Installing the wrong value"], "correct": 2, "short": "An incomplete current path.", "expl": "An open is an incomplete path for current; it can occur with no visible signs of damage.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 8", "topic": "Fault isolation"}, {"q": "The NCATT guide describes a SHORTED resistor as a fault that:", "options": ["Breaks the current path", "Changes its color bands", "Reduces the resistor's power rating", "Allows current to flow across a part of the circuit that should act as an insulator"], "correct": 3, "short": "Current flows where it should be blocked.", "expl": "A short allows current across a portion that should insulate; often from foreign material or close traces.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 8", "topic": "Fault isolation"}, {"q": "A resistor marked Brown-Black-Red-Gold (1,000 ohms +/-5%) measures 1,180 ohms after isolation. It is:", "options": ["Good - within tolerance", "Open", "Out of tolerance (replace it)", "Shorted"], "correct": 2, "short": "Out of tolerance.", "expl": "+/-5% of 1,000 = 950-1,050 ohms. 1,180 is above the range, so it is out of tolerance.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 8", "topic": "Fault isolation"}, {"q": "A 470 ohm +/-10% resistor is within tolerance if it measures between:", "options": ["423 and 517 ohms", "465 and 475 ohms", "447 and 494 ohms", "440 and 500 ohms"], "correct": 0, "short": "423 to 517 ohms.", "expl": "+/-10% of 470 = +/-47, so the legal range is 423 to 517 ohms.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 8", "topic": "Tolerance"}, {"q": "You need a 330 ohm +/-5% resistor. Which color bands?", "options": ["Orange-Orange-Black-Gold", "Orange-Orange-Brown-Silver", "Orange-Black-Brown-Gold", "Orange-Orange-Brown-Gold"], "correct": 3, "short": "Orange-Orange-Brown-Gold.", "expl": "3,3 = Orange,Orange; x10 (one zero) = Brown; +/-5% = Gold -> 330 ohms +/-5%.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Decode"}, {"q": "What does a resistor's POWER RATING (in watts) tell you?", "options": ["Its exact resistance value", "The maximum heat it can dissipate without being damaged", "Its tolerance percentage", "The voltage it produces"], "correct": 1, "short": "Max heat it can dissipate.", "expl": "The power rating is the most heat (watts) the resistor can shed without overheating; P = I-squared x R.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-20", "topic": "Power rating"}, {"q": "Three resistors of 100, 220, and 330 ohms are in SERIES. The total resistance is:", "options": ["650 ohms", "Less than 100 ohms", "About 55 ohms", "330 ohms"], "correct": 0, "short": "650 ohms.", "expl": "In series, resistances add: 100 + 220 + 330 = 650 ohms.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-31", "topic": "Series/parallel"}, {"q": "Two 100 ohm resistors are connected in PARALLEL. The total resistance is:", "options": ["200 ohms", "50 ohms", "100 ohms", "25 ohms"], "correct": 1, "short": "50 ohms.", "expl": "Two equal resistors in parallel = half of one: (100x100)/(100+100) = 50 ohms.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-40", "topic": "Series/parallel"}, {"q": "On a color-banded resistor, the body (base) color of the resistor:", "options": ["Indicates the first digit", "Indicates the tolerance", "Has nothing to do with the resistance value", "Indicates the multiplier"], "correct": 2, "short": "Body color means nothing.", "expl": "The body/base color has nothing to do with the color code and is never the same as a value band.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Color code"}, {"q": "The first color band of a standard 4-band resistor is never which colors?", "options": ["Black or brown", "Green or blue", "Red or orange", "Gold or silver"], "correct": 3, "short": "Never gold or silver.", "expl": "The first (and second) digit band is never gold or silver in color.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-25", "topic": "Color code"}], "drill": [{"label": "Color sequence 0-9", "text": "Black=0, Brown=1, Red=2, Orange=3, Yellow=4, Green=5, Blue=6, Violet=7, Gray=8, White=9."}, {"label": "Memory line", "text": "Bad Boys Race Our Young Girls But Violet Generally Wins (Black, Brown, Red, Orange, Yellow, Green, Blue, Violet, Gray, White)."}, {"label": "Band order (4-band)", "text": "Band 1 = 1st digit, Band 2 = 2nd digit, Band 3 = multiplier (zeros), Band 4 = tolerance. Read end toward center."}, {"label": "Gold tolerance", "text": "Gold tolerance band = +/-5%."}, {"label": "Silver tolerance", "text": "Silver tolerance band = +/-10%."}, {"label": "No tolerance band", "text": "No fourth band = +/-20% tolerance understood."}, {"label": "Open resistor", "text": "Open = broken internal path; ohmmeter reads INFINITE (OL). Can have no visible damage."}, {"label": "Shorted resistor", "text": "Shorted = current flows where it should be blocked; ohmmeter reads 0 ohms."}, {"label": "Out of tolerance", "text": "Reads a real number but outside the color-code +/- range; replace it."}, {"label": "Ohmmeter rule", "text": "POWER OFF and isolate one lead before measuring; the ohmmeter uses its own battery."}, {"label": "Resistor types", "text": "Carbon composition (graphite+filler), film (deposited on ceramic, more precise), wirewound (high current/high power)."}, {"label": "Rheostat vs pot", "text": "Rheostat = 2 terminals, varies CURRENT. Potentiometer = 3 terminals, varies VOLTAGE."}]}, {"n": 4, "title": "Reactive Components", "standards": "9, 10, 11, 12, 13", "lesson": "<h3>Module 4 — Reactive Components (Standards 9, 10, 11, 12, 13)</h3>\n<p>On a real aircraft, almost nothing runs on plain resistance alone. Radios, power supplies, filters, generators, and ignition systems all lean on three \"reactive\" parts: the <strong>inductor</strong> (a coil), the <strong>capacitor</strong> (two plates), and the <strong>transformer</strong> (two coils sharing a magnetic field). This module teaches what each one does, the formulas the AET exam asks verbatim, and how to find a faulty one with a meter.</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box key</span> The two \"reactive\" components store energy and fight a <em>change</em>. An <strong>inductor</strong> stores energy in a <strong>magnetic field</strong> and opposes a change in <strong>current</strong>. A <strong>capacitor</strong> stores energy in an <strong>electric (electrostatic) field</strong> and opposes a change in <strong>voltage</strong>. Burn that pairing in.</p>\n\n<h3>Part 1 — Inductors (Standard 9)</h3>\n<p>An inductor is just a <strong>coil of wire</strong> — many turns wound into loops. When current flows through wire it creates a magnetic field around it. Coil that wire and the fields stack up into one strong field. (FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-56.)</p>\n<p>The magic: when the current <em>tries to change</em>, the collapsing or growing magnetic field induces a voltage that <strong>pushes back against the change</strong>. So an inductor \"doesn't like\" current changing quickly. Slow, steady DC? It barely notices. Fast-changing AC? It fights hard.</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box key</span> <strong>Inductance</strong> is the electrical property that opposes a change in current by storing energy in a magnetic field. In math it uses the symbol <strong>L</strong>. (NCATT Study Guide p. 13.)</p>\n<p><strong>The henry (H).</strong> The henry is the unit of inductance. A coil has <strong>1 henry</strong> when current changing at <strong>1 ampere per second</strong> induces <strong>1 volt</strong> across the coil. In practice you see millihenries (mH) and microhenries (µH). (NCATT p. 5; FAA p. 12-58.)</p>\n<p><strong>What makes inductance bigger?</strong> Four physical factors (FAA p. 12-57):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Number of turns</strong> — more turns = more inductance (inductance varies as the <em>square</em> of the turns; double the turns ≈ 4× the inductance).</li>\n<li><strong>Core material</strong> — an iron/steel core (high permeability) gives far more inductance than an air core.</li>\n<li><strong>Cross-sectional area</strong> — fatter coil = more inductance (varies directly with area).</li>\n<li><strong>Length</strong> — stretching the same turns over a longer coil <em>lowers</em> inductance (double the length = half the inductance).</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box</span> Memory hook for the four factors: <strong>more turns, bigger area, iron core = more L; longer coil = less L.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Inductors in series and parallel.</strong> They behave just like resistors (FAA p. 12-58):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Series:</strong> add them up. L<sub>T</sub> = L1 + L2 + L3 …</li>\n<li><strong>Parallel:</strong> reciprocal rule. 1/L<sub>T</sub> = 1/L1 + 1/L2 + 1/L3 … (so total is smaller than the smallest one).</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Inductive reactance (X<sub>L</sub>).</strong> In an AC circuit, the inductor's opposition to current is called <strong>inductive reactance</strong>, measured in <strong>ohms</strong>. The faster the current changes (higher frequency), the harder the inductor fights — so <strong>X<sub>L</sub> RISES with frequency</strong>. (NCATT p. 7–8; FAA p. 12-59.)</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box key</span> <strong>X<sub>L</sub> = 2&pi;fL</strong> &nbsp;|&nbsp; X<sub>L</sub> = inductive reactance (ohms), f = frequency (Hz/cps), L = inductance (henries), 2&pi; &asymp; 6.28. <strong>Frequency up &rarr; X<sub>L</sub> up.</strong></p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box ex</span> <strong>Worked X<sub>L</sub>:</strong> An AC circuit has L = 0.146 H, f = 60 cps. Find X<sub>L</sub>.<br>\nX<sub>L</sub> = 2&pi; &times; f &times; L = 6.28 &times; 60 &times; 0.146 = <strong>55 ohms</strong>. (FAA p. 12-59.)<br>\nIf the source is 110 V, current I = E / X<sub>L</sub> = 110 / 55 = <strong>2 amperes</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Phase — \"ELI\".</strong> In an inductor, voltage comes first and current drags behind by 90&deg;. The Study Guide's memory word is <strong>ELI</strong>: <strong>E</strong> (voltage) <strong>L</strong>eads <strong>I</strong> (current) in an inductor <strong>L</strong>. Inductance makes current <em>lag</em> voltage. (NCATT p. 8, 13.)</p>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">If you double the number of turns on an air-core coil, roughly what happens to its inductance?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: It increases by about 4&times; — inductance varies as the square of the number of turns. (FAA p. 12-57.)</span></div>\n\n<h3>Part 2 — Capacitors / Theory (Standard 10)</h3>\n<p>A capacitor is <strong>two metal plates separated by an insulator</strong> (the insulator is called the <strong>dielectric</strong>). Connect it to a source and electrons pile onto one plate and leave the other — it <strong>stores charge in an electric (electrostatic) field</strong> between the plates. Think of it as a tiny rechargeable reservoir for electricity. (NCATT p. 4; FAA p. 12-50.)</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box key</span> <strong>Capacitance</strong> is the ability to store electrical charge under a given voltage. A capacitor <strong>opposes a change in VOLTAGE</strong> (the mirror image of the inductor, which opposes a change in current). (NCATT p. 13.)</p>\n<p><strong>The farad.</strong> The farad (F) is the unit of capacitance. <strong>1 farad</strong> holds <strong>1 coulomb</strong> of charge at <strong>1 volt</strong>. A farad is huge, so real parts are rated in <strong>microfarads (µF = 10<sup>-6</sup> F)</strong> and <strong>picofarads (pF = 10<sup>-12</sup> F)</strong>. (NCATT p. 5; FAA p. 12-51.)</p>\n<p><strong>What makes capacitance bigger?</strong> Three factors (FAA p. 12-51 to 12-53):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Plate area</strong> — bigger plates = more capacitance.</li>\n<li><strong>Plate spacing</strong> — plates closer together = more capacitance.</li>\n<li><strong>Dielectric material</strong> — a higher dielectric constant (K) = more capacitance (air K=1, mica K=6, etc.).</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Capacitors in series and parallel — and here's the trap.</strong> Capacitors combine <strong>backwards from resistors</strong> (FAA p. 12-54):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Parallel:</strong> simply ADD. C<sub>T</sub> = C1 + C2 + C3 … (parallel increases total plate area). This is the opposite of resistors.</li>\n<li><strong>Series:</strong> reciprocal rule, 1/C<sub>T</sub> = 1/C1 + 1/C2 + … (like resistors-in-parallel) — total is smaller than the smallest.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box key</span> <strong>Caps in PARALLEL ADD up</strong> (opposite of resistors). Caps in SERIES use the reciprocal rule.</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box ex</span> <strong>Worked parallel:</strong> C1 = 330 µF and C2 = 220 µF in parallel &rarr; C<sub>T</sub> = 330 + 220 = <strong>550 µF</strong>. (FAA p. 12-54.)</p>\n<p><strong>Capacitive reactance (X<sub>C</sub>).</strong> In AC, the capacitor's opposition is <strong>capacitive reactance</strong>, in <strong>ohms</strong>. A capacitor passes fast changes easily, so the <strong>higher the frequency, the LOWER X<sub>C</sub></strong> — exactly opposite the inductor. (NCATT p. 7; FAA p. 12-55.)</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box key</span> <strong>X<sub>C</sub> = 1 / (2&pi;fC)</strong> &nbsp;|&nbsp; X<sub>C</sub> in ohms, f = frequency (Hz), C = capacitance (farads). <strong>Frequency up &rarr; X<sub>C</sub> down.</strong></p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box ex</span> <strong>Worked X<sub>C</sub>:</strong> C = 200 µF = 0.000200 F, f = 60 cps.<br>\nX<sub>C</sub> = 1 / (2&pi;fC) = 1 / (6.28 &times; 60 &times; 0.000200) = 1 / 0.07536 = <strong>about 13 ohms</strong>. (FAA p. 12-61.)</p>\n<p><strong>Phase — \"ICE\".</strong> In a capacitor, current comes first and voltage trails. Memory word <strong>ICE</strong>: <strong>I</strong> (current) leads <strong>C</strong>apacitor's <strong>E</strong> (voltage). Capacitance makes current <em>lead</em> voltage. (NCATT p. 7, 13.) Put the two halves together and the whole exam mnemonic is <strong>\"ELI the ICE man.\"</strong></p>\n<p><strong>RC time constant.</strong> A capacitor doesn't charge instantly — it follows a curve. The <strong>time constant</strong> is the time for the capacitor voltage to reach <strong>63.2%</strong> of the applied voltage; it equals <strong>&tau; = R &times; C</strong> (ohms &times; farads = seconds). It takes about <strong>5 time constants</strong> to reach essentially full charge (99%). (NCATT p. 18; FAA p. 12-52.)</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box ex</span> <strong>Worked time constant:</strong> R = 10,000 &Omega; and C = 100 µF (0.0001 F). &tau; = R &times; C = 10,000 &times; 0.0001 = <strong>1 second</strong> to reach 63.2%; about 5 seconds to fully charge.</p>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Two capacitors, 4 µF and 6 µF, are wired in parallel. What is the total capacitance?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: 10 µF — capacitors in parallel simply add (the opposite of resistors). (FAA p. 12-54.)</span></div>\n\n<h3>Part 3 — Capacitor / Fault Isolation (Standard 11)</h3>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box</span> <strong>SAFETY FIRST: discharge the capacitor before you touch it.</strong> A charged cap can hold a dangerous voltage long after power is off. Short the two leads through a resistor (or an insulated screwdriver on small caps) to bleed it down before testing or handling. Never test a live, charged capacitor.</p>\n<p><strong>Testing a capacitor with an ohmmeter.</strong> The ohmmeter sends a small voltage that charges the cap, and you watch how the needle (or reading) behaves (FAA p. 12-52 charge curve; NCATT p. 19):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Good capacitor:</strong> the meter momentarily reads LOW resistance (charging current flows), then the reading climbs to <strong>HIGH / infinite</strong> as the cap charges up and current stops. That \"charge-then-rise-to-infinite\" swing means it's healthy.</li>\n<li><strong>Shorted capacitor:</strong> reads <strong>0 ohms</strong> and stays there — the plates are touching, so the capacitor's electrical qualities no longer exist. (NCATT p. 19.)</li>\n<li><strong>Open capacitor:</strong> reads <strong>infinite immediately</strong> with <em>no</em> initial charging dip — it never charges, so there's no momentary low reading.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Polarity on electrolytics.</strong> Electrolytic capacitors are <strong>polarized</strong> — they have a marked + and &minus; lead and MUST be installed the right way around. Reverse them and the dielectric breaks down; they can overheat or burst. Always observe polarity, and place the ohmmeter's red/black leads to match when testing. (FAA p. 12-52.)</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box key</span> Ohmmeter cap test: <strong>charges then reads high/infinite = good · 0 &Omega; = shorted · infinite with no charge dip = open.</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">You put an ohmmeter on a capacitor and it reads 0 ohms and never moves. What's wrong?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: The capacitor is shorted — the plates are touching, so it stays at 0 &Omega;. A good cap would charge and then climb to a high/infinite reading. (NCATT p. 19.)</span></div>\n\n<h3>Part 4 — Transformer / Theory (Standard 12)</h3>\n<p>A transformer is <strong>two coils sharing one magnetic field</strong>, usually wound on the same iron core. The coils are <strong>not electrically connected</strong> — energy crosses from one to the other by the changing magnetic field. This crossing is called <strong>mutual induction</strong>. (FAA p. 12-65.)</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box key</span> <strong>Mutual induction:</strong> AC in the first coil makes a changing magnetic field; that field cuts the second coil and induces a voltage in it. A transformer needs a <strong>changing</strong> voltage (AC or pulsing DC) — pure steady DC will NOT transform, because steady DC makes no changing field. (FAA p. 12-65.)</p>\n<p><strong>The parts (FAA p. 12-65):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Primary winding</strong> — the INPUT coil, connected to the power source. (NCATT p. 19.)</li>\n<li><strong>Secondary winding</strong> — the OUTPUT coil, feeding the load. (NCATT p. 19.)</li>\n<li><strong>Iron core</strong> — gives the magnetic lines an easy (low-reluctance) path between the coils.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>The turns ratio — the one formula to know.</strong> Voltage transforms in proportion to the number of turns on each coil (FAA p. 12-66):</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box key</span> <strong>V<sub>p</sub> / V<sub>s</sub> = N<sub>p</sub> / N<sub>s</sub></strong> &nbsp;(primary voltage / secondary voltage = primary turns / secondary turns). Rearranged: <strong>V<sub>s</sub> = V<sub>p</sub> &times; (N<sub>s</sub> / N<sub>p</sub>)</strong>.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Step-up:</strong> more turns on the secondary than the primary &rarr; secondary voltage is <em>higher</em>. (NCATT p. 19.)</li>\n<li><strong>Step-down:</strong> fewer turns on the secondary &rarr; secondary voltage is <em>lower</em>. (NCATT p. 19.)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box key</span> <strong>Current is INVERSE to voltage.</strong> If a transformer steps voltage UP, it steps current DOWN by the same ratio (and vice-versa), because power in &asymp; power out (P = I &times; E). A 4:1 step-up of 10 V / 4 A gives 40 V / 1 A — same 40 watts. (FAA p. 12-66.)</p>\n<p><strong>Isolation.</strong> Because the two windings are not electrically connected, a transformer also provides <strong>isolation</strong> — it passes AC energy while breaking the direct metallic path, which protects circuits and people. An isolation transformer has a 1:1 turns ratio (voltage unchanged) purely for that separation.</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box ex</span> <strong>Worked turns-ratio #1 (step-down):</strong> Primary = 240 V on 100 turns; secondary has 25 turns. Find V<sub>s</sub>.<br>\nV<sub>s</sub> = V<sub>p</sub> &times; (N<sub>s</sub>/N<sub>p</sub>) = 240 &times; (25/100) = 240 &times; 0.25 = <strong>60 V</strong>. Fewer secondary turns &rarr; step-DOWN. (FAA p. 12-66.)</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box ex</span> <strong>Worked turns-ratio #2 (step-up):</strong> Primary = 10 V on 50 turns; secondary has 500 turns. Find V<sub>s</sub>.<br>\nV<sub>s</sub> = 10 &times; (500/50) = 10 &times; 10 = <strong>100 V</strong>. A 1:10 ratio &rarr; step-UP. The current on the secondary would be 1/10 of the primary current. (FAA p. 12-66.)</p>\n<p><strong>Losses (good to recognize).</strong> Real transformers lose a little energy to <strong>eddy currents</strong> (heating of the core), <strong>hysteresis</strong> (lag in the core's magnetization), and copper resistance. (NCATT p. 19.)</p>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">A transformer has 200 primary turns and 50 secondary turns. Is it step-up or step-down, and what does it do to the current?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: Step-DOWN (fewer secondary turns &rarr; lower voltage). Because current is inverse to voltage, it steps the current UP by the same 4:1 ratio. (FAA p. 12-66.)</span></div>\n\n<h3>Part 5 — Transformer / Fault Isolation (Standard 13)</h3>\n<p>Transformers fail mostly as <strong>open windings</strong>, <strong>shorted turns</strong>, or improper installation. You isolate the fault with an ohmmeter checking the windings, plus a ratio check under power. (NCATT p. 20.)</p>\n<p><strong>Ohmmeter continuity of each winding.</strong> A healthy winding is a coil of wire, so it should show <strong>low resistance / continuity</strong>. Read each winding by itself (FAA p. 12-67; NCATT p. 20):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Open winding:</strong> reads <strong>infinite ohms (no continuity)</strong> — the wire is broken; no voltage will come out of that side. An open primary often pops the source fuse/breaker; an open secondary gives <strong>0 volts out</strong>. (NCATT p. 20.)</li>\n<li><strong>Shorted turns:</strong> the winding reads <strong>lower resistance than normal</strong> (turns bypassing each other). Shorted turns overheat the transformer and throw off the output voltage.</li>\n<li><strong>Primary-to-secondary or winding-to-core:</strong> should read <strong>infinite</strong> — the windings must be isolated from each other and from the core. A low reading there means breakdown of the insulation. (NCATT p. 20, resistance testing.)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Checking the ratio.</strong> With safe AC applied to the primary, measure primary and secondary voltages and compare to the rated turns ratio. If V<sub>s</sub>/V<sub>p</sub> doesn't match N<sub>s</sub>/N<sub>p</sub>, the transformer has shorted turns or a winding fault. <strong>Never leave a current-transformer secondary open</strong> while the system runs — it can produce dangerously high voltage; jumper it instead. (FAA p. 12-67.)</p>\n<p><span class=\"bt\">box key</span> Winding ohmmeter results: <strong>infinite = open winding · much-lower-than-spec = shorted turns · low reading between winding and core = insulation breakdown.</strong> Primary&harr;secondary should read open.</p>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">An ohmmeter across a transformer's secondary winding reads infinite ohms. What does that tell you?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: The secondary winding is OPEN (broken wire) — there's no continuity, so it will put out 0 volts even with power on the primary. (NCATT p. 20; FAA p. 12-67.)</span></div>\n\n<h3>Wrap-up — the must-knows</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Inductor</strong> opposes a change in CURRENT, stores energy in a MAGNETIC field, unit = henry. <strong>X<sub>L</sub> = 2&pi;fL</strong>, rises with frequency. <strong>ELI</strong> (E leads I).</li>\n<li><strong>Capacitor</strong> opposes a change in VOLTAGE, stores energy in an ELECTRIC field, unit = farad. <strong>X<sub>C</sub> = 1/(2&pi;fC)</strong>, falls with frequency. <strong>ICE</strong> (I leads E). Caps in PARALLEL ADD. &tau; = RC.</li>\n<li><strong>Transformer:</strong> mutual induction; <strong>V<sub>p</sub>/V<sub>s</sub> = N<sub>p</sub>/N<sub>s</sub></strong>; voltage and current are INVERSE; needs AC.</li>\n<li><strong>Fault tests (ohmmeter):</strong> good cap = charges then high/infinite; shorted cap = 0 &Omega;; open cap = no charge. Open winding = infinite; shorted turns = low. Discharge caps before handling.</li>\n</ul>", "quiz": [{"q": "What does an inductor oppose, and where does it store energy?", "options": ["A change in current; stored in a magnetic field", "A change in voltage; stored in an electric field", "A change in resistance; stored as heat", "A change in frequency; stored in the dielectric"], "correct": 0, "short": "Inductor = magnetic + current", "expl": "An inductor opposes a CHANGE in current and stores energy in a magnetic field. (The capacitor is the voltage/electric-field one.)", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-56", "topic": "Inductors"}, {"q": "What is the basic unit of inductance?", "options": ["Farad", "Ohm", "Henry", "Coulomb"], "correct": 2, "short": "Unit of L = henry", "expl": "The henry (H) is the unit of inductance: 1 H when current changing 1 A/sec induces 1 V.", "cite": "NCATT Study Guide p. 5", "topic": "Inductors"}, {"q": "Which change INCREASES a coil's inductance?", "options": ["Stretching the coil to twice its length", "Adding more turns of wire", "Removing the iron core and using air", "Using a smaller cross-sectional area"], "correct": 1, "short": "More turns = more L", "expl": "More turns increases inductance (it varies as the square of the turns). Longer coil, air core, and smaller area all DECREASE inductance.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-57", "topic": "Inductors"}, {"q": "Doubling the number of turns on a coil (same current) changes the inductance by about what factor?", "options": ["About 2 times", "About half", "No change", "About 4 times"], "correct": 3, "short": "Turns squared", "expl": "Inductance varies as the SQUARE of the number of turns, so doubling turns gives roughly 4x the inductance.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-57", "topic": "Inductors"}, {"q": "Three inductors are connected in SERIES. How do you find total inductance?", "options": ["Reciprocal rule: 1/LT = 1/L1 + 1/L2 + 1/L3", "Add them: LT = L1 + L2 + L3", "Multiply them together", "Total equals the smallest one"], "correct": 1, "short": "Series L adds", "expl": "Inductors in series add directly, just like resistors in series: LT = L1 + L2 + L3.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-58", "topic": "Inductors"}, {"q": "The formula for inductive reactance is:", "options": ["XL = 2πfL", "XL = 1/(2πfL)", "XL = R + L", "XL = 2πfC"], "correct": 0, "short": "XL = 2πfL", "expl": "Inductive reactance XL = 2πfL, measured in ohms. (The 1/(2πf...) form is capacitive reactance.)", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-59", "topic": "Inductive reactance"}, {"q": "As frequency increases, inductive reactance (XL):", "options": ["Decreases", "Stays the same", "Drops to zero", "Increases"], "correct": 3, "short": "XL rises with f", "expl": "XL = 2πfL, so higher frequency means higher inductive reactance. (Capacitive reactance does the opposite.)", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-59", "topic": "Inductive reactance"}, {"q": "Find XL for L = 0.146 H at 60 cps.", "options": ["13 ohms", "110 ohms", "55 ohms", "2 ohms"], "correct": 2, "short": "XL=6.28x60x0.146", "expl": "XL = 2πfL = 6.28 × 60 × 0.146 = 55 ohms.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-59", "topic": "Inductive reactance"}, {"q": "With 110 V across an inductor whose XL = 55 ohms, the current is:", "options": ["2 amperes", "55 amperes", "0.5 ampere", "110 amperes"], "correct": 0, "short": "I = E/XL", "expl": "I = E / XL = 110 / 55 = 2 amperes.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-59", "topic": "Inductive reactance"}, {"q": "In the memory aid 'ELI the ICE man,' the 'ELI' part means:", "options": ["Current leads voltage in an inductor", "Voltage equals current in an inductor", "Voltage (E) leads current (I) in an inductor (L)", "Inductors block all current"], "correct": 2, "short": "ELI: E leads I in L", "expl": "ELI: in an inductor (L), voltage (E) leads current (I) - current lags the voltage.", "cite": "NCATT Study Guide p. 8", "topic": "Phase / ELI ICE"}, {"q": "In a purely inductive AC circuit, the current:", "options": ["Leads the voltage by 90 degrees", "Lags the voltage by 90 degrees", "Is exactly in phase with voltage", "Is 180 degrees out of phase"], "correct": 1, "short": "Inductor: I lags E", "expl": "Inductance causes the current to lag the applied voltage by 90 degrees (ELI).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-56", "topic": "Phase / ELI ICE"}, {"q": "What does a capacitor oppose, and where does it store energy?", "options": ["A change in current; in a magnetic field", "A change in frequency; as heat", "Nothing; it only blocks DC", "A change in voltage; in an electric (electrostatic) field"], "correct": 3, "short": "Cap = electric + voltage", "expl": "A capacitor opposes a CHANGE in voltage and stores energy in an electric (electrostatic) field between its plates.", "cite": "NCATT Study Guide p. 4", "topic": "Capacitors"}, {"q": "A capacitor is basically constructed of:", "options": ["A coil of many turns of wire", "Two parallel plates separated by a dielectric", "A single semiconductor junction", "An iron core with two windings"], "correct": 1, "short": "Plates + dielectric", "expl": "A capacitor is two parallel plates separated by an insulator called the dielectric.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-50", "topic": "Capacitors"}, {"q": "The basic unit of capacitance is the farad, defined as:", "options": ["1 coulomb of charge stored at 1 volt", "1 henry of charge per volt", "1 ampere per second", "1 ohm per second"], "correct": 0, "short": "1 F = 1 C at 1 V", "expl": "One farad is one coulomb of charge stored with one volt across the plates.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-51", "topic": "Capacitors"}, {"q": "One microfarad (µF) equals:", "options": ["10^-12 farad", "10^-3 farad", "10^6 farad", "10^-6 farad"], "correct": 3, "short": "µF = 10^-6 F", "expl": "A microfarad is 10^-6 farad; a picofarad (pF) is 10^-12 farad.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-51", "topic": "Capacitors"}, {"q": "Which change INCREASES capacitance?", "options": ["Moving the plates farther apart", "Using smaller plates", "Moving the plates closer together", "Using a dielectric with a lower K"], "correct": 2, "short": "Closer plates = more C", "expl": "Closer plate spacing increases capacitance. Larger plate area and a higher-K dielectric also increase it.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-51", "topic": "Capacitors"}, {"q": "How do capacitors combine when connected in PARALLEL?", "options": ["They simply add: CT = C1 + C2 + C3", "Reciprocal rule (like resistors in parallel)", "They multiply together", "The total is the smallest value"], "correct": 0, "short": "Caps parallel ADD", "expl": "Capacitors in parallel ADD directly (effective plate area increases) - the OPPOSITE of resistors in parallel.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-54", "topic": "Capacitors"}, {"q": "C1 = 330 µF and C2 = 220 µF are wired in parallel. Total capacitance?", "options": ["132 µF", "110 µF", "550 µF", "72,600 µF"], "correct": 2, "short": "Parallel adds", "expl": "In parallel, capacitances add: 330 + 220 = 550 µF.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-54", "topic": "Capacitors"}, {"q": "Capacitors connected in SERIES are calculated:", "options": ["By simply adding them", "By the reciprocal rule, like resistors in parallel", "By multiplying them", "The same as inductors in series"], "correct": 1, "short": "Series caps = reciprocal", "expl": "Capacitors in series use the reciprocal rule (1/CT = 1/C1 + 1/C2 ...), like resistors in parallel; total is less than the smallest.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-54", "topic": "Capacitors"}, {"q": "The formula for capacitive reactance is:", "options": ["XC = 2πfC", "XC = 2πfL", "XC = R × C", "XC = 1/(2πfC)"], "correct": 3, "short": "XC = 1/(2πfC)", "expl": "Capacitive reactance XC = 1/(2πfC), in ohms.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-55", "topic": "Capacitive reactance"}, {"q": "As frequency increases, capacitive reactance (XC):", "options": ["Increases", "Decreases", "Stays the same", "Becomes infinite"], "correct": 1, "short": "XC falls with f", "expl": "Because XC = 1/(2πfC), higher frequency means LOWER capacitive reactance - opposite of inductive reactance.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-63", "topic": "Capacitive reactance"}, {"q": "Find XC for C = 200 µF (0.000200 F) at 60 cps.", "options": ["About 13 ohms", "About 55 ohms", "About 1,327 ohms", "About 2 ohms"], "correct": 0, "short": "XC=1/(6.28x60xC)", "expl": "XC = 1/(2πfC) = 1/(6.28 × 60 × 0.000200) = 1/0.07536 ≈ 13 ohms.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-61", "topic": "Capacitive reactance"}, {"q": "The 'ICE' half of 'ELI the ICE man' means:", "options": ["Voltage leads current in a capacitor", "Current equals voltage in a capacitor", "Capacitors store magnetic energy", "Current (I) leads voltage (E) in a capacitor (C)"], "correct": 3, "short": "ICE: I leads E in C", "expl": "ICE: in a capacitor (C), current (I) leads voltage (E).", "cite": "NCATT Study Guide p. 7", "topic": "Phase / ELI ICE"}, {"q": "In a purely capacitive AC circuit, the current:", "options": ["Lags the voltage by 90 degrees", "Is in phase with voltage", "Leads the voltage by 90 degrees", "Stops flowing entirely"], "correct": 2, "short": "Cap: I leads E", "expl": "In a capacitive circuit the current reaches maximum ahead of voltage - it leads by 90 degrees (ICE).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-56", "topic": "Phase / ELI ICE"}, {"q": "The RC time constant is the time for the capacitor voltage to reach what percent of the applied voltage?", "options": ["63.2%", "50%", "90%", "100%"], "correct": 0, "short": "τ = 63.2%", "expl": "One time constant (τ = R × C) is the time to reach 63.2% of applied voltage; ~5 time constants for full charge.", "cite": "NCATT Study Guide p. 18", "topic": "Capacitors"}, {"q": "For R = 10,000 ohms and C = 100 µF (0.0001 F), the time constant (τ = RC) is:", "options": ["10 seconds", "0.1 second", "1 second", "100 seconds"], "correct": 2, "short": "τ = R×C", "expl": "τ = R × C = 10,000 × 0.0001 = 1 second.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-52", "topic": "Capacitors"}, {"q": "Before handling or testing a capacitor, you should always:", "options": ["Heat it up first", "Discharge it (short the leads through a resistor)", "Reverse its polarity", "Measure its frequency"], "correct": 1, "short": "Discharge first", "expl": "A charged capacitor can hold a dangerous voltage; always discharge it before handling or testing.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-51", "topic": "Capacitor fault isolation"}, {"q": "You test a capacitor with an ohmmeter. A GOOD capacitor will:", "options": ["Read 0 ohms and stay there", "Read a steady mid-scale resistance forever", "Show negative resistance", "Momentarily read low, then climb to high/infinite"], "correct": 3, "short": "Charges then high", "expl": "A good cap charges (brief low reading) and then the reading rises toward high/infinite as charging current stops.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-52", "topic": "Capacitor fault isolation"}, {"q": "An ohmmeter on a capacitor reads 0 ohms and never changes. The capacitor is:", "options": ["Good", "Shorted", "Open", "Overcharged"], "correct": 1, "short": "0Ω = shorted", "expl": "A reading stuck at 0 ohms means the plates are touching - the capacitor is shorted; its electrical qualities are gone.", "cite": "NCATT Study Guide p. 19", "topic": "Capacitor fault isolation"}, {"q": "An ohmmeter on a capacitor reads infinite immediately with NO initial charging dip. This indicates:", "options": ["An open capacitor", "A shorted capacitor", "A perfectly good capacitor", "A reversed-polarity capacitor"], "correct": 0, "short": "No charge = open", "expl": "No momentary charging current (no dip) means the cap never charges - it is open.", "cite": "NCATT Study Guide p. 19", "topic": "Capacitor fault isolation"}, {"q": "Electrolytic capacitors are POLARIZED, which means:", "options": ["They work in any direction", "They have no dielectric", "They only work on DC of any polarity", "They must be installed observing + and - polarity"], "correct": 3, "short": "Electrolytics are polarized", "expl": "Electrolytic caps have marked + and - leads and must be installed with correct polarity or the dielectric breaks down.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-52", "topic": "Capacitor fault isolation"}, {"q": "By what process does energy cross from a transformer's primary to its secondary?", "options": ["Direct electrical connection", "Capacitive coupling", "Mutual induction (a shared changing magnetic field)", "Resistance heating"], "correct": 2, "short": "Mutual induction", "expl": "The windings are not electrically connected; the changing magnetic field of the primary induces voltage in the secondary by mutual induction.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-65", "topic": "Transformers"}, {"q": "A transformer will NOT operate on:", "options": ["Pure (steady) DC", "Alternating current", "Pulsating DC", "60 Hz AC"], "correct": 0, "short": "Needs a changing field", "expl": "A transformer needs a CHANGING voltage to create a changing magnetic field. Pure steady DC produces no change, so no transformation.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-65", "topic": "Transformers"}, {"q": "The transformer turns-ratio relationship is:", "options": ["Vp/Vs = Ns/Np", "Vp × Vs = Np × Ns", "Vp/Vs = Np/Ns", "Vp/Vs = R only"], "correct": 2, "short": "Vp/Vs = Np/Ns", "expl": "Voltage divides in proportion to turns: Vp/Vs = Np/Ns.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-66", "topic": "Transformers"}, {"q": "A transformer with MORE turns on the secondary than the primary is a:", "options": ["Step-down transformer", "Step-up transformer", "Isolation-only transformer", "Current transformer"], "correct": 1, "short": "More sec turns = step-up", "expl": "More secondary turns gives a higher secondary voltage - a step-UP transformer.", "cite": "NCATT Study Guide p. 19", "topic": "Transformers"}, {"q": "If a transformer steps the voltage UP, what happens to the current?", "options": ["It steps up by the same ratio", "It stays the same", "It drops to zero", "It steps down by the same ratio"], "correct": 3, "short": "Current is inverse", "expl": "Current is inverse to voltage (power in ≈ power out). Step voltage up = step current down by the same ratio.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-66", "topic": "Transformers"}, {"q": "Primary = 240 V on 100 turns; secondary = 25 turns. Secondary voltage?", "options": ["960 V", "60 V", "240 V", "25 V"], "correct": 1, "short": "Vs=Vp(Ns/Np)", "expl": "Vs = Vp × (Ns/Np) = 240 × (25/100) = 60 V (a step-down).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-66", "topic": "Transformers"}, {"q": "Primary = 10 V on 50 turns; secondary = 500 turns. Secondary voltage?", "options": ["100 V", "1 V", "50 V", "5,000 V"], "correct": 0, "short": "Vs=10x(500/50)", "expl": "Vs = 10 × (500/50) = 10 × 10 = 100 V (a 1:10 step-up).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-66", "topic": "Transformers"}, {"q": "A 4:1 step-up transformer is fed 10 V at 4 A on the primary. The secondary output is:", "options": ["40 V at 16 A", "2.5 V at 1 A", "10 V at 4 A", "40 V at 1 A"], "correct": 3, "short": "Power stays same", "expl": "4:1 step-up: voltage 10×4 = 40 V; current 4/4 = 1 A. Power (40 W) is unchanged.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-66", "topic": "Transformers"}, {"q": "You check a transformer winding with an ohmmeter and it reads INFINITE ohms. The winding is:", "options": ["Shorted", "Normal", "Open (broken - no continuity)", "Reversed"], "correct": 2, "short": "Infinite = open winding", "expl": "A healthy winding shows continuity (low resistance). Infinite ohms means an open winding - the wire is broken.", "cite": "NCATT Study Guide p. 20", "topic": "Transformer fault isolation"}, {"q": "A transformer secondary that is OPEN will produce what output voltage with power on the primary?", "options": ["Zero volts (no coupling)", "The full rated voltage", "Twice the rated voltage", "Exactly the primary voltage"], "correct": 0, "short": "Open sec = 0 V out", "expl": "An open secondary has no coupling action, so the fault shows as zero volts output.", "cite": "NCATT Study Guide p. 20", "topic": "Transformer fault isolation"}, {"q": "When checking for SHORTED turns, the affected winding's resistance will typically read:", "options": ["Infinite", "Much higher than normal", "Lower than the normal/spec value", "Exactly normal"], "correct": 2, "short": "Shorted turns = low R", "expl": "Shorted turns bypass part of the winding, so its measured resistance reads lower than the normal specified value (and it overheats).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-67", "topic": "Transformer fault isolation"}, {"q": "A resistance check between a transformer's primary winding and its core should read:", "options": ["Zero ohms", "Infinite (windings isolated from core)", "A low resistance", "The same as the winding resistance"], "correct": 1, "short": "Winding-to-core = open", "expl": "Windings must be insulated from the core and each other, so that reading should be infinite. A low reading means insulation breakdown.", "cite": "NCATT Study Guide p. 20", "topic": "Transformer fault isolation"}, {"q": "The safest way to verify a transformer's ratio is correct is to:", "options": ["Apply DC and measure resistance only", "Leave the current-transformer secondary open under load", "Measure capacitance across the windings", "Apply safe AC and compare secondary/primary voltage to the rated turns ratio"], "correct": 3, "short": "Compare V ratio to N ratio", "expl": "Apply safe AC and compare the measured Vs/Vp to the rated Ns/Np. Never leave a current-transformer secondary open while energized.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p. 12-67", "topic": "Transformer fault isolation"}], "drill": [{"label": "Inductor opposes", "text": "An inductor opposes a CHANGE in current and stores energy in a MAGNETIC field. Unit = henry (H)."}, {"label": "Capacitor opposes", "text": "A capacitor opposes a CHANGE in voltage and stores energy in an ELECTRIC field. Unit = farad (F)."}, {"label": "Inductive reactance", "text": "XL = 2πfL (ohms). Inductive reactance RISES as frequency rises."}, {"label": "Capacitive reactance", "text": "XC = 1/(2πfC) (ohms). Capacitive reactance FALLS as frequency rises."}, {"label": "ELI the ICE man", "text": "ELI: voltage (E) leads current (I) in an inductor (L). ICE: current (I) leads voltage (E) in a capacitor (C)."}, {"label": "Caps in parallel", "text": "Capacitors in PARALLEL ADD: CT = C1 + C2 + C3 (opposite of resistors). In series, use the reciprocal rule."}, {"label": "Inductors combine", "text": "Inductors combine like resistors: series adds (LT = L1+L2+...), parallel uses the reciprocal rule."}, {"label": "Henry definition", "text": "1 henry = current changing 1 ampere per second induces 1 volt."}, {"label": "Farad definition", "text": "1 farad = 1 coulomb stored at 1 volt. µF = 10^-6 F, pF = 10^-12 F."}, {"label": "RC time constant", "text": "Time constant τ = R × C = time to reach 63.2% of applied voltage; ~5τ for full charge."}, {"label": "Turns ratio", "text": "Transformer: Vp/Vs = Np/Ns. Vs = Vp × (Ns/Np). Current is INVERSE to voltage."}, {"label": "Step up vs down", "text": "More secondary turns = step-UP (higher V, lower I). Fewer secondary turns = step-DOWN (lower V, higher I)."}, {"label": "Mutual induction", "text": "A transformer transfers energy by mutual induction and needs a CHANGING voltage (AC). Pure DC will not transform."}, {"label": "Fault tests", "text": "Cap ohmmeter: charges then high/infinite = good; 0Ω = shorted; no charge = open. Winding: infinite = open; low = shorted turns. Discharge caps first."}]}, {"n": 5, "title": "Semiconductors & Analog", "standards": "14", "lesson": "<h3>Why this matters on the flight line</h3>\n<p>Almost every black box on a modern aircraft &mdash; radios, nav receivers, the\nvoltage regulator on the generator, the bridge rectifier that feeds the DC bus,\nevery annunciator LED on the panel &mdash; runs on <strong>semiconductors</strong>.\nIf you understand the <strong>diode</strong> (a one-way valve) and the\n<strong>transistor</strong> (a tiny faucet that lets a small signal control a big\none), you understand the heart of avionics. <strong>Standard 14</strong> wants you\nto explain how analog circuits, devices, and switches work. We start at the atom\nand build up.</p>\n\n<h3>What is a semiconductor? (the in-between material)</h3>\n<p>Think of three buckets:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Conductor</strong> &mdash; lets current flow easily (copper, aluminum).\nLots of free electrons.</li>\n<li><strong>Insulator</strong> &mdash; blocks current (rubber, glass). Almost no free\nelectrons.</li>\n<li><strong>Semiconductor</strong> &mdash; sits <em>in between</em>. By itself it is\na poor conductor, but we can <strong>control</strong> exactly when and how it\nconducts. That control is the whole trick.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The two semiconductor materials you must know are <strong>silicon (Si)</strong>\n&mdash; by far the most common &mdash; and <strong>germanium (Ge)</strong>. A pure\nsilicon crystal is not very useful on its own. We make it useful by\n<strong>doping</strong> it.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">DOPING</span> Doping is the process of adding tiny\namounts of <strong>impurities</strong> to a pure semiconductor to increase its\ncurrent flow &mdash; either by adding a few extra <strong>electrons</strong> or a few\n<strong>holes</strong>. After doping, the material is one of two types:\n<strong>N&#8209;type</strong> or <strong>P&#8209;type</strong>. <em>(FAA-H-8083-30B\np.&nbsp;12&#8209;96)</em></div>\n\n<h3>N-type and P-type &mdash; the two flavors</h3>\n<p>Picture a parking lot.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>N&#8209;type</strong> = <strong>N</strong>egative carriers\n(<strong>extra electrons</strong>). We add a \"donor\" impurity such as phosphorus,\narsenic, or antimony &mdash; atoms with <strong>five</strong> outer electrons. That\nfifth electron has nowhere to bond, so it is free to move. In N&#8209;type the\n<strong>electrons are the majority carrier</strong>. (Parking lot with extra cars\nroaming around.)</li>\n<li><strong>P&#8209;type</strong> = <strong>P</strong>ositive carriers\n(<strong>holes</strong>). We add an \"acceptor\" impurity such as boron, aluminum, or\ngallium &mdash; atoms with only <strong>three</strong> outer electrons. The missing\nfourth bond leaves an empty spot called a <strong>hole</strong>. In P&#8209;type the\n<strong>holes are the majority carrier</strong>. (Parking lot with empty spaces; as a\ncar moves into an empty space, the empty space appears to move the other way.)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Key mental model: an <strong>electron</strong> is a real negative charge that moves;\na <strong>hole</strong> is the <em>absence</em> of an electron that <em>appears</em> to\nmove as a positive charge in the opposite direction.\n<em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;96 to 12&#8209;97)</em></p>\n\n<h3>The PN junction = the DIODE (a one-way valve)</h3>\n<p>One type of material alone is not very useful. The magic happens when you join a\npiece of <strong>P&#8209;type</strong> to a piece of <strong>N&#8209;type</strong>.\nThat boundary is the <strong>PN junction</strong>, and that single junction is a\n<strong>diode</strong>. A diode is a two&#8209;element device that lets current flow\n<strong>in one direction only</strong> &mdash; exactly like a one&#8209;way check\nvalve in a fuel or hydraulic line.</p>\n<p>Where the P and N meet, electrons and holes combine and form a thin\n<strong>depletion region</strong> &mdash; a little \"no&#8209;flow zone\" with a built&#8209;in\nvoltage <strong>barrier</strong>. Whether current flows depends on which way you push\non that barrier, which we call <strong>bias</strong>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">FORWARD BIAS = CONDUCTS</span> Connect the\n<strong>positive</strong> source to the <strong>P</strong> side and the\n<strong>negative</strong> source to the <strong>N</strong> side. This shrinks the\nbarrier, the valve opens, and current flows easily. The diode only needs to overcome\na small turn&#8209;on voltage first:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Silicon (Si): about 0.7&nbsp;V</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Germanium (Ge): about 0.3&nbsp;V</strong></li>\n</ul>\nBelow that, even forward&#8209;biased, almost nothing flows.\n<em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;98 to 12&#8209;99)</em></div>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">REVERSE BIAS = BLOCKS</span> Turn the battery\naround &mdash; <strong>positive</strong> to <strong>N</strong>, <strong>negative</strong>\nto <strong>P</strong>. This <em>widens</em> the depletion region, the barrier grows,\nand current does <strong>not</strong> flow (only a tiny leakage of a few microamps).\nThe valve is shut. <em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;99)</em></div>\n\n<p><strong>The one sentence to memorize:</strong> a PN&#8209;junction diode offers\n<strong>very little resistance when forward biased</strong> and\n<strong>maximum resistance when reverse biased</strong>. That is what makes it the\nbuilding block of a <strong>rectifier</strong> &mdash; the circuit that converts AC to\nDC by only letting current through on one half of the wave.\n<em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;99 to 12&#8209;100)</em></p>\n\n<table>\n<tr><th>Bias condition</th><th>Connection</th><th>Depletion region</th><th>Current</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Forward</strong></td><td>+ to P, &minus; to N</td><td>Narrows</td><td><strong>Flows</strong> (after 0.7&nbsp;V Si)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Reverse</strong></td><td>+ to N, &minus; to P</td><td>Widens</td><td><strong>Blocked</strong> (tiny leakage)</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>Reading the diode &mdash; anode, cathode, the band</h3>\n<p>A diode has two ends: the <strong>anode</strong> (the P side, marked +) and the\n<strong>cathode</strong> (the N side, marked &minus;). Current (conventional flow)\ngoes <strong>anode &rarr; cathode</strong>. Manufacturers mark the\n<strong>cathode</strong> end with a <strong>band</strong>, a dot, colored stripe, or\nthe letter \"k.\" On the schematic symbol, the triangle points from anode to cathode and\nthe <strong>bar</strong> is the cathode. <em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;105 to 12&#8209;106)</em></p>\n\n<h3>Special diodes you must know</h3>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">ZENER DIODE = VOLTAGE REGULATOR</span> A Zener (or\n\"breakdown\" diode) is built to be run <strong>in reverse bias on purpose</strong>.\nBelow its rated voltage it blocks like any reverse&#8209;biased diode. But once the\n<strong>reverse voltage reaches its rated breakdown value</strong>, it suddenly\nconducts and then <strong>holds that voltage constant</strong> &mdash; behaving like a\nconstant&#8209;voltage source. That is why the Zener's job is\n<strong>voltage regulation</strong> (keeping a steady voltage on a bus or reference).\nCommon ratings: 2&nbsp;V to 200&nbsp;V. <em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;103)</em></div>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">LED = LIGHT-EMITTING DIODE</span> An ordinary diode\nturns its energy into <strong>heat</strong>. An LED is built (using gallium, arsenic,\nphosphorus) so that when it is <strong>forward biased</strong>, electrons falling into\nholes release their energy as <strong>light</strong> instead of heat. Used for panel\nindicators, annunciators, instruments, even cabin lighting. Advantages over an\nincandescent bulb: longer life, lower voltage, faster on/off, less heat.\n<em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;103)</em></div>\n\n<p>Other special diodes named in the handbook (general familiarization): the\n<strong>varactor</strong> (a voltage&#8209;controlled capacitor used for tuning), the\n<strong>Schottky</strong> (metal&#8209;to&#8209;silicon, no depletion zone, very fast\nswitching), and the <strong>photodiode</strong>. The two you must be able to explain\ncold are the <strong>Zener (regulation)</strong> and the <strong>LED (light)</strong>.\n<em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;104 to 12&#8209;105)</em></p>\n\n<h3>The TRANSISTOR (the controllable faucet)</h3>\n<p>A diode is one junction. A <strong>transistor</strong> is a\n<strong>three&#8209;terminal device</strong> made of <strong>two</strong> PN junctions\n&mdash; one type of material sandwiched between two of the other. Its job is to\n<strong>amplify</strong> signals and to <strong>switch</strong> current on and off.\nThe three terminals are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Emitter (E)</strong> &mdash; heavily doped; it <em>emits</em> (sends out)\nthe carriers.</li>\n<li><strong>Base (B)</strong> &mdash; the thin, lightly doped middle layer; it is the\n<strong>control</strong> terminal.</li>\n<li><strong>Collector (C)</strong> &mdash; moderately doped; it <em>collects</em> the\ncarriers.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Faucet analogy:</strong> the <strong>base</strong> is the handle. A\n<strong>small base current</strong> (a light touch on the handle) controls a\n<strong>large collector current</strong> (a big gush of water from emitter to\ncollector). A little control &rarr; a lot of output. That is\n<strong>amplification</strong>. Push the handle all the way one direction = fully on;\nall the way the other = fully off. That on/off use is\n<strong>switching</strong>. <em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;105 to 12&#8209;107)</em></p>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">THE TRANSISTOR RULE</span> A\n<strong>small base current controls a large collector current.</strong> For the\ntransistor to amplify, the <strong>emitter&#8209;base junction is forward biased</strong>\n(low resistance, ~0.65&ndash;0.7&nbsp;V on a silicon part) and the\n<strong>collector&#8209;base junction is reverse biased</strong> (high resistance). A\nlow&#8209;power signal injected at the forward&#8209;biased junction produces a\nhigh&#8209;power signal at the reverse&#8209;biased junction.\n<em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;106 to 12&#8209;107)</em></div>\n\n<h3>NPN vs. PNP</h3>\n<p>Because there are two ways to stack the sandwich, there are two transistor types:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>NPN</strong> &mdash; a thin layer of <strong>P</strong> between two\n<strong>N</strong> layers. On the schematic symbol the emitter arrow points\n<strong>OUT</strong> (handy memory: <strong>N</strong>ot <strong>P</strong>ointing in /\narrow <strong>N</strong>ot in).</li>\n<li><strong>PNP</strong> &mdash; a thin layer of <strong>N</strong> between two\n<strong>P</strong> layers. The emitter arrow points <strong>IN</strong>\n(<strong>P</strong>oints i<strong>N</strong>).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The arrow is always on the <strong>emitter</strong>. Arrow direction is the only\nvisual difference between the two symbols, and it tells you the type and the direction\nof conventional current at the emitter. <em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;105 to 12&#8209;106)</em></p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Type</th><th>Layers</th><th>Emitter arrow</th><th>Memory</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>NPN</strong></td><td>N&ndash;P&ndash;N</td><td>Points OUT</td><td>\"<strong>N</strong>ot pointi<strong>N</strong>\"</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>PNP</strong></td><td>P&ndash;N&ndash;P</td><td>Points IN</td><td>\"<strong>P</strong>oints i<strong>N</strong>\"</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>The basic amplifier idea (in one breath)</h3>\n<p>Feed a small input signal into the <strong>forward&#8209;biased base&#8209;emitter</strong>\njunction (low resistance, low current). The same current is forced to flow through the\n<strong>reverse&#8209;biased collector</strong> side across a <strong>high&#8209;resistance</strong>\nload. Same current &times; much higher resistance = much higher power out. The ratio of\noutput to input is called <strong>gain</strong>. The\n<strong>common&#8209;emitter (CE)</strong> configuration gives the best mix of voltage\nand current gain (and inverts the signal 180&deg;), which is why it is the most popular\namplifier wiring. <em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;106, 12&#8209;109)</em></p>\n\n<h3>The other family member: the FET</h3>\n<p>The ordinary transistor above is a <strong>bipolar</strong> transistor and is\n<strong>current&#8209;controlled</strong> (base current is the control). Its cousin the\n<strong>FET</strong> (field&#8209;effect transistor) has terminals\n<strong>source, gate, drain</strong> and is <strong>voltage&#8209;controlled</strong>\n(the gate <em>voltage</em> is the control, drawing almost no current &mdash; very high\ninput resistance). The two FET sub&#8209;types are the <strong>JFET</strong> and the\n<strong>MOSFET</strong>. Like all solid&#8209;state parts, FETs are easily killed by\nstatic &mdash; observe ESD precautions. You do not need FET math for Standard 14, just\nknow it exists and that gate <em>voltage</em> controls source&ndash;drain current.\n<em>(p.&nbsp;12&#8209;108)</em></p>\n\n<h3>Analog switches, relays &amp; solenoids (Standard 14 terms)</h3>\n<p>The Study Guide's term list for Standard 14 is mostly about\n<strong>switches</strong> &mdash; the analog devices that open and close circuits. Know\nthese:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pole</strong> = how many separate circuits the switch controls.\n<strong>Throw</strong> = how many positions/contacts each pole can connect to. So:\n<strong>SPST</strong> (single pole single throw &mdash; simple on/off),\n<strong>SPDT</strong> (single pole double throw &mdash; one circuit, two choices),\n<strong>DPST</strong> (double pole single throw), <strong>DPDT</strong> (double pole\ndouble throw &mdash; two circuits, each with two choices).</li>\n<li><strong>Relay</strong> &mdash; an <strong>electrically controlled</strong> switch:\na small coil current opens/closes contacts to operate a larger circuit (electrical\nversion of the transistor&#8209;as&#8209;switch idea).</li>\n<li><strong>Solenoid</strong> &mdash; an electromagnet with a <strong>movable iron\ncore</strong> pulled into the coil when energized (used for high&#8209;current loads\nlike the starter contactor).</li>\n<li><strong>Normally Open (NO)</strong> = contacts held <em>open</em> by a spring until\nenergized. <strong>Normally Closed (NC)</strong> = contacts held <em>closed</em> by a\nspring until energized.</li>\n<li><strong>Micro switch</strong> &mdash; a precision switch that controls mechanical\nmovement (e.g., gear position). <strong>Proximity switch</strong> &mdash; usually a\nsolid&#8209;state device that detects a target <strong>without physical contact</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Toggle switch</strong> &mdash; the type <strong>most susceptible to shock\nand vibration</strong> in an aircraft; its contacts can open momentarily then re&#8209;close.\nOther electromechanical types: rocker, push&#8209;button, plunger, rotary (selects one of\nseveral circuits).</li>\n<li><strong>Derating</strong> &mdash; deliberately using a switch below its nominal\nrating to get reliable efficiency under reactive (inductive) loads.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>(NCATT AET Study Guide, Standard 14, pp.&nbsp;20&ndash;21)</em></p>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">&#9733; Key numbers &amp; terms (asked almost verbatim)</span>\n<table>\n<tr><td><strong>Semiconductor</strong></td><td>material between a conductor and an insulator; Si or Ge</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Doping</strong></td><td>adding impurities &rarr; N&#8209;type or P&#8209;type</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>N&#8209;type</strong></td><td>extra <strong>electrons</strong> (majority carrier = electrons)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>P&#8209;type</strong></td><td>extra <strong>holes</strong> (majority carrier = holes)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Diode</strong></td><td>one PN junction; one&#8209;way valve</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Forward bias</strong></td><td>+ to P / &minus; to N &rarr; conducts</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Reverse bias</strong></td><td>+ to N / &minus; to P &rarr; blocks</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Turn-on voltage</strong></td><td><strong>Si &asymp; 0.7&nbsp;V</strong>, Ge &asymp; 0.3&nbsp;V</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Zener diode</strong></td><td>runs in reverse breakdown &rarr; <strong>voltage regulation</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>LED</strong></td><td>forward&#8209;biased diode that emits <strong>light</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Transistor</strong></td><td>3 terminals (E, B, C); amplify &amp; switch</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Transistor rule</strong></td><td>small <strong>base</strong> current controls large <strong>collector</strong> current</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>NPN</strong></td><td>arrow points OUT</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>PNP</strong></td><td>arrow points IN</td></tr>\n</table></div>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example &mdash; will this diode conduct?</span>\nA silicon diode has its <strong>anode (P)</strong> tied to +12&nbsp;V and its\n<strong>cathode (N)</strong> tied to ground (0&nbsp;V). Anode is more positive than\ncathode &rarr; <strong>forward biased</strong>. 12&nbsp;V is well above the 0.7&nbsp;V\nturn&#8209;on, so <strong>yes, it conducts</strong>, dropping about 0.7&nbsp;V across\nitself. Flip the battery (cathode +12&nbsp;V, anode 0&nbsp;V) &rarr;\n<strong>reverse biased &rarr; blocks.</strong></div>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example &mdash; transistor as a switch</span>\nAn <strong>NPN</strong> transistor controls a 28&nbsp;V annunciator lamp on the\ncollector. With <strong>no base current</strong>, the transistor is OFF &mdash; lamp\ndark. Apply a small current to the <strong>base</strong> (drive base&ndash;emitter past\n~0.7&nbsp;V), the transistor turns fully ON, the large collector current flows, and the\nlamp lights. A milliamp at the base controlled an amp at the collector &mdash;\namplification used as a switch.</div>\n\n<h3>Check yourself</h3>\n<div class=\"selfq\">1. You dope silicon with phosphorus (5 outer electrons). Is the\nresult N&#8209;type or P&#8209;type, and what is the majority carrier?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: N&#8209;type; the majority carrier is the\n<strong>electron</strong> (the extra 5th electron). P&#8209;type comes from 3&#8209;electron\nimpurities and its carrier is the hole.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">2. A silicon diode is forward biased. About how much voltage does it\ndrop, and what would a germanium diode drop?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: Silicon &asymp; <strong>0.7&nbsp;V</strong>; germanium &asymp;\n<strong>0.3&nbsp;V</strong>.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">3. You connect the positive supply to the N side and negative to the P\nside of a diode. Forward or reverse biased? Does current flow?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: <strong>Reverse biased</strong> (+ to N, &minus; to P). The\ndepletion region widens and current is <strong>blocked</strong> (only tiny leakage).</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">4. What is the specific job of a Zener diode, and which bias direction\ndoes it use?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: <strong>Voltage regulation</strong> &mdash; it operates in\n<strong>reverse</strong> breakdown and holds a constant voltage once its rated breakdown\nvoltage is reached.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">5. In a transistor, which terminal's small current controls the large\ncurrent, and which two terminals does that large current flow between?\n<span class=\"a\">Answer: The small <strong>base</strong> current controls the large\ncurrent, which flows from <strong>emitter to collector</strong>.</span></div>\n\n<p><strong>What's next &mdash; Module 6: Power Supplies &amp; Filters (Standards 15, 16,\n17).</strong> Now that you know the diode is a one&#8209;way valve, you'll see how a\n<strong>rectifier</strong> uses one or more diodes to chop AC into DC (half&#8209;wave and\nfull&#8209;wave bridge), then how <strong>filters</strong> smooth that lumpy DC into clean\npower for the avionics bus. Aim for &ge;73% on this Module 5 quiz before moving on.</p>", "quiz": [{"q": "A semiconductor's electrical behavior places it where compared to other materials?", "options": ["It is between a conductor and an insulator", "It is a perfect insulator like glass", "It has no electrons in its outer shell", "It is a better conductor than copper"], "correct": 0, "short": "Between conductor and insulator", "expl": "A semiconductor conducts better than an insulator but worse than a true conductor; its usefulness is that we can control when it conducts.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-96", "topic": "semiconductor-basics"}, {"q": "Which two elements are the common semiconductor materials?", "options": ["Copper and aluminum", "Silicon and germanium", "Boron and phosphorus", "Selenium and gold"], "correct": 1, "short": "Silicon and germanium", "expl": "Silicon (Si) is the most common semiconductor; germanium (Ge) is the other. Boron and phosphorus are doping impurities, not the base material.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-96", "topic": "semiconductor-basics"}, {"q": "What is doping?", "options": ["Coating the crystal with copper oxide", "Heating silicon until it melts", "Adding small amounts of impurities to increase current flow", "Removing all free electrons from the crystal"], "correct": 2, "short": "Adding impurities to a semiconductor", "expl": "Doping adds impurities that contribute either extra electrons or extra holes, creating N-type or P-type material.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-96", "topic": "doping"}, {"q": "An N-type semiconductor's majority current carriers are:", "options": ["Ions", "Holes", "Protons", "Electrons"], "correct": 3, "short": "Electrons", "expl": "N-type is doped with 5-electron (donor) impurities, leaving an excess of electrons as the majority carrier.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-96", "topic": "n-type"}, {"q": "A P-type semiconductor's majority current carriers are:", "options": ["Holes", "Neutrons", "Free protons", "Electrons"], "correct": 0, "short": "Holes", "expl": "P-type is doped with 3-electron (acceptor) impurities, leaving 'holes' (missing electrons) as the majority carrier.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-97", "topic": "p-type"}, {"q": "A 'hole' in a semiconductor is best described as:", "options": ["A physical crack in the crystal", "An empty place where an electron would go, which acts like a positive charge", "An extra electron that bonds to silicon", "A region of pure copper"], "correct": 1, "short": "An empty electron position acting positive", "expl": "A hole is the absence of an electron; as electrons shift to fill holes, the hole appears to move as a positive charge.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-96", "topic": "p-type"}, {"q": "How many PN junctions does a basic diode have?", "options": ["Three", "Zero", "One", "Two"], "correct": 2, "short": "One PN junction", "expl": "A diode is a single PN junction formed by joining P-type and N-type material. The '1N' prefix on diode part numbers means one junction.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-98", "topic": "diode-basics"}, {"q": "The fundamental job of a diode is to:", "options": ["Step voltage up or down", "Oppose changes in current", "Store electric charge like a capacitor", "Allow current to flow in one direction only"], "correct": 3, "short": "One-way current flow", "expl": "A diode is a one-way valve; it conducts when forward biased and blocks when reverse biased, which lets it rectify AC into DC.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-98", "topic": "diode-basics"}, {"q": "To FORWARD bias a diode, you connect:", "options": ["Positive to the P side, negative to the N side", "Both terminals to the same polarity", "Nothing; a diode needs no bias", "Positive to the N side, negative to the P side"], "correct": 0, "short": "Positive to P, negative to N", "expl": "Forward bias puts positive on the P (anode) and negative on the N (cathode), shrinking the barrier so current flows.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-98", "topic": "forward-bias"}, {"q": "A diode connected positive-to-N and negative-to-P is:", "options": ["Forward biased and conducting", "Reverse biased and blocking", "Short circuited", "Acting as an amplifier"], "correct": 1, "short": "Reverse biased, blocking", "expl": "Positive to N / negative to P widens the depletion region and blocks current (only tiny leakage). This is reverse bias.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-99", "topic": "reverse-bias"}, {"q": "Approximately what forward voltage drop does a SILICON diode have?", "options": ["5 volts", "0.3 volts", "0.7 volts", "1.4 volts"], "correct": 2, "short": "About 0.7 V", "expl": "A silicon PN junction turns on at about 0.7 V; germanium is about 0.3 V.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-107", "topic": "forward-bias"}, {"q": "Approximately what forward voltage drop does a GERMANIUM diode have?", "options": ["0.0 volts", "2.0 volts", "0.7 volts", "0.3 volts"], "correct": 3, "short": "About 0.3 V", "expl": "Germanium turns on at roughly 0.3 V, lower than silicon's 0.7 V.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-99", "topic": "forward-bias"}, {"q": "A PN-junction diode offers maximum resistance when it is:", "options": ["Reverse biased", "Carrying its rated current", "At 0.7 volts", "Forward biased"], "correct": 0, "short": "Reverse biased", "expl": "Forward bias = very little resistance; reverse bias = maximum resistance (essentially blocks current).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-99", "topic": "reverse-bias"}, {"q": "When a diode is reverse biased, the depletion region:", "options": ["Disappears completely", "Gets wider", "Stays exactly the same", "Fills with copper"], "correct": 1, "short": "Gets wider", "expl": "Reverse bias pulls carriers away from the junction, widening the depletion region and blocking current.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-99", "topic": "reverse-bias"}, {"q": "The marked band (or dot) on a diode body indicates which terminal?", "options": ["The gate", "The anode", "The cathode", "The base"], "correct": 2, "short": "The cathode", "expl": "Manufacturers mark the cathode (N side) with a band, dot, colored stripe, or the letter 'k'.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-105", "topic": "diode-basics"}, {"q": "What is the primary function of a Zener diode?", "options": ["Amplify a small signal", "Store energy in a magnetic field", "Emit light when forward biased", "Regulate (hold constant) a voltage"], "correct": 3, "short": "Voltage regulation", "expl": "A Zener operates in reverse breakdown and holds a constant voltage, acting as a voltage regulator.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-103", "topic": "zener"}, {"q": "In what bias condition is a Zener diode normally operated?", "options": ["Reverse bias (breakdown)", "No bias", "Alternating bias only", "Forward bias"], "correct": 0, "short": "Reverse breakdown", "expl": "Unlike an ordinary diode, the Zener is run in reverse at its rated breakdown voltage, where it conducts and regulates.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-103", "topic": "zener"}, {"q": "A Zener diode behaves like what once its rated reverse voltage is reached?", "options": ["An open circuit", "A constant-voltage source", "A pure resistor", "An inductor"], "correct": 1, "short": "A constant-voltage source", "expl": "At breakdown the Zener conducts and clamps the voltage, behaving like a constant-voltage source for regulation.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-103", "topic": "zener"}, {"q": "An LED produces light when it is:", "options": ["Operated at breakdown", "Reverse biased", "Forward biased", "Disconnected"], "correct": 2, "short": "Forward biased", "expl": "In a forward-biased LED, electrons falling into holes release energy as light instead of heat.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-103", "topic": "led"}, {"q": "Compared to an incandescent lamp, an LED offers all of these advantages EXCEPT:", "options": ["Longer life", "Lower operating voltage", "Faster on/off operation", "Much higher heat output"], "correct": 3, "short": "It does NOT produce more heat", "expl": "LEDs produce LESS heat, not more; they also have longer life, lower voltage, and faster switching.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-103", "topic": "led"}, {"q": "How many terminals does a transistor have?", "options": ["Three", "Four", "One", "Two"], "correct": 0, "short": "Three terminals", "expl": "A transistor is a three-terminal device: emitter, base, and collector.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-105", "topic": "transistor-terminals"}, {"q": "The three terminals of a bipolar transistor are:", "options": ["Anode, cathode, gate", "Emitter, base, collector", "Source, gate, drain", "Primary, secondary, core"], "correct": 1, "short": "Emitter, base, collector", "expl": "Emitter (heavily doped), base (thin, lightly doped control layer), and collector (moderately doped).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-105", "topic": "transistor-terminals"}, {"q": "The two primary functions of a transistor are to:", "options": ["Step up and step down", "Rectify and filter", "Amplify and switch", "Store and discharge"], "correct": 2, "short": "Amplify and switch", "expl": "A transistor is used primarily to amplify signals and to switch (control) current within a circuit.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-105", "topic": "transistor-function"}, {"q": "Which transistor terminal is the CONTROL terminal?", "options": ["Cathode", "Emitter", "Collector", "Base"], "correct": 3, "short": "The base", "expl": "The thin base layer is the control terminal; a small base current controls a large collector current.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-107", "topic": "transistor-function"}, {"q": "In a working transistor, a small current at the base controls a large current at the:", "options": ["Collector", "Source", "Gate", "Anode"], "correct": 0, "short": "Collector", "expl": "The core transistor rule: a small base current controls a large collector current (the basis of amplification).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-107", "topic": "transistor-function"}, {"q": "For a transistor to amplify, the emitter-base junction is ___ and the collector-base junction is ___.", "options": ["reverse biased / forward biased", "forward biased / reverse biased", "forward biased / forward biased", "reverse biased / reverse biased"], "correct": 1, "short": "Forward / reverse", "expl": "Emitter-base is forward biased (low resistance) and collector-base is reverse biased (high resistance), producing power gain.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-106", "topic": "transistor-function"}, {"q": "An NPN transistor is built as:", "options": ["Two P layers only", "Three N layers", "P material between two N layers", "N material between two P layers"], "correct": 2, "short": "N-P-N stack", "expl": "NPN = a thin P layer sandwiched between two N layers. PNP is the opposite.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-105", "topic": "npn-pnp"}, {"q": "On a schematic symbol, an NPN transistor's emitter arrow points:", "options": ["Straight up", "There is no arrow", "Inward (toward the base)", "Outward (away from the base)"], "correct": 3, "short": "Outward", "expl": "NPN emitter arrow points OUT ('Not pointiN in'); PNP points IN ('Points iN').", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-106", "topic": "npn-pnp"}, {"q": "A transistor symbol whose emitter arrow points INWARD is which type?", "options": ["PNP", "JFET", "Zener", "NPN"], "correct": 0, "short": "PNP", "expl": "Arrow pointing IN = PNP; arrow pointing OUT = NPN. The arrow is always on the emitter.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-106", "topic": "npn-pnp"}, {"q": "The transistor terminal that is the most heavily doped and emits the carriers is the:", "options": ["Collector", "Emitter", "Gate", "Base"], "correct": 1, "short": "Emitter", "expl": "The emitter is heavily doped and emits carriers; the collector is moderately doped; the base is lightly doped and thin.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-105", "topic": "transistor-terminals"}, {"q": "Unlike the bipolar transistor (current-controlled), a FET is:", "options": ["Not a semiconductor at all", "A type of diode", "Voltage-controlled, via its gate", "Current-controlled, via its base"], "correct": 2, "short": "Voltage-controlled (gate)", "expl": "A FET (JFET/MOSFET) uses gate VOLTAGE to control source-to-drain current and has very high input resistance.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-108", "topic": "transistor-function"}, {"q": "Gain, as used with transistor amplifiers, means:", "options": ["The reverse leakage current", "The number of junctions", "The amount of heat lost", "The magnitude of amplification (output vs. input)"], "correct": 3, "short": "Magnitude of amplification", "expl": "Gain expresses how much the transistor amplifies; the common-emitter (CE) configuration gives the best voltage/current gain combination.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-109", "topic": "transistor-function"}, {"q": "A relay is best described as:", "options": ["An electrically controlled switch that opens/closes contacts to operate another circuit", "A device that stores charge", "A pure mechanical hinge with no coil", "A diode that emits light"], "correct": 0, "short": "Electrically controlled switch", "expl": "A relay uses a small coil current to open/close contacts controlling a larger circuit, much like a transistor used as a switch.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide Std 14 p.21", "topic": "analog-switches"}, {"q": "'Normally Open' (NO) relay contacts are:", "options": ["Held closed by a spring until energized", "Held open by a spring until energized", "Welded shut permanently", "Always carrying current"], "correct": 1, "short": "Held open by spring until energized", "expl": "NO contacts are held open by a spring and close when the relay is energized; NC contacts are the opposite.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide Std 14 p.21", "topic": "analog-switches"}, {"q": "'DPDT' describes a switch that is:", "options": ["A proximity sensor", "Single pole, single throw", "Double pole, double throw", "Diode-protected, dual-tap"], "correct": 2, "short": "Double Pole Double Throw", "expl": "DPDT = Double Pole Double Throw: two separate circuits, each able to connect to either of two positions.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide Std 14 p.20", "topic": "analog-switches"}, {"q": "Which switch type is described as the MOST susceptible to shock and vibration in an aircraft?", "options": ["Proximity switch", "Micro switch", "Rotary switch", "Toggle switch"], "correct": 3, "short": "Toggle switch", "expl": "The Study Guide notes the toggle switch is most susceptible to shock/vibration; its contacts may open momentarily then re-close.", "cite": "NCATT AET Study Guide Std 14 p.21", "topic": "analog-switches"}], "drill": [{"label": "Semiconductor", "text": "A material BETWEEN a conductor and an insulator; the two are silicon (Si) and germanium (Ge)."}, {"label": "Doping", "text": "Adding impurities to a semiconductor to make it N-type (extra electrons) or P-type (extra holes)."}, {"label": "N-type / P-type", "text": "N-type = majority carrier is the ELECTRON; P-type = majority carrier is the HOLE."}, {"label": "Diode", "text": "One PN junction; a ONE-WAY valve that passes current in only one direction."}, {"label": "Forward bias", "text": "+ to P / - to N -> diode CONDUCTS. Reverse bias (+ to N / - to P) -> diode BLOCKS."}, {"label": "Diode drop", "text": "Forward voltage drop: SILICON about 0.7 V; GERMANIUM about 0.3 V."}, {"label": "Diode resistance", "text": "Very LOW resistance forward biased; MAXIMUM resistance reverse biased."}, {"label": "Zener diode", "text": "Run in REVERSE breakdown on purpose -> its job is VOLTAGE REGULATION (holds a constant voltage)."}, {"label": "LED", "text": "A FORWARD-biased diode that emits LIGHT (less heat, longer life, lower voltage than a bulb)."}, {"label": "Transistor", "text": "Three terminals - Emitter, Base, Collector; used to AMPLIFY and SWITCH."}, {"label": "Transistor rule", "text": "A small BASE current controls a large COLLECTOR current (amplification)."}, {"label": "NPN vs PNP", "text": "NPN emitter arrow points OUT; PNP emitter arrow points IN. Arrow is always on the emitter."}]}, {"n": 6, "title": "Power Supplies & Filters", "standards": "15, 16, 17", "lesson": "<h3>Why this matters on a real aircraft</h3>\n<p>Almost every avionics box on an airplane needs <strong>clean, steady DC voltage</strong> to work. But a lot of aircraft power is <strong>AC</strong> (from alternators, inverters, the 115&nbsp;V 400&nbsp;Hz bus). A <strong>power supply</strong> is the circuit that turns that messy AC into smooth DC. If the power supply or its filters fail, your radio hums, your display flickers, or the box just dies. Standards <strong>15 (Rectifiers)</strong>, <strong>16 (Filters)</strong>, and <strong>17 (Frequency-Sensitive Filters)</strong> are all about this job.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">The whole job in one line</span>\n<p>A power supply does four things in order: <strong>STEP DOWN &rarr; RECTIFY &rarr; FILTER &rarr; REGULATE</strong>. Memorize that chain. Each stage cleans the power up a little more.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>STEP DOWN</strong> (transformer) &mdash; lower the AC voltage to what we need.</li>\n<li><strong>RECTIFY</strong> (diodes) &mdash; force the AC to flow one direction only &rarr; <em>pulsating DC</em>.</li>\n<li><strong>FILTER</strong> (capacitor/inductor) &mdash; smooth the pulses into nearly flat DC.</li>\n<li><strong>REGULATE</strong> (Zener/regulator) &mdash; hold the voltage rock-steady as the load changes.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Stage 1 &mdash; The Transformer (step down)</h3>\n<p>The transformer takes the high AC line voltage and <strong>steps it down</strong> to the lower AC voltage the circuit needs. It does not change AC into DC &mdash; it only changes the <em>size</em> of the AC. (You learned transformers in Module 4: turns ratio sets the voltage ratio.) It also <strong>isolates</strong> the box from the main power line for safety.</p>\n\n<h3>Stage 2 &mdash; The Rectifier (AC &rarr; pulsating DC)</h3>\n<p>This is the heart of Standard 15. A <strong>rectifier</strong> uses <strong>diodes</strong> to convert AC into DC. The Study Guide defines a diode as <em>\"the simplest semiconductor, formed when an N-type material is joined with a P-type material,\"</em> and says diodes <strong>\"allow current to flow in one direction only.\"</strong> Changing AC into DC this way is called <strong>rectification</strong>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Analogy: one-way turnstiles</span>\n<p>Think of diodes as <strong>one-way turnstiles</strong> in a subway. AC current tries to flow back and forth, but the diodes only let it go one way. What comes out the other side is current that always flows in the same direction &mdash; DC. It's bumpy (it \"pulses\"), but it never reverses.</p></div>\n\n<p><strong>Forward bias vs. reverse bias.</strong> A silicon diode needs about <strong>0.7&nbsp;VDC</strong> of the correct polarity to turn ON (low-resistance state) &mdash; that's <strong>forward bias</strong>. With voltage the wrong way, the diode is OFF (high-resistance state) and acts like an open switch &mdash; that's <strong>reverse bias</strong>. (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-98 to 12-99.)</p>\n\n<h4>The three rectifier circuits you must know</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Rectifier</th><th># of diodes</th><th>What it does with the AC wave</th><th>Output / ripple</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Half-wave</strong></td><td><strong>1 diode</strong></td><td>Keeps only the positive half; the negative half is thrown away (diode is reverse biased, current = 0)</td><td>Worst &mdash; big gaps, <strong>roughest</strong> ripple, least efficient</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Full-wave center-tap</strong></td><td><strong>2 diodes</strong></td><td>Flips the negative half up using a center-tapped transformer</td><td>Better &mdash; no gaps, smoother, double the pulse rate</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Full-wave bridge</strong></td><td><strong>4 diodes</strong></td><td>Flips the negative half up using a 4-diode bridge (no center tap needed)</td><td>Best &mdash; no gaps, smoothest of the three, most common</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">How the full-wave BRIDGE works (4 diodes)</span>\n<p>On the <strong>positive</strong> half-cycle, two diodes (D1 &amp; D3) are forward biased and conduct; the other two are reverse biased (open). On the <strong>negative</strong> half-cycle, the other pair (D2 &amp; D4) conducts. The key point from FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-102: <em>\"during both alternations of the input waveform, the current passes through the load resistor in the same direction.\"</em> The negative swing gets <strong>flipped up</strong> to the positive side &mdash; that's why there are no gaps.</p></div>\n\n<p><strong>Ripple.</strong> The output of any rectifier is not flat DC &mdash; it's <strong>pulsating DC</strong>. That leftover AC bumpiness riding on the DC is called <strong>ripple</strong>. <strong>Less ripple = cleaner DC.</strong> Half-wave has the most ripple; full-wave (bridge or center-tap) has less because it fills in the gaps. The Study Guide ties <strong>ripple amplitude</strong> to the <em>frequency of the ripple in the rectifier output</em>.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Three-phase rectifier.</strong> On bigger aircraft systems, three-phase AC is rectified. Because three phases overlap, the output is already very smooth &mdash; very low ripple &mdash; even before filtering.</p>\n\n<h3>Stage 3 &mdash; The Filter (smooth the pulses)</h3>\n<p>Standard 16. A rectifier gives pulsating DC; the <strong>filter</strong> smooths those pulses into nearly flat DC. The two workhorses are the <strong>capacitor</strong> and the <strong>inductor (choke)</strong>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Analogy: a reservoir behind a dam</span>\n<p>A <strong>capacitor filter is like a water reservoir.</strong> When the rectifier pulse is high, the capacitor <strong>charges</strong> (the reservoir fills). When the pulse drops toward zero in the valley, the capacitor <strong>discharges</strong> into the load (the reservoir releases water to keep the river flowing). It <strong>fills in the valleys</strong>, so the load sees a steadier voltage. FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-111: the capacitor <em>\"charges when the rectifier output tends to increase and discharges when the voltage output tends to decrease&hellip; the voltage across the load is kept fairly constant.\"</em></p></div>\n\n<table>\n<tr><th>Filter element</th><th>How it's connected</th><th>What it does</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Capacitor</strong> (C)</td><td><strong>Parallel</strong> with the load</td><td>Low impedance to AC ripple (bypasses it to ground); high impedance to DC (passes DC to load). Fills the valleys.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Inductor / choke</strong> (L)</td><td><strong>Series</strong> with the load</td><td>High impedance to AC ripple (blocks it); low impedance to DC (passes DC). Opposes changes in current.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>LC filter</strong></td><td>Choke in series + cap in parallel</td><td>Combines both &mdash; much smoother than either alone.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Pi (&pi;) filter</strong></td><td>Cap &ndash; choke &ndash; cap (looks like the letter &pi;)</td><td>Best smoothing of the common passive filters.</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Capacitor input vs. choke input.</strong> A <strong>capacitor-input filter</strong> has the capacitor connected first, directly across the rectifier output. A <strong>choke-input filter</strong> puts the choke first. (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-111.)</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Active vs. passive filters (Study Guide, Standard 16)</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Passive filter</strong> &mdash; <em>\"produces no gain\"</em>; built only from R, L, and C; no external power. The capacitor/inductor power-supply filters above are passive.</li>\n<li><strong>Active filter</strong> &mdash; <em>\"produces a current or voltage gain\"</em>; uses an amplifier (like an op-amp) plus R and C, and needs power to run.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Stage 4 &mdash; The Regulator (hold voltage steady)</h3>\n<p>Even after filtering, the DC voltage can drift up and down when the <strong>load</strong> changes or the input sags. A <strong>regulator</strong> locks it to a fixed value. The Study Guide says the job of <strong>Power Supply Circuits</strong> is to <em>\"keep the output voltage constant as the load current changes.\"</em></p>\n<p>The classic part is the <strong>Zener diode</strong>. A Zener is run in <strong>reverse</strong> and is built to \"break down\" at a chosen voltage (2&ndash;200&nbsp;V). Once the circuit reaches that voltage, the Zener conducts and <em>\"behaves like a constant voltage source,\"</em> holding the output steady. (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-103.) That's why a Zener is the basic <strong>voltage regulator</strong>.</p>\n\n<h3>Standard 17 &mdash; Frequency-Sensitive Filters</h3>\n<p>Standards 15&ndash;16 cleaned up <em>power</em>. Standard 17 is about filters that pick which <strong>frequencies</strong> of a <em>signal</em> get through. The Study Guide's definition: frequency-sensitive filters <em>\"pass a certain range of frequencies from the generator to the load and reject all others,\"</em> are <em>\"placed between the signal source and the load,\"</em> and <em>\"act as frequency-sensitive voltage dividers.\"</em></p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">The secret: reactance changes with frequency</span>\n<p>Remember from Module 4:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Capacitor:</strong> X<sub>C</sub> = 1 / (2&pi;fC). As frequency goes <strong>up</strong>, X<sub>C</sub> goes <strong>down</strong> &mdash; a cap passes HIGH frequencies, blocks LOW.</li>\n<li><strong>Inductor:</strong> X<sub>L</sub> = 2&pi;fL. As frequency goes <strong>up</strong>, X<sub>L</sub> goes <strong>up</strong> &mdash; an inductor blocks HIGH frequencies, passes LOW.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Filters just arrange R, C, and L so this frequency-dependent reactance steers the signal where you want it.</p></div>\n\n<h4>The four frequency-sensitive filters</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Filter</th><th>Passes</th><th>Blocks (attenuates)</th><th>Built from</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Low-pass</strong></td><td><strong>Low</strong> frequencies</td><td>High frequencies</td><td>R&ndash;C (cap across load) or R&ndash;L (inductor in series)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>High-pass</strong></td><td><strong>High</strong> frequencies</td><td>Low frequencies</td><td>R&ndash;C (cap in series) &mdash; opposite of low-pass</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Band-pass</strong></td><td>A <strong>middle band</strong> of frequencies</td><td>Frequencies above and below the band</td><td>Low-pass + high-pass <strong>in series</strong> (resonant circuit)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Band-stop</strong> (band-reject / notch)</td><td>Everything <strong>except</strong> the band</td><td>One middle band</td><td>Low-pass + high-pass <strong>in parallel</strong></td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Cutoff frequency</strong> is the dividing line &mdash; the Study Guide says it's <em>\"the frequency at which attenuation starts to increase rapidly.\"</em> Below/above it (depending on the filter), the signal gets cut.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Crystals and tuning.</strong> Very precise filters use <strong>quartz crystals</strong> (piezoelectric) that <em>\"vibrate at a specific resonant frequency when voltage is applied.\"</em> A <strong>tuning circuit</strong> is a resonant L&ndash;C circuit you can adjust to change the frequency it selects. (Study Guide, Standard 17.)</p>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Plain analogies for the four filters</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Low-pass</strong> = a bass speaker (subwoofer): lets the low rumble through, cuts the highs.</li>\n<li><strong>High-pass</strong> = a tweeter: lets the highs through, cuts the lows.</li>\n<li><strong>Band-pass</strong> = tuning a radio to one station: only that band gets through.</li>\n<li><strong>Band-stop / notch</strong> = removing one annoying hum frequency while keeping everything else.</li>\n</ul></div>\n\n<h3>Putting it all together</h3>\n<p>AC comes in &rarr; the <strong>transformer</strong> steps it down &rarr; the <strong>rectifier</strong> (1, 2, or 4 diodes) makes pulsating DC &rarr; the <strong>filter</strong> (cap/choke) smooths the ripple &rarr; the <strong>regulator</strong> (Zener) holds it steady &rarr; clean DC out to the avionics box. Standard 17's frequency-sensitive filters are a separate tool for picking signal frequencies, not for power smoothing &mdash; but they use the same X<sub>C</sub>/X<sub>L</sub> ideas.</p>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">A rectifier built from <strong>4 diodes</strong> with no center tap is called what? <span class=\"a\">Answer: a full-wave bridge rectifier.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Which rectifier produces the <strong>most ripple</strong> and is the least efficient? <span class=\"a\">Answer: the half-wave rectifier (1 diode &mdash; it throws away half the wave).</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">In a capacitor filter, what happens during the <strong>valley</strong> between rectifier pulses? <span class=\"a\">Answer: the capacitor discharges into the load, filling the valley and keeping the voltage fairly constant (the reservoir analogy).</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">A filter that <strong>passes low frequencies and blocks high frequencies</strong> is called what? <span class=\"a\">Answer: a low-pass filter.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">What component is the basic <strong>voltage regulator</strong> that holds DC steady by breaking down at a set reverse voltage? <span class=\"a\">Answer: a Zener diode.</span></div>", "quiz": [{"q": "What is the overall job of a power supply circuit?", "options": ["Turn DC into AC", "Increase a signal's frequency", "Turn messy AC into clean, steady DC", "Store energy magnetically"], "correct": 2, "short": "AC in, clean DC out", "expl": "A power supply steps down, rectifies, filters, and regulates so an avionics box gets steady DC.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 15; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-100", "topic": "power-supply"}, {"q": "In the power-supply chain, which order is correct?", "options": ["Filter -> Rectify -> Regulate -> Step down", "Rectify -> Step down -> Regulate -> Filter", "Step down -> Rectify -> Filter -> Regulate", "Regulate -> Filter -> Rectify -> Step down"], "correct": 2, "short": "Step down, rectify, filter, regulate", "expl": "Transformer steps down, diodes rectify, cap/choke filters, Zener/regulator holds it steady.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-100 to 12-112", "topic": "power-supply"}, {"q": "A rectifier converts AC into DC using which component?", "options": ["Diodes", "Resistors", "Transformers only", "Crystals"], "correct": 0, "short": "Diodes", "expl": "Diodes allow current to flow one direction only, which is rectification.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 15; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-100", "topic": "rectifier"}, {"q": "How many diodes are in a HALF-WAVE rectifier?", "options": ["1", "2", "4", "6"], "correct": 0, "short": "1 diode", "expl": "A half-wave rectifier uses a single diode and passes only one half of the AC wave.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-101", "topic": "rectifier-diodes"}, {"q": "How many diodes are in a full-wave BRIDGE rectifier?", "options": ["1", "2", "8", "4"], "correct": 3, "short": "4 diodes", "expl": "A full-wave bridge uses four diodes and needs no center-tapped transformer.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-102", "topic": "rectifier-diodes"}, {"q": "How many diodes does a full-wave CENTER-TAP rectifier use?", "options": ["1", "2", "4", "3"], "correct": 1, "short": "2 diodes", "expl": "A center-tap full-wave rectifier uses two diodes with a center-tapped transformer.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-102", "topic": "rectifier-diodes"}, {"q": "Which rectifier produces the MOST ripple (roughest output)?", "options": ["Full-wave bridge", "Half-wave", "Full-wave center-tap", "Three-phase"], "correct": 1, "short": "Half-wave", "expl": "Half-wave throws away half the AC cycle, leaving big gaps and the most ripple.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-101", "topic": "ripple"}, {"q": "Why is a full-wave rectifier smoother than a half-wave?", "options": ["It uses bigger diodes", "It raises the voltage", "It removes the DC component", "It flips the negative half-cycle up, filling the gaps"], "correct": 3, "short": "It fills the gaps", "expl": "Full-wave conducts on both alternations so current always flows the same direction through the load with no gaps.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-102", "topic": "rectifier"}, {"q": "The output of a rectifier (before filtering) is best described as:", "options": ["Pulsating DC", "Pure AC", "Pure flat DC", "A square wave only"], "correct": 0, "short": "Pulsating DC", "expl": "Rectified output is DC that pulses; it never reverses but is not yet smooth.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-101 to 12-102", "topic": "rectifier"}, {"q": "'Ripple' in a power supply refers to:", "options": ["The leftover AC bumpiness riding on the DC output", "The diode forward voltage", "The transformer turns ratio", "The cutoff frequency of a filter"], "correct": 0, "short": "Leftover AC on the DC", "expl": "Ripple is the residual AC variation in a rectifier's DC output; less ripple = cleaner DC.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 15; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-111", "topic": "ripple"}, {"q": "Per the Study Guide, a diode is formed when:", "options": ["Two N-type materials are joined", "Two resistors are placed in series", "An N-type material is joined with a P-type material", "A coil is wound on iron"], "correct": 2, "short": "N joined with P", "expl": "A diode is the simplest semiconductor, an N-type joined to a P-type (a PN junction).", "cite": "Study Guide Std 15", "topic": "diode"}, {"q": "About how much forward voltage does a silicon diode need to start conducting?", "options": ["0 volts", "7 volts", "12 volts", "0.7 volts"], "correct": 3, "short": "0.7 VDC", "expl": "It takes roughly 0.7 VDC of correct polarity to forward-bias a silicon diode.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 15; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-98", "topic": "diode-bias"}, {"q": "A reverse-biased diode behaves like:", "options": ["A short circuit", "An open circuit (high resistance)", "A capacitor", "An amplifier"], "correct": 1, "short": "Open circuit", "expl": "Reverse bias is a high-resistance state; the diode blocks current and acts like an open switch.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 15; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-99", "topic": "diode-bias"}, {"q": "What does the FILTER stage of a power supply do?", "options": ["Steps the voltage down", "Smooths pulsating DC into nearly flat DC", "Converts AC to DC", "Generates a carrier frequency"], "correct": 1, "short": "Smooths the pulses", "expl": "The filter removes ripple, turning pulsating DC into nearly steady DC.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-111", "topic": "filter"}, {"q": "In a capacitor filter, how is the capacitor connected to the load?", "options": ["In series with the load", "Across the transformer primary", "In place of the diode", "In parallel with the load"], "correct": 3, "short": "Parallel with the load", "expl": "The filter capacitor is connected in parallel with the load to bypass AC ripple to ground.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-111", "topic": "filter-cap"}, {"q": "How does a capacitor smooth the rectifier output?", "options": ["It charges on the pulse peaks and discharges into the load during the valleys", "It blocks all DC", "It converts DC back to AC", "It increases the ripple frequency"], "correct": 0, "short": "Charges on peaks, discharges in valleys", "expl": "Like a reservoir, the cap fills the valleys by discharging when the rectifier output dips, keeping voltage constant.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-111", "topic": "filter-cap"}, {"q": "In a filter, the inductor (choke) is connected:", "options": ["In parallel with the load", "Across the rectifier diode", "In series with the load", "In place of the regulator"], "correct": 2, "short": "In series", "expl": "A filter choke is placed in series; it offers high impedance to AC ripple and low impedance to DC.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-111", "topic": "filter-choke"}, {"q": "Why does a series choke help filter ripple?", "options": ["High impedance to AC ripple, low impedance to DC", "It shorts the DC to ground", "It rectifies the remaining AC", "It steps up the voltage"], "correct": 0, "short": "Blocks AC, passes DC", "expl": "An inductor opposes current change, so it blocks the AC ripple while passing DC.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-111", "topic": "filter-choke"}, {"q": "A filter shaped C-choke-C, resembling a Greek letter, is called a:", "options": ["L filter", "T filter", "Notch filter", "Pi filter"], "correct": 3, "short": "Pi filter", "expl": "A pi-type filter (capacitor, choke, capacitor) resembles the Greek letter pi and gives strong smoothing.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-111 to 12-112", "topic": "filter-config"}, {"q": "Per the Study Guide, a PASSIVE filter:", "options": ["Produces a current or voltage gain", "Always uses an op-amp", "Produces no gain and needs no external power", "Only works on DC"], "correct": 2, "short": "No gain", "expl": "Passive filters use only R, L, and C, produce no gain, and require no external power source.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 16; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-112", "topic": "active-passive"}, {"q": "Per the Study Guide, an ACTIVE filter:", "options": ["Uses only resistors", "Produces a current or voltage gain", "Produces no gain", "Is the same as a rectifier"], "correct": 1, "short": "Has gain", "expl": "An active filter produces a current or voltage gain and uses an amplifier plus R/C.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 16", "topic": "active-passive"}, {"q": "What is the job of the REGULATION stage?", "options": ["Convert AC to DC", "Increase the ripple", "Keep the output voltage constant as the load current changes", "Select a signal frequency"], "correct": 2, "short": "Hold voltage steady", "expl": "Regulation keeps output voltage constant despite load or input changes.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 15 (Power Supply Circuits); FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-103", "topic": "regulation"}, {"q": "Which component is the classic voltage regulator that holds DC steady at a set value?", "options": ["A Zener diode", "A standard rectifier diode", "An LED", "A varactor"], "correct": 0, "short": "Zener diode", "expl": "A Zener diode breaks down at a chosen reverse voltage and acts like a constant-voltage source.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-103", "topic": "regulation"}, {"q": "How is a Zener diode operated when used as a regulator?", "options": ["Forward biased near 0.7 V", "Reverse biased at its breakdown voltage", "With no bias at all", "As an oscillator"], "correct": 1, "short": "Reverse biased at breakdown", "expl": "A Zener regulates by operating in reverse breakdown, where it holds a constant voltage.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-103", "topic": "regulation"}, {"q": "A LOW-PASS filter:", "options": ["Passes low frequencies, blocks high", "Passes high frequencies, blocks low", "Blocks all frequencies", "Passes only one narrow band"], "correct": 0, "short": "Passes low, blocks high", "expl": "A low-pass filter passes low frequencies and attenuates frequencies above the cutoff.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 17; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-112", "topic": "low-pass"}, {"q": "A HIGH-PASS filter:", "options": ["Passes low frequencies, attenuates high", "Passes high frequencies, attenuates low", "Rejects a middle band", "Passes everything equally"], "correct": 1, "short": "Passes high, blocks low", "expl": "A high-pass filter passes high frequencies and attenuates those below the cutoff; it is the opposite of low-pass.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 17; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-112", "topic": "high-pass"}, {"q": "A BAND-PASS filter:", "options": ["Rejects a middle band of frequencies", "Passes a middle band while attenuating high and low frequencies", "Passes only DC", "Passes all frequencies above cutoff"], "correct": 1, "short": "Passes a middle band", "expl": "A band-pass filter passes a chosen middle band and attenuates frequencies above and below it.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 17; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-112", "topic": "band-pass"}, {"q": "A BAND-STOP (band-reject / notch) filter:", "options": ["Passes only one middle band", "Passes most frequencies but attenuates one middle band", "Passes only low frequencies", "Is the same as a low-pass filter"], "correct": 1, "short": "Rejects one band", "expl": "A band-stop/notch filter passes most frequencies but strongly attenuates one band; it is the opposite of band-pass.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 17; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-112", "topic": "band-stop"}, {"q": "A band-pass filter is built by combining a high-pass and low-pass filter connected:", "options": ["Back-to-back as diodes", "In parallel", "In series", "Through a transformer"], "correct": 2, "short": "In series", "expl": "Connecting a low-pass and high-pass in series forms a band-pass filter.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-112", "topic": "band-pass"}, {"q": "A band-stop filter is built by combining a high-pass and low-pass filter connected:", "options": ["In series", "Through a center tap", "In a bridge", "In parallel"], "correct": 3, "short": "In parallel", "expl": "Connecting a low-pass and high-pass in parallel forms a band-stop (notch) filter.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-112", "topic": "band-stop"}, {"q": "As frequency increases, capacitive reactance (Xc):", "options": ["Increases", "Stays the same", "Decreases", "Becomes infinite"], "correct": 2, "short": "Xc goes down", "expl": "Xc = 1/(2*pi*f*C); higher frequency means lower Xc, so a capacitor passes highs and blocks lows.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-112 (filter operation)", "topic": "reactance"}, {"q": "As frequency increases, inductive reactance (Xl):", "options": ["Increases", "Decreases", "Stays the same", "Goes to zero"], "correct": 0, "short": "Xl goes up", "expl": "Xl = 2*pi*f*L; higher frequency means higher Xl, so an inductor blocks highs and passes lows.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-112 (filter operation)", "topic": "reactance"}, {"q": "The Study Guide says frequency-sensitive filters act as:", "options": ["Amplifiers with gain", "Constant current sources", "Frequency-sensitive voltage dividers", "Rectifiers"], "correct": 2, "short": "Frequency-sensitive voltage dividers", "expl": "Filters sit between source and load and act as frequency-sensitive voltage dividers.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 17", "topic": "freq-filter"}, {"q": "Per the Study Guide, the 'cutoff frequency' is:", "options": ["The ripple amplitude", "The diode forward voltage", "The transformer resonance", "The frequency where attenuation starts to increase rapidly"], "correct": 3, "short": "Where attenuation ramps up", "expl": "Cutoff frequency is the frequency at which attenuation begins to increase rapidly.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 17", "topic": "cutoff"}, {"q": "Quartz crystals used in precise filters work because they:", "options": ["Store DC charge", "Amplify signals", "Rectify AC", "Vibrate at a specific resonant frequency when voltage is applied"], "correct": 3, "short": "Piezoelectric resonance", "expl": "Piezoelectric quartz crystals vibrate at a set resonant frequency when voltage is applied, giving very selective filtering.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 17", "topic": "crystal"}, {"q": "A three-phase rectifier output, compared to a single-phase half-wave output, has:", "options": ["Much more ripple", "Reversed polarity", "No DC component", "Much less ripple (smoother)"], "correct": 3, "short": "Less ripple", "expl": "Overlapping phases make three-phase rectifier output very smooth, with low ripple even before filtering.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 15", "topic": "rectifier"}], "drill": [{"label": "Power-supply chain", "text": "Step down -> Rectify -> Filter -> Regulate (AC in, clean DC out)."}, {"label": "Half-wave rectifier", "text": "Uses 1 diode; passes one half of the AC wave; most ripple, least efficient."}, {"label": "Full-wave center-tap", "text": "Uses 2 diodes with a center-tapped transformer; smoother than half-wave."}, {"label": "Full-wave bridge", "text": "Uses 4 diodes; no center tap needed; smoothest of the three; most common."}, {"label": "Diode", "text": "Simplest semiconductor (P joined to N); allows current one direction only = rectification."}, {"label": "Forward bias", "text": "About 0.7 VDC of correct polarity turns a silicon diode ON (low resistance)."}, {"label": "Ripple", "text": "Leftover AC bumpiness on the DC output; less ripple = cleaner DC."}, {"label": "Capacitor filter", "text": "Connected in parallel with the load; charges on peaks, discharges in valleys to smooth DC."}, {"label": "Choke (inductor) filter", "text": "Connected in series; blocks AC ripple, passes DC."}, {"label": "Zener diode", "text": "Reverse-biased regulator; breaks down at a set voltage and holds output constant."}, {"label": "Low-pass filter", "text": "Passes LOW frequencies, attenuates HIGH frequencies."}, {"label": "High-pass filter", "text": "Passes HIGH frequencies, attenuates LOW frequencies."}, {"label": "Band-pass filter", "text": "Passes a MIDDLE band; low-pass + high-pass in SERIES."}, {"label": "Band-stop / notch", "text": "Rejects one middle band, passes the rest; low-pass + high-pass in PARALLEL."}, {"label": "Active vs passive", "text": "Passive filter = no gain (R/L/C only); active filter = has gain (uses an amplifier)."}]}, {"n": 7, "title": "Signal Circuits", "standards": "18, 19", "lesson": "<h3>Why this matters on a real aircraft</h3>\n<p>So far every circuit you've studied either <em>moved</em> power around or <em>cleaned it up</em>. Now we build circuits that <strong>create a signal</strong> and circuits that <strong>shape a signal</strong>. An <strong>oscillator</strong> is the heartbeat of almost every avionics box: it makes the radio carrier wave, the clock pulse in a computer, the tone in an audio warning, and the timing in a navigation set. A <strong>limiter (clipper)</strong> trims a waveform down so it can't get too big and damage the next stage, or so it comes out the exact shape the circuit needs. Standard <strong>18 (Wave Generation Circuits)</strong> is the oscillator; Standard <strong>19 (Limiter Circuits)</strong> is the clipper.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Note</span>\n<p>These are <strong>NCATT Level A/B</strong> tasks &mdash; the exam wants you to <em>identify basic facts and terms</em>, not design the circuit. So learn the <strong>names, what each one does, and the key definitions verbatim</strong>. You do not have to do the math.</p></div>\n\n<h3>Part 1 &mdash; Wave Generation (Standard 18)</h3>\n\n<h4>What an oscillator is</h4>\n<p>The Study Guide's exact definition: an oscillator is an <em>\"electronic circuit that converts DC into AC at predetermined frequencies and amplitudes.\"</em> In plain English: <strong>you feed it steady DC, and it spits out a repeating AC waveform</strong> &mdash; over and over, at a frequency and size you chose when you built it. Its <em>\"primary purpose is to generate a repetitive waveform at a constant (peak-to-peak) amplitude and specific frequency and to maintain this waveform within certain limits.\"</em></p>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Example</span>\n<p>Think of a <strong>child on a swing</strong>. Give one steady push at the right moment each time (that's the DC energy and the feedback), and the swing keeps going back and forth at its own steady rhythm. Stop pushing and friction slows it to a stop. An oscillator is that swing: the amplifier supplies the little push each cycle, and the LC or RC network sets the rhythm (the frequency).</p></div>\n\n<h4>The three things every oscillator needs</h4>\n<p>Memorize these three ingredients &mdash; the exam loves the \"what does an oscillator require\" question:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>1. Amplification (a gain device).</strong> The Study Guide says: <em>\"without the amplifier, electronic oscillation would be quickly dampened out by the resistance in the wiring of the circuit.\"</em> The amplifier replaces the energy lost to resistance each cycle &mdash; that's the \"push\" on the swing. (Usually a transistor or op-amp.)</li>\n<li><strong>2. Positive (regenerative) feedback.</strong> Some of the output is fed back to the input <em>in phase</em>, so it reinforces itself. The Study Guide is blunt: <em>\"a regenerative feedback path makes any amplifier an oscillator.\"</em> Positive feedback = regenerative feedback.</li>\n<li><strong>3. A frequency-determining network.</strong> A part that decides the rhythm &mdash; either an <strong>LC</strong> (inductor + capacitor \"tank\") network or an <strong>RC</strong> (resistor + capacitor) network, or a <strong>crystal</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Key terms</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Oscillator</strong> &mdash; converts DC into AC at a predetermined frequency and amplitude; makes a repeating waveform.</li>\n<li><strong>Regenerative feedback</strong> &mdash; positive feedback; \"makes any amplifier an oscillator.\"</li>\n<li><strong>Frequency-determining network</strong> &mdash; the LC tank, RC, or crystal that sets the frequency.</li>\n<li><strong>Amplifier</strong> &mdash; replaces circuit losses so the oscillation doesn't die out (damp out).</li>\n</ul></div>\n\n<h4>Named oscillators in the Study Guide</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Oscillator</th><th>What it is (Study Guide wording)</th><th>Output</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>LC tank oscillator</strong></td><td>Used in communications receivers; <em>\"stores energy alternately in the inductor and the capacitor\"</em></td><td>Sine wave (sinusoidal)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Hartley oscillator</strong></td><td>Uses a <strong>tapped coil in parallel with a capacitor</strong> to control the AC frequency</td><td>Sine wave</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Crystal-controlled oscillator</strong></td><td>Contains a piezoelectric crystal; <em>\"output frequency is determined by the resonant frequency of the crystal\"</em></td><td>Sine wave</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Example: the LC \"tank\"</span>\n<p>An inductor and a capacitor wired together pass energy back and forth: the cap charges, dumps into the coil's magnetic field, the field collapses and recharges the cap the other way, and so on. The Study Guide says this storage method <em>\"produces an output that is sinusoidal\"</em> &mdash; a smooth sine wave. It's called a <strong>tank</strong> because it holds energy sloshing back and forth, like water in a tank. An LC tank can <em>\"produce useful power at two or three times the frequency of the fundamental pulse rate.\"</em></p></div>\n\n<h4>Crystal oscillators = stability</h4>\n<p>A <strong>quartz crystal</strong> is <strong>piezoelectric</strong>: apply a voltage and it vibrates at one very precise resonant frequency (and vibrating it makes a voltage). Because that quartz frequency barely drifts with temperature or age, a <strong>crystal-controlled oscillator is the most stable / most accurate</strong> oscillator. That's why radios, transponders, and computer clocks use crystals &mdash; you need the frequency to stay nailed down. <strong>Crystal = stability</strong> is the one-line takeaway.</p>\n\n<h4>Waveform types you must recognize</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Waveform</th><th>Looks like</th><th>Plain description</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Sine</strong></td><td>Smooth rolling hills</td><td>The natural waveform of AC power and LC/crystal oscillators; smooth, no sharp corners.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Square</strong></td><td>Flat tops and bottoms, vertical sides</td><td>Snaps between two levels (HIGH/LOW). Used for clocks and digital timing.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Sawtooth</strong></td><td>A slow ramp up, then a sudden drop</td><td>Ramps up steadily then snaps back to zero; used to sweep an old CRT/radar display.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Triangle</strong></td><td>Even ramp up, even ramp down</td><td>Like sawtooth but the down-slope is as slow as the up-slope; a symmetrical \"tent.\"</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Wave-shaping circuits: the multivibrators</h4>\n<p>A <strong>multivibrator</strong> is a two-transistor circuit where the transistors <strong>take turns conducting</strong> &mdash; one ON while the other is OFF, then they swap. It naturally makes <strong>square/rectangular</strong> waves and pulses (not smooth sine waves). There are exactly <strong>three types</strong>, and the exam wants you to match each to \"how many stable states\":</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Multivibrator</th><th>Stable states</th><th>Study Guide definition / what it does</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Astable</strong> (free-running)</td><td><strong>Zero</strong> stable states</td><td><em>\"Two conditions of temporary stability and no permanent condition of stability.\"</em> It never rests &mdash; it flips back and forth on its own, so it runs free and makes a continuous square wave. (A = \"not stable.\")</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Monostable</strong> (one-shot)</td><td><strong>One</strong> stable state</td><td><em>\"One permanent stable mode of operation.\"</em> It rests in one state until a trigger kicks it; it puts out one pulse, then falls back. (\"Mono\" = one.)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Bistable</strong> (flip-flop)</td><td><strong>Two</strong> stable states</td><td><em>\"One transistor conducts until an external pulse stops it; then the other transistor takes over.\"</em> It needs a trigger to change <em>and</em> stays put either way &mdash; that's a memory cell / flip-flop. (\"Bi\" = two.)</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Note</span>\n<p>Easy memory hook: count the stable states. <strong>A-stable = 0</strong> (none, free-running), <strong>Mono-stable = 1</strong> (one), <strong>Bi-stable = 2</strong> (two, a flip-flop you'll meet again in the Digital module). The prefix tells you the number.</p></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">What three things does every oscillator need to keep oscillating? <span class=\"a\">Answer: (1) an amplifier (gain), (2) positive/regenerative feedback, and (3) a frequency-determining network (LC, RC, or crystal).</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Why does an oscillator need an amplifier at all? <span class=\"a\">Answer: without it, the oscillation would quickly damp out (die) due to the resistance in the circuit wiring; the amplifier replaces the lost energy each cycle.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Which oscillator is the most stable/accurate, and why? <span class=\"a\">Answer: the crystal-controlled oscillator &mdash; the piezoelectric quartz crystal's resonant frequency barely drifts, so the output frequency stays locked.</span></div>\n\n<h3>Part 2 &mdash; Limiter / Clipper Circuits (Standard 19)</h3>\n\n<h4>What a limiter does</h4>\n<p>A <strong>limiter</strong> (also called a <strong>clipper</strong>) <strong>chops off part of a waveform's amplitude</strong> &mdash; it sets a ceiling (and/or floor) and won't let the signal go past it. Two reasons you'd want that:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Protection</strong> &mdash; keep a too-big spike from reaching and damaging a sensitive stage downstream.</li>\n<li><strong>Wave shaping</strong> &mdash; deliberately flatten the top (or bottom) of a wave to change its shape &mdash; for example, clip a sine wave hard enough on both sides and it starts to look like a square wave.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Example</span>\n<p>Think of the <strong>governor on a go-kart engine</strong>. No matter how hard you mash the pedal, the governor caps the top speed. A limiter does the same to voltage: the signal can do whatever it wants <em>below</em> the limit, but the moment it tries to climb past the set level, the circuit flattens it right there. The peak gets \"clipped\" off like a hedge trimmer leveling the top of a bush.</p></div>\n\n<h4>The workhorse part: the diode</h4>\n<p>Clippers are built mostly from <strong>diodes</strong> (sometimes a Zener). It works because of <strong>forward and reverse bias</strong> &mdash; the same idea from rectifiers (Module 6). A diode is basically a one-way switch:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Forward biased</strong> (correct polarity, &gt;~0.7&nbsp;V on silicon) &rarr; the diode <strong>conducts</strong> (turns ON, low resistance). When it conducts at the clip level it shunts the extra signal away, holding the output flat.</li>\n<li><strong>Reverse biased</strong> (wrong polarity) &rarr; the diode <strong>blocks</strong> (OFF, high resistance, acts like an open). The signal passes through untouched.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>By choosing which way the diode faces, you decide whether the <strong>top</strong> or the <strong>bottom</strong> of the wave gets clipped.</p>\n\n<h4>Series vs. shunt clippers</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Type</th><th>Where the diode sits</th><th>What it does</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Series clipper</strong></td><td>Diode <strong>in series</strong> with the load (in line with the signal path)</td><td>When the diode is reverse biased it opens the path, so that part of the wave is removed/blocked from reaching the load.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Shunt (parallel) clipper</strong></td><td>Diode <strong>in parallel</strong> across the load</td><td>When the diode conducts, it shorts that part of the signal to ground (shunts it away), so the output is held flat at the clip level.</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Biased clippers &mdash; setting the clip level</h4>\n<p>A plain diode clips near zero (about &plusmn;0.7&nbsp;V). To clip at a <strong>higher</strong> level, add a <strong>bias voltage</strong> (a battery or reference) in series with the diode. That raises the \"ceiling\" so the wave isn't trimmed until it climbs past the bias level. This is a <strong>biased clipper</strong>: the bias sets <em>where</em> the clipping happens.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Note</span>\n<p>A <strong>Zener diode</strong> makes an excellent limiter. The handbook (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-103) says the zener <em>\"functions as a voltage regulator, waveform clipper, and other related functions.\"</em> Because a zener only clips one direction, <em>\"two diodes connected in opposite directions must be used\"</em> to clip both the top and bottom of an AC wave &mdash; that gives you a clean symmetrical clip on both alternations.</p></div>\n\n<h4>Clippers vs. clampers (don't mix them up)</h4>\n<p>The exam likes this contrast. Both use diodes; they do <strong>opposite jobs</strong>:</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th></th><th>Clipper (limiter)</th><th>Clamper</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Job</strong></td><td><strong>Removes</strong> part of the wave</td><td><strong>Shifts</strong> the whole wave up or down</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Effect</strong></td><td>Cuts off the top and/or bottom; changes the <em>shape</em></td><td>Adds a DC level so the wave sits higher/lower; keeps the same <em>shape</em></td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Key part</strong></td><td>Diode (+ optional bias)</td><td>Diode + a <strong>capacitor</strong> (which stores the DC offset)</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>One-liner: a <strong>clipper chops the wave; a clamper moves the wave.</strong> The giveaway is the capacitor &mdash; a clamper has one to hold the DC shift; a basic clipper doesn't.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Example</span>\n<p><strong>Clipper:</strong> take a sine wave that swings &plusmn;10&nbsp;V and clip it at +5&nbsp;V &mdash; the top is now a flat line at 5&nbsp;V; the bottom still dips to &minus;10&nbsp;V. Shape changed. <strong>Clamper:</strong> take that same &plusmn;10&nbsp;V sine and clamp it so the bottom sits on 0&nbsp;V &mdash; now it swings from 0&nbsp;V up to +20&nbsp;V. Same sine shape, just lifted up. Different jobs entirely.</p></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">In one sentence, what does a limiter (clipper) do? <span class=\"a\">Answer: it clips/limits the amplitude of a waveform &mdash; cutting off the part above (and/or below) a set level &mdash; to protect a circuit or shape the signal.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">What is the difference between a clipper and a clamper? <span class=\"a\">Answer: a clipper removes part of the waveform (changes its shape); a clamper shifts the whole waveform up or down by a DC level (keeps its shape) and uses a capacitor to do it.</span></div>\n\n<h3>Tie it together</h3>\n<p>Standard 18 <strong>makes</strong> the signal (oscillator: DC in, repeating AC out &mdash; needs amplifier + positive feedback + LC/RC/crystal; crystal = most stable; multivibrators count their stable states 0/1/2). Standard 19 <strong>trims</strong> the signal (limiter/clipper: diodes clip the amplitude to a set level; series vs. shunt; biased to set the level; clipper chops, clamper shifts). Both are diode- and transistor-based building blocks you'll see inside every radio and computer on the aircraft.</p>", "quiz": [{"q": "Per the Study Guide, an oscillator is an electronic circuit that:", "options": ["Converts AC into DC at a fixed voltage", "Increases only the current of a signal", "Stores charge to smooth ripple", "Converts DC into AC at predetermined frequencies and amplitudes"], "correct": 3, "short": "DC in, AC out", "expl": "The Study Guide defines an oscillator as a circuit that converts DC into AC at predetermined frequencies and amplitudes.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Oscillator)", "topic": "oscillator-def"}, {"q": "What is the primary purpose of an oscillator?", "options": ["To rectify AC into pulsating DC", "To regulate a constant DC output voltage", "To attenuate unwanted frequencies", "To generate a repetitive waveform at a constant amplitude and specific frequency"], "correct": 3, "short": "Repetitive waveform", "expl": "Its primary purpose is to generate a repetitive waveform at constant (peak-to-peak) amplitude and a specific frequency, and hold it within limits.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Oscillator)", "topic": "oscillator-def"}, {"q": "Which three things must an oscillator have to keep oscillating?", "options": ["Amplification, positive feedback, and a frequency-determining network", "A transformer, a rectifier, and a filter", "Two resistors and one capacitor only", "A battery, a switch, and a relay"], "correct": 0, "short": "Gain + feedback + freq network", "expl": "An oscillator needs amplification (gain), positive/regenerative feedback, and a frequency-determining LC/RC/crystal network.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Oscillator, Regenerative Feedback)", "topic": "oscillator-req"}, {"q": "Why does an oscillator need an amplifier?", "options": ["To convert its output to DC", "To rectify the feedback signal", "To raise the supply voltage to 115 V", "To replace energy lost to wiring resistance so oscillation does not damp out"], "correct": 3, "short": "Replaces losses", "expl": "Without the amplifier, oscillation would quickly be damped out by the resistance in the circuit wiring.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Oscillator)", "topic": "oscillator-req"}, {"q": "In an oscillator, the type of feedback that 'makes any amplifier an oscillator' is:", "options": ["Negative feedback", "Degenerative feedback", "Positive (regenerative) feedback", "No feedback at all"], "correct": 2, "short": "Positive/regenerative", "expl": "A regenerative (positive) feedback path makes any amplifier an oscillator.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Regenerative Feedback Path)", "topic": "feedback"}, {"q": "The part of an oscillator that sets the output frequency is the:", "options": ["Load resistor", "Bias diode", "Heat sink", "Frequency-determining network (LC, RC, or crystal)"], "correct": 3, "short": "Frequency-determining network", "expl": "An LC tank, RC network, or crystal is the frequency-determining network that sets the oscillator's frequency.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18", "topic": "oscillator-req"}, {"q": "An LC tank oscillator produces its sinusoidal output because it:", "options": ["Stores energy alternately in the inductor and the capacitor", "Switches a transistor fully on and off", "Rectifies the input with four diodes", "Uses a tapped resistor divider"], "correct": 0, "short": "L and C swap energy", "expl": "The LC tank stores energy alternately in the inductor and capacitor, which produces a sinusoidal (sine-wave) output.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (LC Tank Oscillator)", "topic": "lc-tank"}, {"q": "A Hartley oscillator controls its frequency using a:", "options": ["Tapped coil in parallel with a capacitor", "Single fixed resistor", "Center-tapped transformer and two diodes", "Pair of back-to-back zener diodes"], "correct": 0, "short": "Tapped coil + cap", "expl": "A Hartley oscillator uses a tapped coil in parallel with a capacitor to control the AC frequency.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Hartley Oscillator)", "topic": "hartley"}, {"q": "In a crystal-controlled oscillator, the output frequency is determined by:", "options": ["The supply voltage", "The load resistance", "The resonant frequency of the piezoelectric crystal", "The number of transistors used"], "correct": 2, "short": "Crystal resonance", "expl": "The output frequency is set by the resonant frequency of the piezoelectric crystal in the oscillator.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Crystal-controlled Oscillator)", "topic": "crystal-osc"}, {"q": "Which oscillator is the MOST stable and accurate in frequency?", "options": ["Crystal-controlled oscillator", "RC phase-shift oscillator", "Astable multivibrator", "Hartley oscillator"], "correct": 0, "short": "Crystal", "expl": "A quartz crystal's resonant frequency barely drifts, so a crystal-controlled oscillator is the most stable/accurate.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Crystal-controlled Oscillator)", "topic": "crystal-stability"}, {"q": "A piezoelectric quartz crystal works because it:", "options": ["Stores DC charge like a capacitor", "Amplifies the input current", "Vibrates at a specific resonant frequency when voltage is applied", "Rectifies AC into DC"], "correct": 2, "short": "Vibrates at resonance", "expl": "A piezoelectric crystal vibrates at one specific resonant frequency when voltage is applied, giving precise frequency control.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 17/18 (Use of Crystals)", "topic": "crystal-stability"}, {"q": "A crystal-controlled oscillator typically produces what waveform?", "options": ["A square wave", "A sawtooth wave", "A triangle wave", "A sine wave"], "correct": 3, "short": "Sine wave", "expl": "A crystal-controlled oscillator produces a sine wave.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Crystal-controlled Oscillator)", "topic": "waveform"}, {"q": "Which waveform ramps up steadily and then drops back sharply to zero?", "options": ["Sawtooth", "Sine", "Square", "DC"], "correct": 0, "short": "Sawtooth", "expl": "A sawtooth waveform ramps up gradually then snaps back down; it is used to sweep CRT/radar displays.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (waveform types)", "topic": "waveform"}, {"q": "A waveform that snaps between two flat levels (HIGH and LOW) with vertical sides is a:", "options": ["Sine wave", "Sawtooth wave", "Square wave", "Triangle wave"], "correct": 2, "short": "Square wave", "expl": "A square wave has flat tops/bottoms and vertical transitions; it is common for clocks and digital timing.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-101", "topic": "waveform"}, {"q": "A multivibrator is best described as a circuit in which:", "options": ["Four diodes rectify an AC input", "Two transistors alternate conducting to make square/pulse waveforms", "A coil and capacitor store energy to make a sine wave", "A single diode clips a waveform"], "correct": 1, "short": "Transistors alternate", "expl": "A multivibrator uses two transistors that take turns conducting, producing square waves and pulses.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Multivibrators)", "topic": "multivibrator"}, {"q": "An ASTABLE multivibrator has:", "options": ["Two conditions of temporary stability and no permanent stable state", "One permanent stable state", "Two permanent stable states", "No transistors at all"], "correct": 0, "short": "Zero stable states", "expl": "An astable multivibrator has two temporarily stable conditions and no permanent stable state, so it free-runs.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Astable Multivibrator)", "topic": "astable"}, {"q": "A MONOSTABLE multivibrator (one-shot) has:", "options": ["No stable state", "One permanent stable mode of operation", "Two permanent stable states", "Three stable states"], "correct": 1, "short": "One stable state", "expl": "A monostable multivibrator has one permanent stable mode; a trigger produces a single pulse, then it returns.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Monostable Multivibrator)", "topic": "monostable"}, {"q": "In a BISTABLE multivibrator, the transistors:", "options": ["Both conduct continuously", "Never conduct", "Have no stable state and oscillate freely", "One conducts until an external pulse stops it, then the other takes over"], "correct": 3, "short": "Two stable states", "expl": "A bistable multivibrator has one transistor conduct until a pulse stops it, then the other takes over; it has two stable states (a flip-flop).", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Bistable Multivibrator)", "topic": "bistable"}, {"q": "Which multivibrator is 'free-running' and produces a continuous output without any trigger?", "options": ["Monostable", "Bistable", "Astable", "Crystal"], "correct": 2, "short": "Astable", "expl": "The astable multivibrator has no stable state, so it free-runs and continuously generates an output.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Astable Multivibrator)", "topic": "astable"}, {"q": "A multivibrator that acts as a memory cell / flip-flop, needing a trigger to change and staying put either way, is the:", "options": ["Astable", "Monostable", "Bistable", "LC tank"], "correct": 2, "short": "Bistable", "expl": "The bistable (flip-flop) has two stable states and needs a trigger to switch between them, making it a memory element.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18 (Bistable Multivibrator)", "topic": "bistable"}, {"q": "What is the main job of a limiter (clipper) circuit?", "options": ["To convert DC into AC", "To clip/limit a waveform's amplitude to a set level", "To store charge for smoothing ripple", "To step a voltage up or down"], "correct": 1, "short": "Clip amplitude", "expl": "A limiter (clipper) clips or limits the amplitude of a waveform to protect a circuit or shape the signal.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 19 (Limiter Circuits)", "topic": "limiter-def"}, {"q": "Limiter/clipper circuits are built mainly from which component?", "options": ["Transformers", "Diodes", "Crystals", "Relays"], "correct": 1, "short": "Diodes", "expl": "Clippers are built mostly from diodes (sometimes zeners), using forward/reverse bias to clip the wave.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 19 (Diodes)", "topic": "clipper-part"}, {"q": "A diode clips a waveform because, depending on the signal polarity, it is either:", "options": ["Charged or discharged", "Forward biased (conducts) or reverse biased (blocks)", "Heated or cooled", "Magnetized or demagnetized"], "correct": 1, "short": "Forward vs reverse bias", "expl": "A clipping diode conducts when forward biased and blocks when reverse biased, which removes part of the wave.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 19 (Forward/Reverse Bias); FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-103", "topic": "clipper-bias"}, {"q": "In a SHUNT (parallel) clipper, the diode is connected:", "options": ["In parallel across the load and shorts part of the signal to ground when it conducts", "In series with the load only", "In place of the load resistor", "Across the transformer primary"], "correct": 0, "short": "Parallel across load", "expl": "A shunt clipper places the diode in parallel with the load; when it conducts it shunts that part of the signal away, holding the output flat.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 19 (Limiter Circuits)", "topic": "shunt-clipper"}, {"q": "In a SERIES clipper, the diode is connected:", "options": ["In parallel with the load", "In series (in line) with the signal path to the load", "Across the power supply", "Inside the oscillator tank"], "correct": 1, "short": "In series", "expl": "A series clipper places the diode in line with the signal; when reverse biased it opens the path and blocks that part of the wave.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 19 (Limiter Circuits)", "topic": "series-clipper"}, {"q": "What does adding a bias voltage to a diode clipper do (a 'biased clipper')?", "options": ["Removes the need for the diode", "Doubles the signal frequency", "Converts the clipper into a rectifier", "Sets the level at which clipping begins"], "correct": 3, "short": "Sets clip level", "expl": "A bias voltage in series with the diode raises the clip 'ceiling', setting where the waveform begins to be clipped.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 19 (Limiter Circuits)", "topic": "biased-clipper"}, {"q": "Per the FAA handbook, a zener diode can be used as a:", "options": ["Sine-wave oscillator", "Transformer", "Waveform clipper (limiter)", "Air-core inductor"], "correct": 2, "short": "Zener as clipper", "expl": "The handbook states the zener functions as a voltage regulator, waveform clipper, and related functions.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-103", "topic": "zener-clipper"}, {"q": "To clip BOTH the top and bottom of an AC waveform with zener diodes, you must use:", "options": ["A single zener diode", "Two zener diodes connected in opposite directions", "A transformer and one diode", "Four resistors"], "correct": 1, "short": "Two opposite zeners", "expl": "A zener clips only one direction, so two zeners in opposite directions are needed to clip both alternations of AC.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-103", "topic": "zener-clipper"}, {"q": "What is the key difference between a clipper and a clamper?", "options": ["A clipper removes part of the wave; a clamper shifts the whole wave up or down", "They are two names for the same circuit", "A clipper uses transformers; a clamper uses diodes", "A clamper only works on DC; a clipper only on AC"], "correct": 0, "short": "Chop vs. shift", "expl": "A clipper cuts off part of the waveform (changes its shape); a clamper shifts the entire waveform by a DC level (keeps its shape).", "cite": "Study Guide Std 19 (Limiter Circuits)", "topic": "clipper-clamper"}, {"q": "Which component, present in a clamper but not in a basic clipper, stores the DC offset?", "options": ["A resistor", "An inductor", "A capacitor", "A transformer"], "correct": 2, "short": "Capacitor", "expl": "A clamper uses a capacitor to store and add the DC level that shifts the waveform; a basic clipper does not need one.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 19", "topic": "clipper-clamper"}, {"q": "If you clip a sine wave hard on both the top and bottom, its shape begins to resemble a:", "options": ["Sawtooth wave", "Square wave", "Pure DC level", "Triangle wave"], "correct": 1, "short": "Square wave", "expl": "Heavily clipping a sine wave flattens both peaks, so it starts to look like a square wave; clippers shape signals this way.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 19 (Limiter Circuits)", "topic": "wave-shaping"}, {"q": "One practical reason to put a limiter ahead of a sensitive stage is to:", "options": ["Increase the signal frequency", "Protect that stage from over-amplitude (too-large) spikes", "Convert the signal to DC", "Add gain to the signal"], "correct": 1, "short": "Protect from spikes", "expl": "A limiter caps the amplitude so an oversized spike cannot reach and damage the downstream circuit.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 19 (Limiter Circuits)", "topic": "limiter-use"}], "drill": [{"label": "Oscillator (definition)", "text": "Converts DC into AC at predetermined frequencies and amplitudes; makes a repeating waveform."}, {"label": "Oscillator needs 3 things", "text": "Amplification (gain) + positive/regenerative feedback + a frequency-determining network (LC, RC, or crystal)."}, {"label": "Why the amplifier", "text": "Without it the oscillation damps out from wiring resistance; the amp replaces lost energy each cycle."}, {"label": "Regenerative feedback", "text": "Positive feedback; 'makes any amplifier an oscillator.'"}, {"label": "LC tank oscillator", "text": "Stores energy alternately in L and C -> produces a sine (sinusoidal) output; used in comm receivers."}, {"label": "Hartley oscillator", "text": "Uses a tapped coil in parallel with a capacitor to set the AC frequency."}, {"label": "Crystal oscillator = stability", "text": "Frequency set by the piezoelectric crystal's resonance; most stable/accurate; outputs a sine wave."}, {"label": "Waveform types", "text": "Sine (smooth), square (flat tops, vertical sides), sawtooth (ramp then snap), triangle (even up/down)."}, {"label": "Multivibrator", "text": "Two transistors alternately conducting; makes square waves/pulses. Count the stable states."}, {"label": "Astable / Monostable / Bistable", "text": "Astable = 0 stable states (free-running); Monostable = 1 (one-shot pulse); Bistable = 2 (flip-flop/memory)."}, {"label": "Limiter / clipper", "text": "Clips/limits a waveform's amplitude to a set level; protects circuits or shapes the signal."}, {"label": "Clipper vs clamper", "text": "Clipper CHOPS part of the wave (changes shape); clamper SHIFTS the whole wave by a DC level (keeps shape, uses a capacitor). Diode clips via forward/reverse bias; bias sets the clip level; zener can clip (two opposite zeners for both AC halves)."}]}, {"n": 8, "title": "Digital", "standards": "20, 21", "lesson": "<h3>Why this matters on a real aircraft</h3>\n<p>Open up any modern avionics box &mdash; a GPS, a flight computer, an autopilot, a glass cockpit display &mdash; and the brains inside are <strong>digital</strong>. Digital circuits don't think in smooth voltages like the analog stuff from Module 5; they think in <strong>two states: ON or OFF, 1 or 0, HIGH or LOW</strong>. Standard <strong>20 (Digital Numbering Systems)</strong> teaches the <em>number languages</em> these circuits use (binary, octal, hex). Standard <strong>21 (Digital Logic Functions)</strong> teaches the <em>decision-making building blocks</em> (logic gates). Master both and you can read a logic diagram and a databus the way you read a wiring diagram.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">The whole module in one line</span>\n<p><strong>Digital = two states.</strong> We count with those two states using <strong>binary</strong>, write it shorter with <strong>octal</strong> or <strong>hexadecimal</strong>, and we make decisions with <strong>logic gates</strong> (AND, OR, NOT, NAND, NOR, XOR). That's it.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>PART 1 &mdash; DIGITAL NUMBERING SYSTEMS (Standard 20)</h3>\n\n<h4>Why digital uses binary</h4>\n<p>The FAA handbook says it plainly: the binary system <em>&ldquo;is based on the fact that switches or valves have two states: open or closed (on/off).&rdquo;</em> A transistor inside a chip is either switched ON (current flows = <strong>1</strong>) or OFF (no current = <strong>0</strong>). There is no &ldquo;halfway.&rdquo; Because every switch is one of just two things, the natural way to count is with just two digits. (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;3-27.)</p>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Analogy: light switches</span>\n<p>Picture a row of ordinary wall light switches. Each switch is only ever <strong>up (1)</strong> or <strong>down (0)</strong> &mdash; never tilted halfway. A row of these switches <em>is</em> a binary number. Eight switches = an 8-bit byte. The computer reads which switches are up and adds up their values.</p></div>\n\n<h4>The four number systems and their bases</h4>\n<p>A &ldquo;base&rdquo; (or radix) just tells you <strong>how many different digit symbols the system uses</strong> and what each place is worth.</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>System</th><th>Base</th><th>Digits used</th><th>Each place is a power of&hellip;</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Binary</strong></td><td><strong>2</strong></td><td>0, 1</td><td>2 (&hellip;8, 4, 2, 1)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Octal</strong></td><td><strong>8</strong></td><td>0&ndash;7</td><td>8 (&hellip;64, 8, 1)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Decimal</strong></td><td><strong>10</strong></td><td>0&ndash;9</td><td>10 (&hellip;100, 10, 1)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Hexadecimal</strong></td><td><strong>16</strong></td><td>0&ndash;9 then A&ndash;F</td><td>16 (&hellip;256, 16, 1)</td></tr>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Binary (base 2)</strong> &mdash; the Study Guide: <em>&ldquo;composed of two digits (1 and 0)&hellip; operates in Base 2&hellip; mathematical computation based on powers of two.&rdquo;</em></li>\n<li><strong>Decimal (base 10)</strong> &mdash; the everyday system, <em>&ldquo;uses numbers 0&ndash;9&hellip; operates in Base 10.&rdquo;</em></li>\n<li><strong>Octal (base 8)</strong> &mdash; <em>&ldquo;composed of eight digits (0&ndash;7)&hellip; operates in Base 8&hellip; each digit represents three bits, a triad.&rdquo;</em></li>\n<li><strong>Hexadecimal (base 16)</strong> &mdash; <em>&ldquo;composed of 16 units (decimal 0&ndash;9 and letters A&ndash;F for decimal 10&ndash;15)&hellip; operates in Base 16&hellip; each digit represents four bits.&rdquo;</em></li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Hex letters &mdash; memorize cold</span>\n<p>After 9, hex keeps going with letters: <strong>A=10, B=11, C=12, D=13, E=14, F=15.</strong> So one hex digit covers 0 through 15 &mdash; exactly the 16 values that <strong>4 binary bits</strong> can make. That's the whole reason hex exists: it's a shorthand for groups of 4 bits.</p></div>\n\n<h4>Bits, nibbles, and bytes</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Term</th><th>How many bits</th><th>Note</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Bit</strong> (binary digit)</td><td><strong>1</strong></td><td>Each single 0 or 1. Study Guide: &ldquo;Each zero or one is a binary number.&rdquo;</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Nibble</strong></td><td><strong>4</strong></td><td>Half a byte; = exactly one hex digit.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Byte</strong></td><td><strong>8</strong></td><td>Study Guide: a byte &ldquo;consists of eight bits.&rdquo; = two hex digits.</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Converting BINARY &rarr; DECIMAL (the place-value method)</h4>\n<p>The handbook's method: <em>&ldquo;add up the place values that have a 1&rdquo;</em> (skip the zeros). The place values from right to left are 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128&hellip; (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;3-27.)</p>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example: 1011 &rarr; decimal</span>\n<p>Write the place values under each bit (right to left = 1, 2, 4, 8):</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Bit</th><td>1</td><td>0</td><td>1</td><td>1</td></tr>\n<tr><th>Place value</th><td>8</td><td>4</td><td>2</td><td>1</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>Add only the places with a 1: <strong>8 + 0 + 2 + 1 = 11</strong>. So binary <strong>1011 = 11 decimal.</strong></p></div>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example: 10110011 &rarr; decimal (from the handbook)</span>\n<p>Place values: 128, 64, 32, 16, 8, 4, 2, 1. The 1s sit under 128, 32, 16, 2, 1:</p>\n<p><strong>128 + 0 + 32 + 16 + 0 + 0 + 2 + 1 = 179.</strong> Binary 10110011 = 179 decimal. (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;3-28.)</p></div>\n\n<h4>Converting DECIMAL &rarr; BINARY</h4>\n<p>Two ways &mdash; both give the same answer.</p>\n<p><strong>Way A (subtract place values &mdash; the handbook's method):</strong> Start with the biggest place value that fits, subtract it, put a 1 there, and keep going. The Study Guide's other way: <em>&ldquo;sequentially dividing the number by 2 and recording each remainder.&rdquo;</em></p>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example: 233 &rarr; binary (from the handbook)</span>\n<p>233 &minus; 128 = 105 &rarr; 1&hellip; · 105 &minus; 64 = 41 &rarr; 1&hellip; · 41 &minus; 32 = 9 &rarr; 1&hellip; · 9 is less than 16 &rarr; 0 · 9 &minus; 8 = 1 &rarr; 1 · 1 less than 4 &rarr; 0 · 1 less than 2 &rarr; 0 · 1 &minus; 1 = 0 &rarr; 1.</p>\n<p>Reading the digits: <strong>233 = 11101001 binary.</strong> (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;3-28.)</p></div>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example: 13 &rarr; binary (divide-by-2 method)</span>\n<p>13&divide;2 = 6 r<strong>1</strong> · 6&divide;2 = 3 r<strong>0</strong> · 3&divide;2 = 1 r<strong>1</strong> · 1&divide;2 = 0 r<strong>1</strong>. Read the remainders <em>bottom-up</em>: <strong>1101</strong>. Check: 8+4+0+1 = 13. So 13 = <strong>1101 binary.</strong></p></div>\n\n<h4>Converting HEX &rarr; DECIMAL</h4>\n<p>Same place-value idea, but the places are powers of 16: &hellip;256, 16, 1. Replace any letter with its value (A=10&hellip;F=15), multiply by the place, add.</p>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example: 2F &rarr; decimal</span>\n<p>2F has two digits. Left place = 16s, right place = 1s. F = 15.</p>\n<p>(2 &times; 16) + (15 &times; 1) = 32 + 15 = <strong>47.</strong> So hex <strong>2F = 47 decimal.</strong></p></div>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example: 1A &rarr; decimal</span>\n<p>(1 &times; 16) + (A=10 &times; 1) = 16 + 10 = <strong>26.</strong> So hex <strong>1A = 26 decimal.</strong></p></div>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">The 4-bit shortcut (binary &harr; hex)</span>\n<p>Because one hex digit = 4 bits (one nibble), you can convert by groups of four. Binary <strong>1010 = A</strong>, <strong>1111 = F</strong>, <strong>0010 = 2</strong>. So binary 0010&nbsp;1111 = hex <strong>2F</strong>. This is why programmers love hex &mdash; it shrinks a long binary string to a few easy digits.</p></div>\n\n<h4>BCD &mdash; Binary Coded Decimal (the basics)</h4>\n<p><strong>BCD</strong> is a halfway system: you take each <em>decimal</em> digit and write it as its own <strong>4-bit binary nibble</strong>. You do NOT convert the whole number at once. It's used so digital circuits can drive decimal displays easily.</p>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example: 47 in BCD</span>\n<p>Handle each decimal digit separately: 4 = <strong>0100</strong>, 7 = <strong>0111</strong>. So 47 in BCD = <strong>0100 0111</strong>. (Note: that's different from 47's true binary, 101111 &mdash; BCD trades efficiency for easy decimal display.) Each decimal digit always uses 4 bits, and BCD only uses the patterns 0000&ndash;1001 (0&ndash;9).</p></div>\n\n<h4>Displaying digital data</h4>\n<p>The Study Guide notes digital data is shown as <em>&ldquo;alphanumeric characters produced by visible segments on LED or LCD devices,&rdquo;</em> typically <em>&ldquo;seven or less segments&hellip; to form the numbers 0&ndash;9&rdquo;</em> &mdash; that's the classic <strong>seven-segment display</strong> on a transponder or radio.</p>\n\n<h3>PART 2 &mdash; DIGITAL LOGIC FUNCTIONS (Standard 21)</h3>\n\n<h4>What a logic gate is</h4>\n<p>The Study Guide defines <strong>logic gates</strong> as <em>&ldquo;switching circuits connected together to make a variety of digital systems,&rdquo;</em> and a <strong>main logic gate</strong> as one that <em>&ldquo;can handle AND, OR, NOT, NOR, NAND, and EXCLUSIVE OR decisions.&rdquo;</em> Boolean logic is the math behind it: the handbook says it uses just two truth values, <em>true and false, represented by the binary digits 1 and 0.</em> (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-121.)</p>\n<p>A <strong>truth table</strong> <em>&ldquo;describes the behavior of a logic gate&rdquo;</em> &mdash; it lists every possible input combination and the output for each. Learn the gates by their truth tables.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Positive vs. negative logic</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Positive logic:</strong> the higher voltage = <strong>1</strong>, the lower voltage = 0. (the normal case)</li>\n<li><strong>Negative logic:</strong> the higher voltage = 0, the lower voltage = 1. (reversed)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>(Study Guide, Standard 21.) Unless told otherwise, assume positive logic.</p></div>\n\n<h4>AND gate &mdash; both inputs must be 1</h4>\n<p>Two or more inputs, one output. Output is 1 <strong>only when ALL inputs are 1</strong>. <em>Analogy: two switches in SERIES &mdash; the light comes on only if you close switch A AND switch B.</em> On aircraft, AND logic drives things like &ldquo;autopilot can engage only when ALL valid signals are present.&rdquo; (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-124.)</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>A</th><th>B</th><th>AND output</th></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>0</td></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td>1</td><td>0</td></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>0</td><td>0</td></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td><strong>1</strong></td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>OR gate &mdash; any input 1 gives a 1</h4>\n<p>Two or more inputs, one output. Output is 1 <strong>when ANY input is 1</strong>; output is 0 only when all inputs are 0. The handbook: <em>&ldquo;a high on any one of the inputs produces a high on the output.&rdquo;</em> <em>Analogy: two switches in PARALLEL &mdash; the light comes on if you close switch A OR switch B.</em> Example: a &ldquo;DOOR UNSAFE&rdquo; light that comes on if the cabin door OR the baggage door is open. (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-122.)</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>A</th><th>B</th><th>OR output</th></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>0</td></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td>1</td><td><strong>1</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>0</td><td><strong>1</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td><strong>1</strong></td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>NOT gate (inverter) &mdash; flips the input</h4>\n<p>The Study Guide is precise: an inverter <em>&ldquo;performs the&hellip; NOT logic function,&rdquo;</em> has <em>&ldquo;one input and one output that are always in opposition,&rdquo;</em> and &mdash; important &mdash; <em>&ldquo;an inverter is a logic device, NOT a gate.&rdquo;</em> Put in a 1, get out a 0; put in a 0, get out a 1.</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Input</th><th>NOT output</th></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td><strong>1</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>0</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>NAND gate &mdash; NOT-AND (AND, then inverted)</h4>\n<p>Study Guide: NAND <em>&ldquo;means NOT AND&hellip; usually followed by an inverter.&rdquo;</em> So take the AND result and flip it. Output is 0 <strong>only when all inputs are 1</strong>; otherwise output is 1. (Exactly the opposite of AND.) (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-125.)</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>A</th><th>B</th><th>NAND output</th></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td>0</td><td><strong>1</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td>1</td><td><strong>1</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>0</td><td><strong>1</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>0</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>NOR gate &mdash; NOT-OR (OR, then inverted)</h4>\n<p>Study Guide: NOR <em>&ldquo;means NOT OR&hellip; usually followed by an inverter.&rdquo;</em> Take the OR result and flip it. Output is 1 <strong>only when ALL inputs are 0</strong>; any 1 input makes the output 0. (Exactly the opposite of OR.) (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-126.)</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>A</th><th>B</th><th>NOR output</th></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td>0</td><td><strong>1</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td>1</td><td>0</td></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>0</td><td>0</td></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>0</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>XOR gate &mdash; EXCLUSIVE OR (inputs must differ)</h4>\n<p>Study Guide: the EXCLUSIVE OR gate <em>&ldquo;requires inputs to be different to obtain an output.&rdquo;</em> Output is 1 <strong>only when the inputs are DIFFERENT</strong> (one 1 and one 0); if both inputs are the same, output is 0. <em>Analogy: the two switches that control one stairway light from top and bottom &mdash; the light toggles whenever the switches disagree.</em> (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-126.)</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>A</th><th>B</th><th>XOR output</th></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td>0</td><td>0</td></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td>1</td><td><strong>1</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>0</td><td><strong>1</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>1</td><td>0</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">The &ldquo;universal&rdquo; gates &mdash; NAND and NOR</span>\n<p><strong>NAND and NOR are called universal gates</strong> because you can build <em>any</em> other logic function (AND, OR, NOT, XOR&hellip;) using only NAND gates, or only NOR gates. That's why a chip maker can mass-produce just one gate type and wire it into anything. Remember: <strong>NAND = AND inverted, NOR = OR inverted.</strong></p></div>\n\n<h4>Reading a simple logic diagram</h4>\n<p>Each gate has a standard symbol; signals flow <strong>left (inputs) to right (output)</strong>. To find the output of a chain: write the 1s and 0s on the input wires, work each gate one at a time using its truth table, and carry the result forward to the next gate. Example chain: A=1, B=0 into an AND gate &rarr; AND output = 0 &rarr; feed that 0 into a NOT (inverter) &rarr; final output = 1. (That two-gate chain &ldquo;AND then NOT&rdquo; <em>is</em> a NAND.)</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Quick memory hooks</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>AND</strong> = <strong>A</strong>ll must be 1 (both switches).</li>\n<li><strong>OR</strong> = at least <strong>O</strong>ne is 1 (either switch).</li>\n<li><strong>NOT</strong> = iNverts (one in, one out, opposite).</li>\n<li><strong>NAND / NOR</strong> = the same as AND / OR but with the answer flipped (the N = NOT on the front).</li>\n<li><strong>XOR</strong> = 1 only when inputs differ (eXclusive).</li>\n</ul></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">What base is the binary numbering system, and what two digits does it use? <span class=\"a\">Answer: base 2, using only 0 and 1.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Convert the binary number <strong>1011</strong> to decimal. <span class=\"a\">Answer: 8 + 0 + 2 + 1 = <strong>11</strong>.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">In hexadecimal, what decimal value does the letter <strong>F</strong> stand for, and how many bits does one hex digit represent? <span class=\"a\">Answer: F = 15; one hex digit represents 4 bits (a nibble).</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">An <strong>AND</strong> gate has inputs A=1 and B=0. What is its output? And what would a <strong>NAND</strong> gate output for the same inputs? <span class=\"a\">Answer: AND outputs 0 (both inputs must be 1). NAND is AND inverted, so it outputs 1.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Which two gates are called the &ldquo;universal&rdquo; gates, and why? <span class=\"a\">Answer: NAND and NOR &mdash; because you can build any other logic function using only NANDs, or only NORs.</span></div>", "quiz": [{"q": "Why does digital electronics use the binary number system?", "options": ["Because a switch (transistor) has only two states: on or off", "Because aircraft run on 2 volts", "Because binary is faster to write than decimal", "Because binary can store decimal points"], "correct": 0, "short": "Two states: on/off", "expl": "Binary is based on the fact that switches/valves have two states, open or closed (on/off) - matching a transistor that is either on (1) or off (0).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.3-27; Study Guide Std 20", "topic": "why-binary"}, {"q": "What base (radix) does the BINARY numbering system operate in?", "options": ["Base 8", "Base 2", "Base 10", "Base 16"], "correct": 1, "short": "Base 2", "expl": "Binary operates in Base 2 and is composed of two digits, 1 and 0; its math is based on powers of two.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20", "topic": "binary-base"}, {"q": "Which numbering system uses the digits 0 through 7 and operates in Base 8?", "options": ["Binary", "Decimal", "Octal", "Hexadecimal"], "correct": 2, "short": "Octal", "expl": "The octal system is composed of eight digits (0-7) and operates in Base 8; each octal digit represents three bits (a triad).", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20", "topic": "octal"}, {"q": "What base does the DECIMAL system operate in, and what digits does it use?", "options": ["Base 8, digits 0-7", "Base 2, digits 0-1", "Base 16, digits 0-F", "Base 10, digits 0-9"], "correct": 3, "short": "Base 10, 0-9", "expl": "The decimal numbering system uses numbers 0-9 and operates in Base 10.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20", "topic": "decimal"}, {"q": "The HEXADECIMAL system operates in Base 16. What does it use after the digit 9?", "options": ["The letters A through F", "It starts over at 0", "The digits 10 through 15 written out", "The symbols + and -"], "correct": 0, "short": "Letters A-F", "expl": "Hex is composed of 16 units: decimal 0-9 and the letters A-F standing for decimal 10-15.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20", "topic": "hex-digits"}, {"q": "In hexadecimal, what decimal value does the letter C represent?", "options": ["10", "12", "11", "15"], "correct": 1, "short": "C = 12", "expl": "In hex: A=10, B=11, C=12, D=13, E=14, F=15.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20", "topic": "hex-letters"}, {"q": "Convert the binary number 1011 to decimal.", "options": ["7", "13", "11", "15"], "correct": 2, "short": "11", "expl": "Place values 8,4,2,1: add the 1s -> 8 + 0 + 2 + 1 = 11.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.3-27", "topic": "bin-to-dec"}, {"q": "Convert the binary number 1101 to decimal.", "options": ["11", "12", "14", "13"], "correct": 3, "short": "13", "expl": "Place values 8,4,2,1: 8 + 4 + 0 + 1 = 13.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.3-27", "topic": "bin-to-dec"}, {"q": "Convert the binary number 10110011 to decimal.", "options": ["179", "173", "183", "211"], "correct": 0, "short": "179", "expl": "128 + 0 + 32 + 16 + 0 + 0 + 2 + 1 = 179 (the handbook's worked example).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.3-28", "topic": "bin-to-dec"}, {"q": "What is the place value of the leftmost bit in an 8-bit binary number?", "options": ["64", "128", "256", "100"], "correct": 1, "short": "128", "expl": "An 8-bit number's place values are 128,64,32,16,8,4,2,1; the leftmost (most significant) bit is 128.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.3-27", "topic": "place-value"}, {"q": "Per the FAA method, how do you convert a binary number to decimal?", "options": ["Multiply every bit by 2", "Divide the number by 2 repeatedly", "Add up the place values that have a 1 (ignore the zeros)", "Subtract 1 from each digit"], "correct": 2, "short": "Add place values of the 1s", "expl": "To convert binary to decimal, add up the place values that have a 1; places with a zero contribute nothing.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.3-27", "topic": "bin-to-dec-method"}, {"q": "Per the Study Guide, one way to convert a decimal number to binary is to:", "options": ["Multiply it by 16", "Add 8 each time", "Look it up in a hex table", "Sequentially divide the number by 2 and record each remainder"], "correct": 3, "short": "Divide by 2, keep remainders", "expl": "A decimal number may be converted to binary by sequentially dividing by 2 and recording each remainder.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20", "topic": "dec-to-bin"}, {"q": "Convert the decimal number 13 to binary.", "options": ["1101", "1011", "1110", "1001"], "correct": 0, "short": "1101", "expl": "13 = 8 + 4 + 0 + 1 = 1101. (Divide-by-2 remainders read bottom-up also give 1101.)", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.3-28", "topic": "dec-to-bin"}, {"q": "Convert the decimal number 233 to binary.", "options": ["11100101", "11101001", "10111001", "11110001"], "correct": 1, "short": "11101001", "expl": "233-128=105(1),-64=41(1),-32=9(1),<16(0),-8=1(1),<4(0),<2(0),-1=0(1) -> 11101001 (handbook example).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.3-28", "topic": "dec-to-bin"}, {"q": "Convert the hexadecimal number 2F to decimal.", "options": ["29", "31", "47", "45"], "correct": 2, "short": "47", "expl": "(2 x 16) + (F=15 x 1) = 32 + 15 = 47.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20 (hex conversions)", "topic": "hex-to-dec"}, {"q": "Convert the hexadecimal number 1A to decimal.", "options": ["20", "30", "110", "26"], "correct": 3, "short": "26", "expl": "(1 x 16) + (A=10 x 1) = 16 + 10 = 26.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20 (hex conversions)", "topic": "hex-to-dec"}, {"q": "What is a 'bit'?", "options": ["A single binary digit - one 0 or one 1", "Eight binary numbers", "A group of four binary digits", "A decimal place value"], "correct": 0, "short": "One binary digit", "expl": "A binary digit (bit) is each single zero or one.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20", "topic": "bit"}, {"q": "How many bits are in a BYTE?", "options": ["2", "4", "8", "16"], "correct": 2, "short": "8 bits", "expl": "A byte consists of eight bits.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20", "topic": "byte"}, {"q": "How many bits are in a NIBBLE?", "options": ["2", "4", "8", "16"], "correct": 1, "short": "4 bits", "expl": "A nibble is 4 bits - half a byte - and equals exactly one hexadecimal digit.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20", "topic": "nibble"}, {"q": "One hexadecimal digit represents how many binary bits?", "options": ["2 bits", "3 bits", "4 bits", "8 bits"], "correct": 2, "short": "4 bits", "expl": "Each hexadecimal digit represents four bits (one nibble), which is why hex is shorthand for groups of 4 bits.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20", "topic": "hex-bits"}, {"q": "In Binary Coded Decimal (BCD), how is each decimal digit handled?", "options": ["Each decimal digit is written as its own 4-bit binary group", "The whole number is converted to binary at once", "Each digit is written in hexadecimal", "Each digit is doubled"], "correct": 0, "short": "Each digit = 4-bit group", "expl": "BCD writes each decimal digit separately as a 4-bit nibble, so 47 = 0100 0111.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20", "topic": "bcd"}, {"q": "A logic gate's behavior is described by a:", "options": ["Color code", "Truth table", "Turns ratio", "Bode plot"], "correct": 1, "short": "Truth table", "expl": "A truth table describes the behavior of a logic gate, listing the output for every input combination.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 21", "topic": "truth-table"}, {"q": "An AND gate produces a 1 (high) output only when:", "options": ["Any one input is 1", "All inputs are 0", "All inputs are 1", "The inputs are different"], "correct": 2, "short": "All inputs 1", "expl": "An AND gate outputs 1 only when ALL inputs are 1 - like two switches in series.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-124; Study Guide Std 21", "topic": "and"}, {"q": "An AND gate has inputs A=1 and B=0. What is the output?", "options": ["1", "Both", "Undefined", "0"], "correct": 3, "short": "0", "expl": "AND requires ALL inputs to be 1; since B=0, the output is 0.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-124", "topic": "and-output"}, {"q": "An OR gate produces a 1 output when:", "options": ["Any one (or more) input is 1", "All inputs are 0", "Only when all inputs are 1", "Only when inputs are equal"], "correct": 0, "short": "Any input 1", "expl": "A high on any one of the inputs produces a high output; OR outputs 0 only when all inputs are 0.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-122; Study Guide Std 21", "topic": "or"}, {"q": "An OR gate has inputs A=0 and B=0. What is the output?", "options": ["1", "0", "Either", "Toggles"], "correct": 1, "short": "0", "expl": "An OR gate outputs 0 only when ALL inputs are 0.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-122", "topic": "or-output"}, {"q": "Per the Study Guide, which statement about the NOT gate / inverter is correct?", "options": ["It is a gate with two inputs", "It outputs 1 only when both inputs are 1", "It has one input and one output that are always in opposition (1 in gives 0 out)", "It requires inputs to be different"], "correct": 2, "short": "One in, one out, opposite", "expl": "The inverter performs the NOT function, has one input and one output always in opposition (1 in -> 0 out), and is a logic device, not a gate.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 21", "topic": "not-inverter"}, {"q": "The NAND gate is equivalent to:", "options": ["An OR gate followed by an inverter", "Two inverters", "An XOR gate", "An AND gate followed by an inverter"], "correct": 3, "short": "AND then inverter", "expl": "NAND means NOT AND; it is an AND gate usually followed by an inverter, so its output is the AND result flipped.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-125; Study Guide Std 21", "topic": "nand"}, {"q": "A NAND gate has inputs A=1 and B=1. What is the output?", "options": ["0", "1", "Either", "Undefined"], "correct": 0, "short": "0", "expl": "NAND outputs 0 only when ALL inputs are 1 (it is the opposite of AND, which would output 1 here).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-125", "topic": "nand-output"}, {"q": "The NOR gate is equivalent to:", "options": ["An AND gate followed by an inverter", "An OR gate followed by an inverter", "An inverter only", "A NAND gate"], "correct": 1, "short": "OR then inverter", "expl": "NOR means NOT OR; it is an OR gate followed by an inverter, so its output is the OR result flipped.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-126; Study Guide Std 21", "topic": "nor"}, {"q": "A NOR gate outputs a 1 only when:", "options": ["Any input is 1", "All inputs are 1", "All inputs are 0", "The inputs differ"], "correct": 2, "short": "All inputs 0", "expl": "NOR is the opposite of OR: its output is 1 only when ALL inputs are 0; any 1 makes it 0.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-126", "topic": "nor-output"}, {"q": "An EXCLUSIVE OR (XOR) gate produces a 1 output when:", "options": ["Both inputs are 1", "Both inputs are 0", "The two inputs are the same", "The two inputs are different"], "correct": 3, "short": "Inputs different", "expl": "The EXCLUSIVE OR gate requires its inputs to be different to obtain an output.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-126; Study Guide Std 21", "topic": "xor"}, {"q": "An XOR gate has inputs A=1 and B=1. What is the output?", "options": ["0", "1", "Either", "Toggles"], "correct": 0, "short": "0", "expl": "XOR outputs 1 only when inputs differ; with both inputs the same (1 and 1), the output is 0.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-126", "topic": "xor-output"}, {"q": "Which two gates are called the 'universal' gates?", "options": ["AND and OR", "NAND and NOR", "NOT and XOR", "OR and NOR"], "correct": 1, "short": "NAND and NOR", "expl": "NAND and NOR are universal because any other logic function can be built using only NAND gates or only NOR gates.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-125 to 12-126; Study Guide Std 21", "topic": "universal"}, {"q": "In Boolean logic used by digital circuits, the two truth values true and false are represented by:", "options": ["+ and -", "Hex A and F", "The binary digits 1 and 0", "High and middle voltages"], "correct": 2, "short": "1 and 0", "expl": "Boolean logic uses only two truth values, true and false, represented by the binary digits 1 and 0.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-121", "topic": "boolean"}, {"q": "Under POSITIVE logic, which voltage level represents a 1?", "options": ["The lower (less positive) voltage", "Zero volts only", "Negative voltage only", "The higher (more positive) voltage"], "correct": 3, "short": "Higher voltage = 1", "expl": "In positive logic the more positive (higher) voltage stands for 1 and the lower voltage stands for 0; negative logic reverses this.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 21", "topic": "positive-logic"}], "drill": [{"label": "Binary", "text": "Base 2 - uses only the digits 0 and 1; math based on powers of two."}, {"label": "Octal", "text": "Base 8 - uses digits 0-7; each octal digit = 3 bits (a triad)."}, {"label": "Decimal", "text": "Base 10 - the everyday system, uses digits 0-9."}, {"label": "Hexadecimal", "text": "Base 16 - uses 0-9 then A-F (A=10...F=15); each hex digit = 4 bits."}, {"label": "Bit", "text": "One binary digit - a single 0 or 1."}, {"label": "Nibble", "text": "4 bits - half a byte; equals exactly one hex digit."}, {"label": "Byte", "text": "8 bits - equals two hex digits."}, {"label": "Binary to decimal", "text": "Add the place values (128,64,32,16,8,4,2,1) that have a 1; ignore the zeros."}, {"label": "AND gate", "text": "Output = 1 only when ALL inputs are 1 (both switches). Series."}, {"label": "OR gate", "text": "Output = 1 when ANY input is 1; 0 only if all inputs are 0 (either switch). Parallel."}, {"label": "NOT (inverter)", "text": "One input, one output, always opposite: 1 in -> 0 out, 0 in -> 1 out. A device, not a gate."}, {"label": "NAND / NOR", "text": "NAND = AND inverted; NOR = OR inverted. These two are the UNIVERSAL gates."}, {"label": "XOR (Exclusive OR)", "text": "Output = 1 only when the inputs are DIFFERENT; same inputs give 0."}]}, {"n": 9, "title": "Safety & Shop Practices", "standards": "22, 23, 24, 27, 29", "lesson": "<h3>Why this matters on a real aircraft</h3>\n<p>This module is the one that keeps <strong>you alive</strong> and keeps the <strong>airplane airworthy</strong>. It bundles five Standards that every avionics shop lives by every single day: <strong>22 (Hazards/Safety)</strong>, <strong>23 (Hazardous Materials)</strong>, <strong>24 (FOD Prevention)</strong>, <strong>27 (Handling ESD Devices)</strong>, and <strong>29 (Use Safety Devices)</strong>. None of it is hard math. It is mostly facts, lists, and habits &mdash; and the test asks them straight. The good news: a lot of this transfers directly to your A&P general material, so you already half-know it.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">The five jobs in one line each</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Hazards/Safety (22)</strong> &mdash; don't get shocked, burned, or fried; know your fire classes and how to shut power off.</li>\n<li><strong>Hazmat (23)</strong> &mdash; read the safety data sheet, label it, store it right, dispose of it legally.</li>\n<li><strong>FOD (24)</strong> &mdash; a dropped washer can wreck an engine; control your tools, clean as you go.</li>\n<li><strong>ESD (27)</strong> &mdash; an invisible spark you can't even feel can kill a circuit board; ground yourself.</li>\n<li><strong>Safety devices (29)</strong> &mdash; cotter pins, safety wire, fuses, and breakers stop things from coming loose or burning up.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h3>STANDARD 22 &mdash; Hazards &amp; Safety Practices</h3>\n\n<h4>Electrical shock &mdash; it's the CURRENT that kills, not the voltage</h4>\n<p>Here is the single most important safety idea in electronics: <strong>current (amperes) through your body is what injures or kills you, not voltage by itself.</strong> Voltage is just the push; current is what actually flows through your heart. It only takes a tiny amount. A current of roughly <strong>0.1 to 0.2 ampere (100 to 200 milliamperes)</strong> across the chest can stop your heart (fibrillation). That is a <em>fraction</em> of what a single light bulb draws. Even your skin's resistance can drop fast when you're sweaty, letting more current flow.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Analogy: the garden hose</span>\n<p>Think of <strong>voltage as water pressure</strong> and <strong>current as the actual water flowing through</strong>. A high-pressure hose that's pinched shut moves no water and does no damage. The danger is when water actually <em>flows through</em> you. That's why a low-voltage circuit can still be deadly if conditions let real current pass &mdash; and why \"it's only 28 volts\" is a careless attitude around an aircraft bus, capacitors, or a charged coil.</p></div>\n\n<p><strong>First aid for electrical shock</strong> (Study Guide, Std 22). Memorize the order:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>TURN OFF THE POWER</strong> as fast as possible &mdash; this is step one, always.</li>\n<li>If you can't kill the power, <strong>do NOT touch the victim</strong> &mdash; if you do, the current passes through <em>you</em> too.</li>\n<li>Use a <strong>dry, non-conducting object</strong> &mdash; a dry wooden pole, broom, or chair &mdash; to push or pull the victim clear.</li>\n<li>Once free: keep the victim <strong>lying down</strong>, slightly elevate the legs, cover with a blanket for warmth, get qualified medical help, don't leave them alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Shutting power off the right way: Lockout / Tagout (LOTO)</span>\n<p>The Study Guide calls this <em>\"Elimination/Termination of Circuit Power\"</em>: the procedural steps for <strong>shutting down, isolating, blocking, and securing</strong> equipment to control hazardous energy. <strong>Lockout/tagout devices</strong> physically lock a switch or breaker OFF and hang a tag so nobody can re-energize the circuit while you're working in it. A <strong>job briefing</strong> (covering hazards, procedures, special precautions, energy-source controls, and PPE) happens before the work starts.</p></div>\n\n<h4>PPE and eye protection</h4>\n<p><strong>Personal Protective Equipment (PPE)</strong> protects you based on the four ways hazards get into a body: <strong>inhalation, skin absorption, ingestion, and eye/skin contact</strong> (Study Guide, Std 22). PPE is <strong>hazard-specific</strong> &mdash; the right glove for a solvent isn't the right glove for a hot part. <strong>Eye protection</strong> (safety glasses/goggles/face shield) is required any time there's a splash, dust, flying-debris, or arc risk. Electrical <strong>insulated gloves and sleeves</strong> are worn when exposed to shock hazards. Hearing protection (earplugs/earmuffs) is required around loud equipment &mdash; OSHA's limit is <strong>90 dB(A) over an 8-hour day</strong>.</p>\n\n<h4>Fire safety &mdash; the fire triangle and the four fire classes</h4>\n<p>Fire needs three things at once: <strong>FUEL + HEAT + OXYGEN</strong> (the fire triangle). Remove any one and the fire goes out. (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;1-5.)</p>\n<p>This is the highest-value memorization in the module. The NFPA classes fires by <strong>what is burning</strong>, and each class has the extinguisher you should reach for:</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Class</th><th>What's burning</th><th>Best / acceptable extinguisher</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Class A</strong></td><td><strong>Ordinary combustibles</strong> &mdash; wood, paper, cloth, upholstery, rubbish</td><td><strong>Water</strong> (best); also CO&#8322;, multipurpose dry chemical</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Class B</strong></td><td><strong>Flammable liquids</strong> &mdash; fuel, oil, grease, solvents, paint</td><td><strong>CO&#8322;</strong> or dry chemical or Halon (NOT water &mdash; it spreads the fire)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Class C</strong></td><td><strong>Energized electrical</strong> &mdash; live wiring, motors, panels, equipment</td><td><strong>CO&#8322;</strong> or Halon or dry chemical &mdash; a <strong>non-conductive</strong> agent (NEVER plain water)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Class D</strong></td><td><strong>Flammable metals</strong> &mdash; magnesium (wheels/brakes), from welding</td><td><strong>Dry powder ONLY</strong> &mdash; never water or CO&#8322; (cooling causes explosive expansion)</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Memory hook for the classes</span>\n<p><strong>A</strong>shes (ordinary stuff that leaves ash) &middot; <strong>B</strong>oils/<strong>B</strong>arrels (liquids in barrels) &middot; <strong>C</strong>urrent (electrical) &middot; <strong>D</strong>ynamite metals. The one the exam loves: an <strong>electrical fire is Class C</strong> &mdash; and you must use a <strong>non-conductive</strong> agent like CO&#8322;, because spraying water on energized equipment can shock or electrocute you. <strong>De-energize first if you can.</strong></p></div>\n\n<p><strong>CO&#8322;</strong> works on A, B, and C by smothering (removing oxygen) and cooling &mdash; but never use it on Class D (it can make the metal explode). <strong>Water</strong> is best on A only. <strong>Dry powder</strong> is the only safe choice for Class D. To operate most extinguishers: <strong>pull the pin, aim at the base of the fire, squeeze the lever, sweep side to side</strong> (the \"PASS\" idea), standing about 8 feet back. (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;1-5 to 1-8.)</p>\n\n<h3>STANDARD 23 &mdash; Hazardous Materials Handling</h3>\n<p>Solvents, cleaners, degreasers, adhesives, coatings, fuels &mdash; the shop is full of chemicals that are <strong>toxic, corrosive, flammable, reactive, or explosive</strong>. Standard 23 is about handling them without hurting yourself or the environment.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">The SDS / MSDS &mdash; the chemical's instruction sheet</span>\n<p>The <strong>Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS)</strong> &mdash; now called the <strong>Safety Data Sheet (SDS)</strong> under the modern GHS standard &mdash; is the form that lists everything about a chemical: <em>physical data (melting/boiling/flash point), toxicity, health effects, first aid, reactivity, storage, disposal, protective equipment, and spill handling.</em> (Study Guide, Std 23.) Key rules:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Chemical <strong>suppliers are required by law to provide</strong> the SDS to purchasers.</li>\n<li>Employers must <strong>keep them and make them readily accessible during every work shift</strong> in the work area.</li>\n<li><strong>Before</strong> you use an unfamiliar chemical &mdash; read its SDS.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<p><strong>Labeling.</strong> Every container must have a <strong>waterproof label</strong> listing: the <strong>substance/trade name, the manufacturer, the hazards, and the date</strong>. Never use a chemical from an unlabeled container. OSHA's <strong>Hazard Communication program</strong> ties labels + SDSs + training together so workers know what they're exposed to.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Storage.</strong> Stack and secure containers so they can't slide, fall, or collapse. <strong>Store incompatible substances apart</strong> &mdash; on different shelves or in non-flammable storage cabinets. Keep aisles clear. Keep storage areas free of trip/fire/explosion hazards. (Study Guide, Std 23.)</p>\n\n<p><strong>Disposal.</strong> The <strong>EPA</strong> controls hazardous waste &mdash; generation, transport, treatment, storage, and disposal. Hard rules:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Never pour hazardous materials down the drain</strong> (it can wreck a wastewater plant).</li>\n<li><strong>Never pour hazardous waste down a storm drain</strong> &mdash; it runs straight to a lake or stream.</li>\n<li>Put solvent waste, <strong>oily rags, and flammable liquids in covered, fire-resistant containers</strong> until removed. (Oily rags can spontaneously combust.)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Solvents, fumes &amp; ventilation</span>\n<p>Solvents like <strong>acetone</strong> (colorless, volatile, <em>extremely flammable</em>) and <strong>MEK (methyl ethyl ketone)</strong> dissolve other substances but throw off <strong>flammable, toxic vapors</strong>. Always use them with <strong>good ventilation</strong>, away from ignition sources, with the right respirator/gloves/eye protection. The <strong>Permissible Exposure Level (PEL)</strong> is the allowable amount of a hazardous substance in the breathing air. When in doubt &mdash; ventilate and check the SDS.</p></div>\n\n<h3>STANDARD 24 &mdash; FOD Prevention</h3>\n<p><strong>FOD</strong> has two meanings you must keep straight (Study Guide, Std 24):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>FOD = Foreign Object Debris</strong> &mdash; the <em>thing</em>: any substance, debris, or article alien to the system that has gotten into the product and could cause damage (a washer, a safety-wire clipping, a dropped bolt, a rag, a tool).</li>\n<li><strong>FOD = Foreign Object Damage</strong> &mdash; the <em>harm</em>: any damage attributed to a foreign object, in physical or economic terms.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>(<strong>FOE = Foreign Object Elimination</strong> is the program/process used to assure a FOD-free product.)</p>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Why one dropped washer is a catastrophe</span>\n<p>A loose washer or safety-wire clipping left in an aircraft can get sucked into a turbine engine and shred the blades, or jam a flight-control linkage, or short out an electrical connector. A single missing tool the size of your finger, left behind a panel, can cause a crash. That's why <strong>FOD is treated as deadly serious</strong> &mdash; the cost of one tiny object is potentially an airplane and lives.</p></div>\n\n<p><strong>Tool control / accountability</strong> is how you make sure nothing gets left behind. Methods (Study Guide, Std 24): <strong>shadow box / shadow board</strong> (every tool has a painted outline; an empty outline means a tool is missing), <strong>tethers</strong>, the <strong>chit system</strong>, <strong>tool inventory sheets/logs</strong>, tool ID marking, consolidated tool kits, <strong>sponge counts</strong>, and electronic tool-accountability systems. You <strong>inventory tools before and after</strong> every job.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Clean as you go.</strong> The Study Guide's literal rules: clean the immediate area when work pauses or when debris could migrate somewhere you can't see; <strong>inspect and clean all tools after the job or end of shift</strong>; clean the area before inspection; clean at the end of each shift; and the golden rule &mdash; <strong>\"If you drop something or hear something drop &mdash; pick it up!\"</strong></p>\n\n<h3>STANDARD 27 &mdash; Handling Electrostatic (ESD) Devices</h3>\n<p>Modern avionics are full of <strong>static-sensitive parts</strong> &mdash; circuit boards, microchips, and solid-state devices. <strong>Electrostatic Discharge (ESD)</strong> is, per the Study Guide, <em>\"the instantaneous discharge of static electricity that has built up on one surface or point and is discharged to another.\"</em> The scary part: a static zap far too small for you to feel or hear &mdash; well under the ~3,000 volts it takes to feel a spark &mdash; can still destroy a microchip.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">How static builds &mdash; and three ways it kills a part</span>\n<p>Static builds by <strong>friction</strong> &mdash; walking across carpet, sliding out of a chair, peeling tape, low humidity. Your body becomes a charged capacitor. Touch a sensitive pin and that charge dumps into the device. The Study Guide lists three kinds of <strong>electrostatic damage</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Catastrophic failure</strong> &mdash; the part dies instantly.</li>\n<li><strong>Delayed failure</strong> &mdash; weakened now, fails later in flight (the dangerous one &mdash; it passed your bench test).</li>\n<li><strong>Degradation</strong> &mdash; the part still works but performs worse / shorter life.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<p><strong>ESD protection</strong> (Study Guide, Std 27 &mdash; \"Proper Grounding and Handling\"):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Wear a grounded conductive wrist strap</strong> &mdash; it <em>connects your body to ground</em> so charge drains off harmlessly instead of dumping into the part. The strap <strong>must be grounded to earth ground</strong>; an ungrounded strap does nothing. (It also has a built-in resistor for <em>your</em> safety so you're not a bare wire to ground.)</li>\n<li>Work on a <strong>grounded ESD mat / grounded workstation surface</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Drain your body charge</strong> by touching the grounded metal case of the equipment before handling.</li>\n<li><strong>Touch only the part</strong> you're installing/removing &mdash; <strong>do not touch the bare pins/leads</strong>; handle the device by its <strong>case/edges</strong>.</li>\n<li>Transport and store ESD parts in <strong>conductive covers / protective (anti-static) packaging</strong> &mdash; conductive bags.</li>\n<li><strong>Higher humidity</strong> helps (moist air bleeds off static); dry winter air is the worst for ESD.</li>\n<li>The military ESD caution standard is <strong>MIL-STD-129</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Analogy: the doorknob spark, but invisible</span>\n<p>You know the little zap when you touch a doorknob in winter? That spark is thousands of volts. A microchip can be <strong>destroyed by a zap so weak you'd never feel it.</strong> The grounded wrist strap is like a tiny ground wire keeping you at the <em>same</em> charge level as the bench and the part &mdash; so there's never a difference to spark across.</p></div>\n\n<h3>STANDARD 29 &mdash; Use Safety Devices</h3>\n<p>Aircraft live with <strong>constant vibration and temperature swings</strong>, which loosen fasteners and connectors. Safety devices keep things from backing off, breaking loose, or burning up.</p>\n\n<table>\n<tr><th>Device</th><th>What it does</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Cotter pin</strong></td><td>A split pin pushed through a hole in a bolt/castle nut and bent over to <strong>mechanically lock the nut</strong> so it can't unscrew. Single-use &mdash; install a new one each time.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Safety wire (lock wire)</strong></td><td>Wire threaded through fasteners/connectors and twisted so that <strong>vibration can only tighten them, never loosen them</strong>. Used on anything not self-locking.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Fuse</strong></td><td>A thin metal link that <strong>melts and breaks the circuit</strong> when current gets too high &mdash; protects wiring/equipment. One-time; replace it.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Circuit breaker</strong></td><td>A <strong>resettable</strong> switch that trips (opens) on overcurrent, then can be reset after the fault is fixed &mdash; same protective job as a fuse, reusable.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Warning placard</strong></td><td>A label/sign that warns of a hazard or states a limit (e.g., \"HIGH VOLTAGE,\" \"NO STEP,\" weight limits). Part of communicating danger.</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Safety wire specifics (Study Guide, Std 29)</span>\n<ul>\n<li>Installed with <strong>safety-wire pliers</strong> that lock/twist when you squeeze the handles.</li>\n<li>Comes in sizes from <strong>0.020\" to 0.041\"</strong> diameter. The general-purpose size for equipment fasteners is <strong>0.032\"</strong>. Use the smaller <strong>0.020\"</strong> on electrical connectors and small screws (heavier wire would break out the connector collar holes).</li>\n<li><strong>Wire so vibration tightens, never loosens.</strong> Use correct size, proper tension, proper number of twists per inch, a proper pigtail, and keep it off adjacent parts.</li>\n<li><strong>Safety-wire clippings are a serious FOD hazard &mdash; track and dispose of every clipping.</strong> (Note how 29 loops right back to 24!)</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<p><strong>Shear wire</strong> is a special safety wire (copper or brass) that is <em>designed to break</em> when force is applied. It's used on <strong>emergency equipment</strong> &mdash; switch handles, exit-handle guards, and fire extinguishers &mdash; so the seal shows the item hasn't been used, yet it breaks easily in an emergency. (Study Guide, Std 29.)</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Fuse vs. circuit breaker &mdash; the one-liner</span>\n<p>Both protect a circuit by <strong>opening on overcurrent</strong>. The difference: a <strong>fuse is sacrificial</strong> (it melts &mdash; you replace it); a <strong>circuit breaker is resettable</strong> (it trips &mdash; you reset it after fixing the fault). Both protect the <em>wiring and equipment</em> from overheating and fire.</p></div>\n\n<h3>Putting it all together</h3>\n<p>Safety isn't a separate task &mdash; it's woven through everything. You de-energize and lock out before working (22), you read the SDS and ventilate before you open the solvent (23), you control every tool and clipping so nothing's left behind (24), you ground yourself before touching a board (27), and you safety the fasteners and protect the circuits when you button it up (29). Notice the connections: a safety-wire clipping (29) is FOD (24); a Class C fire (22) means de-energizing electrical (22/29); a charged capacitor is a shock hazard (22) even at \"low\" voltage. The exam asks these as plain facts &mdash; know the lists cold.</p>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">An electrical fire involving energized equipment is which fire class, and what kind of extinguisher must you use? <span class=\"a\">Answer: Class C &mdash; use a non-conductive agent like CO&#8322; (or Halon/dry chemical). NEVER plain water (it conducts and can electrocute you).</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">What actually injures or kills you in an electrical shock &mdash; the voltage or the current? <span class=\"a\">Answer: the CURRENT (amperes) flowing through the body. As little as ~0.1 A across the chest can stop the heart. Voltage is only the push.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">For an ESD wrist strap to actually protect a circuit board, what is the one essential requirement? <span class=\"a\">Answer: it must be connected (grounded) to earth ground &mdash; that's how the static charge drains off your body. An ungrounded strap does nothing.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Before using an unfamiliar chemical solvent, what document do you read, and where must your employer keep it? <span class=\"a\">Answer: the SDS/MSDS (Safety Data Sheet) &mdash; it must be readily accessible in the work area during every work shift.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">You're safety-wiring a fastener and snip off the pigtail. Why can't you just leave the clipping there? <span class=\"a\">Answer: safety-wire clippings are a serious FOD hazard &mdash; you must track and dispose of every clipping (clean as you go).</span></div>", "quiz": [{"q": "An energized electrical fire (live wiring, motors, panels) is which class of fire?", "options": ["Class A", "Class B", "Class C", "Class D"], "correct": 2, "short": "Class C", "expl": "Class C fires involve energized electrical wiring and equipment; use a non-conductive agent.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.1-5", "topic": "fire-class"}, {"q": "Which extinguisher must you AVOID on a Class C (electrical) fire?", "options": ["Carbon dioxide (CO2)", "Plain water", "Dry chemical", "Halon"], "correct": 1, "short": "Never water on electrical", "expl": "Water conducts electricity; using it on energized equipment can electrocute the operator. Use CO2, Halon, or dry chemical.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.1-5", "topic": "extinguisher"}, {"q": "Class A fires involve:", "options": ["Flammable liquids like fuel and solvents", "Energized electrical equipment", "Flammable metals like magnesium", "Ordinary combustibles like wood, paper, and cloth"], "correct": 3, "short": "Ordinary combustibles", "expl": "Class A fires involve ordinary combustible materials such as wood, cloth, paper, and upholstery.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.1-5", "topic": "fire-class"}, {"q": "Class B fires involve:", "options": ["Flammable petroleum products, greases, solvents, and paints", "Wood, paper, and cloth", "Energized electrical wiring", "Burning magnesium"], "correct": 0, "short": "Flammable liquids", "expl": "Class B fires involve flammable liquids: fuel, oil, grease, solvents, and paint.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.1-5", "topic": "fire-class"}, {"q": "A Class D fire involves what, and which extinguishing agent is correct?", "options": ["Paper; water", "Electrical equipment; CO2", "Flammable metals like magnesium; dry powder only", "Fuel; foam"], "correct": 2, "short": "Metals; dry powder only", "expl": "Class D fires involve flammable metals (e.g., magnesium). Use dry powder only; water or CO2 can cause explosive expansion of the hot metal.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.1-5 to 1-6", "topic": "fire-class"}, {"q": "A CO2 extinguisher is effective on which fire classes?", "options": ["Class D only", "Class A only", "Classes A, B, and C", "All four classes including D"], "correct": 2, "short": "CO2 = A, B, C", "expl": "CO2 extinguishers are used on Class A, B, and C fires by smothering (removing oxygen). Never use CO2 on Class D.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.1-5", "topic": "extinguisher"}, {"q": "Three things must be present at once for a fire (the fire triangle). They are:", "options": ["Fuel, heat, and oxygen", "Fuel, water, and air", "Spark, smoke, and ash", "Voltage, current, and resistance"], "correct": 0, "short": "Fuel + heat + oxygen", "expl": "Fire requires fuel, heat, and oxygen; remove any one and the fire goes out.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.1-5", "topic": "fire-triangle"}, {"q": "In an electrical shock, what actually injures or kills the body?", "options": ["The voltage alone", "The current (amperes) flowing through the body", "The frequency of the source", "The resistance of the wire"], "correct": 1, "short": "Current kills", "expl": "It is the current passing through the body that causes injury; voltage is only the push that drives it. Very small currents can be lethal.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22; FAA-H-8083-30B p.1-5", "topic": "shock"}, {"q": "What is the FIRST action when someone is being electrically shocked?", "options": ["Pour water on them", "Pull them off with your bare hands immediately", "Turn off the power as quickly as possible", "Give them water to drink"], "correct": 2, "short": "Turn off the power first", "expl": "Turn off the power first. If you can't, do not touch the victim or the current passes through you too.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22 (First Aid for Electrical Shock)", "topic": "shock-firstaid"}, {"q": "If you cannot shut off the power, how should you move a shock victim clear of the source?", "options": ["Grab their arm directly", "Splash water to break the contact", "Use a metal hook", "Use a dry, non-conducting object like a dry wooden pole or broom"], "correct": 3, "short": "Use a dry non-conductor", "expl": "Use a dry, non-conducting object (wooden pole, broom, chair) to push or pull the victim clear without touching them.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22 (First Aid for Electrical Shock)", "topic": "shock-firstaid"}, {"q": "Locking a switch or breaker OFF and tagging it so no one can re-energize the circuit is called:", "options": ["FOD control", "A job briefing", "Lockout/tagout", "An SDS"], "correct": 2, "short": "Lockout/tagout", "expl": "Lockout/tagout devices shut down, isolate, block, and secure equipment to control hazardous energy sources.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22 (Elimination/Termination of Circuit Power)", "topic": "loto"}, {"q": "Per the Study Guide, PPE selection considers the ways hazards enter the body. Which list is correct?", "options": ["Inhalation, skin absorption, ingestion, eye/skin contact", "Vibration, heat, cold, noise", "Voltage, current, resistance, power", "Fuel, heat, oxygen, ignition"], "correct": 0, "short": "Inhale, absorb, ingest, contact", "expl": "PPE addresses inhalation, skin absorption, ingestion, and eye or skin contact, and is hazard-specific.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22 (PPE)", "topic": "ppe"}, {"q": "Circuit protection devices listed in the Study Guide include:", "options": ["Cotter pins and safety wire", "Respirators and gloves", "Fuses, current limiters, thermal protectors, and circuit breakers", "Shadow boards and tethers"], "correct": 2, "short": "Fuses, limiters, breakers", "expl": "Circuit protection devices include fuses, current limiters, thermal protectors (switches), and circuit breakers.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22 (Circuit Protection Devices)", "topic": "circuit-protection"}, {"q": "A Safety Data Sheet (SDS/MSDS) provides information such as:", "options": ["Toxicity, health effects, first aid, storage, disposal, and spill handling", "Aircraft weight and balance", "Wire gauge and color codes", "Tie-down rope dimensions"], "correct": 0, "short": "Chemical hazard data", "expl": "An SDS lists physical data, toxicity, health effects, first aid, reactivity, storage, disposal, protective equipment, and spill handling.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 23 (Material Safety Data Sheet)", "topic": "sds"}, {"q": "Who is legally required to supply the SDS to the purchaser of a chemical?", "options": ["The EPA", "The chemical supplier", "The end user", "The fire department"], "correct": 1, "short": "Supplier provides SDS", "expl": "Hazardous chemical suppliers are required by law to supply MSDSs/SDSs to purchasers.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 23 (MSDS Compliance/Chemical Suppliers)", "topic": "sds"}, {"q": "Which is a hard rule for hazardous-waste disposal?", "options": ["Pour solvents down the sink if diluted", "Burn oily rags in the open", "Store waste in open buckets", "Never pour hazardous waste down a drain or storm drain"], "correct": 3, "short": "Never down the drain", "expl": "Never pour hazardous materials down a drain or storm drain; it damages wastewater plants or contaminates lakes and streams.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 23 (Specifics to Follow at Jobsite)", "topic": "disposal"}, {"q": "Which federal agency has authority to control hazardous waste?", "options": ["OSHA", "FAA", "NFPA", "EPA"], "correct": 3, "short": "EPA", "expl": "The EPA controls the generation, transportation, treatment, storage, and disposal of hazardous waste.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 23 (Environmental Protection Agency)", "topic": "disposal"}, {"q": "Per the Study Guide, every chemical container label must list:", "options": ["Substance/trade name, manufacturer, hazards, and date", "Only the price", "Only a barcode", "The technician's name"], "correct": 0, "short": "Name, maker, hazards, date", "expl": "Containers must carry waterproof labels listing the substance/trade name, manufacturer, hazards, and date.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 23 (Labels)", "topic": "labeling"}, {"q": "Acetone is described in the Study Guide as:", "options": ["A non-flammable cleaner", "Colorless, volatile, and extremely flammable", "A safe drinking solvent", "A solid at room temperature"], "correct": 1, "short": "Extremely flammable", "expl": "Acetone is an organic solvent that is colorless, volatile, and extremely flammable; use with ventilation and away from ignition.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22 (Hazardous Liquids)", "topic": "solvents"}, {"q": "In FOD terminology, 'Foreign Object Debris' refers to:", "options": ["The damage caused to an engine", "A required maintenance tool", "An approved aircraft part", "A substance or article alien to the system that could cause damage"], "correct": 3, "short": "The alien object itself", "expl": "Foreign Object Debris is any substance, debris, or article alien to a vehicle/system that has invaded the product and could cause damage.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 24 (FOD)", "topic": "fod-def"}, {"q": "A painted outline showing exactly where each tool belongs, so a missing tool is obvious, is called a:", "options": ["Shadow box / shadow board", "Lockout tag", "Safety Data Sheet", "Warning placard"], "correct": 0, "short": "Shadow board", "expl": "A shadow box/board is a tool-control method: an empty outline immediately shows a tool is missing.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 24 (Tool Control and Management)", "topic": "tool-control"}, {"q": "Why is a single dropped washer or safety-wire clipping treated so seriously on an aircraft?", "options": ["It is expensive to replace", "It violates a paperwork rule only", "It can be ingested by an engine, jam a control, or short a connector and cause catastrophic damage", "It only affects appearance"], "correct": 2, "short": "It can destroy the aircraft", "expl": "Small FOD can be ingested by an engine, jam flight controls, or short electrical connectors, causing catastrophic damage.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 24 (FOD Prevention)", "topic": "fod-why"}, {"q": "The Study Guide's 'clean as you go' rule includes which famous instruction?", "options": ["Leave debris for the cleanup crew", "If you drop something or hear something drop, pick it up", "Only clean at the end of the month", "Never inspect your tools"], "correct": 1, "short": "Drop it, pick it up", "expl": "Clean as you go: inspect/clean tools after each job and 'if you drop something or hear something drop, pick it up.'", "cite": "Study Guide Std 24 (Clean As You Go)", "topic": "clean-as-you-go"}, {"q": "Per the Study Guide, ESD (electrostatic discharge) is:", "options": ["A slow leak of current through a resistor", "The instantaneous discharge of static electricity from one surface to another", "A type of fuse", "The same thing as corrosion"], "correct": 1, "short": "Instant static discharge", "expl": "ESD is the instantaneous discharge of static electricity built up on one point and discharged to another.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22/27 (ESD)", "topic": "esd-def"}, {"q": "Why is ESD so dangerous to microelectronics?", "options": ["It heats the whole shop", "It only damages large parts", "It is harmless to electronics", "A static zap too small for a person to feel can still destroy a circuit board or chip"], "correct": 3, "short": "Unfelt zap kills chips", "expl": "Static-sensitive devices can be damaged by a discharge far below what a person can feel, causing catastrophic, delayed, or degraded failure.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 27 (Handling of Electrostatic Devices)", "topic": "esd-why"}, {"q": "For an ESD wrist strap to protect a part, it must be:", "options": ["Made of plastic", "Worn loosely", "Connected (grounded) to earth ground", "Left disconnected"], "correct": 2, "short": "Grounded to earth", "expl": "A conductive wrist strap must connect the body to earth ground so static charge drains off; ungrounded, it does nothing.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22/27 (Conductive Wrist Strap)", "topic": "esd-strap"}, {"q": "Which shop condition makes static-electricity (ESD) buildup WORSE?", "options": ["High humidity", "Low humidity (dry air)", "A grounded mat", "A wrist strap"], "correct": 1, "short": "Low humidity worsens ESD", "expl": "Dry, low-humidity air lets static build up; higher humidity bleeds charge off and reduces ESD risk.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 27 (Handling of Electrostatic Devices)", "topic": "esd-humidity"}, {"q": "The three kinds of electrostatic damage listed in the Study Guide are:", "options": ["Galvanic, pitting, exfoliation", "Catastrophic failure, delayed failure, and degradation", "Open, short, and ground fault", "Class A, B, and C"], "correct": 1, "short": "Catastrophic, delayed, degradation", "expl": "Electrostatic damage includes total catastrophic failure, delayed failure, and degradation to the circuit.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 27 (Electrostatic Damage)", "topic": "esd-damage"}, {"q": "Why is safety wire (lock wire) installed on aircraft fasteners?", "options": ["To carry electrical current", "To make the fastener look finished", "To increase the fastener's weight", "So vibration can only tighten the fastener, never loosen it"], "correct": 3, "short": "Vibration can't loosen it", "expl": "Safety wire secures non-self-locking fasteners/connectors so the constant vibration of flight cannot loosen them.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 29 (Safety Wire)", "topic": "safety-wire"}, {"q": "What is the general-purpose diameter of safety wire used for securing equipment fasteners?", "options": ["0.010 inch", "0.032 inch", "0.125 inch", "0.250 inch"], "correct": 1, "short": "0.032 inch", "expl": "0.032-inch safety wire is the general-purpose size; use 0.020-inch on electrical connectors and small screws.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 29 (Types and Sizes of Safety Wire)", "topic": "safety-wire-size"}, {"q": "Per the Study Guide, safety-wire clippings are:", "options": ["Harmless and can be left in place", "A serious FOD hazard that must be tracked and disposed of", "Reusable on the next job", "Recycled into new wire on the spot"], "correct": 1, "short": "Clippings are FOD", "expl": "Keep track of safety-wire clippings and dispose of them properly because they pose a serious FOD hazard.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 29 (Acceptable Safety Wire Practices)", "topic": "safety-wire-fod"}, {"q": "What is the main difference between a fuse and a circuit breaker?", "options": ["A fuse is resettable; a breaker melts", "They do completely different jobs", "A breaker only works on AC and a fuse only on DC", "A fuse melts and is replaced; a circuit breaker trips and can be reset"], "correct": 3, "short": "Fuse melts; breaker resets", "expl": "Both open the circuit on overcurrent to protect wiring/equipment; a fuse is sacrificial (replace it), a breaker is resettable.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22 (Circuit Protection Devices)", "topic": "fuse-breaker"}, {"q": "A cotter pin is used to:", "options": ["Conduct signals between boards", "Filter ripple from a power supply", "Mechanically lock a castle nut or bolt so it cannot unscrew", "Ground an ESD strap"], "correct": 2, "short": "Locks a nut", "expl": "A cotter pin is inserted through a hole and bent over to mechanically lock a nut/bolt against loosening; it is single-use.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 29 (Use Safety Devices)", "topic": "cotter-pin"}, {"q": "Shear wire is used on emergency equipment because it is designed to:", "options": ["Never break under any load", "Carry high current", "Resist corrosion only", "Break when a force is applied"], "correct": 3, "short": "Designed to break", "expl": "Shear wire (copper/brass) is used on switch handles, exit-handle guards, and fire extinguishers; it breaks when force is applied.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 29 (Shear Wire)", "topic": "shear-wire"}, {"q": "A label or sign warning of a hazard or stating a limitation (e.g., 'HIGH VOLTAGE') is a:", "options": ["Warning placard", "Safety Data Sheet", "Shadow board", "Cotter pin"], "correct": 0, "short": "Warning placard", "expl": "Warning placards communicate hazards or limits and are a key safety device for alerting personnel.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 29 (Use Safety Devices)", "topic": "placard"}, {"q": "Roughly how much current through the chest can be enough to stop a person's heart?", "options": ["About 0.1 ampere (100 milliamperes)", "About 50 amperes", "About 200 amperes", "There is no dangerous level"], "correct": 0, "short": "~0.1 A is lethal", "expl": "As little as roughly 0.1-0.2 A across the chest can cause fatal heart fibrillation; current, not voltage, is the killer.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22 (electrical shock safety)", "topic": "shock-level"}, {"q": "Before working on a circuit, a 'job briefing' (Study Guide) covers all of these EXCEPT:", "options": ["Hazards associated with the job", "Energy source controls and PPE requirements", "Work procedures and special precautions", "The current resale value of the aircraft"], "correct": 3, "short": "Not resale value", "expl": "A job briefing covers job hazards, work procedures, special precautions, energy-source controls, and PPE requirements.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22 (Job Briefings)", "topic": "job-briefing"}, {"q": "The standard way to operate most fire extinguishers is best summarized as:", "options": ["Aim at the top of the flames and hold still", "Pull the pin, aim at the base of the fire, squeeze, and sweep side to side", "Throw it into the fire", "Spray from directly overhead only"], "correct": 1, "short": "Pull, aim, squeeze, sweep", "expl": "Pull the pin, aim at the base of the fire, squeeze the lever, and sweep side to side (the PASS method), standing about 8 feet back.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.1-8", "topic": "extinguisher-use"}], "drill": [{"label": "Class C fire", "text": "Energized electrical fire = Class C. Use a NON-conductive agent (CO2 / Halon / dry chemical). NEVER plain water."}, {"label": "Fire classes A/B/C/D", "text": "A = ordinary combustibles (wood/paper); B = flammable liquids (fuel/solvent); C = energized electrical; D = flammable metals (magnesium)."}, {"label": "Class D extinguisher", "text": "Flammable-metal fire = dry powder ONLY. Water or CO2 makes hot metal explode."}, {"label": "Fire triangle", "text": "Fuel + Heat + Oxygen. Remove any one and the fire goes out."}, {"label": "Current kills, not voltage", "text": "It's the current (amps) through the body that injures. ~0.1 A across the chest can stop the heart."}, {"label": "Shock first aid", "text": "TURN OFF THE POWER first. If you can't, don't touch the victim; use a dry wooden pole to move them clear."}, {"label": "Lockout/tagout", "text": "Lock a switch/breaker OFF and tag it so no one re-energizes the circuit while you work."}, {"label": "SDS / MSDS", "text": "Safety Data Sheet lists toxicity, first aid, storage, disposal. Supplier must provide it; employer keeps it accessible every shift."}, {"label": "Hazmat disposal", "text": "Never pour hazardous waste down a drain or storm drain. EPA controls hazardous waste. Oily rags -> covered fire-resistant container."}, {"label": "FOD two meanings", "text": "Foreign Object Debris = the object; Foreign Object Damage = the harm it causes."}, {"label": "FOD tool control", "text": "Shadow board/box, tethers, chit system, inventory logs. Inventory tools before and after every job. Drop it -> pick it up."}, {"label": "ESD wrist strap grounded", "text": "A conductive wrist strap MUST be grounded to earth ground to drain static. Ungrounded = useless."}, {"label": "ESD handling", "text": "Static you can't feel destroys chips. Handle by the case/edges, not bare pins; store in conductive bags; high humidity helps."}, {"label": "Safety wire / clippings", "text": "Safety wire so vibration can only TIGHTEN fasteners. 0.032 in general-purpose. Clippings are a serious FOD hazard -> track and dispose."}]}, {"n": 10, "title": "Tools, Pubs & Corrosion", "standards": "25, 26, 28", "lesson": "<h3>Why this matters on a real aircraft</h3>\n<p>This module ties together the three skills a working avionics tech uses on almost every job. <strong>Standard 25 (Technical Publications)</strong> is how you find out what to do &mdash; you always work to the <strong>approved data</strong>, never from memory. <strong>Standard 26 (Use Common Tools)</strong> is doing the job right with the right tool, including <strong>torque</strong>. <strong>Standard 28 (Corrosion Control)</strong> is the slow killer of avionics: a corroded pin, ground strap, or connector causes the <strong>intermittent faults</strong> that drive techs crazy. Master these three and you stop guessing and start working like a professional.</p>\n\n<h3>PART 1 &mdash; Technical Publications (Standard 25)</h3>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">The one rule that never changes</span>\n<p><strong>You always work to the data.</strong> Never &ldquo;wing it&rdquo; from memory. The manufacturer's instructions and FAA-approved data tell you the exact steps, torque values, wire gauges, and limits. The Study Guide says to <em>&ldquo;consult manuals for guidance when installing and maintaining aircraft systems and components&rdquo;</em> and to <em>&ldquo;select the most appropriate way to install or maintain the component.&rdquo;</em></p></div>\n\n<h4>The publications you must know (and what each one is FOR)</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Publication</th><th>What it is / when you reach for it</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Maintenance / Installation Manual</strong></td><td>The manufacturer's step-by-step instructions for working on a system or component. Your primary &ldquo;how-to.&rdquo;</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Wiring Diagram Manual (WDM)</strong></td><td>Shows how components are connected electrically using <strong>standardized symbols</strong> &mdash; wiring, connectors, terminal boards. Used to <strong>troubleshoot and repair</strong> circuits.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Schematic Diagram</strong></td><td>Shows the electrical/fluid system with <strong>symbols, not pictures</strong>; does NOT show physical location. Used mainly for troubleshooting.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Block Diagram</strong></td><td>High-level diagram of functional <strong>blocks</strong> with arrows showing signal/energy flow. Used for troubleshooting or teaching how a system works.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Illustrated Parts Catalog (IPC)</strong> / Installation Diagram</td><td>Picture of the system with <strong>callouts</strong> identifying and locating each component &mdash; you order parts and find part numbers here.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Airworthiness Directive (AD)</strong></td><td>FAA legal order to fix an <strong>unsafe condition</strong>. <strong>Compliance is MANDATORY</strong> and has a timeframe. (Issued under 14 CFR Part 39.)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Service Bulletin (SB)</strong></td><td>Manufacturer's <strong>recommendation</strong> about a defect or improvement. <strong>NOT mandatory</strong> under the FARs <em>unless</em> it's referenced by an AD.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Supplemental Type Certificate (STC)</strong></td><td>FAA approval of a <strong>design alteration</strong> (airframe, engine, propeller, or a new avionics install).</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Minimum Equipment List (MEL)</strong></td><td>FAA-approved list of equipment that may be <strong>inoperative</strong> while the aircraft still legally flies (14 CFR 91.213).</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>AC 43.13-1B/2B</strong></td><td>FAA acceptable methods/techniques for repair. The Study Guide says: <em>consult AC 43.13-1B/2B <strong>if no maintenance manual exists</strong></em> for the aircraft.</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">AD vs. SB &mdash; the classic trap question</span>\n<p><strong>AD = MANDATORY</strong> (FAA, legal, safety, has a deadline). <strong>SB = recommended</strong> (manufacturer) &mdash; it only becomes mandatory when an AD points to it. If a test question asks &ldquo;which document <em>requires</em> compliance,&rdquo; the answer is the <strong>AD</strong>.</p></div>\n\n<h4>How to actually FIND a procedure (the ATA chapter system)</h4>\n<p>Aircraft manuals are organized by the <strong>ATA 100 chapter system</strong> &mdash; a standard numbering scheme so every manufacturer files the same system in the same chapter. A chapter number looks like <strong>CC-SS-UU</strong> (chapter&ndash;section&ndash;subject). A few you'll see constantly in avionics:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Chapter 20</strong> &mdash; Standard Practices (wiring, bonding, hardware)</li>\n<li><strong>Chapter 23</strong> &mdash; Communications (COMM radios)</li>\n<li><strong>Chapter 24</strong> &mdash; Electrical Power</li>\n<li><strong>Chapter 25</strong> &mdash; Equipment/Furnishings</li>\n<li><strong>Chapter 31</strong> &mdash; Indicating/Recording (instruments, displays)</li>\n<li><strong>Chapter 34</strong> &mdash; Navigation (NAV, GPS, autopilot sensors)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To find a procedure: open the manual &rarr; go to the <strong>ATA chapter</strong> for that system &rarr; use the <strong>Table of Contents and Index</strong> &rarr; read the <strong>legend/key</strong> for symbols on any diagram &rarr; follow the <strong>callouts</strong>. The Study Guide spells this out: <em>&ldquo;Check the Table of Contents. Check the index&hellip; Refer to the symbols in the legend or key&hellip; Read the labels and callouts on a drawing.&rdquo;</em></p>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Plain-English analogy</span>\n<p>The ATA chapter system is like a <strong>library Dewey Decimal system for airplanes</strong>. Every book (system) has a fixed shelf number, so whether you're holding a Cessna manual or a Boeing manual, &ldquo;electrical power&rdquo; is always in the same chapter (24). You don't memorize procedures &mdash; you memorize <strong>how to look them up.</strong></p></div>\n\n<h3>PART 2 &mdash; Common Tools (Standard 26)</h3>\n\n<p>Standard 26 is a <strong>Level 2b</strong> outcome &mdash; meaning you should be able to do most of the task and pick the right tool. The Study Guide lists the &ldquo;common tools&rdquo;: hammers and mallets, screwdrivers, pliers and cutters, punches, wrenches (including <strong>spanner, torque, and Allen</strong>), snips, hacksaws, files, drills, reamers, countersinks, <strong>wire strippers, crimpers, pin extractors</strong>, magnifying glasses, <strong>analog and/or digital multimeters</strong>, rules, scribers, <strong>calipers, micrometer calipers, vernier scales</strong>, taps, and dies.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">The three proficiency rules (Study Guide, Std 26)</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Choose the tool best suited for the job</strong> &mdash; the right tool, not the closest tool.</li>\n<li><strong>Some tools have more than one use</strong> &mdash; but don't abuse a tool (a screwdriver is not a pry bar or chisel).</li>\n<li><strong>Safety &amp; care</strong> &mdash; handle and care for tools properly. The Guide's own example: <em>&ldquo;improper use of a hammer can damage an aircraft and cause physical injury.&rdquo;</em></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h4>Torque &mdash; and why it matters</h4>\n<p><strong>Torque</strong> is rotational (twisting) force, measured in <strong>inch-pounds (in-lb)</strong> or <strong>foot-pounds (ft-lb)</strong>. A <strong>torque wrench</strong> applies an exact, measured amount so a fastener is neither too loose nor too tight.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Too little torque</strong> &rarr; the fastener vibrates loose &rarr; a connector backs off, a ground strap loosens &rarr; <strong>intermittent electrical faults.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Too much torque</strong> &rarr; you <strong>stretch/strip the threads</strong> or crack the part &mdash; a failure waiting to happen.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Key conversion (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;7-50):</strong> to get <strong>foot-pounds, divide inch-pounds by 12</strong> (because 1&nbsp;ft = 12&nbsp;in). Example: 240&nbsp;in-lb &divide; 12 = <strong>20&nbsp;ft-lb</strong>.</p>\n<p>The handbook gives the torque formula <strong>F &times; L = T</strong> (Force &times; Lever length = Torque), and shows the three common torque wrenches: the <strong>flexible-beam</strong>, the <strong>rigid-frame (dial)</strong>, and the <strong>ratchet (click) type</strong>. Rules from the standard torque table (p.&nbsp;7-50): <strong>tighten by rotating the nut, not the bolt head, when possible</strong>; do <strong>not lubricate</strong> threads unless the manual says to; and <strong>never exceed the maximum value.</strong> Using a <strong>drive-end extension</strong> changes the wrench reading &mdash; you must recompute it with the proper formula.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Analogy: a fishing scale on a wrench</span>\n<p>A torque wrench is just a wrench with a built-in scale. Tightening a bolt &ldquo;good and tight&rdquo; by feel is guessing; the torque wrench tells you the <strong>exact</strong> twisting force the engineer specified, so every joint is the same and nothing works loose in flight.</p></div>\n\n<h4>Measuring &amp; making tools</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Tool</th><th>What it does</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Multimeter (DMM)</strong></td><td>As a <em>tool</em> it measures voltage, current, resistance, and continuity &mdash; your #1 troubleshooting instrument. (Detailed in Module 11.)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Caliper</strong></td><td>Measures length, outside diameter, inside diameter, and depth. A <strong>vernier or dial/digital caliper</strong> reads to about 0.001&nbsp;in.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Micrometer (&ldquo;mic&rdquo;)</strong></td><td>More precise than a caliper &mdash; measures small thicknesses/diameters to about <strong>0.001&nbsp;in</strong> (a vernier mic to 0.0001&nbsp;in). Used to check wire/pin/sheet dimensions.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Wire stripper</strong></td><td>Removes insulation <em>without nicking the conductor</em> (a nicked strand creates a weak, high-resistance, corrosion-prone spot).</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Crimper</strong></td><td>Forms a <strong>gas-tight</strong> mechanical/electrical bond between a terminal/contact and a wire. The <strong>right die for the contact</strong> matters &mdash; a bad crimp is a future intermittent.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Pin/contact extractor</strong></td><td>Removes a contact from a connector housing without damaging it.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Soldering iron</strong></td><td>Joins conductors with solder; a clean tip + correct heat = a shiny, sound joint (a &ldquo;cold&rdquo; dull joint is high-resistance and unreliable).</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Calibration &mdash; a precision tool you can't trust is useless</span>\n<p>Measuring and torque tools must be <strong>calibrated</strong>: checked against a known standard on a schedule so their readings are accurate. A torque wrench reading 20&nbsp;ft-lb that's actually applying 30 is worse than no torque wrench at all. Out-of-calibration or out-of-date tools are <strong>removed from service.</strong> (Calibration overlaps Standard 32, Test Equipment.)</p></div>\n\n<h3>PART 3 &mdash; Corrosion Control (Standard 28)</h3>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">What corrosion IS (memorize this definition)</span>\n<p>The Study Guide: corrosion is the <strong>&ldquo;chemical or electrochemical deterioration of a material, usually metal, due to a reaction with its environment&rdquo;</strong> &mdash; and it <strong>&ldquo;may be visible, or not visible.&rdquo;</strong> FAA-H-8083-30B (p.&nbsp;8-1) agrees: corrosion is the deterioration of metal by <strong>chemical or electrochemical attack</strong>, and it can happen <strong>internally as well as on the surface.</strong></p></div>\n\n<p>The Study Guide flags corrosion as <em>&ldquo;a major contributing cause to the reduction of avionics equipment reliability.&rdquo;</em> That's the avionics angle: corrosion eats the <strong>contact surfaces</strong> &mdash; connector pins, terminal lugs, ground straps, bonding jumpers. Even a thin film of corrosion adds <strong>resistance</strong> at a connection, and resistance at a junction is exactly what causes <strong>intermittent, hard-to-find faults</strong> that come and go with vibration and temperature.</p>\n\n<h4>The electrochemical cell &mdash; the engine behind corrosion</h4>\n<p>Electrochemical corrosion needs <strong>three things at once</strong> (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;8-5): (1) an <strong>anode</strong> and a <strong>cathode</strong> (a difference in electrical potential), and (2) a <strong>conductive liquid (electrolyte)</strong> bridging them. Remove any one &mdash; usually the electrolyte (moisture) &mdash; and corrosion <strong>cannot occur.</strong> That is the entire basis of corrosion control.</p>\n<p>The handbook ranks metals by <strong>&ldquo;nobility&rdquo;</strong> in the <strong>galvanic series</strong> (p.&nbsp;8-6). The <strong>less noble (more active)</strong> a metal &mdash; magnesium, then aluminum &mdash; the <strong>more easily it corrodes</strong>. The <strong>more noble</strong> metals (gold, silver, titanium) resist corrosion. In any pairing, the <strong>more active metal becomes the anode and corrodes.</strong></p>\n\n<h4>The corrosion types the test asks (Study Guide, Std 28)</h4>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Type</th><th>Definition (Study Guide / FAA-H-8083-30B)</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Galvanic (dissimilar-metal)</strong></td><td>Occurs when <strong>two different metals contact each other in the presence of an electrolyte.</strong> The more active metal corrodes. THE big one for avionics &mdash; e.g., an aluminum structure against a steel fastener, or a tin terminal on a copper bus.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Pitting</strong></td><td>A severe, concentrated cell corrosion <strong>localized in pits</strong>, usually with a <strong>white or gray powder.</strong> Most common on aluminum and magnesium (oxide-film metals).</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Intergranular</strong></td><td>Corrosion <strong>within the metal along the grain boundaries</strong> (the crystal-structure seams). Often hidden.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Exfoliation</strong></td><td>An <strong>extreme form of intergranular</strong> corrosion that <strong>lifts/separates the metal into layers</strong> (like flaking pages), destroying strength.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Surface (uniform)</strong></td><td>The most common form &mdash; general roughening/etching with a powdery deposit over a broad area.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Concentration cell</strong></td><td>Caused by differences in the solution's <strong>oxygen</strong> or <strong>metal-ion</strong> concentration (e.g., crevices, under gaskets/faying surfaces). The low-oxygen area becomes the anode and corrodes.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Fretting</strong></td><td>Damage where two surfaces <strong>rub/vibrate</strong> against each other &mdash; relevant to connectors that move under vibration.</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Galvanic corrosion = a tiny battery you didn't want</span>\n<p>Put two different metals together with a little salty moisture and you've built a <strong>battery</strong>: the active metal (anode) gives up electrons and dissolves away. That's why a steel screw in an aluminum bracket grows white powder, and why a corroded ground point reads high resistance. The cure is to <strong>break the cell</strong>: keep moisture out, or insulate the two metals from each other.</p></div>\n\n<h4>How to RECOGNIZE corrosion (by its color/look)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Aluminum / magnesium</strong> &rarr; <strong>white or gray powdery</strong> deposit (snow-like mounds).</li>\n<li><strong>Steel / iron</strong> &rarr; <strong>reddish-brown</strong> oxide = <strong>rust.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Copper / brass / bronze</strong> &rarr; <strong>green or blue-green</strong> powdery deposit.</li>\n<li><strong>Hidden corrosion</strong> &rarr; may show only as <strong>blistered/lifted paint</strong>, or be invisible until you clean the area. The handbook says every corrosion inspection <strong>starts with a thorough cleaning</strong> of the area, then a visual check with a flashlight (and a mirror/magnifier).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>How to TREAT corrosion (general sequence)</h4>\n<p>FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;8-14: a complete corrosion treatment is <strong>(1) clean and strip the area &rarr; (2) remove as much corrosion product as practicable (mechanical or chemical) &rarr; (3) neutralize residue left in pits/crevices &rarr; (4) restore the protective surface film &rarr; (5) apply a protective coating/paint.</strong> If the damage <strong>exceeds the manufacturer's limits, the part is replaced.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Avionics-specific cautions:</strong> on a corroded <strong>connector or ground point</strong> you clean the contact surfaces, but you must use the <strong>right method for the metal</strong> &mdash; never steel wool/steel brushes on aluminum or titanium (it embeds steel particles that start <em>new</em> galvanic corrosion), and never harsh abrasives that remove plating from a contact. Re-protect the joint after cleaning.</p>\n\n<h4>How to PREVENT corrosion (protective finishes &amp; good practice)</h4>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Prevention = keep the cell from forming</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Keep moisture out</strong> &mdash; the #1 control. Cooling-air systems that remove moisture, sealants, gaskets, drain holes kept clear, covers on parked aircraft, good housekeeping. (Study Guide, Std 28.)</li>\n<li><strong>Protective finishes</strong> &mdash; an <strong>intact paint/primer film is the most effective barrier</strong> (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;8-23). Other finishes: <strong>anodizing</strong> (thickens aluminum's oxide film), <strong>alodine / chemical conversion coating</strong> (chromate film), <strong>cladding (&ldquo;Alclad&rdquo;)</strong> &mdash; pure-aluminum layer over the alloy, and <strong>plating</strong> with tin, nickel, or cadmium. (AC 43.13-1B Ch.6.)</li>\n<li><strong>Conductor plating to resist oxidation</strong> &mdash; the Study Guide notes avionics conductors are plated with <strong>tin, silver, or nickel</strong> to prevent corrosion of the copper.</li>\n<li><strong>Insulate dissimilar metals</strong> &mdash; the Study Guide lists <em>&ldquo;insulation to prevent conductive paths&rdquo;</em> and <em>&ldquo;sealants&rdquo;</em>: separate the two metals (washers, finishes, sealant) so no electrolyte can bridge them. This is THE fix for galvanic corrosion at a joint.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<p><strong>Tie it back to avionics:</strong> a high-resistance, corroded <strong>ground/bond</strong> point ruins shielding and creates noise; a corroded <strong>connector pin</strong> gives you the classic &ldquo;works when I wiggle it&rdquo; intermittent. So corrosion control isn't just structures &mdash; for an avionics tech it's <strong>signal integrity and reliability.</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Which document requires <strong>mandatory</strong> compliance to fix an unsafe condition &mdash; an AD or a Service Bulletin? <span class=\"a\">Answer: an Airworthiness Directive (AD). A Service Bulletin is only a recommendation unless an AD references it.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">A bolt's torque is 240&nbsp;inch-pounds. What is that in <strong>foot-pounds</strong>? <span class=\"a\">Answer: 20 ft-lb &mdash; divide inch-pounds by 12 (240 &divide; 12 = 20).</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">What type of corrosion occurs when <strong>two different metals touch in the presence of an electrolyte</strong>? <span class=\"a\">Answer: galvanic (dissimilar-metal) corrosion &mdash; the more active metal becomes the anode and corrodes.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">You find a <strong>white, powdery</strong> deposit on an aluminum bracket. What is it, and what color would <strong>steel</strong> corrosion be instead? <span class=\"a\">Answer: that white/gray powder is aluminum corrosion (often pitting); steel corrosion is reddish-brown rust.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Why does corrosion on a connector pin or ground point cause <strong>intermittent</strong> faults? <span class=\"a\">Answer: corrosion adds resistance at the contact; with vibration and temperature changes that resistance varies, so the circuit works and fails on and off.</span></div>", "quiz": [{"q": "What is the number-one rule when performing any maintenance task?", "options": ["Always work to the approved data / manufacturer's instructions", "Work from memory once you've done it before", "Use whatever tool is closest", "Ask another tech instead of reading the manual"], "correct": 0, "short": "Work to the data", "expl": "You always consult the manuals and approved data; never guess from memory.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 25", "topic": "pubs-rule"}, {"q": "Which document is the FAA legal order that REQUIRES you to fix an unsafe condition?", "options": ["Airworthiness Directive (AD)", "Service Bulletin", "Service Letter", "Illustrated Parts Catalog"], "correct": 0, "short": "AD", "expl": "An AD is mandatory FAA action with a compliance timeframe to correct an unsafe condition.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 25; 14 CFR Part 39", "topic": "ad-sb"}, {"q": "Compliance with a manufacturer's Service Bulletin (SB) is:", "options": ["Not required unless the SB is referenced by an AD", "Mandatory only on jets", "Always mandatory under the FARs", "Never required under any condition"], "correct": 0, "short": "SB recommended unless AD-backed", "expl": "An SB is a recommendation; it is not FAR-required unless an AD makes it mandatory.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 25", "topic": "ad-sb"}, {"q": "Which publication shows how components are connected electrically using standardized symbols, used to troubleshoot and repair circuits?", "options": ["Flight manual", "Weight and balance", "Minimum Equipment List", "Wiring diagram"], "correct": 3, "short": "Wiring diagram", "expl": "Wiring diagrams use standardized symbols to show electrical connections for troubleshooting/repair.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 25", "topic": "diagrams"}, {"q": "A SCHEMATIC diagram is best described as one that:", "options": ["Shows the exact physical location of every part", "Lists all the aircraft's part numbers", "Uses symbols (not pictures) and does not show physical location; used mainly for troubleshooting", "Is the FAA's legal repair order"], "correct": 2, "short": "Symbols, no location", "expl": "A schematic uses symbols rather than pictures and does not show physical locations; it's for troubleshooting.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 25", "topic": "diagrams"}, {"q": "A diagram that shows functional units as BLOCKS with arrows for the flow between them is a:", "options": ["Wiring diagram", "Schematic diagram", "Block diagram", "Installation diagram"], "correct": 2, "short": "Block diagram", "expl": "A block diagram shows functional blocks and signal/energy flow; high-level, used for troubleshooting or teaching.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 25", "topic": "diagrams"}, {"q": "Which publication uses callouts to identify and locate each component so you can find part numbers and order parts?", "options": ["Airworthiness Directive", "Schematic", "Illustrated Parts Catalog (IPC) / installation diagram", "Service Letter"], "correct": 2, "short": "IPC", "expl": "The IPC/installation diagram pictures the system with callouts identifying and locating components.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 25", "topic": "diagrams"}, {"q": "Per the Study Guide, what should you consult if NO maintenance manual exists for maintaining an aircraft?", "options": ["The MEL", "AC 43.13-1B/2B", "The weight and balance", "A Service Letter"], "correct": 1, "short": "AC 43.13-1B/2B", "expl": "The Study Guide says to consult AC 43.13-1B/2B when no maintenance manual exists.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 25", "topic": "pubs-which"}, {"q": "An FAA-approved list of equipment that may be inoperative while the aircraft still legally flies is the:", "options": ["Minimum Equipment List (MEL)", "STC", "IPC", "AD"], "correct": 0, "short": "MEL", "expl": "The MEL lists installed equipment that may be inoperative while operation continues (14 CFR 91.213).", "cite": "Study Guide Std 25; 14 CFR 91.213", "topic": "pubs-which"}, {"q": "A Supplemental Type Certificate (STC) is an FAA document that approves:", "options": ["A pilot's medical", "A tool calibration", "An inoperative instrument", "A design alteration to an aircraft (e.g., a new avionics installation)"], "correct": 3, "short": "STC = design alteration", "expl": "An STC approves an aircraft type-design alteration, such as installing new equipment.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 25", "topic": "pubs-which"}, {"q": "Aircraft maintenance manuals are organized by a standardized numbering scheme so each system is filed the same way. That scheme is the:", "options": ["SAE grade system", "NEC code", "ATA 100 chapter system", "ASTM F3245 list"], "correct": 2, "short": "ATA chapter system", "expl": "The ATA 100 chapter system standardizes how systems are numbered across manufacturers.", "cite": "FAA tech-pub practice; Study Guide Std 25", "topic": "ata"}, {"q": "To quickly find a procedure in a manual, the Study Guide recommends you:", "options": ["Read every page front to back", "Call the manufacturer first", "Check the Table of Contents and index, and use the legend/key and callouts", "Skip to the last chapter"], "correct": 2, "short": "TOC, index, legend, callouts", "expl": "The Guide lists checking the TOC/index, reading the legend/key for symbols, and following callouts.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 25", "topic": "find-proc"}, {"q": "The NCATT proficiency rules for common tools include all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["Choose the tool best suited for the job", "Recognize some tools have more than one use", "Use any tool that fits, even if it's the wrong one", "Handle and care for tools safely"], "correct": 2, "short": "Right tool, not any tool", "expl": "You must choose the tool best suited for the job, not just any tool that fits.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 26", "topic": "tool-rules"}, {"q": "Why is applying the correct TORQUE to a fastener important?", "options": ["It makes the bolt lighter", "Too little lets it vibrate loose; too much strips/cracks the part", "It changes the wire gauge", "Torque only matters on engines"], "correct": 1, "short": "Loose vs. stripped", "expl": "Under-torque vibrates loose (intermittents); over-torque strips threads or cracks the part.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.7-50", "topic": "torque"}, {"q": "A torque value is listed as 360 inch-pounds. In foot-pounds that is:", "options": ["36 ft-lb", "30 ft-lb", "12 ft-lb", "4,320 ft-lb"], "correct": 1, "short": "30 ft-lb", "expl": "Divide inch-pounds by 12: 360 / 12 = 30 ft-lb.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.7-50", "topic": "torque-math"}, {"q": "To convert inch-pounds to foot-pounds you:", "options": ["Multiply by 12", "Add 12", "Multiply by 60", "Divide by 12"], "correct": 3, "short": "Divide by 12", "expl": "There are 12 inches in a foot, so ft-lb = in-lb / 12.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.7-50", "topic": "torque-math"}, {"q": "Which is NOT one of the three common torque-wrench types in the handbook?", "options": ["Flexible-beam", "Rigid-frame (dial)", "Ratchet (click) type", "Spark-plug type"], "correct": 3, "short": "3 types: beam, dial, click", "expl": "The handbook shows flexible-beam, rigid-frame (dial), and ratchet (click) torque wrenches.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.7-51", "topic": "torque-tools"}, {"q": "Per the standard torque table rules, you should generally:", "options": ["Lubricate every bolt before torquing", "Always exceed the maximum value for safety", "Tighten by rotating the nut (not the bolt head) when possible", "Use any extension without changing the reading"], "correct": 2, "short": "Rotate the nut", "expl": "Tighten by rotating the nut when possible; don't lubricate unless told; never exceed max.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.7-50", "topic": "torque-rules"}, {"q": "Using a drive-end extension on a torque wrench:", "options": ["Has no effect on the reading", "Changes the dial reading needed, so it must be recomputed with the proper formula", "Doubles the torque automatically", "Is never allowed"], "correct": 1, "short": "Recompute the reading", "expl": "An extension changes the effective lever length, so the wrench reading must be recomputed.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.7-50", "topic": "torque-rules"}, {"q": "Which measuring tool gives the most precise reading of a small thickness or diameter (about 0.001 in)?", "options": ["A steel rule", "A tape measure", "A micrometer caliper", "A protractor"], "correct": 2, "short": "Micrometer", "expl": "A micrometer reads to about 0.001 in (vernier mic to 0.0001 in), finer than a rule.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 26 (measuring tools)", "topic": "measuring"}, {"q": "What is the purpose of CALIBRATION of a torque wrench or multimeter?", "options": ["To make it lighter", "To check it against a known standard so its readings are accurate", "To change its units", "To remove corrosion"], "correct": 1, "short": "Keep readings accurate", "expl": "Calibration verifies a tool against a known standard; out-of-cal tools are removed from service.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 26/32 (precision tools)", "topic": "calibration"}, {"q": "A crimping tool is used to:", "options": ["Measure resistance", "Read voltage", "Remove corrosion", "Form a gas-tight mechanical/electrical bond between a contact and a wire"], "correct": 3, "short": "Crimp contact to wire", "expl": "A crimper forms a solid gas-tight connection between a terminal/contact and the wire; the right die matters.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 26", "topic": "tools-use"}, {"q": "When stripping a wire, why must you avoid nicking the conductor strands?", "options": ["It looks bad", "It changes the color code", "It wastes wire", "A nicked strand is a weak, high-resistance, corrosion-prone spot that can fail"], "correct": 3, "short": "Nicks weaken/raise resistance", "expl": "A nick reduces cross-section, raises resistance, and invites corrosion and breakage.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 26; FAA wiring practice", "topic": "tools-use"}, {"q": "The Study Guide defines corrosion as the:", "options": ["Mechanical wear of a tool", "Heating of a wire under load", "Chemical or electrochemical deterioration of a material (usually metal) due to its environment", "Buildup of static charge"], "correct": 2, "short": "Chemical/electrochemical deterioration", "expl": "Corrosion is chemical or electrochemical deterioration of metal reacting with its environment; may be visible or not.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 28; FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-1", "topic": "corr-def"}, {"q": "Why is corrosion a special concern for an AVIONICS technician?", "options": ["It only affects the airframe, not avionics", "It corrodes connector pins, terminals, and grounds, causing intermittent faults and lost reliability", "It improves conductivity", "It only matters on the engine"], "correct": 1, "short": "Intermittents at contacts", "expl": "Corrosion adds resistance at pins/terminals/grounds, causing intermittent faults; it's a major reliability killer.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 28", "topic": "corr-avionics"}, {"q": "Galvanic corrosion occurs when:", "options": ["A single metal sits in dry air", "Two different metals are in contact in the presence of an electrolyte", "A wire carries too much current", "Paint is applied too thick"], "correct": 1, "short": "Dissimilar metals + electrolyte", "expl": "Galvanic (dissimilar-metal) corrosion needs two different metals touching with an electrolyte present.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 28; FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-4", "topic": "galvanic"}, {"q": "In a galvanic couple, which metal corrodes?", "options": ["The more noble (less active) metal", "Neither corrodes", "Both corrode equally", "The more active (less noble) metal becomes the anode and corrodes"], "correct": 3, "short": "Active metal corrodes", "expl": "The more active/less noble metal becomes the anode and corrodes; the noble metal is the cathode.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-6 (galvanic series)", "topic": "galvanic"}, {"q": "Electrochemical corrosion requires which combination to occur?", "options": ["Only dry metal", "High voltage alone", "Only sunlight", "An anode, a cathode, and a conductive liquid (electrolyte)"], "correct": 3, "short": "Anode + cathode + electrolyte", "expl": "You need a difference in potential (anode/cathode) plus an electrolyte bridging them.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-5", "topic": "corr-cell"}, {"q": "Removing which single factor will stop electrochemical corrosion and is the basis of corrosion control?", "options": ["The electrolyte (moisture)", "The anode", "The cathode", "The paint"], "correct": 0, "short": "Remove the moisture", "expl": "Removing the conductive medium (moisture) breaks the cell so corrosion cannot occur.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-5", "topic": "corr-cell"}, {"q": "Pitting corrosion is best recognized as:", "options": ["Concentrated localized pits, usually with white or gray powder", "A green powder over the whole part", "A reddish-brown stain only", "A blue liquid"], "correct": 0, "short": "Pits + white/gray powder", "expl": "Pitting is concentrated cell corrosion localized in pits, usually with white or gray powder.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 28; FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-6", "topic": "types"}, {"q": "Corrosion that forms WITHIN the metal along its grain boundaries is called:", "options": ["Surface corrosion", "Fretting corrosion", "Galvanic corrosion", "Intergranular corrosion"], "correct": 3, "short": "Intergranular", "expl": "Intergranular corrosion attacks along the metal's grain boundaries, often hidden inside the metal.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 28", "topic": "types"}, {"q": "Exfoliation corrosion is:", "options": ["A mild surface stain", "Corrosion only on copper", "An extreme form of intergranular corrosion that lifts the metal into layers, destroying strength", "The same as rust on steel"], "correct": 2, "short": "Layered, extreme intergranular", "expl": "Exfoliation is severe intergranular corrosion that separates/lifts metal layers and ruins strength.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 28; FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-19", "topic": "types"}, {"q": "You find a white, powdery deposit on an aluminum part. By contrast, corrosion on a STEEL part appears as:", "options": ["Reddish-brown rust", "Green powder", "Blue-green deposit", "Black film only"], "correct": 0, "short": "Steel = reddish-brown rust", "expl": "Aluminum/magnesium corrosion is white/gray powder; steel/iron corrosion is reddish-brown rust.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-3 (Fig 8-2)", "topic": "recognize"}, {"q": "Corrosion on copper, brass, or bronze typically appears as:", "options": ["A green or blue-green powdery deposit", "Reddish-brown rust", "White snow-like mounds", "No deposit at all"], "correct": 0, "short": "Green/blue-green", "expl": "Copper-base metals form a green or blue-green powdery corrosion product.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-3 (Fig 8-2)", "topic": "recognize"}, {"q": "Per the handbook, every corrosion inspection begins with:", "options": ["A thorough cleaning of the area to be inspected", "Painting the area", "Replacing the part", "Applying sealant"], "correct": 0, "short": "Clean first", "expl": "All corrosion inspections start with a thorough cleaning of the area, then a visual inspection.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-11", "topic": "inspect"}, {"q": "Which is the MOST effective barrier for preventing corrosion on a metal surface?", "options": ["Leaving the metal bare", "A good, intact paint/primer finish", "Storing in salt air", "Higher operating voltage"], "correct": 1, "short": "Intact paint finish", "expl": "A good intact paint finish is the most effective barrier between metal and corrosive media.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-23", "topic": "prevent"}, {"q": "The BEST way to prevent galvanic corrosion at a joint of two dissimilar metals is to:", "options": ["Add more electrolyte", "Insulate/separate the two metals (finishes, sealant) so no electrolyte can bridge them", "Bolt them tighter", "Leave the joint unpainted"], "correct": 1, "short": "Insulate the metals", "expl": "Breaking the cell by insulating/separating the metals (Study Guide: insulation and sealants) prevents galvanic corrosion.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 28", "topic": "prevent"}, {"q": "Avionics copper conductors are plated with tin, silver, or nickel mainly to:", "options": ["Make them heavier", "Prevent corrosion (oxidation) of the copper", "Increase resistance", "Change the color code"], "correct": 1, "short": "Plating resists oxidation", "expl": "Conductor plating (tin, silver, nickel) protects copper from corrosion/oxidation.", "cite": "Study Guide (conductor plating)", "topic": "prevent"}, {"q": "Why should you NEVER use steel wool or a steel brush to clean corrosion off an aluminum part?", "options": ["Embedded steel particles start NEW galvanic corrosion on the aluminum", "It's too slow", "It's too expensive", "It removes the part number"], "correct": 0, "short": "Steel particles start new corrosion", "expl": "Steel particles left on aluminum form dissimilar-metal couples and start fresh galvanic corrosion.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-19 to 8-20 (anodized/titanium cautions)", "topic": "treat"}, {"q": "The general corrosion TREATMENT sequence is:", "options": ["Clean/strip, remove corrosion, neutralize residue, restore the protective film, recoat", "Paint, then ignore it", "Only wipe it with a dry rag", "Replace the whole aircraft"], "correct": 0, "short": "Clean, remove, neutralize, recoat", "expl": "Clean/strip, remove corrosion, neutralize residue in pits, restore surface film, apply protective coating.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-14", "topic": "treat"}, {"q": "If corrosion damage EXCEEDS the manufacturer's allowable limits, you must:", "options": ["Paint over it and continue", "Ignore it until the next check", "Reduce the inspection interval only", "Replace the part (or repair per the structural repair manual)"], "correct": 3, "short": "Replace if over limits", "expl": "When corrosion exceeds damage limits, the part must be replaced or repaired per the manual.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.8-14, 8-21", "topic": "treat"}], "drill": [{"label": "Work to the data", "text": "Always use the manufacturer's instructions / approved data. Never guess from memory."}, {"label": "AD vs SB", "text": "AD = MANDATORY FAA order (unsafe condition, has a deadline). SB = manufacturer recommendation, not required unless an AD cites it."}, {"label": "Wiring vs schematic vs block", "text": "Wiring diagram = standardized symbols, how parts connect. Schematic = symbols, no physical location. Block = functional blocks with flow arrows."}, {"label": "IPC", "text": "Illustrated Parts Catalog uses callouts to identify/locate components and find part numbers."}, {"label": "No manual? Use AC 43.13", "text": "Consult AC 43.13-1B/2B when no maintenance manual exists for the aircraft."}, {"label": "ATA chapter system", "text": "Standard numbering so each system is filed the same across manufacturers (e.g., 24 = Electrical Power, 34 = Navigation)."}, {"label": "Torque conversion", "text": "Foot-pounds = inch-pounds / 12 (12 inches per foot). 240 in-lb = 20 ft-lb."}, {"label": "Why torque matters", "text": "Too little = vibrates loose (intermittents). Too much = strips threads / cracks the part."}, {"label": "Three torque wrenches", "text": "Flexible-beam, rigid-frame (dial), and ratchet (click). An extension changes the reading - recompute it."}, {"label": "Calibration", "text": "Check a tool against a known standard so readings are accurate; out-of-cal tools are removed from service."}, {"label": "Corrosion definition", "text": "Chemical or electrochemical deterioration of metal reacting with its environment; may be visible or not."}, {"label": "Galvanic corrosion", "text": "Two DIFFERENT metals + an electrolyte. The more active (less noble) metal becomes the anode and corrodes. The big avionics one at connectors."}, {"label": "Recognize by color", "text": "Aluminum/magnesium = white/gray powder; steel = reddish-brown rust; copper/brass = green or blue-green powder."}]}, {"n": 11, "title": "Wiring & Test Equipment", "standards": "30, 31, 32", "lesson": "<h3>Why this matters on a real aircraft</h3>\n<p>Every black box, light, radio, and sensor on an aircraft is only as good as the <strong>wire</strong> that feeds it and the <strong>test gear</strong> you use to check it. A nicked strand, a loose crimp, a bad ground, or the wrong meter on the wrong setting can ground an airplane &mdash; or worse, start a fire. This module is the heart of the avionics technician's day-to-day work. It covers three Standards at once: <strong>30 (Aircraft Wiring)</strong>, <strong>31 (Perform Wire Maintenance)</strong>, and <strong>32 (Use Test Equipment / Special Tools)</strong>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">The three jobs in one line</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Std 30 &mdash; Know the wire:</strong> what types exist, how it's sized (AWG), how to pick it, route it, ground it, bond it, and shield it.</li>\n<li><strong>Std 31 &mdash; Fix the wire:</strong> strip without nicking, crimp gas-tight, solder clean, splice, terminate, and inspect.</li>\n<li><strong>Std 32 &mdash; Measure it:</strong> use the multimeter, oscilloscope, megohmmeter, and bonding tester &mdash; connected the right way, on the right setting, safely.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Part 1 &mdash; AIRCRAFT WIRING (Standard 30)</h3>\n\n<h4>Wire types you must recognize</h4>\n<p>The Study Guide lists four families of aircraft wire. Know what each looks like and what it's for.</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Wire type</th><th>What it is</th><th>Used for</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Single conductor</strong></td><td>One insulated wire in a jacket</td><td>Most aircraft systems. The <strong>aircraft structure</strong> provides the return path back to the source (a \"single-wire\" system).</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Multiconductor</strong></td><td>Two or more insulated wires in the <em>same</em> jacket</td><td>Electrical power distribution; provides dielectric, impact, and mechanical strength.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Twisted pair</strong></td><td>Two (or more) separately insulated wires twisted together</td><td>Onboard communications, lighting circuits (e.g., the standby magnetic compass light), Ethernet/LANs.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Coaxial (coax)</strong></td><td>One center conductor surrounded by a metallic braided shield</td><td>Data transmission and <strong>RF signal distribution</strong> (antennas, radios), and Ethernet.</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Plain-English: what is \"single-wire\"?</span>\n<p>In your car and in most aircraft, you don't run two wires to every light. You run <strong>one</strong> wire out, and the metal body/airframe carries the current back. That metal-return idea is what \"single conductor\" means &mdash; <em>the structure is the second wire</em>. This is why <strong>good grounding and bonding (Part 1 below) is so critical</strong>: if the airframe return path is bad, nothing works right.</p></div>\n\n<h4>Insulation &amp; conductors</h4>\n<p>The metal that carries current is the <strong>conductor</strong>; the plastic/rubber around it is the <strong>insulation</strong>. Common insulating materials: plastic, rubber, glass, ceramics, air (vacuum), or oil. Conductors are usually <strong>copper or aluminum</strong> (silver is used rarely &mdash; great conductor but expensive).</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th></th><th>Copper</th><th>Aluminum</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Conductivity</td><td><strong>Higher</strong> (better conductor)</td><td>Only ~60% of copper's conductivity</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Weight</td><td>Heavier</td><td><strong>Lighter</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Cost</td><td>More expensive</td><td>Cheaper</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Workability</td><td>More ductile, higher tensile strength, easier to solder</td><td>Harder to solder; needs special care at terminals</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>To stop corrosion (oxidation), copper conductors are often <strong>plated</strong> with <strong>tin, silver, or nickel</strong>. Match the plating to the temperature: tin for normal temps, silver/nickel for hotter areas.</p>\n\n<h4>WIRE GAUGE &mdash; the AWG rule (memorize this cold)</h4>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">THE #1 wiring fact on the exam</span>\n<p><strong>American Wire Gauge (AWG)</strong> is the wire-sizing standard. The rule that trips people up:</p>\n<p><strong>As the gauge NUMBER gets LARGER, the wire DIAMETER gets SMALLER.</strong></p>\n<p>So a #4 wire is <em>fat</em> (carries lots of current), and a #22 wire is <em>thin</em> (carries little). Backwards from what people expect. The test loves to bait you with the reverse &mdash; don't take it.</p></div>\n\n<h4>Selecting the right wire (three things at once)</h4>\n<p>AC 43.13-1B &para;11-66 says wires must be sized so they: have <strong>mechanical strength</strong> for service; do <strong>not exceed allowable voltage drop</strong>; are <strong>protected by the circuit protection</strong> (breaker/fuse); and <strong>meet current-carrying requirements</strong>. The Study Guide boils the sizing factors down to three:</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Factor</th><th>What it means</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Current-carrying ability</strong></td><td>The wire must carry the load amps without overheating. Bigger current &rarr; bigger wire (smaller AWG number).</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Permissible voltage drop</strong></td><td>Long thin wires \"eat\" voltage (IR drop). Main power-wire drop should not exceed <strong>2%</strong> of the regulated voltage. Longer runs &rarr; bigger wire.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Allowable power loss</strong> + mechanical strength</td><td>Don't pick wire so thin it loses power as heat or breaks from vibration/flexing.</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Mechanical rule:</strong> &para;11-66 says wire with <strong>fewer than 19 strands must not be used</strong>, and wire smaller than #20 needs extra clamps, grouping, and support at terminations. (AC 43.13-1B &para;11-66, p.&nbsp;11-31.)</p>\n<p>The Study Guide's <strong>criteria for selecting electrical wire</strong> (the environment list): abrasion resistance, arc resistance (non-carbon-tracking), corrosion resistance, cut-through strength, flame resistance, fluid resistance, heat-distortion resistance, notch-propagation resistance, and smoke-emission resistance.</p>\n\n<h4>Markings / identification</h4>\n<p>Aircraft wire is <strong>marked (stenciled)</strong> along its length with a wire-identification code so a technician can trace any wire to its circuit on the wiring diagram. Always replace wire with <strong>equivalent</strong> wire and keep the identification readable (AC 43.13-1B &para;11-97, &para;11-108).</p>\n\n<h4>Routing, clamping &amp; separation</h4>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Keep signal away from power</span>\n<p>The golden routing rule: <strong>route sensitive/signal wiring away from power wiring.</strong> AC 43.13-1B &para;11-106 (EMI) says interference <em>increases with the length of parallel runs and decreases with greater separation.</em> So you keep noisy power wires and quiet signal wires apart, and you cross them at right angles when you must cross.</p>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>System separation (&para;11-105):</strong> wires of <em>redundant</em> systems go in <strong>separate bundles and separate connectors</strong> so one fault can't kill both. Power feeders from different sources are also kept separate. Ground wires from separate power sources attach to the airframe at <strong>separate points</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Clamping (&para;11-146):</strong> bundles are supported by <strong>clamps</strong> at regular intervals so they don't sag, chafe, or vibrate against structure.</li>\n<li><strong>Slack &amp; bend radius (&para;11-117, 11-118):</strong> leave a little slack between supports; don't bend wire bundles tighter than the minimum radius.</li>\n<li><strong>Heat &amp; fluids (&para;11-125, 11-127):</strong> route wire away from high-temperature parts and away from flammable-fluid/gas lines (an arcing fault near fuel is a fire).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Bonding &amp; grounding (why this matters)</h4>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Grounding vs. Bonding &mdash; know the difference</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>GROUNDING</strong> = connecting a conductive object to the airframe (or a return path) <em>to complete a normal or fault circuit safely</em>. Grounding is about <strong>carrying current</strong> back to the source. (AC 43.13-1B &para;11-186.)</li>\n<li><strong>BONDING</strong> = electrically connecting metal parts together so they're all at the <em>same electrical potential</em> with a <strong>low-impedance path</strong>. Bonding is about <strong>equalizing</strong> &mdash; it usually doesn't carry working current. (AC 43.13-1B &para;11-187.)</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<p><strong>Why bonding matters &mdash; the four reasons (&para;11-185).</strong> Inadequate bonding or grounding causes: <strong>EMI</strong>, <strong>electrostatic-discharge damage</strong> to sensitive electronics, <strong>personnel shock hazard</strong>, and <strong>damage from lightning strike</strong>. So bonding gives a lightning strike and static charge a safe path to dissipate, kills EMI by providing RF return paths, and protects people from shock.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Metallic surface bonding (&para;11-187b):</strong> ALL conducting objects on the outside of the airframe must be electrically connected to it (joints, conductive hinges, or <strong>bond straps</strong>) so they can conduct static charges and <strong>lightning strikes</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Static bonds (&para;11-187c):</strong> isolated conductive parts over ~3&nbsp;in&sup2; that pick up static should bond to structure; <strong>under 1 ohm</strong> clean-and-dry generally dissipates the charge.</li>\n<li><strong>Bonding jumpers (&para;11-189):</strong> a <strong>bonding jumper</strong> is a short strap that bonds two parts together (e.g., across a vibration isolator or a movable panel). Make it <strong>as short as practicable</strong>; each connection's resistance must <strong>not exceed .003 ohm</strong>. Remove paint/anodize from the contact area, and use the right jumper metal (aluminum for most, copper for steel/brass/bronze) to avoid dissimilar-metal corrosion.</li>\n<li><strong>Equipment bond (&para;11-188f):</strong> exposed frames of electrical/electronic equipment need a low-resistance bond of <strong>less than 2.5 milliohms</strong> to structure.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Shielding (EMI control)</h4>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Shielded cable &mdash; the metal raincoat</span>\n<p>A <strong>shield</strong> is a metallic braid (or foil) wrapped around the signal conductor. AC 43.13-1B &para;11-89: <em>\"Shielding is the process of applying a metallic covering to wiring and equipment to eliminate interference caused by stray electromagnetic energy.\"</em> <strong>EMI</strong> happens when electromagnetic fields (radio waves) induce unwanted high-frequency voltages in a wire &mdash; which can cause system inaccuracy or failure.</p>\n<p><strong>The key maintenance fact: GROUND THE SHIELD.</strong> Shielded wire is <em>typically grounded at both ends</em> (or at connectors), depending on the application. Use &ge;85% shield coverage for sensitive circuits. The shield only works if it's grounded &mdash; an ungrounded shield does nothing. (AC 43.13-1B &para;11-89, p.&nbsp;11-47; &para;11-106.)</p></div>\n\n<h4>Connectors</h4>\n<p><strong>Connectors</strong> let harnesses plug into equipment and let sections come apart for maintenance. Inspect for corrosion, bent/pushed-back pins, security, and moisture. A bad connector pin (over-crimped) reads as an <strong>open</strong> on an ohmmeter (AC 43.13-1B &para;11-100).</p>\n\n<h3>Part 2 &mdash; WIRE MAINTENANCE (Standard 31)</h3>\n\n<h4>Stripping insulation WITHOUT nicking</h4>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">The #1 stripping rule</span>\n<p>Stripping = removing insulation to expose the conductor. The cardinal sin is <strong>nicking, cutting, or breaking the copper strands</strong> &mdash; a nicked strand is a weak point that breaks under vibration. AC 43.13-1B &para;11-157:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Keep cutting tools <strong>sharp</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Adjust the stripping tool to the wire size</strong> so it cuts only the insulation, not the strands.</li>\n<li>Remove <strong>no more insulation than necessary</strong>.</li>\n<li>Damage must stay within Table&nbsp;11-15 limits (e.g., for 24&ndash;14 AWG copper: <strong>max 2 nicked, none broken</strong>).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>(AC 43.13-1B &para;11-157, p.&nbsp;11-70.)</p></div>\n\n<h4>Crimping &mdash; the gas-tight connection</h4>\n<p>A <strong>crimp</strong> squeezes a terminal or splice barrel down onto the bare conductor so tightly the metals cold-weld into a <strong>gas-tight</strong> joint &mdash; no air can get in to corrode it. This is the standard, preferred aircraft termination.</p>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Crimp rules (AC 43.13-1B &para;11-178)</span>\n<ul>\n<li>Use a <strong>high-quality, ratchet-type crimping tool</strong> that's <strong>calibrated</strong> and sized/adjusted to the wire (it has a positioner per wire size).</li>\n<li>The <strong>crimp depth must be right for the wire size.</strong> Too deep &rarr; it cuts/breaks strands. Not deep enough &rarr; it's loose, won't hold, and corrodes (high resistance).</li>\n<li>The <strong>full-cycle ratchet</strong> must be tamper-proof so the tool can't release mid-crimp.</li>\n<li>Use a <strong>Go/No-Go gauge</strong> to verify crimp dimensions. Tool calibration is done <em>only</em> by the manufacturer or an approved lab.</li>\n<li><strong>Pre-insulated crimp ring-tongue terminals are preferred</strong> (&para;11-174). Crimp copper lugs to copper wire, aluminum lugs to aluminum wire only.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>(AC 43.13-1B &para;11-178, p.&nbsp;11-78 to 11-79.)</p></div>\n\n<h4>Soldering &mdash; good joint vs. cold joint</h4>\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Good solder joint vs. cold joint</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Good joint:</strong> the parts are hot enough that the solder <em>flows and wets</em> the metal &mdash; smooth, shiny, concave fillet. Mechanically and electrically sound.</li>\n<li><strong>Cold joint:</strong> the metal wasn't hot enough, so the solder just \"blobbed\" on without bonding &mdash; dull, grainy, lumpy. It looks connected but cracks open later, leaving an intermittent <strong>open</strong>. FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-82 specifically warns: <em>a \"cold\" solder joint cracks leaving a wire disconnected</em> &mdash; a classic hard-to-find fault.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<p><strong>Crimp vs. solder &mdash; when to use which?</strong> In modern aircraft work, <strong>crimping is generally preferred</strong> over soldering for terminations: a proper crimp is gas-tight, repeatable with a calibrated tool, and not prone to the cold-joint or wicking problems of solder. Soldering is used where specified (some connector contacts, shield terminations, board-level repair). A crimp's quality is verified with a Go/No-Go gauge; a solder joint's quality is judged visually (shiny vs. dull). When in doubt, follow the manufacturer's data.</p>\n\n<h4>Splices, terminal lugs &amp; terminals</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Splicing (&para;11-167):</strong> permitted if it doesn't hurt reliability. Keep splices to a <strong>minimum</strong>; <strong>no more than one splice per wire segment</strong> between connectors; <strong>stagger</strong> splices in a bundle so it doesn't bulge; don't splice within 12&nbsp;inches of a termination (with listed exceptions); avoid splices in high-vibration areas. (p.&nbsp;11-75.)</li>\n<li><strong>Terminal lugs (&para;11-174):</strong> the wire-to-terminal joint must be at least as strong as the wire itself, with negligible added resistance. <strong>No more than four lugs</strong> (or three lugs + a bus bar) on one stud. On a stud, the <strong>largest-diameter lug goes on the bottom, smallest on top</strong>. Solderless crimp copper lugs (MIL-T-7928) are the standard.</li>\n<li><strong>Terminal blocks (&para;11-177):</strong> terminals must be firmly held with two nuts or locking provisions; never let insulation be what holds the connection together; provide barriers so adjacent studs can't touch.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Inspection &amp; continuity</h4>\n<p>The Study Guide (Std 31) says a <strong>continuity check</strong> traces circuit paths to confirm current can flow end-to-end. It identifies <strong>good vs. bad fuses</strong>, <strong>open or shorted conductors</strong>, verifies <strong>switch operation</strong>, and finds good vs. faulty lamps. You do it with an <strong>ohmmeter</strong> (power OFF): a good path reads ~0 ohms (short/continuity); an open reads infinity. <em>Note from the Study Guide: ensure your test equipment and tools are <strong>calibrated</strong> before performing continuity checks.</em></p>\n\n<h3>Part 3 &mdash; TEST EQUIPMENT / SPECIAL TOOLS (Standard 32)</h3>\n\n<h4>The DMM / Multimeter &mdash; your everyday meter</h4>\n<p>The Study Guide calls the <strong>multimeter</strong> the <em>\"most versatile electrical measuring instrument used by aircraft technicians.\"</em> One instrument that can be set as a <strong>voltmeter, ammeter, or ohmmeter</strong> &mdash; it measures <strong>voltage, current, and resistance</strong>. Comes in <strong>analog</strong> (needle) and <strong>digital (DMM)</strong> form. DMMs are preferred today: easier to read, more accurate, and higher input resistance (less loading on the circuit). The Study Guide notes a DMM's <strong>allowable error</strong> tells you how close the displayed value is to the true value.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">THE meter-connection rules (exam gold &mdash; memorize)</span>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Meter</th><th>Measures</th><th>How to connect</th><th>Power</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Voltmeter</strong></td><td>Voltage (across)</td><td><strong>PARALLEL</strong> with the component</td><td>Power <strong>ON</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Ammeter</strong></td><td>Current (through)</td><td><strong>SERIES</strong> &mdash; break the circuit and insert it</td><td>Power <strong>ON</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Ohmmeter</strong></td><td>Resistance / continuity</td><td><strong>Across</strong> the isolated component</td><td>Power <strong>OFF</strong> (it has its own battery)</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Voltmeter &rarr; PARALLEL. Ammeter &rarr; SERIES. Ohmmeter &rarr; POWER OFF.</strong> Say it like a chant. (FAA-H-8083-30B pp.&nbsp;12-69 to 12-81.)</p></div>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Why those rules &mdash; and the deadly mistake</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Voltmeter is high-resistance</strong> so it can sit <em>across</em> a component without stealing much current. Use a high-resistance voltmeter to avoid \"shunting\" (loading) the circuit (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-71).</li>\n<li><strong>Ammeter is very low-resistance</strong> so it can sit <em>in</em> the current path. <strong>NEVER connect an ammeter across a voltage source</strong> &mdash; its near-zero resistance lets huge current flow and destroys the meter (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-69, Precaution #2).</li>\n<li><strong>Ohmmeter supplies its own power</strong>, so the circuit must be <strong>de-energized</strong> and the component <strong>isolated</strong> (disconnected) &mdash; leaving it in-circuit gives a parallel-path false reading and can damage the meter (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-81).</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<p><strong>Range &amp; reading tips:</strong> if unsure of the value, start on the <strong>highest range</strong> and work down so you don't \"peg\" the meter; the <strong>most accurate analog readings are near mid-scale (about half-scale deflection)</strong>. <strong>Zero</strong> the ohmmeter (short the leads, adjust to 0) before each use. Observe correct <strong>polarity</strong> &mdash; red lead to (+), black to (&minus;).</p>\n\n<h4>The Oscilloscope &mdash; seeing the waveform</h4>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Scope = a meter that draws the signal over TIME</span>\n<p>A DMM gives you one number. An <strong>oscilloscope</strong> draws the actual <strong>waveform &mdash; voltage on the vertical axis, time on the horizontal axis</strong> &mdash; so you can SEE the shape of a signal. The Study Guide: oscilloscopes <em>\"display the waveforms of electrical signals\"</em> and measure <strong>voltage (AC peak-to-peak) and time to determine frequency</strong>, and show <strong>phase relationships</strong> to find malfunctions.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Volts/Division</strong> sets how many volts each vertical box equals &rarr; read amplitude.</li>\n<li><strong>Seconds/Division</strong> sets how much time each horizontal box equals &rarr; read the <strong>period</strong>; then <strong>frequency = 1 / period</strong>. (Example: 4 divisions &times; 10&nbsp;&micro;s = 40&nbsp;&micro;s period &rarr; f = 1/40&micro;s = 25&nbsp;kHz.)</li>\n<li><strong>Trigger</strong> locks the wave so it stops drifting; <strong>Focus/Intensity</strong> sharpen/brighten the trace.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Analog scopes</strong> amplify and sweep the real signal at a set rate; <strong>digital scopes</strong> high-speed-sample the signal into stored \"digital words.\" (FAA-H-8083-30B pp.&nbsp;12-77 to 12-78; Study Guide Std 32.)</p></div>\n\n<h4>Function / Signal Generator</h4>\n<p>A <strong>function (signal) generator</strong> is the opposite of a scope: instead of <em>reading</em> a signal, it <strong>produces</strong> a known test signal (sine, square, or sawtooth) at a chosen frequency and amplitude. You inject that known signal into a circuit and watch the output on a scope to see how the circuit responds. (Pairs with Module 7 wave-generation theory.)</p>\n\n<h4>The Megohmmeter (Megger) &mdash; insulation resistance</h4>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Megger = high-voltage insulation tester</span>\n<p>The <strong>megger (megohmmeter)</strong> is a <strong>high-range ohmmeter with a hand-cranked DC generator</strong>. It measures <strong>insulation resistance</strong> and other very high resistances, and is used for ground, continuity, and short-circuit testing of power systems. Its advantage over a plain ohmmeter: it applies a <strong>high \"breakdown\" voltage</strong> to prove the insulation won't leak or short under electrical stress. <strong>Use a megger to test insulation; use a plain ohmmeter for ordinary low resistance.</strong> (FAA-H-8083-30B p.&nbsp;12-72.)</p></div>\n\n<h4>Continuity tester &amp; Bonding tester</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Continuity tester:</strong> a simple ohmmeter (or buzzer) that confirms a complete path exists &mdash; reads near-zero/short for good, infinity for open. Power must be off.</li>\n<li><strong>Bonding tester:</strong> bonds/grounds need <em>very</em> low resistance (milliohms), too low for an ordinary ohmmeter to read accurately. AC 43.13-1B &para;11-188 <strong>strongly recommends using a bonding tester</strong> and a high-quality instrument (AN/USM-21A or equivalent), or a <strong>millivolt-drop test</strong>, to measure those tiny values after the bonding connection is complete. (AC 43.13-1B &para;11-188, p.&nbsp;11-83.)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Calibration &amp; using the right meter safely</h4>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Calibration first &mdash; every time</span>\n<p>The Study Guide repeats it twice (Std 31 and Std 32): <strong>\"Ensure test equipment and tools required are calibrated.\"</strong> An out-of-cal meter lies. Before testing: confirm the meter is calibrated, pick the <strong>right meter for the job</strong> (DMM for V/A/&Omega;, scope for waveforms, megger for insulation, bonding tester for bonds), set the <strong>right function and range</strong>, observe <strong>polarity</strong>, and follow the connection rules above. Picking the wrong meter or setting can destroy the meter, the circuit, or give a reading that grounds an airplane for the wrong reason.</p></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">In AWG, does a <strong>larger gauge number</strong> mean a bigger or smaller wire? <span class=\"a\">Answer: SMALLER. As the gauge number gets larger, the wire diameter gets smaller (e.g., #22 is thin, #4 is fat).</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">You need to read the <strong>current</strong> flowing through a wire. How do you connect the meter? <span class=\"a\">Answer: as an AMMETER in SERIES &mdash; break the circuit and insert the meter in the current path (power on). Never connect it across a voltage source.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Before checking a resistor or doing a continuity check with an <strong>ohmmeter</strong>, what two things must be true? <span class=\"a\">Answer: power must be OFF (de-energized) and the component isolated/disconnected from the circuit &mdash; the ohmmeter supplies its own power and an in-circuit part gives a false parallel-path reading.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Name two of the four reasons <strong>bonding</strong> matters on an aircraft. <span class=\"a\">Answer (any two): controls EMI, prevents electrostatic-discharge damage, prevents personnel shock hazard, and provides a safe path for lightning-strike currents.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Which instrument <strong>draws the waveform</strong> (voltage over time) instead of just giving one number, and which one measures <strong>insulation resistance with a high test voltage</strong>? <span class=\"a\">Answer: the OSCILLOSCOPE draws the waveform; the MEGOHMMETER (megger) measures insulation resistance with a high breakdown voltage.</span></div>", "quiz": [{"q": "In the American Wire Gauge (AWG) system, as the gauge NUMBER gets larger, the wire diameter:", "options": ["Gets smaller", "Gets larger", "Stays the same", "Doubles each step"], "correct": 0, "short": "Bigger number = smaller wire", "expl": "AWG is backwards from intuition: a larger gauge number means a smaller-diameter wire (e.g., #22 is thin, #4 is fat).", "cite": "Study Guide Std 30 (AWG)", "topic": "awg"}, {"q": "Per the Study Guide, which is NOT one of the wire-sizing factors for AWG?", "options": ["Allowable power loss", "Color of the insulation", "Permissible voltage drop", "Current-carrying ability"], "correct": 1, "short": "Not insulation color", "expl": "Wire sizing factors are allowable power loss, permissible voltage drop, and current-carrying ability.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 30", "topic": "wire-selection"}, {"q": "Per AC 43.13-1B, wires must be sized so they all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["Have sufficient mechanical strength", "Do not exceed allowable voltage drop", "Are always the smallest gauge available", "Are protected by the circuit protection device"], "correct": 2, "short": "Not 'smallest available'", "expl": "Wires must have mechanical strength, stay within voltage-drop limits, be protected by the breaker/fuse, and meet current requirements; smallest gauge is not a goal.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-66, p.11-31", "topic": "wire-selection"}, {"q": "The voltage drop in main power wires should not exceed what percentage of the regulated voltage?", "options": ["10 percent", "25 percent", "50 percent", "2 percent"], "correct": 3, "short": "2%", "expl": "AC 43.13-1B limits main power-wire voltage drop to 2 percent of the regulated voltage.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-66, p.11-31", "topic": "voltage-drop"}, {"q": "Which conductor material has higher conductivity but is heavier and more expensive?", "options": ["Copper", "Aluminum", "Nickel", "Tin"], "correct": 0, "short": "Copper", "expl": "Copper has higher conductivity than aluminum but is heavier and more costly; aluminum has only ~60% of copper's conductivity.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 30 (Conductors)", "topic": "conductors"}, {"q": "A coaxial aircraft wire consists of:", "options": ["Two insulated wires twisted together", "One center conductor surrounded by a metallic braided shield", "One insulated wire in a jacket", "Three conductors in one jacket"], "correct": 1, "short": "Center + braided shield", "expl": "Coax is one center conductor surrounded by a metallic braided shield, used for data and RF signal distribution.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 30 (Coaxial)", "topic": "wire-types"}, {"q": "Twisted pair aircraft wire is typically used for:", "options": ["High-current power feeders", "Grounding heavy loads", "Onboard communications and low-level signal circuits", "Lightning protection straps"], "correct": 2, "short": "Comms/signal", "expl": "Twisted pair (two separately insulated wires twisted together) is used for onboard communications and circuits such as the standby compass light.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 30 (Twisted Pair)", "topic": "wire-types"}, {"q": "Per AC 43.13-1B, aircraft wire must contain at least how many strands (no wire with fewer may be used)?", "options": ["3 strands", "7 strands", "100 strands", "19 strands"], "correct": 3, "short": "19 strands minimum", "expl": "Wire containing fewer than 19 strands must not be used; stranding provides flexibility and vibration resistance.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-66, p.11-31", "topic": "wire-selection"}, {"q": "The golden rule for routing signal wiring relative to power wiring is:", "options": ["Keep signal wiring away from power wiring", "Bundle them tightly together", "Always run them in the same connector", "Splice them together at midpoint"], "correct": 0, "short": "Separate signal from power", "expl": "Keep sensitive signal wiring away from power wiring; EMI increases with parallel-run length and decreases with separation.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-106, p.11-56", "topic": "routing"}, {"q": "Wires of redundant aircraft systems should be:", "options": ["Routed in the same bundle for neatness", "Routed in separate bundles and separate connectors", "Always soldered together", "Grounded to a single common point"], "correct": 1, "short": "Separate bundles", "expl": "Redundant systems are routed in separate bundles and connectors so a single fault cannot disable multiple systems.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-105, p.11-56", "topic": "separation"}, {"q": "Wire bundles are physically supported along their length by:", "options": ["Solder", "Heat shrink only", "Clamps", "Paint"], "correct": 2, "short": "Clamps", "expl": "Clamps support wire bundles at intervals to prevent sag, chafing, and vibration damage.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-146, p.11-65", "topic": "clamping"}, {"q": "BONDING differs from grounding in that bonding primarily:", "options": ["Carries the main load current", "Replaces the circuit breaker", "Increases wire gauge", "Provides a low-impedance path to keep metal parts at the same potential"], "correct": 3, "short": "Equalize potential", "expl": "Bonding provides a low-impedance path connecting metal parts so they share the same potential; it usually does not carry working current.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-187, p.11-82", "topic": "bonding"}, {"q": "Per AC 43.13-1B, inadequate bonding or grounding can cause all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": ["Reduced fuel flow to the engine", "EMI", "Electrostatic-discharge damage to electronics", "Personnel shock hazard or lightning-strike damage"], "correct": 0, "short": "Not fuel flow", "expl": "Bad bonding/grounding causes EMI, ESD damage, shock hazard, and lightning damage — it is an electrical, not a fuel, concern.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-185, p.11-80", "topic": "bonding-purpose"}, {"q": "A bonding jumper connection's resistance should not exceed:", "options": ["3 ohms", ".003 ohm", "30 ohms", "300 ohms"], "correct": 1, "short": ".003 ohm", "expl": "Bonding jumpers must be as short as practicable, with each connection's resistance not exceeding .003 ohm.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-189, p.11-84", "topic": "bonding-jumper"}, {"q": "Shielding is best described as:", "options": ["Adding a circuit breaker", "Doubling the wire gauge", "Applying a metallic covering to wiring to eliminate interference from stray electromagnetic energy", "Coating wire with paint"], "correct": 2, "short": "Metallic EMI covering", "expl": "Shielding applies a metallic covering to wiring/equipment to eliminate interference caused by stray electromagnetic energy.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-89, p.11-47", "topic": "shielding"}, {"q": "For shielding to actually work, the shield must be:", "options": ["Left floating (not connected)", "Painted over", "Cut at every connector", "Connected to ground (typically at both ends or at connectors)"], "correct": 3, "short": "Ground the shield", "expl": "A shield only suppresses EMI when it is grounded; shielded wire is typically grounded at both ends or at connectors.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-89, p.11-47", "topic": "shielding"}, {"q": "The most important rule when STRIPPING insulation from aircraft wire is:", "options": ["Avoid nicking, cutting, or breaking the conductor strands", "Strip as much insulation as possible", "Use a dull blade", "Heat the insulation with a torch"], "correct": 0, "short": "Don't nick the strands", "expl": "Strip with sharp, size-adjusted tools so you avoid nicking, cutting, or breaking strands; remove no more insulation than necessary.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-157, p.11-70", "topic": "stripping"}, {"q": "A properly made crimp connection is described as:", "options": ["Loose and springy", "Gas-tight", "Hollow", "Coated in flux"], "correct": 1, "short": "Gas-tight", "expl": "A correct crimp squeezes the barrel onto the conductor to form a gas-tight joint that resists corrosion.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-178, p.11-78", "topic": "crimping"}, {"q": "Per AC 43.13-1B, crimp terminal lugs and splices must be installed using:", "options": ["Pliers", "A hammer and punch", "A high-quality, calibrated ratchet-type crimping tool sized to the wire", "Any available crimper"], "correct": 2, "short": "Calibrated ratchet crimper", "expl": "Crimps require a high-quality, calibrated, ratchet-type crimp tool with the correct positioner/adjustment for the wire size.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-178, p.11-78", "topic": "crimping"}, {"q": "To verify a crimp's dimensions are correct, a technician uses a:", "options": ["Voltmeter", "Torque wrench", "Megger", "Go/No-Go gauge"], "correct": 3, "short": "Go/No-Go gauge", "expl": "Suitable Go/No-Go gauges are used to confirm crimp dimensions before and during crimping operations.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-178, p.11-79", "topic": "crimping"}, {"q": "A 'cold' solder joint is one that:", "options": ["Was not heated enough, so solder did not bond, leaving a dull joint that cracks open", "Is shiny and smooth with good wetting", "Has too much current flowing", "Is the strongest possible joint"], "correct": 0, "short": "Dull, didn't bond, cracks", "expl": "A cold joint forms when the metal isn't hot enough; the dull, grainy joint never truly bonds and later cracks into an intermittent open.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-82", "topic": "soldering"}, {"q": "For most aircraft wire terminations, the generally preferred method over soldering is:", "options": ["Twisting and taping", "Crimping with a calibrated tool", "Wire nuts", "Welding"], "correct": 1, "short": "Crimp preferred", "expl": "A proper crimp is gas-tight, repeatable, and verifiable with a gauge, so crimping is generally preferred; solder is used where specified.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-174/¶11-178, p.11-76 to 11-79", "topic": "crimp-vs-solder"}, {"q": "Pre-insulated crimp-type terminals on a stud: how many terminal lugs (max) may be placed on one stud?", "options": ["Exactly ten", "Unlimited", "No more than four", "Only one"], "correct": 2, "short": "Max four per stud", "expl": "No more than four terminal lugs (or three lugs plus a bus bar) should be connected to any one stud.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-174c, p.11-77", "topic": "terminals"}, {"q": "A continuity check with an ohmmeter is used to:", "options": ["Measure AC frequency", "Charge a capacitor", "Generate a test signal", "Confirm a complete path and identify open/shorted conductors, good/bad fuses, and switch operation"], "correct": 3, "short": "Verify the path", "expl": "A continuity check traces circuit paths to verify current can flow and identifies opens/shorts, good vs. bad fuses, and switch operation.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 31 (Continuity Checks)", "topic": "continuity"}, {"q": "The Study Guide calls which instrument the 'most versatile electrical measuring instrument used by aircraft technicians'?", "options": ["The multimeter", "The oscilloscope", "The megger", "The signal generator"], "correct": 0, "short": "Multimeter", "expl": "The multimeter is the most versatile meter; it can be set as a voltmeter, ammeter, or ohmmeter to read voltage, current, and resistance.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 4/32 (Multimeter)", "topic": "multimeter"}, {"q": "A voltmeter is connected to a circuit:", "options": ["In series with the component", "In parallel (across) the component", "With power removed", "Through a shunt only"], "correct": 1, "short": "Parallel", "expl": "A voltmeter is connected in parallel (across) the component, with power on.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-71, p.12-79", "topic": "meter-connection"}, {"q": "An ammeter is connected to a circuit:", "options": ["In parallel across the load", "Across the battery terminals", "In series by breaking the circuit and inserting the meter", "With its leads shorted"], "correct": 2, "short": "Series", "expl": "An ammeter is connected in series with the element through which current flows, by opening the circuit and inserting the meter.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-69, p.12-80", "topic": "meter-connection"}, {"q": "Why must you NEVER connect an ammeter across a voltage source?", "options": ["It reads zero", "It only works on AC", "It would read resistance instead", "Its very low resistance allows huge current that damages the meter"], "correct": 3, "short": "Low R = huge current", "expl": "An ammeter has extremely low resistance; placed across a source, even a small voltage drives a very high current that destroys it.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-69 (Precaution 2)", "topic": "meter-safety"}, {"q": "When using an OHMMETER to check a component, the circuit must be:", "options": ["De-energized (power off) with the component isolated", "Energized at full voltage", "Connected to a signal generator", "Running under load"], "correct": 0, "short": "Power off, isolated", "expl": "An ohmmeter supplies its own power, so the circuit must be de-energized and the component disconnected to avoid damage and false readings.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-71, p.12-81", "topic": "meter-connection"}, {"q": "On an analog meter, the most accurate readings are taken:", "options": ["Near the far-left zero", "At about mid-scale (half-scale deflection)", "Near full-scale (pegged)", "Anywhere on the scale"], "correct": 1, "short": "Mid-scale", "expl": "The most accurate analog readings occur at about half-scale (mid-scale) deflection; start high and work down to reach it.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-69, p.12-80", "topic": "meter-use"}, {"q": "An oscilloscope is different from a DMM because it primarily:", "options": ["Gives a single numeric value", "Measures only resistance", "Displays the waveform — voltage versus time — so you can see the signal's shape", "Supplies test power to a circuit"], "correct": 2, "short": "Shows the waveform", "expl": "A scope displays voltage over time (the waveform), revealing amplitude, period/frequency, and phase — a DMM gives only one number.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-77; Study Guide Std 32", "topic": "oscilloscope"}, {"q": "The Study Guide says an oscilloscope measures voltage as which value, plus time to find frequency?", "options": ["DC average only", "RMS resistance", "Ohms", "AC peak-to-peak"], "correct": 3, "short": "AC peak-to-peak", "expl": "Oscilloscopes measure voltage (AC peak-to-peak) and time to determine frequencies, and show phase relationships.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 32 (Oscilloscopes)", "topic": "oscilloscope"}, {"q": "A function (signal) generator is used to:", "options": ["Produce a known test signal (sine, square, sawtooth) to inject into a circuit", "Measure insulation resistance", "Display waveforms", "Crimp terminals"], "correct": 0, "short": "Produces a test signal", "expl": "A signal/function generator produces a known waveform at a chosen frequency and amplitude to drive a circuit under test.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18/32 (wave generation)", "topic": "signal-generator"}, {"q": "The megger (megohmmeter) is specifically used to measure:", "options": ["Small resistances under 1 ohm", "Insulation resistance and other very high resistances using a high test voltage", "AC frequency", "Current draw"], "correct": 1, "short": "Insulation resistance", "expl": "A megger is a high-range ohmmeter with a hand-cranked generator; it measures insulation resistance with a high 'breakdown' voltage.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-72", "topic": "megger"}, {"q": "What gives the megger its advantage over an ordinary ohmmeter?", "options": ["It uses no battery", "It reads only continuity", "It applies a high potential (breakdown voltage) to test insulation under stress", "It is connected in series with the load"], "correct": 2, "short": "High test voltage", "expl": "The megger measures resistance with a high 'breakdown' voltage, proving insulation won't leak or short under electrical stress.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-72", "topic": "megger"}, {"q": "To measure the very low resistance of a bonding/grounding connection, AC 43.13-1B recommends:", "options": ["A standard pocket ohmmeter", "A signal generator", "An oscilloscope", "A bonding tester or millivolt-drop test (high-quality low-resistance instrument)"], "correct": 3, "short": "Bonding tester", "expl": "Bond resistances are in milliohms; AC 43.13-1B recommends a bonding tester (or millivolt-drop test) to measure them accurately.", "cite": "AC 43.13-1B ¶11-188, p.11-83", "topic": "bonding-tester"}, {"q": "Per both the Study Guide and AC 43.13-1B, before performing continuity checks or using test equipment, you must ensure the equipment is:", "options": ["Calibrated", "Brand new", "Battery-powered", "Analog only"], "correct": 0, "short": "Calibrated", "expl": "The Study Guide and AC 43.13-1B both stress ensuring test equipment and tools are calibrated before use.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 31/32; AC 43.13-1B ¶11-188", "topic": "calibration"}, {"q": "Compared to an analog multimeter, a digital multimeter (DMM) generally offers:", "options": ["Lower accuracy and more loading", "Greater accuracy, easier reading, and higher input resistance (less loading)", "No ability to measure resistance", "A built-in oscilloscope only"], "correct": 1, "short": "More accurate, less loading", "expl": "DMMs are easier to read, more accurate, and have higher input resistance, so they load the circuit less than analog meters.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-79; Study Guide Std 32", "topic": "dmm"}, {"q": "A continuity tester (or ohmmeter) shows a GOOD, complete connection as:", "options": ["Infinite resistance", "A high AC voltage", "Near-zero resistance (a short)", "Negative resistance"], "correct": 2, "short": "Near zero ohms", "expl": "A good continuous path reads near-zero resistance; an open path reads infinity (very high resistance).", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-81; Study Guide Std 31", "topic": "continuity"}, {"q": "When choosing the right meter: to see a signal's SHAPE and timing you use a scope; to test wire INSULATION you use a:", "options": ["Voltmeter", "Ammeter", "Signal generator", "Megohmmeter"], "correct": 3, "short": "Megger for insulation", "expl": "Match the tool to the job: oscilloscope for waveforms, megger for insulation resistance, DMM for V/A/ohms, bonding tester for bonds.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-72, p.12-77", "topic": "right-meter"}], "drill": [{"label": "AWG rule", "text": "Bigger gauge NUMBER = SMALLER wire (e.g., #22 thin, #4 fat). Backwards from intuition."}, {"label": "Wire selection", "text": "Size for current-carrying ability, permissible voltage drop (≤2% on main power), and mechanical strength/power loss. Min 19 strands."}, {"label": "Single-conductor system", "text": "Most aircraft use one wire out; the airframe structure is the return path — so good grounding is critical."}, {"label": "Copper vs aluminum", "text": "Copper = higher conductivity, heavier, easier to solder. Aluminum = ~60% conductivity, lighter, cheaper."}, {"label": "Grounding vs bonding", "text": "Grounding completes a normal/fault circuit (carries current). Bonding gives a low-impedance path so parts share the same potential."}, {"label": "Why bonding matters", "text": "Prevents EMI, electrostatic-discharge damage, personnel shock, and lightning-strike damage."}, {"label": "Bonding jumper", "text": "Short strap bonding two parts; each connection ≤ .003 ohm. Remove paint/anodize at the contact point."}, {"label": "Shielding", "text": "Metallic braid kills EMI — but only if the shield is GROUNDED (typically both ends/at connectors)."}, {"label": "Stripping", "text": "Use sharp, size-adjusted tools; do NOT nick/cut/break strands; remove no more insulation than necessary."}, {"label": "Crimp = gas-tight", "text": "Use a calibrated ratchet crimp tool sized to the wire; verify with a Go/No-Go gauge. Too deep cuts strands; too shallow = loose/high resistance."}, {"label": "Cold solder joint", "text": "Dull, grainy joint that never bonded (metal too cold). Cracks open later — intermittent open. Good joint is shiny and well-wetted."}, {"label": "Meter connection rules", "text": "Voltmeter = PARALLEL (power on). Ammeter = SERIES (never across a source). Ohmmeter = POWER OFF, component isolated."}, {"label": "Oscilloscope vs megger", "text": "Scope draws the waveform (V vs time; f = 1/period). Megger measures insulation resistance with a high test voltage."}, {"label": "Calibrate first", "text": "Always confirm test equipment is calibrated, pick the right meter, set the right range, and observe polarity (red +, black −)."}]}, {"n": 12, "title": "Aircraft Fundamentals", "standards": "33, 34", "lesson": "<h3>Why this matters on a real aircraft</h3>\n<p>You are an <strong>avionics tech</strong>, not a pilot &mdash; but every radio, antenna, and black box you touch lives <em>inside an airframe</em> that you have to find your way around, work near safely, and not get hurt by. Standard <strong>33 (Aircraft Structures)</strong> teaches you the parts of the airplane, how it is built, and the names mechanics use to tell you <em>where</em> a box or antenna lives. Standard <strong>34 (Aircraft Handling &amp; Safety)</strong> keeps you alive on the ramp &mdash; props, jet intakes, hot exhaust, fuel, and moving aircraft all kill people every year. Learn the words and the danger zones cold.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">The two halves of this module</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>STRUCTURES (Std 33)</strong> &mdash; the major parts, the flight controls, the three axes of flight, how the airframe is built, and how mechanics locate things by station/zone.</li>\n<li><strong>HANDLING &amp; SAFETY (Std 34)</strong> &mdash; danger areas, towing, jacking, mooring/tie-down, chocks, marshalling, fueling safety, FOD, fire safety, and red \"Remove Before Flight\" tags.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Part 1 &mdash; The major structural parts</h3>\n<p>An airplane has four big structural groups. Memorize these four words &mdash; mechanics use them constantly.</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Part</th><th>Where it is</th><th>What it does</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Fuselage</strong></td><td>Central body, aft of the firewall and forward of the empennage</td><td>The main body; holds the cockpit/cabin, passengers, cargo, and most avionics.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Wings (airfoils)</strong></td><td>Out each side</td><td>Generate <strong>lift</strong>. The <strong>spar</strong> is the main spanwise beam that carries the flight and landing loads.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Empennage</strong> (tail)</td><td>Rear of the aircraft</td><td>The tail group: vertical fin (with the rudder) + horizontal stabilizer (with the elevator). Keeps the plane stable.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Landing gear</strong></td><td>Underneath</td><td>Supports the aircraft on the ground; takes the landing loads. <strong>Tricycle</strong> gear = nosewheel up front; <strong>tailwheel</strong> (conventional) = small wheel at the tail.</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>The <strong>empennage</strong> is just the fancy word for the <strong>tail</strong>. The Study Guide says it \"contains the vertical fin (stabilizer) upon which the rudder is located\" and \"the horizontal stabilizer upon which the elevator is located.\" (Study Guide p.&nbsp;54.)</p>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Plain analogy: a dart</span>\n<p>Think of a paper dart. The long body is the <strong>fuselage</strong>. The flat sides that make it glide are the <strong>wings</strong>. The fins at the back that keep it pointed straight are the <strong>empennage (tail)</strong>. Same job on a real airplane.</p></div>\n\n<h3>Part 2 &mdash; The three axes of flight (memorize this table)</h3>\n<p>Every airplane turns around three imaginary lines that all pass through the <strong>center of gravity (CG)</strong> &mdash; the point where all the weight is considered to act. Each axis has its own motion name. This is the single most-tested idea in Standard 33.</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Axis</th><th>Direction it runs</th><th>Motion name</th><th>Control surface</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Longitudinal</strong></td><td>Nose to tail (lengthwise)</td><td><strong>ROLL</strong></td><td><strong>Ailerons</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Lateral</strong></td><td>Wingtip to wingtip (spanwise)</td><td><strong>PITCH</strong></td><td><strong>Elevator</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Vertical</strong></td><td>Top to bottom (straight up/down)</td><td><strong>YAW</strong></td><td><strong>Rudder</strong></td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">The memory hook &mdash; \"A-E-R\"</span>\n<p><strong>A</strong>ileron / <strong>E</strong>levator / <strong>R</strong>udder lines up with <strong>R</strong>oll / <strong>P</strong>itch / <strong>Y</strong>aw and with <strong>Lo</strong>ngitudinal / <strong>La</strong>teral / <strong>V</strong>ertical. Say it as a chain:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ailerons &rarr; Roll &rarr; Longitudinal axis</strong> (nose-to-tail line).</li>\n<li><strong>Elevator &rarr; Pitch &rarr; Lateral axis</strong> (wingtip-to-wingtip line).</li>\n<li><strong>Rudder &rarr; Yaw &rarr; Vertical axis</strong> (top-to-bottom line).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The classic trap on the exam: they swap \"roll\" and \"yaw,\" or pair the elevator with the wrong axis. Roll is NOT yaw. Pitch is the elevator, not the rudder.</p></div>\n\n<h3>Part 3 &mdash; The flight-control surfaces</h3>\n<p>There are <strong>primary</strong> flight controls (ailerons, elevator, rudder) and <strong>secondary</strong> ones (flaps, trim tabs).</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ailerons</strong> (primary) &mdash; on the <em>outboard trailing edge</em> of each wing. Move opposite each other to <strong>roll</strong> about the longitudinal axis. Controlled by turning the wheel / moving the stick left-right.</li>\n<li><strong>Elevator</strong> (primary) &mdash; hinged to the trailing edge of the <em>horizontal stabilizer</em>. Controls <strong>pitch</strong> about the lateral axis. Pull the wheel back &rarr; elevator up &rarr; nose pitches up. A <strong>stabilator</strong> is a one-piece stabilizer-plus-elevator.</li>\n<li><strong>Rudder</strong> (primary) &mdash; hinged to the <em>vertical fin</em>. Controls <strong>yaw</strong> about the vertical axis. Worked by the <strong>foot pedals</strong> (right pedal = nose yaws right).</li>\n<li><strong>Flaps</strong> (secondary) &mdash; <em>inboard</em> of the ailerons on the wing trailing edge. Lower to add <strong>lift and drag</strong> for slower takeoff and landing.</li>\n<li><strong>Trim tabs</strong> (secondary) &mdash; small tabs on the trailing edge of a primary control. They hold a control in position so the pilot does not have to push, <strong>reducing pilot workload</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">The four forces (one line each)</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Lift</strong> &mdash; up; made by the wings. <strong>Weight</strong> &mdash; down; made by gravity. In steady level flight, <strong>lift = weight</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Thrust</strong> &mdash; forward; made by the powerplant. <strong>Drag</strong> &mdash; backward; resistance of the air. Steady speed means <strong>thrust = drag</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Bernoulli's Principle</strong>: as air speeds up, its pressure drops. Faster air over the curved (cambered) top of the wing = lower pressure on top = <strong>lift</strong>. (Study Guide pp.&nbsp;55&ndash;56.)</li>\n</ul></div>\n\n<h3>Part 4 &mdash; How the airframe is built (and why you care)</h3>\n<p>Two construction families:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Truss</strong> &mdash; a welded framework of tubes (Pratt or Warren truss). Older / simpler aircraft.</li>\n<li><strong>Monocoque family</strong> &mdash; the skin carries load. Sub-types: <em>true monocoque</em> (skin only), <em>reinforced shell</em>, and <strong>semimonocoque</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Semimonocoque &mdash; know this one</span>\n<p>The Study Guide calls <strong>semimonocoque</strong> \"the most common type of fuselage construction.\" It \"derives its strength from internal parts such as <strong>bulkheads, longerons, keel beams, and drag struts</strong>\" working together with the skin. (Study Guide pp.&nbsp;53&ndash;54.)</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Bulkheads / formers</strong> &mdash; the cross-section rings (give shape, run side-to-side).</li>\n<li><strong>Longerons / stringers</strong> &mdash; the long lengthwise members (run nose-to-tail).</li>\n<li><strong>Skin</strong> &mdash; the stressed outer covering that also carries load.</li>\n</ul></div>\n\n<h4>Stations and zones &mdash; the avionics tech's map</h4>\n<p>This is the practical payoff of Standard 33 for <em>you</em>. A maintenance manual will say \"the comm transceiver is at <strong>FS&nbsp;347, BL&nbsp;0, WL&nbsp;120, zone&nbsp;200</strong>.\" If you do not know what those mean, you cannot find the box or its antenna. The airframe is measured on a grid:</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Reference</th><th>Measures</th><th>From where</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Fuselage Station (FS)</strong></td><td>Fore-and-aft position</td><td>Inches aft of the <strong>datum</strong> (a fixed zero point, often the nose or firewall)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Buttock / Butt Line (BL)</strong></td><td>Left-right position</td><td>Inches left or right of the aircraft centerline</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Water Line (WL)</strong></td><td>Vertical position</td><td>Inches above a fixed horizontal reference</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Zone</strong></td><td>A numbered <em>region</em> of the aircraft (e.g. zone 200 = fuselage, 300 = empennage, 500/600 = wings)</td><td>Manufacturer's zoning system; speeds locating equipment, wiring, and access panels</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>Stations give an <strong>exact coordinate</strong>; zones give a <strong>general neighborhood</strong>. You use both to locate avionics boxes, wire bundles, connectors, and access panels in the manual.</p>\n\n<h4>Where avionics and antennas mount</h4>\n<p>Black boxes usually live in an <strong>avionics bay / rack</strong> behind the instrument panel or in the nose/tail. <strong>Antennas</strong> are mounted on the skin where they have a clear \"view\": comm/nav and GPS antennas often on <strong>top</strong> of the fuselage, transponder/DME and marker antennas on the <strong>bottom</strong>, the ADF sense antenna flush on top, and the glideslope often in the nose. The Study Guide's preflight checklist tells the avionics tech to inspect every antenna for <strong>security, missing fasteners, skin cracks, deteriorated seals, and inadvertent paint</strong> &mdash; paint or a cracked seal kills antenna performance. (Study Guide p.&nbsp;59.)</p>\n\n<h3>Part 5 &mdash; Ground danger areas (Standard 34): the zones that hurt you)</h3>\n<p>The ramp is, in the FAA's words, \"a place of dangerous activity.\" The biggest killers are spinning props, jet intakes, and hot/high-velocity exhaust.</p>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">The danger areas &mdash; commit these to memory</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Propellers</strong> &mdash; treat <em>every</em> prop as live (a hot mag can fire a \"dead\" engine). Never walk through the prop arc. Stay clear of <strong>prop wash / prop blast</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Jet (turbine) inlet / intake</strong> &mdash; a running jet can <strong>suck a person in</strong>. Keep the area in front of the inlet clear of people, equipment, and FOD. (FAA p.&nbsp;1-13.)</li>\n<li><strong>Jet exhaust</strong> &mdash; behind a turbine is a blast of <strong>hot, high-velocity gas</strong> that can blow you down, burn you, or hurl debris. The exhaust hazard zone extends well behind the engine. (FAA p.&nbsp;1-18, Fig.&nbsp;1-17.)</li>\n<li><strong>Hearing</strong> &mdash; jet and prop noise damages hearing; wear protection.</li>\n</ul></div>\n\n<h3>Part 6 &mdash; Towing, marshalling, chocks, jacking, mooring</h3>\n<h4>Towing</h4>\n<p>Towing a big aircraft is a <strong>team</strong> job. The Study Guide tow team is: <strong>one team leader</strong>, <strong>one qualified person in the cockpit on the brakes</strong> (NOT to steer &mdash; only to stop if the tow bar fails), <strong>one tow-vehicle driver</strong>, <strong>two wing-walkers</strong>, and <strong>one tail-walker</strong>. Key rules: use the <strong>proper tow bar</strong>; tricycle-gear and tailwheel aircraft are generally <strong>towed forward</strong>; <strong>charge the brakes</strong> first; keep <strong>chocks immediately available</strong>; and <strong>brakes are never applied except on an emergency command</strong> from a ground team member. No one rides on or under a moving aircraft. (Study Guide pp.&nbsp;56&ndash;58.)</p>\n\n<h4>Marshalling</h4>\n<p>The <strong>marshaller (signalman)</strong> directs the aircraft or tug with standardized hand/wand signals. A signalman walking backward must glance behind often to avoid <strong>backing into a propeller</strong> or tripping over a <strong>chock, fire bottle, or tie-down line</strong>. (FAA p.&nbsp;1-19.)</p>\n\n<h4>Chocks</h4>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Chocks &mdash; the simple, vital one</span>\n<p><strong>Wheel chocks</strong> are wedges placed <strong>fore and aft</strong> (in front of AND behind) the main-gear wheels to keep the aircraft from rolling. The rule appears everywhere: \"Chock all wheels fore and aft,\" and during towing \"chocks must be immediately available.\" (FAA pp.&nbsp;1-8, 1-10; Study Guide p.&nbsp;57.)</p></div>\n\n<h4>Jacking</h4>\n<p><strong>Jacking</strong> lifts the aircraft off its wheels for weighing, gear swings, or wheel/brake work. Use only the manufacturer's <strong>jack points</strong>, jack on <strong>level ground in a hangar</strong> out of the wind, use jacks of adequate capacity with <strong>safety locks/collars</strong>, and raise it <strong>evenly</strong>. Never work under an aircraft on jacks without the locks engaged. (FAA, jacking/weighing safety.)</p>\n\n<h4>Mooring / tie-down</h4>\n<p><strong>Mooring (tie-down)</strong> secures a parked aircraft against wind. Head the aircraft <strong>into the prevailing wind</strong>, tie down at the proper <strong>tie-down rings</strong> (never to a lift strut &mdash; it can bend the strut), use anti-slip knots like the <strong>bowline</strong>, leave about <strong>1 inch of slack</strong> in manila rope (it shrinks when wet), and install <strong>control/gust locks</strong>. (FAA p.&nbsp;1-8.)</p>\n\n<h3>Part 7 &mdash; Fueling safety, FOD, and the ramp</h3>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Fueling &mdash; the bonding rule is the heart of it</span>\n<p>Flowing fuel builds <strong>static electricity</strong>; a single spark can ignite fuel vapor. Before fuel flows you must <strong>bond and ground</strong>: connect the fueling unit to the aircraft and the aircraft to ground so they are at the <em>same</em> electrical potential, with <strong>no spark</strong>. Rules from FAA pp.&nbsp;1-26 to 1-28:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Bond/ground first.</strong> Attach grounds to <strong>bare metal or proper grounding points</strong> &mdash; <em>never</em> use the exhaust or propeller as a ground.</li>\n<li><strong>Ground the nozzle to the aircraft, then open the tank.</strong></li>\n<li>Turn <strong>OFF all electrical and electronic systems, including radar</strong>, before fueling.</li>\n<li>No <strong>flame or spark sources</strong>; no smoking; nothing loose in shirt pockets.</li>\n<li>Use the <strong>correct grade</strong> (AVGAS is color-coded; Jet A is marked black). <strong>Never mix AVGAS and jet fuel.</strong></li>\n<li>Do not fuel with <strong>lightning within 5 miles</strong>, or within <strong>500 ft of operating ground radar</strong>.</li>\n<li>Have the <strong>correct fire extinguisher</strong> staged.</li>\n</ul></div>\n\n<p><strong>FOD (Foreign Object Damage/Debris).</strong> Any loose item on the ramp &mdash; a tool, a cap, a rag, a bit of safety wire &mdash; can be sucked into an engine or blown into someone. Keep the area in front of jet inlets clear; do not carry loose items in shirt pockets; pick up after every job; use shadow boards / tool inventory so nothing is left behind. (This ties back to Standard 24, FOD Prevention.)</p>\n\n<p><strong>Working around energized systems &amp; red-tags.</strong> Treat aircraft systems as <strong>live</strong> until proven dead. Before working on a circuit, pull and <strong>red-tag</strong> the breaker or open and tag the disconnect; a residual charge can stay in <strong>capacitors and coils</strong> even after power-off (a Class-C electrical-fire and shock hazard). Use <strong>placards / \"DO NOT OPERATE\" tags</strong> so no one re-energizes a system you are in.</p>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">\"Remove Before Flight\" (RBF) streamers</span>\n<p>Items that stick out and must come off before flight &mdash; <strong>pitot covers, intake/exhaust plugs, landing-gear pins, control/gust locks</strong> &mdash; carry a <strong>red streamer</strong> with white \"REMOVE BEFORE FLIGHT\" lettering, attached with safety pins. It warns personnel of dangers and, critically, of items that would make systems <strong>inoperative if left on</strong> (a covered pitot tube = no airspeed). Failure to remove them is a known cause of accidents. (Study Guide pp.&nbsp;57&ndash;58.)</p></div>\n\n<h3>Part 8 &mdash; Fire safety on the ramp</h3>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">The fire triangle and fire classes</span>\n<p>A fire needs three things: <strong>fuel + heat + oxygen</strong>. Remove any one and it goes out. Fire <strong>classes</strong> tell you which extinguisher to grab:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Class A</strong> &mdash; ordinary combustibles (wood, paper, cloth). Best agent: <strong>water</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Class B</strong> &mdash; flammable liquids (fuel, oil, solvents, grease). Use <strong>CO&#8322; / dry chemical / Halon</strong>; <em>not</em> water.</li>\n<li><strong>Class C</strong> &mdash; <strong>energized electrical</strong> equipment/wiring. Use a <strong>non-conductive</strong> agent: <strong>CO&#8322; or Halon</strong>; never plain water on live electrical.</li>\n<li><strong>Class D</strong> &mdash; burning <strong>metal</strong> (magnesium wheels/brakes). Use <strong>dry powder</strong> only; never water or CO&#8322; (cooling causes explosive expansion).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>During engine start a <strong>fireguard</strong> stands by with a <strong>CO&#8322; extinguisher of at least 5 lb</strong>. To use an extinguisher: pull the pin, stand back ~8&nbsp;ft, aim at the <strong>base</strong> of the fire, squeeze, and sweep side to side. (FAA pp.&nbsp;1-5 to 1-8, 1-13.)</p></div>\n\n<h3>Putting it together</h3>\n<p><strong>Structures:</strong> fuselage + wings + empennage + landing gear; three axes (longitudinal/roll/aileron, lateral/pitch/elevator, vertical/yaw/rudder); semimonocoque skin-and-stringer build; stations (FS/BL/WL) and zones let you find avionics and antennas. <strong>Handling &amp; safety:</strong> respect the prop arc, jet inlet, and exhaust; tow as a team; chock fore-and-aft; jack on the right points with locks; tie down into the wind; bond/ground before fueling and never mix fuels; control FOD; red-tag energized systems and pull RBF streamers; match the extinguisher class to the fire.</p>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">An avionics box must roll the aircraft left or right &mdash; which axis is that, what motion is it, and which control surface commands it? <span class=\"a\">Answer: the <strong>longitudinal</strong> axis (nose-to-tail); the motion is <strong>roll</strong>; the <strong>ailerons</strong> command it.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">A maintenance manual locates a transceiver at \"FS 312.\" What does FS tell you? <span class=\"a\">Answer: <strong>Fuselage Station</strong> &mdash; the fore-and-aft position, measured in inches aft of the datum (zero reference). It pins down where along the length of the fuselage the box is.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Why must you bond/ground an aircraft and the fuel truck before fueling? <span class=\"a\">Answer: flowing fuel builds <strong>static electricity</strong>; bonding/grounding equalizes potential so no spark jumps that could ignite the fuel vapor.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">You have an energized electrical (Class C) fire in an avionics rack. Which extinguishing agents are appropriate, and which must you avoid? <span class=\"a\">Answer: use a <strong>non-conductive agent &mdash; CO&#8322; or Halon</strong>; <strong>never use water</strong> on energized electrical (shock hazard).</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">What is the semimonocoque fuselage, and what internal members give it strength? <span class=\"a\">Answer: the <strong>most common</strong> fuselage type; the load-carrying skin works with internal members &mdash; <strong>bulkheads, longerons, keel beams, and drag struts</strong>.</span></div>", "quiz": [{"q": "Motion about the LONGITUDINAL axis is called what, and which surface controls it?", "options": ["Pitch; elevator", "Roll; ailerons", "Yaw; rudder", "Yaw; ailerons"], "correct": 1, "short": "Roll; ailerons", "expl": "The longitudinal axis runs nose-to-tail; motion about it is roll, commanded by the ailerons.", "cite": "Study Guide pp.53,55", "topic": "axes"}, {"q": "Motion about the LATERAL axis (wingtip to wingtip) is called what, and which surface controls it?", "options": ["Roll; ailerons", "Yaw; rudder", "Pitch; elevator", "Pitch; rudder"], "correct": 2, "short": "Pitch; elevator", "expl": "The lateral axis runs wingtip-to-wingtip; motion about it is pitch, commanded by the elevator.", "cite": "Study Guide pp.53,55", "topic": "axes"}, {"q": "Motion about the VERTICAL axis is called what, and which surface controls it?", "options": ["Yaw; rudder", "Roll; ailerons", "Pitch; elevator", "Yaw; elevator"], "correct": 0, "short": "Yaw; rudder", "expl": "The vertical axis runs top-to-bottom; motion about it is yaw, commanded by the rudder.", "cite": "Study Guide pp.53,55", "topic": "axes"}, {"q": "Which control surface is operated by the rudder PEDALS?", "options": ["Ailerons", "Elevator", "Flaps", "Rudder"], "correct": 3, "short": "Rudder", "expl": "The rudder is operated by foot pedals; right pedal yaws the nose right.", "cite": "Study Guide p.55", "topic": "controls"}, {"q": "Flaps are SECONDARY flight controls that primarily:", "options": ["Roll the aircraft", "Yaw the aircraft", "Trim the elevator", "Increase lift and drag for takeoff and landing"], "correct": 3, "short": "Add lift and drag", "expl": "Flaps lower to increase lift, drag, and effective wing area for slower takeoff and landing.", "cite": "Study Guide p.55", "topic": "controls"}, {"q": "What is the purpose of a trim tab?", "options": ["To roll the aircraft", "To reduce pilot effort by holding a primary control in position", "To increase top speed", "To act as the main lift device"], "correct": 1, "short": "Reduces pilot workload", "expl": "Trim tabs on a control's trailing edge aerodynamically hold the control, reducing pilot effort and workload.", "cite": "Study Guide p.55", "topic": "controls"}, {"q": "The central body of the aircraft, aft of the firewall and forward of the empennage, is the:", "options": ["Fuselage", "Empennage", "Nacelle", "Spar"], "correct": 0, "short": "Fuselage", "expl": "The fuselage is the central body containing the cockpit/cabin, passengers, cargo, and most avionics.", "cite": "Study Guide p.53", "topic": "structures"}, {"q": "The empennage is another name for the aircraft's:", "options": ["Wing", "Tail group", "Landing gear", "Engine cowling"], "correct": 1, "short": "Tail group", "expl": "The empennage is the tail: it holds the vertical fin (rudder) and horizontal stabilizer (elevator).", "cite": "Study Guide p.54", "topic": "structures"}, {"q": "In a wing, the main spanwise member that carries the flight and landing loads is the:", "options": ["Bulkhead", "Spar", "Longeron", "Fairing"], "correct": 1, "short": "Spar", "expl": "The spar is the principal spanwise beam of the wing; it carries the flight and landing loads.", "cite": "Study Guide p.54", "topic": "structures"}, {"q": "Which fuselage construction is described as the MOST COMMON type?", "options": ["True monocoque", "Pratt truss", "Semimonocoque", "Warren truss"], "correct": 2, "short": "Semimonocoque", "expl": "Semimonocoque, which derives strength from internal members plus the skin, is the most common fuselage type.", "cite": "Study Guide p.54", "topic": "construction"}, {"q": "A semimonocoque fuselage derives its strength from internal parts such as:", "options": ["Only the outer skin", "Bulkheads, longerons, keel beams, and drag struts", "Lift struts and bracing wires", "The propeller and cowling"], "correct": 1, "short": "Bulkheads/longerons/keel beams/drag struts", "expl": "Semimonocoque combines the stressed skin with internal members: bulkheads, longerons, keel beams, and drag struts.", "cite": "Study Guide pp.53-54", "topic": "construction"}, {"q": "For an avionics tech, a 'Fuselage Station (FS)' identifies a location's:", "options": ["Left-right position from centerline", "Vertical height", "Electrical potential", "Fore-and-aft position from the datum"], "correct": 3, "short": "Fore-and-aft from datum", "expl": "FS gives the fore-and-aft position in inches aft of the datum, pinning a component along the fuselage length.", "cite": "Study Guide p.53 (structures/terminology)", "topic": "stations"}, {"q": "Why does an avionics technician need to understand aircraft zones and stations?", "options": ["To calculate engine thrust", "To locate equipment, antennas, wiring, and access panels in the manual", "To set the trim", "To mix fuel grades"], "correct": 1, "short": "To locate equipment/antennas", "expl": "Stations give exact coordinates and zones give general regions, so the tech can find boxes, antennas, wiring, and panels.", "cite": "Study Guide pp.52-53 (Std 33)", "topic": "zones"}, {"q": "During the avionics preflight, antennas must be inspected for security, missing fasteners, skin cracks, deteriorated seals, and:", "options": ["Inadvertent paint", "Correct color band", "Fuel grade", "Tire pressure"], "correct": 0, "short": "Inadvertent paint", "expl": "Paint over an antenna degrades its performance; the Study Guide lists it as a required antenna inspection item.", "cite": "Study Guide p.59", "topic": "avionics-mount"}, {"q": "Around a running TURBINE (jet) engine, the area in front of the inlet must be kept clear because the inlet can:", "options": ["Freeze nearby personnel", "Suck in people, debris, or property (FOD)", "Emit radiation", "Leak fuel"], "correct": 1, "short": "Suction/ingestion hazard", "expl": "A turbine inlet creates strong suction that can ingest personnel, equipment, and FOD; keep it clear.", "cite": "FAA p.1-11 to 1-13", "topic": "danger-areas"}, {"q": "The hazard directly BEHIND a running turbine engine is:", "options": ["A magnetic field", "Static electricity only", "A blast of hot, high-velocity exhaust gas", "Cold-soak frost"], "correct": 2, "short": "Hot exhaust blast", "expl": "Turbine exhaust is a high-velocity, high-temperature blast that can burn, knock down personnel, and throw debris.", "cite": "FAA p.1-18, Fig.1-17", "topic": "danger-areas"}, {"q": "Why should you treat any propeller as if it could turn at any moment?", "options": ["Props are always electrically live", "The prop is spring-loaded", "A hot magneto can fire and start a 'dead' engine", "Prop wash is harmless"], "correct": 2, "short": "Hot mag can fire it", "expl": "A faulty/hot magneto can ignite the engine even when it appears off, so every prop is treated as live.", "cite": "FAA Ch.1 ground safety", "topic": "danger-areas"}, {"q": "Wheel chocks are correctly placed:", "options": ["Fore and aft of the main-gear wheels", "Only behind the nosewheel", "On top of the wing", "Under the tail skid only"], "correct": 0, "short": "Fore and aft of main wheels", "expl": "Chocks go in front of and behind the main-gear wheels to keep the aircraft from rolling.", "cite": "FAA p.1-8; Study Guide p.57", "topic": "chocks"}, {"q": "During towing, the qualified person seated in the cockpit is there to:", "options": ["Steer the aircraft", "Run the engines", "Talk to passengers", "Operate the brakes only in an emergency, e.g. if the tow bar fails"], "correct": 3, "short": "Brakes in emergency, not steer", "expl": "That person is on the brakes for emergencies (tow bar failure); they do NOT steer the aircraft.", "cite": "Study Guide pp.56-57", "topic": "towing"}, {"q": "During a tow, aircraft brakes should be applied:", "options": ["Whenever the cockpit person decides", "Only on an emergency command from a ground tow-team member", "Continuously, to slow the tug", "Never, under any circumstance"], "correct": 1, "short": "Only on emergency ground command", "expl": "Brakes are applied only on an emergency command from a tow-team member on the ground.", "cite": "Study Guide p.57", "topic": "towing"}, {"q": "When jacking an aircraft, you must lift only at the:", "options": ["Manufacturer's designated jack points", "Nearest flat skin panel", "Wing tips", "Propeller hub"], "correct": 0, "short": "Manufacturer jack points", "expl": "Jack only at the approved jack points, on level ground, with jacks of adequate capacity and safety locks engaged.", "cite": "FAA Ch.1/Ch.6 jacking safety", "topic": "jacking"}, {"q": "When mooring (tying down) a parked aircraft, you should head it:", "options": ["Downwind", "Into the prevailing wind", "Perpendicular to the wind", "Toward the hangar regardless of wind"], "correct": 1, "short": "Into the wind", "expl": "Head the aircraft into the prevailing/forecast wind and tie down at the proper tie-down rings.", "cite": "FAA p.1-8", "topic": "mooring"}, {"q": "Tie-down rope should never be tied to a:", "options": ["Tie-down ring", "Tie-down anchor", "Wing tie-down loop", "Lift strut"], "correct": 3, "short": "Lift strut", "expl": "Tying to a lift strut can bend it if the rope slips; use the provided tie-down rings/loops. Use anti-slip knots like the bowline.", "cite": "FAA p.1-8", "topic": "mooring"}, {"q": "Before fuel begins to flow, the single most important electrical safety step is to:", "options": ["Turn on the radar to monitor", "Bond and ground the aircraft and fueling unit", "Disconnect the battery and discard it", "Paint the antennas"], "correct": 1, "short": "Bond and ground", "expl": "Bonding/grounding equalizes potential so static electricity cannot spark and ignite fuel vapor.", "cite": "FAA p.1-26 to 1-28", "topic": "fueling"}, {"q": "Which item must NEVER be used as a grounding point when fueling?", "options": ["Bare metal structure", "A proper grounding receptacle", "The propeller or engine exhaust", "A wing tie-down loop with bare metal"], "correct": 2, "short": "Prop / exhaust", "expl": "Never ground to the propeller or exhaust; use bare metal or proper grounding points.", "cite": "FAA p.1-28", "topic": "fueling"}, {"q": "AVGAS and Jet A fuel must be:", "options": ["Never mixed", "Mixed for better performance", "Mixed only in turbine engines", "Used interchangeably"], "correct": 0, "short": "Never mixed", "expl": "Mixing the wrong fuel can cause power loss, detonation, or engine damage; never mix AVGAS and jet fuel.", "cite": "FAA p.1-25 to 1-26", "topic": "fueling"}, {"q": "FOD stands for foreign object damage/debris. A key FOD-prevention practice is:", "options": ["Carrying spare hardware in your shirt pocket", "Leaving rags near the inlet", "Keeping the area clear and accounting for all tools/items", "Fueling with electronics on"], "correct": 2, "short": "Keep area clear, account for tools", "expl": "Pick up loose items, keep jet inlets clear, and inventory tools so nothing is ingested or blown into people.", "cite": "FAA p.1-13 (FOD); Std 24", "topic": "fod"}, {"q": "A red 'REMOVE BEFORE FLIGHT' streamer is attached to items such as pitot covers and gear pins because:", "options": ["They are decorative", "They keep the aircraft warm", "They improve aerodynamics", "Leaving them on can make systems inoperative and cause accidents"], "correct": 3, "short": "Warns; prevents inop systems", "expl": "RBF streamers warn personnel and flag items that, if left on, render systems inoperative (e.g. covered pitot = no airspeed).", "cite": "Study Guide pp.57-58", "topic": "rbf-tags"}, {"q": "When working on an energized electrical system, you should first:", "options": ["Spray it with water", "Increase the voltage to test it", "Pull and red-tag the breaker / open and tag the disconnect", "Remove the placards"], "correct": 2, "short": "De-energize and red-tag", "expl": "De-energize, then red-tag/placard so no one re-energizes the system; residual charge can remain in caps and coils.", "cite": "FAA Ch.1 safety; placard practice", "topic": "energized"}, {"q": "A Class C fire involves:", "options": ["Wood and paper", "Flammable liquids", "Energized electrical wiring and equipment", "Burning magnesium"], "correct": 2, "short": "Energized electrical", "expl": "Class C fires involve energized electrical equipment and wiring. (A fire needs the triangle of fuel + heat + oxygen.)", "cite": "FAA p.1-5", "topic": "fire"}, {"q": "Which extinguishing agent must you AVOID on an energized (Class C) electrical fire?", "options": ["CO2", "Halon", "Dry chemical", "Water"], "correct": 3, "short": "Water", "expl": "Plain water conducts electricity; use a non-conductive agent like CO2 or Halon on energized electrical fires.", "cite": "FAA p.1-5 to 1-6", "topic": "fire"}, {"q": "A Class D fire (burning metal such as magnesium) is best fought with:", "options": ["Dry powder", "Water", "CO2", "Foam"], "correct": 0, "short": "Dry powder", "expl": "Dry powder is used on Class D metal fires; water or CO2 cooling causes explosive expansion of the hot metal.", "cite": "FAA p.1-5 to 1-7", "topic": "fire"}, {"q": "During engine start, the fireguard must stand by with a CO2 extinguisher of at least:", "options": ["1-pound capacity", "5-pound capacity", "20-pound capacity", "No minimum"], "correct": 1, "short": "5-pound CO2", "expl": "A fireguard familiar with starting procedures stands by with a CO2 extinguisher of at least 5-pound capacity.", "cite": "FAA p.1-13", "topic": "fire"}, {"q": "Bernoulli's Principle, the main source of wing lift, states that as a fluid's velocity increases, its pressure:", "options": ["Increases", "Decreases", "Stays the same", "Becomes zero"], "correct": 1, "short": "Pressure decreases", "expl": "Faster airflow over the cambered top of the wing lowers pressure there, producing lift. A stabilator is a one-piece horizontal stabilizer-plus-elevator.", "cite": "Study Guide pp.55-56", "topic": "theory"}], "drill": [{"label": "Longitudinal axis", "text": "Runs nose-to-tail; motion = ROLL; controlled by the AILERONS."}, {"label": "Lateral axis", "text": "Runs wingtip-to-wingtip; motion = PITCH; controlled by the ELEVATOR."}, {"label": "Vertical axis", "text": "Runs top-to-bottom; motion = YAW; controlled by the RUDDER."}, {"label": "A-E-R memory chain", "text": "Aileron/Elevator/Rudder = Roll/Pitch/Yaw = Longitudinal/Lateral/Vertical."}, {"label": "Four major parts", "text": "Fuselage (body), Wings (lift), Empennage (tail), Landing gear (ground support)."}, {"label": "Empennage", "text": "The TAIL: vertical fin holds the rudder; horizontal stabilizer holds the elevator."}, {"label": "Semimonocoque", "text": "Most common fuselage; skin + bulkheads, longerons, keel beams, drag struts."}, {"label": "Stations & zones", "text": "FS=fore/aft, BL=left/right, WL=up/down, Zone=region; used to LOCATE avionics & antennas."}, {"label": "Jet danger areas", "text": "INLET sucks in; EXHAUST blasts hot high-velocity gas behind; keep inlet clear of FOD."}, {"label": "Chocks", "text": "Wheel wedges placed FORE AND AFT of the main-gear wheels to stop rolling."}, {"label": "Fueling = bond/ground first", "text": "Bond & ground before fuel flows; never ground to prop/exhaust; never mix AVGAS & Jet A."}, {"label": "Fire classes", "text": "A=ordinary(water), B=liquids, C=energized electrical (NO water; CO2/Halon), D=metal (dry powder)."}]}, {"n": 13, "title": "Exam Prep & Endorsements", "standards": "All — capstone", "lesson": "<h3>The finish line: what Module 13 is for</h3>\n<p>You've worked through every domain of the AET: DC and Ohm's law, components, semiconductors, power supplies, signal circuits, digital logic, safety, wiring, and aircraft fundamentals. This capstone does two jobs. First, it gets you <strong>ready to pass the actual exam</strong> &mdash; the reality of the test, a smart test-taking strategy, and the highest-yield facts to nail cold. Second, it shows you the <strong>endorsement ladder</strong> that comes <em>after</em> AET &mdash; the credentials that turn your certificate into a real FAA career pathway. The quiz for this module is a <strong>comprehensive mock exam</strong> mixing every domain, just like the real thing.</p>\n\n<h3>Part 1 &mdash; The exam reality (know exactly what you're walking into)</h3>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">The AET exam at a glance</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>90 multiple-choice questions</strong>, four options each (A&ndash;D).</li>\n<li><strong>73% to pass.</strong> 90 &times; 0.73 &asymp; 65.7, so you must get <strong>66 correct</strong>. That means you can <strong>miss up to 24</strong> and still pass.</li>\n<li><strong>~2 hours</strong> total. That works out to about <strong>80 seconds per question</strong> &mdash; plenty of time if you keep moving.</li>\n<li><strong>Proctored, no prerequisites, lifetime certification (no renewal).</strong></li>\n<li>Administered by <strong>SpaceTEC Partners (SPI)</strong> via Credential Testing Services under ASTM standard <strong>F3245</strong>. It is <em>not</em> an ETA International cert.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<p>Read that pass math again, because it matters for your nerves: <strong>you do not need to be perfect.</strong> A quarter of the test can go wrong and you still walk out certified. Your job is not to know everything &mdash; it's to bank the questions you <em>do</em> know and not throw away easy points.</p>\n\n<h3>Part 2 &mdash; Test-taking strategy (worth several free points)</h3>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">The six habits that bank points</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Eliminate distractors first.</strong> On a 4-option question, if you can cross off two obviously wrong answers, you've gone from a 25% guess to a 50% guess. Most questions have at least one silly distractor &mdash; kill it.</li>\n<li><strong>Watch your units.</strong> Milli (m) = &times;0.001, kilo (k) = &times;1000, mega (M) = &times;1,000,000. A right number with the wrong prefix is a wrong answer. Convert everything to base units (volts, amps, ohms) before you do Ohm's-law math.</li>\n<li><strong>Don't overthink it.</strong> The AET tests <em>fundamentals</em>, not trick logic. If an answer looks like the plain, textbook truth, it usually is. Your first instinct on a definition question is usually right.</li>\n<li><strong>Flag and return.</strong> If a question stalls you for more than ~90 seconds, pick your best guess, <strong>flag it</strong>, and move on. Never leave it blank (there's no penalty for guessing). Come back with fresh eyes at the end.</li>\n<li><strong>Manage time: ~80 sec/question.</strong> At the halfway clock (~60 min) you should be near question 45. If you're behind, speed up on the easy ones so you have margin for the hard ones.</li>\n<li><strong>Answer EVERY question.</strong> A blank is a guaranteed zero; a guess is a free 25%. Before you submit, make sure nothing is left empty.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Part 3 &mdash; The highest-yield topics to nail cold</h3>\n<p>If you only had one evening left, you'd drill these. They show up again and again across the domains, and they're all things you can know <em>perfectly</em> rather than approximately.</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Topic</th><th>The thing to have cold</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Ohm's law &amp; Watt's law</strong></td><td>E&nbsp;=&nbsp;I&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;R and P&nbsp;=&nbsp;I&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;E. Rearrange any way: I&nbsp;=&nbsp;E/R, R&nbsp;=&nbsp;E/I, P&nbsp;=&nbsp;I&sup2;R&nbsp;=&nbsp;E&sup2;/R.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Resistor color code</strong></td><td>Black&nbsp;0, Brown&nbsp;1, Red&nbsp;2, Orange&nbsp;3, Yellow&nbsp;4, Green&nbsp;5, Blue&nbsp;6, Violet&nbsp;7, Gray&nbsp;8, White&nbsp;9. Gold&nbsp;=&nbsp;&plusmn;5%, Silver&nbsp;=&nbsp;&plusmn;10%, none&nbsp;=&nbsp;&plusmn;20%.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>ELI the ICE man</strong></td><td>In an inductor (L), <strong>E leads I</strong> (voltage leads current). In a capacitor (C), <strong>I leads E</strong> (current leads voltage).</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Meter rules</strong></td><td>Voltmeter in <strong>parallel</strong> (high impedance). Ammeter in <strong>series</strong> (low impedance). Ohmmeter only on a <strong>de-energized</strong> circuit.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Rectifier diode counts</strong></td><td>Half-wave&nbsp;=&nbsp;1 diode; full-wave center-tap&nbsp;=&nbsp;2; full-wave bridge&nbsp;=&nbsp;4.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Logic gates</strong></td><td>AND&nbsp;=&nbsp;all 1s for a 1. OR&nbsp;=&nbsp;any 1 for a 1. NOT&nbsp;=&nbsp;inverts. NAND/NOR&nbsp;=&nbsp;AND/OR then inverted. XOR&nbsp;=&nbsp;1 only when inputs differ.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Fire classes</strong></td><td>A&nbsp;=&nbsp;ordinary combustibles; B&nbsp;=&nbsp;flammable liquids; C&nbsp;=&nbsp;energized electrical; D&nbsp;=&nbsp;combustible metals. Never use water on a C (electrical) fire.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>ESD</strong></td><td>Electrostatic-sensitive devices (CMOS/MOSFET ICs) are killed by static. Wear a grounded wrist strap; handle at a grounded ESD bench; store in anti-static bags.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>AWG (wire gauge)</strong></td><td>Smaller AWG number = <strong>larger</strong> wire = more current capacity. (22 AWG is thin; 4 AWG is thick.)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Bonding &amp; grounding</strong></td><td>Bonding ties metal parts together to one electrical potential (controls static, lightning, EMI); grounding ties the system to the airframe reference.</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"box ex\"><span class=\"bt\">Worked example &mdash; an exam-style Ohm's law item with a unit trap</span>\n<p>\"A 12&nbsp;V source drives a 2&nbsp;k&Omega; resistor. What is the current?\" The trap is the <strong>k</strong>. Convert: 2&nbsp;k&Omega;&nbsp;=&nbsp;2000&nbsp;&Omega;. Then I&nbsp;=&nbsp;E/R&nbsp;=&nbsp;12&nbsp;/&nbsp;2000&nbsp;=&nbsp;<strong>0.006&nbsp;A&nbsp;=&nbsp;6&nbsp;mA</strong>. If you forgot the k and used 2&nbsp;&Omega;, you'd get 6&nbsp;A &mdash; off by a thousand. <strong>Always convert prefixes first.</strong></p></div>\n\n<h3>Part 4 &mdash; The endorsement ladder (the real career payoff)</h3>\n<p>Passing the AET is the foundation, not the finish. The AET certificate is the <strong>prerequisite</strong> for a set of focused <strong>endorsements</strong> &mdash; each is a separate exam that proves you specialize in one avionics area. <strong>You must pass the AET first</strong> before you can sit any endorsement.</p>\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">The five AET endorsements</span>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Endorsement</th><th>What it covers</th><th>Exam</th></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>AEIT</strong> &mdash; Aircraft Electronics Installation Technician</td><td>Installing avionics: wiring, mounting, integration, the install-side trade</td><td><strong>106 q / 70%</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>ANS</strong> &mdash; Autonomous Navigation Systems</td><td>Self-contained nav (INS/IRS, GPS-as-standalone) that doesn't depend on ground stations</td><td><strong>50 q / 70%</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>DNS</strong> &mdash; Dependent Navigation Systems</td><td>Nav that <em>depends</em> on external/ground signals (VOR, ILS, DME, ground-based aids)</td><td><strong>50 q / 70%</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>OCS</strong> &mdash; Onboard Communications &amp; Safety</td><td>Intercom/audio, CVR, ELT, and onboard safety/communication systems</td><td><strong>50 q / 70%</strong></td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>RCS</strong> &mdash; Radio Communication Systems</td><td>Transmitters/receivers/transceivers, comm systems, SATCOM, RF/EMF safety</td><td><strong>50 q / 70%</strong></td></tr>\n</table>\n</div>\n<p><strong>What the RCS endorsement looks like inside.</strong> The NCATT RCS Standard is built around four subject areas: <strong>I. Safety</strong> (antenna contact, Radio Frequency Radiation (RFR) and Electromagnetic Field (EMF) hazards, ground operation of weather radar), <strong>II. Radio Transmitters/Receivers</strong> (including receiver sensitivity, tuning circuits, oscillators, modulators/demodulators, filters, wave propagation, FAA &amp; FCC rules), <strong>III. Communication Systems</strong>, and <strong>IV. Satellite Communication (SATCOM)</strong>. Each task is rated on NCATT's level scale &mdash; <em>performance</em> 1&ndash;4 (limited &rarr; highly proficient) and <em>knowledge</em> a&ndash;d (nomenclature &rarr; advanced theory). Notice how much overlaps what you already studied: oscillators, filters, and tuning circuits are straight out of your signal and power-supply modules. <strong>The endorsements reuse the AET fundamentals &mdash; that's the whole point of the ladder.</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"box key\"><span class=\"bt\">Why the ladder matters: 14 CFR 65.101</span>\n<p>The real prize: <strong>AET + one avionics endorsement</strong> satisfies the formal-training prong of <strong>14 CFR 65.101(a)(5)(ii)</strong> toward an <strong>FAA Repairman Certificate</strong>. In plain English: the certificate alone is a r&eacute;sum&eacute; line, but the certificate <em>plus</em> an endorsement is a documented training pathway the FAA recognizes when an employer applies for a repairman certificate on your behalf. That's the credential that actually unlocks avionics shop work.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Part 5 &mdash; AET vs. CAET: confirm before you book</h3>\n<p>One last honest flag before you schedule the test. In <strong>March 2025 the AEA launched the CAET</strong> (Certified AET) as the modernized successor to the AET (100&nbsp;q, 90&nbsp;min, 70% to pass, ~$119). The AET is becoming a <strong>legacy</strong> credential. The <em>study content is nearly identical</em>, so everything in this course serves both exams &mdash; but the credential names differ, and some employers will ask for one specifically.</p>\n<div class=\"box\"><span class=\"bt\">Your decision checklist</span>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Confirm with your target avionics employer</strong> which credential they want on a r&eacute;sum&eacute; &mdash; AET or CAET. Ask before you pay for a seat.</li>\n<li>If you take and pass the <strong>AET</strong>, a <strong>~$49 upgrade exam</strong> (50&nbsp;q, 80% to pass) converts AET&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp;CAET. So the AET is never a dead end.</li>\n<li>Either way, <strong>study the same material</strong> &mdash; this course covers both. The decision is about which seat to book, not what to learn.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h3>You're ready &mdash; a word before the mock exam</h3>\n<p>Think about where you started: voltage, current, and resistance were just words. Now you can read a color code, count diodes in a rectifier, trace a signal through a filter, fill a logic-gate truth table, and pick the right fire extinguisher for an electrical fire. That's the entire blueprint. The mock exam below mixes every domain at exam difficulty &mdash; treat it like the real thing: ~80 seconds a question, eliminate distractors, watch your units, flag-and-return, and answer every single item. Hit <strong>73%+</strong> and you're ready to book. You've done the work. Go get it.</p>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">You can miss how many questions on the 90-question AET and still pass at 73%? <span class=\"a\">Answer: up to 24 (you need 66 correct).</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">Which endorsement covers nav systems that DEPEND on ground stations like VOR and ILS? <span class=\"a\">Answer: DNS &mdash; Dependent Navigation Systems.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">What does AET + one endorsement satisfy toward an FAA Repairman Certificate? <span class=\"a\">Answer: the formal-training prong of 14 CFR 65.101(a)(5)(ii).</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">If a question stalls you for 90+ seconds, what should you do? <span class=\"a\">Answer: pick your best guess, flag it, move on, and return at the end &mdash; never leave it blank.</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"selfq\">If you pass the AET but your employer wants the CAET, what's the fix? <span class=\"a\">Answer: take the ~$49 upgrade exam (50 q, 80% to pass) to convert AET to CAET.</span></div>", "quiz": [{"q": "A 24 V source is across a 6 ohm resistor. What is the current?", "options": ["4 A", "144 A", "0.25 A", "30 A"], "correct": 0, "short": "I = E/R", "expl": "I = E/R = 24/6 = 4 A.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 5; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-39", "topic": "ohms-law"}, {"q": "Which formula gives power?", "options": ["P = E - I", "P = I x E", "P = R / I", "P = E + R"], "correct": 1, "short": "P = I x E", "expl": "Watt's law: power equals current times voltage (P = I x E).", "cite": "Study Guide Std 5; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-41", "topic": "watts-law"}, {"q": "2 mA equals how many amps?", "options": ["2000 A", "0.2 A", "0.002 A", "2 A"], "correct": 2, "short": "0.002 A", "expl": "Milli means times 0.001, so 2 mA = 0.002 A. Watch your prefixes.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 1; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-2", "topic": "units"}, {"q": "In a SERIES circuit, the current is:", "options": ["Highest at the source only", "Different in every component", "Always zero", "The same through every component"], "correct": 3, "short": "Same everywhere", "expl": "A series circuit has one path, so the same current flows through every component.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 4; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-44", "topic": "series"}, {"q": "In a PARALLEL circuit, the voltage across each branch is:", "options": ["The same across every branch", "Divided evenly by current", "Zero", "Higher in the longer branch"], "correct": 0, "short": "Same voltage", "expl": "All parallel branches share the same two nodes, so they see the same voltage.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 4; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-47", "topic": "parallel"}, {"q": "In the resistor color code, the digit for GREEN is:", "options": ["3", "5", "7", "9"], "correct": 1, "short": "Green = 5", "expl": "Black0 Brown1 Red2 Orange3 Yellow4 Green5 Blue6 Violet7 Gray8 White9.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 7; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-32", "topic": "color-code"}, {"q": "A GOLD tolerance band means:", "options": ["+/-1%", "+/-10%", "+/-5%", "+/-20%"], "correct": 2, "short": "+/-5%", "expl": "Gold = +/-5%, Silver = +/-10%, no band = +/-20%.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 7; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-32", "topic": "tolerance"}, {"q": "An open resistor in a series string causes:", "options": ["More current", "Higher voltage at the source", "A short to ground", "No current (open circuit)"], "correct": 3, "short": "No current", "expl": "An open breaks the only path, so series current stops.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 8; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-44", "topic": "fault"}, {"q": "In 'ELI the ICE man,' for an inductor (L):", "options": ["Voltage leads current (E before I)", "Current leads voltage", "They are always in phase", "There is no current"], "correct": 0, "short": "E leads I in L", "expl": "ELI: in an inductor, E (voltage) leads I (current).", "cite": "Study Guide Std 9; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-66", "topic": "eli-ice"}, {"q": "In 'ELI the ICE man,' for a capacitor (C):", "options": ["Voltage leads current", "Current leads voltage (I before E)", "They are 180 degrees out", "Current is zero"], "correct": 1, "short": "I leads E in C", "expl": "ICE: in a capacitor, I (current) leads E (voltage).", "cite": "Study Guide Std 10; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-58", "topic": "eli-ice"}, {"q": "The unit of capacitance is the:", "options": ["Henry", "Ohm", "Farad", "Tesla"], "correct": 2, "short": "Farad", "expl": "Capacitance is measured in farads; inductance in henries.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 10", "topic": "units"}, {"q": "A transformer with a primary:secondary turns ratio of 1:3 fed 10 V AC outputs about:", "options": ["3.3 V", "0 V", "10 V", "30 V"], "correct": 3, "short": "30 V", "expl": "Voltage scales with turns ratio: 10 V x 3 = 30 V.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 12; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-79", "topic": "transformer"}, {"q": "A diode allows current to flow:", "options": ["In one direction only", "In both directions", "Only when cold", "Only as AC"], "correct": 0, "short": "One direction", "expl": "A diode conducts in one direction only when forward biased.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 15; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-98", "topic": "diode"}, {"q": "A silicon diode needs about how much forward voltage to conduct?", "options": ["0 V", "0.7 V", "7 V", "12 V"], "correct": 1, "short": "0.7 V", "expl": "A silicon diode forward-biases at roughly 0.7 VDC.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 15; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-98", "topic": "diode-bias"}, {"q": "An NPN transistor's three terminals are:", "options": ["Anode, cathode, gate", "Source, drain, gate", "Emitter, base, collector", "Plus, minus, ground"], "correct": 2, "short": "E, B, C", "expl": "A bipolar junction transistor has an emitter, base, and collector.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 14; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-104", "topic": "transistor"}, {"q": "A small base current controlling a large collector current is what transistor action?", "options": ["Rectification", "Oscillation", "Filtering", "Amplification"], "correct": 3, "short": "Amplification", "expl": "A transistor amplifies: a small base signal controls a larger collector current.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 14; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-105", "topic": "transistor"}, {"q": "How many diodes are in a full-wave BRIDGE rectifier?", "options": ["4", "2", "1", "6"], "correct": 0, "short": "4 diodes", "expl": "A full-wave bridge uses four diodes and needs no center tap.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-102", "topic": "rectifier-diodes"}, {"q": "The filter capacitor in a power supply is connected:", "options": ["In series with the load", "In parallel with the load", "In place of a diode", "Across the AC line only"], "correct": 1, "short": "Parallel", "expl": "A filter capacitor sits in parallel with the load to bypass ripple.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-111", "topic": "filter"}, {"q": "Which component is the classic voltage regulator?", "options": ["Standard rectifier diode", "LED", "Zener diode", "Resistor"], "correct": 2, "short": "Zener", "expl": "A Zener diode regulates by holding a constant reverse-breakdown voltage.", "cite": "FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-103", "topic": "regulation"}, {"q": "A LOW-PASS filter:", "options": ["Passes high frequencies, blocks low", "Passes one narrow band", "Blocks everything", "Passes low frequencies, blocks high"], "correct": 3, "short": "Passes low", "expl": "A low-pass filter passes low frequencies and attenuates highs.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 17; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-112", "topic": "filter-freq"}, {"q": "An oscillator's job is to:", "options": ["Generate a repeating waveform/signal", "Convert AC to DC", "Block all current", "Store charge only"], "correct": 0, "short": "Generates a waveform", "expl": "An oscillator produces a continuous repeating output signal.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-116", "topic": "oscillator"}, {"q": "A limiter (clipper) circuit:", "options": ["Amplifies the whole signal", "Removes part of a waveform above/below a set level", "Rectifies three-phase AC", "Stores energy in a field"], "correct": 1, "short": "Clips the waveform", "expl": "A limiter clips off the portion of a waveform beyond a set amplitude.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 19; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-112", "topic": "limiter"}, {"q": "For oscillation to be sustained, a circuit needs gain plus:", "options": ["Negative feedback", "No feedback", "Positive (regenerative) feedback", "A short circuit"], "correct": 2, "short": "Positive feedback", "expl": "Oscillators use positive feedback to sustain a continuous output.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 18; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-116", "topic": "oscillator"}, {"q": "An AND gate outputs a 1 only when:", "options": ["Any input is 1", "Inputs differ", "All inputs are 0", "All inputs are 1"], "correct": 3, "short": "All inputs 1", "expl": "AND outputs 1 only when every input is 1.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 21; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-124", "topic": "logic-and"}, {"q": "An OR gate outputs a 1 when:", "options": ["Any input is 1", "All inputs are 1 only", "No input is 1", "Inputs are equal"], "correct": 0, "short": "Any input 1", "expl": "OR outputs 1 if at least one input is 1.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 21; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-124", "topic": "logic-or"}, {"q": "A NOT gate (inverter):", "options": ["Adds two bits", "Outputs the opposite of its input", "Outputs 1 only for two 1s", "Stores a bit"], "correct": 1, "short": "Inverts", "expl": "A NOT gate outputs the logical opposite of its single input.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 21; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-124", "topic": "logic-not"}, {"q": "The decimal number 5 in binary is:", "options": ["111", "011", "101", "110"], "correct": 2, "short": "101", "expl": "5 = 4 + 1 = 101 in binary.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-122", "topic": "binary"}, {"q": "An XOR gate outputs a 1 when:", "options": ["Both inputs are 1", "Both inputs are 0", "The inputs are the same", "The inputs are different"], "correct": 3, "short": "Inputs differ", "expl": "XOR (exclusive OR) outputs 1 only when its inputs differ.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 21; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-124", "topic": "logic-xor"}, {"q": "Hexadecimal is base:", "options": ["16", "8", "10", "2"], "correct": 0, "short": "Base 16", "expl": "Hexadecimal is base 16 (digits 0-9 and A-F).", "cite": "Study Guide Std 20; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-122", "topic": "number-systems"}, {"q": "A Class C fire involves:", "options": ["Ordinary combustibles", "Energized electrical equipment", "Flammable liquids", "Combustible metals"], "correct": 1, "short": "Electrical", "expl": "Class C is an energized-electrical fire; never use water on it.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22", "topic": "fire-class"}, {"q": "Which fire class is FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS?", "options": ["Class A", "Class C", "Class B", "Class D"], "correct": 2, "short": "Class B", "expl": "Class B fires involve flammable liquids like fuel and solvents.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 22", "topic": "fire-class"}, {"q": "When handling an electrostatic-sensitive device, you should:", "options": ["Rub it on a cloth", "Store it loose in a pocket", "Hold it by the pins", "Wear a grounded wrist strap at a grounded ESD bench"], "correct": 3, "short": "Grounded wrist strap", "expl": "ESD parts require a grounded wrist strap, ESD bench, and anti-static bags.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 27", "topic": "esd"}, {"q": "FOD stands for:", "options": ["Foreign Object Debris/Damage", "Fuel Oil Drain", "Final Operational Data", "Forward Operations Deck"], "correct": 0, "short": "Foreign Object Debris", "expl": "FOD = Foreign Object Debris (and the Damage it causes).", "cite": "Study Guide Std 24", "topic": "fod"}, {"q": "A safety wire (lock wire) is installed so that it:", "options": ["Lets a fastener loosen freely", "Tends to tighten the fastener / prevents loosening", "Carries main current", "Insulates the part"], "correct": 1, "short": "Prevents loosening", "expl": "Safety wire is routed to resist loosening of the secured fastener.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 29", "topic": "safety-device"}, {"q": "The authoritative source for a maintenance procedure is the:", "options": ["Mechanic's memory", "A coworker's advice", "Manufacturer's maintenance manual / technical publication", "Any internet forum"], "correct": 2, "short": "Maintenance manual", "expl": "Always use the current manufacturer technical publication for procedures.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 25", "topic": "tech-pubs"}, {"q": "Dissimilar metals in contact with an electrolyte cause:", "options": ["Magnetism", "Improved conductivity", "No effect", "Galvanic corrosion"], "correct": 3, "short": "Galvanic corrosion", "expl": "Dissimilar metals plus an electrolyte create galvanic (dissimilar-metal) corrosion.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 28; FAA-H-8083-30B Ch.8", "topic": "corrosion"}, {"q": "A torque wrench is used to:", "options": ["Apply a specified fastener tightness", "Cut wire", "Measure voltage", "Strip insulation"], "correct": 0, "short": "Apply set torque", "expl": "A torque wrench applies a precise, specified tightening force.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 26", "topic": "tools"}, {"q": "In American Wire Gauge (AWG), a SMALLER gauge number means the wire is:", "options": ["Thinner with less capacity", "Thicker with more current capacity", "Always aluminum", "Non-conductive"], "correct": 1, "short": "Smaller # = thicker", "expl": "Smaller AWG number = larger diameter = more current capacity.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 30; AC 43.13-1B Ch.11", "topic": "awg"}, {"q": "A voltmeter is connected to a circuit:", "options": ["In series", "In place of the load", "In parallel across the component", "Only when de-energized"], "correct": 2, "short": "Parallel", "expl": "A voltmeter (high impedance) connects in parallel across the measured points.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 32; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-50", "topic": "meter"}, {"q": "An ammeter is connected to a circuit:", "options": ["In parallel", "Never while powered", "Across the source only", "In series so current flows through it"], "correct": 3, "short": "Series", "expl": "An ammeter (low impedance) connects in series so current passes through it.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 32; FAA-H-8083-30B p.12-50", "topic": "meter"}, {"q": "Bonding (electrical bonding) primarily:", "options": ["Ties metal parts to a common potential to control static, lightning, and EMI", "Increases circuit resistance", "Steps up voltage", "Replaces grounding entirely"], "correct": 0, "short": "Common potential", "expl": "Bonding joins metal parts to one potential, controlling static, lightning, and EMI.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 30; AC 43.13-1B Ch.11", "topic": "bonding"}, {"q": "A wire crimp terminal must be:", "options": ["Soldered with acid flux", "Sized for the wire gauge and crimped with the proper tool", "Twisted on by hand", "Larger than the wire by two sizes"], "correct": 1, "short": "Right size + tool", "expl": "Crimp terminals must match the wire gauge and be crimped with the correct tool.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 31; AC 43.13-1B Ch.11", "topic": "wiring"}, {"q": "A semi-monocoque structure carries loads through:", "options": ["The skin alone", "The engine mounts only", "A combination of skin and internal frames/stringers", "Hydraulic fluid"], "correct": 2, "short": "Skin + frames", "expl": "Semi-monocoque shares loads between the skin and internal frames/stringers.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 33; FAA-H-8083-30B Ch.1", "topic": "structures"}, {"q": "Before working near aircraft, you should always:", "options": ["Skip the safety brief", "Ignore the danger zones", "Run engines unattended", "Follow ground-handling and safety procedures (chocks, grounding, hazards)"], "correct": 3, "short": "Follow ground safety", "expl": "Aircraft handling requires following ground-safety procedures and respecting hazard zones.", "cite": "Study Guide Std 34", "topic": "handling"}, {"q": "To pass the 90-question AET at 73%, you must answer at least how many correctly?", "options": ["66", "60", "50", "73"], "correct": 0, "short": "66 correct", "expl": "90 x 0.73 = 65.7, so you need 66 correct (may miss up to 24).", "cite": "aet-coach identity; ASTM F3245", "topic": "exam-logistics"}, {"q": "Which credential is required BEFORE you can take any avionics endorsement (AEIT, ANS, DNS, OCS, RCS)?", "options": ["A&P certificate", "The AET", "An FCC license", "A college degree"], "correct": 1, "short": "AET first", "expl": "Each endorsement requires passing the AET first.", "cite": "aet-coach identity", "topic": "endorsements"}, {"q": "The DNS endorsement covers navigation systems that:", "options": ["Are fully self-contained", "Only use SATCOM", "Depend on external/ground signals (VOR, ILS, DME)", "Do not exist on aircraft"], "correct": 2, "short": "Dependent nav", "expl": "DNS = Dependent Navigation Systems, which rely on ground-based aids.", "cite": "aet-coach identity (endorsement ladder)", "topic": "endorsements"}, {"q": "AET plus one avionics endorsement satisfies the formal-training prong of which regulation toward an FAA Repairman Certificate?", "options": ["14 CFR 65.71", "14 CFR 43.13", "FAR 91.205", "14 CFR 65.101(a)(5)(ii)"], "correct": 3, "short": "65.101(a)(5)(ii)", "expl": "AET + an endorsement meets the formal-training prong of 14 CFR 65.101(a)(5)(ii).", "cite": "aet-coach identity", "topic": "endorsements"}, {"q": "If you pass the AET but your employer wants the CAET, you can:", "options": ["Take a ~$49 upgrade exam (50 q, 80% pass)", "Retake the entire AET", "Do nothing; they are identical names", "Wait two years"], "correct": 0, "short": "$49 upgrade exam", "expl": "A ~$49 upgrade exam (50 q, 80%) converts AET to CAET.", "cite": "aet-coach identity", "topic": "aet-vs-caet"}, {"q": "During the exam, the smartest move on a question that stalls you for over 90 seconds is to:", "options": ["Leave it blank", "Guess, flag it, and return at the end", "Stare until it makes sense", "Quit the exam"], "correct": 1, "short": "Guess, flag, return", "expl": "Guess your best, flag it, move on, and revisit; never leave a blank.", "cite": "aet-coach exam strategy", "topic": "test-strategy"}], "drill": [{"label": "Pass math", "text": "90 questions, 73% to pass = 66 correct; you may miss up to 24. ~80 sec/question over ~2 hours."}, {"label": "Ohm's & Watt's law", "text": "E = I x R and P = I x E. Convert prefixes (k, m, M) to base units BEFORE doing the math."}, {"label": "Color code", "text": "Bk0 Br1 R2 O3 Y4 Gn5 Bl6 V7 Gy8 W9. Gold=+/-5%, Silver=+/-10%, none=+/-20%."}, {"label": "ELI the ICE man", "text": "In L: E leads I (voltage first). In C: I leads E (current first)."}, {"label": "Meter rules", "text": "Voltmeter = parallel. Ammeter = series. Ohmmeter = de-energized circuit only."}, {"label": "Rectifier diode counts", "text": "Half-wave = 1 diode; full-wave center-tap = 2; full-wave bridge = 4."}, {"label": "Logic gates", "text": "AND=all 1s. OR=any 1. NOT=inverts. XOR=1 only when inputs differ. NAND/NOR=AND/OR then inverted."}, {"label": "Fire classes", "text": "A=combustibles, B=flammable liquids, C=energized electrical, D=metals. Never water on a Class C."}, {"label": "ESD", "text": "Static kills CMOS/MOSFET ICs. Grounded wrist strap + grounded ESD bench + anti-static bags."}, {"label": "AWG", "text": "Smaller gauge NUMBER = thicker wire = more current capacity."}, {"label": "Bonding vs grounding", "text": "Bonding ties metal parts to one potential (static/lightning/EMI). Grounding ties system to airframe reference."}, {"label": "Endorsement ladder", "text": "After AET: AEIT (106q/70%), ANS, DNS, OCS, RCS (each 50q/70%). Must pass AET first."}, {"label": "65.101 pathway", "text": "AET + one endorsement satisfies 14 CFR 65.101(a)(5)(ii) toward an FAA Repairman Certificate."}, {"label": "AET vs CAET", "text": "CAET launched March 2025 (100q/90min/70%/~$119). Confirm with employer; ~$49 upgrade converts AET to CAET."}]}]};
